(8, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Hackerprenomics: The Forbes Article', 'hackerprenomics-the-forbes-article', '<p>Earlier this month, Forbes&#39; contributor Venkatesh Rao published an interesting column at Forbes.com titled, &quot;The Rise of Developeronomics&quot; at <a href=\"http://www.forbes.com/sites/venkateshrao/2011/12/05/the-rise-of-developeronomics/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.forbes.com/sites/venkateshrao/2011/12/05/the-rise-of-developeronomics/</a>. Not knowing if/when Forbes.com takes columns off its site (anyone still do this?), I re-created it here. There is another recent column by another contributor, David Kirkpatrick, called &quot;Now Every Company is a Software Company&quot; at <a href=\"http://www.forbes.com/sites/techonomy/2011/11/30/now-every-company-is-a-software-company/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.forbes.com/sites/techonomy/2011/11/30/now-every-company-is-a-software-company/</a> Both are very interesting columns. Rastin Mehr is ahead of Forbes in enunciating &quot;developeronimics&quot;. A point I&#39;ve been trying to hammer over your head, including in my recent post &quot;<a href=\"index.php?option=com_k2&amp;view=item&amp;id=47:users-are-powerful-with-foss-belong-to-hackerpreneur-clubs\" target=\"_blank\">Users are Powerful with FOSS by Belonging to Hackerpreneur Clubs</a>&quot;. Although Venkatesh Rao calls it &quot;developeronomics&quot;, he should &quot;Rastin-ize&quot; it into &quot;Hackerprenomics&quot;, and &quot;Bob-ize&quot; it into &quot;Hackerpreneur-Club-omics&quot; (hehe), by virtue of this one paragraph:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Investing in good developers is such a good bet at the moment, that if you have money and you happen to find a talented developer who seems to like you and wants to work with you, you should give him/her your money to build something, anything, even if you have no really good product ideas (those are cheap; I&rsquo;ll sell you a dozen for a dollar).If you don&rsquo;t have money, you should offer up whatever other kind of surplus you do have. <strong>The NPV on a strong and positive relationship with a talented developer today is ridiculously high</strong>. If you gain the trust of a talented developer to the point that they are likely to drop any active gig in the future in favor of joining one of your projects, the value is through the roof. The world is your oyster, which you with your developer will open.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>NPV = Net Present Value. The difference between the present value of a stream of cash inflows; and, the present value of a stream of cash outflows. Put another way: devs make you money. I&#39;ll be talking to Rastin and Ash about &quot;Hackerpreneur-nomics&quot; on this week&#39;s podcast at <a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2011/tbbs43\" target=\"_blank\">http://SouthLaSalleMedia.com/2011/tbbs43</a>. Here is the Forbes article:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>There is a theory in evolutionary biology that reciprocal altruism and cooperation first appeared as a solution to the food storage problem. If you were an early hominid and you killed a large mammoth, you could not possibly eat it all before it rotted. So you shared it. The best bank for your excess capital was your friend&rsquo;s stomach. That way, you could play banker when your friend killed the next mammoth. I was thinking of this little idea recently in the context of human wealth. Unless you are a professional investor (and probably even then), places to store surplus capital today where it will even be safe and/or not depreciate too fast (let alone generate a return) are getting incredibly hard to find. The stock market seems to be a secular, bearish bloodbath. Volatility and unexpected temporary rallies are making short games dangerous. Even staying liquid in dollars seems to have its dangers, due to threats of devaluation and unfamiliar new terms like &ldquo;quantitative easing&rdquo; which us average investors are starting to hear for the first time. The Euro isn&rsquo;t exactly a great alternative at the moment. Investing in gold and similar commodities seems to require a somewhat apocalyptic mindset and decisions about whether or not you want access to the actual metal if things go to hell (which isn&rsquo;t to say such a mindset isn&rsquo;t justified at the moment). But there is one safe haven, if you know how to invest in it: software developers.\r\n<p>The Right Investment for Pre-Apocalyptic Times</p>\r\nThe one absolutely solid place to store your capital today &mdash; if you know how to do it &ndash; is in software developers&rsquo; wallets. If the world survives looming financial apocalypse dangers at all, this is the one investment that will weather the storms. It doesn&rsquo;t matter whether you are an individual or a corporation, or what corner of the world you inhabit. You need to find a way to invest in software developers. In what follows, I am deliberately going to talk about the developers like they are products in a meat market. For practical purposes, they are, since the vast majority of them haven&rsquo;t found a way to use their own scarcity to their advantage. Which means others find a way to do so. In capitalism, every human is either a capitalist, somebody else&rsquo;s capital, or economically worthless. Today, this abstract point specifically translates to: people who can invest in developers, developers, and everybody else. This means that if you are in apparently more fundamental professions &mdash; perhaps you are a baker with a small business &mdash; you are effectively useless, not because bread isn&rsquo;t important, but because surviving in the bread business is now a matter of having developers on your side who can help you win in a game that Yelp, Groupon and other software companies are running to their advantage. If your bakery doesn&rsquo;t have an iPhone app, it will soon be at the mercy of outfits like Yelp. And god forbid, if you don&rsquo;t have a skill, like baking, which the developer-centric economy can actually use, you are in deep trouble. One reason the Occupy Wall Street movement is not having the impact it seems like it should, based on sheer numbers of people involved, is that many participants simply have no cards left to play in this national game of economic poker. We&rsquo;ll switch from this meat-market perspective to the humanist developer point of view at the end of the post. Investing in good developers is such a good bet at the moment, that if you have money and you happen to find a talented developer who seems to like you and wants to work with you, you should give him/her your money to build something, anything, even if you have no really good product ideas (those are cheap; I&rsquo;ll sell you a dozen for a dollar). If you don&rsquo;t have money, you should offer up whatever other kind of surplus you do have. <strong>The NPV on a strong and positive relationship with a talented developer today is ridiculously high. If you gain the trust of a talented developer to the point that they are likely to drop any active gig in the future in favor of joining one of your projects, the value is through the roof. The world is your oyster, which you with your developer will open.</strong> I warned you I was going to objectify and dehumanize programmers. On the flip side of the coin, I&rsquo;ve known people with complementary talents (such as raising money or marketing products) who return the loyalty in extreme ways &mdash; insisting on working with their trusted developers even if that means walking away from million dollar deals. But the rules of investing in developer capital are entirely different from the rules of investing in other types of human capital (a term due to economist A. W. Lewis, from 1953, at the peak of the industrial economy) or non-human capital assets. You do not stock up on programmers the same way you stock up on construction workers, soldiers, chemists, mechanical engineers, real estate or dollars (in fact, &ldquo;stocks&rdquo; is the wrong word, you have to think in terms of what John Hagel calls &ldquo;flows,&rdquo; but that&rsquo;s a subtlety we&rsquo;ll ignore in this post, and stick to the stock metaphor). <strong>At the moment, the only thing potentially more valuable than a relationship with a great developer is a relationship with a survivalist who is good with things like guns, bunkers and cabins in woods (that&rsquo;s in case the apocalypse does come about in 2012, with bullets for currency). Which you think is the better bet depends on exactly how gloomy and bearish you are. I am pretty gloomy, but not yet gloomy enough to turn to survivalist capital investments.</strong> The entire software industry realizes this, and is building up a long position in quality software talent (emphasis on quality) as fast as possible, and by any means necessary, including large companies acquiring smaller ones purely for talent, with every intention of throwing away every other asset the acquisition brings in (lending a whole new meaning to the term &ldquo;talent acquisition.&rdquo;) As software eats the world and every company turns into a software company, people in other parts of the economy are slowly starting to understand what&rsquo;s going on and are belatedly trying to get in on the action. They will almost certainly fail unless they learn how to compete with the software industry itself. But more on that later.\r\n\r\n<p>The Anatomy of the Software Talent Wars</p>\r\nIn the midst of a thoroughly gloomy labor market, the genuine desperation you see in the software talent wars is almost surreal. Almost every day, I see big companies, little companies, entrepreneurs, wannabe entrepreneurs and even venture capitalists join in the hunt. The talent hunters infest LinkedIn, troll Quora, and trawl Facebook and Google+. Cartoons of homeless-looking CEOs holding up signs that say &ldquo;Looking for a technical co-founder&rdquo; are doing the rounds. Heck, I am one of these talent hunters (any star iOS developers out there interested in working with me?). Eager new angel investors are willing to throw money at any project that appears to involve a strong developer or two, trusting that even if the investment fails, having first shot at subsequent projects the talent gets into, will be worthwhile. Entire startups are being formed purely to keep good software teams together. Gilded-cage workplaces full of gourmet buffets, high-tech nap pods, and daycare facilities are just the tip of the iceberg. They are primarily mechanisms available to sufficiently large, Too Big to Fail software companies like Google, Facebook and Microsoft. In a game where these majors set the bar in terms of cash and quality-of-life compensation, and very young startups set the bar in terms of providing realistic shots at big windfalls, no other type of business has any chance of really competing for top talent, with any mix of cash and stock it can conjure up. The talent wars actually play out on a much larger stage. The fight over the mind of a talented developer begins long before he or she even thinks about taking a paying job. Sometimes the fight begins in middle school. The reason is that the software industry, unlike almost any other, can get talent into its pipeline extremely early, by way of dominant programming languages, development environments, data and tools. A talented high-school kid who starts hacking away at an iPhone app at 14 is likely to stay in orbit around Apple for his/her entire career. A kid whose first programming stunt is a Google Maps mashup using other Google tools and APIs, is just as likely to stay in orbit around Google. A little known fact about Google, for instance, is that its investment in Python (one of the three languages the company uses for its work) was in part a strategic bet on an under-valued language, when it noticed that other companies were missing the growing talent pool in Python. The result is that cash-rich software majors, options-rich startups and relationship-rich industry insiders have been sucking up all available quality talent among them, leaving other industries and economic sectors starving. This is creating a have/have-not talent divide that is unprecedented. This divide will soon surpass the infamous geopolitical North/South divide in importance. No, I am not exaggerating. Why does the software industry buck the general trend of high unemployment (or at least the thriving part of it)? Is it a tech bubble? Yes and no. The actual technology markets being explored may well turn out to be a bubble, but to the extent that the investment is actually investment in people who will live out long careers in the sector, it is not. It is interesting to note that &ldquo;investing in people&rdquo; is so much the default mental model in the software industry that outliers such as Sequoia Capital, who consciously buck the trend, have to take pains to point out that they invest in markets and trends, not people or teams. In any other industry, this would go without saying. It is fairly clear, for instance, that the energy industry invests in promising energy markets and alternative-energy technology trends, not in energy experts. In other industries, investing in people is the exceptional strategy (such as Zappos in the shoe industry or Southwest in the airline industry). One reason this is the case is that software development talent is incredibly hard to assess upfront, and its value can be highly situation-dependent, which means intake volumes and intra-industry churn have to be high (since a potential star may not flourish in your environment). People risks are high enough that developing capabilities to deal with it becomes central to success. Traditional front-end mechanisms, such as universities, are not particularly good at creating or even spotting and nurturing star developer talent. To the point that industry luminaries like Peter Thiel are, rather mischievously, offering to pay truly talented developers to drop out of college and go the startup route instead. Another reason is that software skills are the most portable high-end skills on the planet. Spotting and temporarily attracting talent doesn&rsquo;t mean you get to keep it. Stock option-slavery and golden handcuffs for talent from acquired companies aside, there&rsquo;s not much you can do to combat social and economic mobility. Not only can software developers switch industries easily, they can even survive on their own much more easily. A nuclear engineer really cannot do much without nuclear reactors or bombs to work with. A biochemist needs a lab and a phalanx of lawyers who know how to deal with the FDA. A software developer on the other hand, can float free on the Internet, making money in mercenary ways, with no deep loyalties, if he/she so desires. Until the Internet shuts down, no other profession comes close in terms of the mobility it grants to those skilled in it.\r\n\r\n<p>But the most important reason is the 10x phenomenon.</p>\r\nThe thing is, software talent is extraordinarily nonlinear. It even has a name: the 10x engineer (the colloquial idea, originally due to Frederick Brooks, that a good programmer isn&rsquo;t just marginally more productive than an average one, but an order of magnitude more productive). In software, leverage increases exponentially with expertise due to the very nature of the technology. While other domains exhibit 10x dynamics, nowhere is it as dominant as in software. What&rsquo;s more, while other industries have come up with systems to (say) systematically use mediocre chemists or accountants in highly leveraged ways, the software industry hasn&rsquo;t. It&rsquo;s still a kind of black magic. One big reason is that other industries turn x&rsquo;ers into 10xers primarily using software tools (a mechanical engineer equipped with CAD software suddenly becomes a 10x mechanical engineer). While the world is full of tools that software engineers have built for themselves, the 10x phenomenon, and the industry&rsquo;s reliance on it, doesn&rsquo;t seem to get engineered or managed away. Because the 10xers keep inventing new tools for themselves to stay 10xers. This means that employment levels have to be higher, while 10xers are being discovered and put to good use.\r\n\r\n<p>Risk Management in Software Talent Investment</p>\r\nOn the flip side &mdash; and this doesn&rsquo;t have a name, perhaps it should be called the &ldquo;-10x effect&rdquo; &mdash; bad software developers aren&rsquo;t just a minor drag or inefficiency. For a variety of subtle reasons, they can be catastrophically toxic in a complex software system. A bad engineer writing dangerously buggy or ill-conceived software can create a ticking time-bomb that will cost thousands of times the original investment to clean up after, once it explodes. What&rsquo;s more, the clean-up effort will absorb the talents of many more good developers for a longer period of time. By contrast, incompetence and bad errors in domains like aerospace engineering are relatively more visible and easy to catch and fix early, before the costs escalate. Delayed crises (such as an aircraft model that develops a critical safety issue late in its career) are also much easier to contain, isolate and fix. The Y2K crisis wasn&rsquo;t even due to bad engineering. It was merely due to mediocre and pragmatic engineering. Imagine what bad engineering at the heart of today&rsquo;s software systems can cost to fix over decades. Worse, imagine the impact of talented 10xers who turn to the Dark Side (i.e., consciously turn into -100xers). Or good guys who leave backdoors open in systems they build, as insurance policies. The result is that investing in developer capital isn&rsquo;t just about hiring programmers and sorting them by talent. It is about sorting and allocating them into risk classes. Traditional talent managers simply don&rsquo;t think in terms of risk management and investment when it comes to human capital. If they are not thinking of human capital in purely commodity terms, they are at best thinking of it in terms of deterministic cost/benefit terms. A typical hiring manager will say things like &ldquo;the hiring costs for a position is equivalent to six months of the salary you plan to pay.&rdquo; This sort of book-keeping logic simply does not work for software engineers. Big software companies don&rsquo;t think this way. They manage sorting based on both talent and risk, and at the level of the entire industry and individual careers, rather than at the level of employment relationships. How do they do this?\r\n\r\n<p>The Lifecycle of Software Talent</p>\r\nFirst, big software companies invest very early in a large volume of prospects, by offering development tools and environments that can short-circuit the education system and snare talent as early as possible. Next, they keep the talent hooked via contests, scholarships, innovative internship models (such as Google&rsquo;s Summer of Code) and other pre-work-life mechanisms all the way through college. Then they hire a large number, watch performance and sort the talent based on the potential for returns and risk. They have to offer great buffets of course, but in addition, they have to build in incompetence insurance mechanisms to manage the damage bad software engineers can do. They have to invest in technologies (such as Google with Python) with an eye on talent rather than the marketplace. The relationship doesn&rsquo;t stop with employment. The software talent is so valuable that you pretty much have to set up open ecosystems (based on APIs, access to valuable data resources like mapping data, and open source elements) so you can keep them hooked to your broader technology universe even after they leave. An ex-Microsoft engineer is valuable anywhere in the economy if he voices support for buying Microsoft wherever he goes. As a developer ages, and finds it harder and harder to switch technologies, at some point, he or she is considered hooked for the rest of their natural lives to some technology &mdash; Java or C++ or the Facebook API say &mdash; that they can be expected to grow old with. When a technology hits that point of maturity, talent that&rsquo;s hooked to it starts getting devalued along with falling retention costs. The buffets become skimpier, compensation drops, churn is lowered, and the talent retires into the sunset with the technology. It&rsquo;s quite poignant really, like a crew going down with a ship. There are two exceptions to this end-of-life rule for software engineers and their ships. The really talented ones retain an evergreen ability to reinvent themselves around the latest, youngest technology layer, seemingly at will. The other exception is the Big Crisis exception. If a time-bomb planted by an incompetent in an old geological layer of software suddenly goes off, causing earthquakes that ripple up through newer layers, the grizzled veterans may find a sudden new market for their skills (we saw a little of that with Y2K, but fixing that mess didn&rsquo;t require much talent; one can conceive of more critical failures that will require getting retired heroes and heroines out of retirement, Armageddon style, to fix things). In other words, you not only have to start relationships with kids, you have to provide security and quality of life for the low-risk types who want houses, kids and great school districts, and an entrepreneurial opportunity space for those who itch to throw off managerial shackles and make their own way in the world. You have to cater to both risk-averse and gambler types. And you have to find ways to gracefully put the veterans out to pasture in much kinder (and more expensive) ways than in other fields, because they just might turn into your insurance policy if things blow up. Though this isn&rsquo;t yet an important dynamic, as the Boomers retire, and take with them a lot of knowledge of early geological layers of the software-eaten planet, managing risk around old software will turn into a major business. When the last veterans of the earliest still-in-use software layers start to die, we will be in historically unprecedented territory. If you pull all this off successfully, as a large software company, an investment in a young person at age 12 will yield returns for you throughout their lives, whether or not they work for you directly. They will start out as pure investments, start yielding dividends by age 18 or so, return your investment by age 30, provide business model insurance as your company matures (a major reason Java is still relevant, for instance, is that there is a ton of talent still invested in it), and eventually turn into crisis insurance policies (this by the way, is the &ldquo;flow&rdquo; you have to manage, as opposed to a &ldquo;stock&rdquo; of employees on your bench). Speaking of history, let&rsquo;s put all this in perspective for non-software-industry types who still don&rsquo;t understand just how epochal the birth of the software industry is for the rest of the economy.\r\n\r\n<p>Year 43 of Software Eating the World</p>\r\nAs Alan Kay, a major pioneer of today&rsquo;s software-eaten planet, pointed out recently, the Internet doesn&rsquo;t have stop, shut down, or rewind buttons. Once it was turned on, history was essentially rebooted. Software began eating away at the pre-software layers of civilization on the planet, and depositing software-infused layers instead. One of these days, we&rsquo;ll recognize the enormous significance of what&rsquo;s going on and replace the BC/AD distinction with BI/AI (Before Internet/After Internet), with January 1, Year 0 reset to October 29, 1969, the day the Internet was turned on (if you want to start right, 2012 is actually Year 43, AI). And yes, this time, there will be a Year 0, if programmers have anything to do with it. Which brings us to David Kirpatrick&rsquo;s now famous line that every company is now a software company. We are only just beginning to understand how software is now the core function of every company, no matter what it makes or what service it actually provides. So far, the rest of the economy has managed to live off whatever talent the software industry itself cannot soak up (for reasons ranging from talent not wanting to move to California to talent being interested in things other than software itself). In most non-software companies, developers have so far accepted a sort of second-class-citizen status despite their increasing scarcity and increasingly critical roles. That is about to change. As every company starts to re-organize around a recognition of the criticality of software to its business model, cataclysimic changes will ripple through the economy. To the extent that the growth of the base of software talent cannot keep up with demand, companies and entire industry sectors will start to collapse as they fail to adequately fuel their need for software talent. Those that survive will find themselves increasingly beholden to those with large amounts of developer capital. To the extent that you cannot run your own IT, Microsoft will run it for you. Even your non-software employees will effectively be controlled by the likes of Google, Apple and Facebook, who will set the bar for employee expectations via the direct-to-consumer software markets (this is the much-discussed &ldquo;consumerization of IT&rdquo; meme). Can the non-software sector compete at all? It&rsquo;s hard, but not impossible. The biggest bargaining chip other industries have is data. To fight the consumerization-of-IT force that comes in with your employees, and the Microsoftening of your business model that comes in via the IT department, your one weapon is access to data that is not about software. I&rsquo;ll write more about that another day. If you don&rsquo;t know how to use that one weapon you do possess, it will get taken away from you (the cartography, movie, music, news, publishing and restaurant retail industries have already learned this the hard way).\r\n\r\n<p>The View from the Talent Side</p>\r\nNobody likes being a commodity in a meat market, even as a highly valued 10x prime cut. If and when a human being who is also a valuable capital asset clues up about their his/her economic role, resistance begins. Software developers are smart. By and large the vast majority clue up, and do so relatively early. The clueless 10x developer who gets traded around with as little friction as stocks or cash is rare indeed. If you find one, resist the urge to exploit him/her for immediate gain, and invest in getting them clued up instead. You&rsquo;ll secure vastly more value in the form of relationship capital that way. The natural reaction that forms once a good developer recognizes his/her own value is to turn to either an individualist-mercenary mindset or a collectivist guild-like mindset. The individualists turn into hard bargainers as they carefully probe their own market value and frequently re-negotiate relationships. They carefully invest in keeping their skill-base current and avoiding being shunted into the sunset end of the ecosystem for as long as possible. This sort of developer likes to hedge bets, stay invested in multiple projects and keep one foot in the open source world at all times. They position themselves for massive upsides when that is a possibility, and the ability to walk away from failures with their own reputations intact where there is real risk. There is a reason star mercenary technical talent is the asset that gets sold fastest in a fire-sale when a startup crashes. There is a mad scramble for a CTO who successfully manages to blame the business end for the failure. The other kind of developer turns to guild-like structures, which serve as centers of balance-of-power politics in the constant wars against the developer-capitalists. Except that instead of taking on the dynamics of class warfare along an upper-lower dimension, the conflict takes the form of exit warfare along an inside-outside dimension. Rather than form a union to negotiate with management, the talented developer will simply exit a situation he/she does not like, and use guild-like resources to move to a better situation. Stock options are simply not as effective in limiting mobility as the power of Russian nobility to whip serfs into immobility once was. The result is a precarious balance of power between developers and developer-capitalists, and a cyclic center-periphery flow of developer-capital, as individual developers take themselves in and out of circulation. The result is a new kind of economics: Welcome to the world of Developeronomics.</blockquote>\r\n', '<p>Earlier this month, Forbes&#39; contributor Venkatesh Rao published an interesting column at Forbes.com titled, &quot;The Rise of Developeronomics&quot;...</p>\r\n', '<p>Earlier this month, Forbes&#39; contributor Venkatesh Rao published an interesting column at Forbes.com titled, &quot;The Rise of Developeronomics&quot;...</p>\r\n', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/hackerprenomics-the-forbes-article', 'investments1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2011-12-13', '2011-12-13 15:00:00', 1, '2011-12-13 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(9, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Introducing Continuous Integration', 'introducing-continuous-integration', '<p>I finally sat down this week, cleared my head, closed my screens, and started reading the PDF.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It didn&rsquo;t take long to realize that CI = money. For site owners and consultants &mdash; really!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jenkins, the CI server, is FOSS. It&rsquo;s free! Anyone can download it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Page 32 in the PDF (<a href=\"http://www.wakaleo.com/books/jenkins-the-definitive-guide\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.wakaleo.com/books/jenkins-the-definitive-guide</a>):</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Continuous Integration &hellip; is a real game changer&hellip; [as] it radically alters<br />\r\nthe way teams think about the whole development process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A good Continous Integration infrastructure can:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>streamline the development process right through to deployment;</li>\r\n	<li>help detect and fix bugs faster;</li>\r\n	<li>provide a useful project dashboard for both developers and non-developers;</li>\r\n	<li>ultimately,&nbsp;<strong>deliver more real business value to the end user</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s more!</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>In essence, Continuous Integration is&nbsp;<strong>about reducing risk</strong>&nbsp;by:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>faster feedback &mdash; identify and fix integration and regression issues faster, resulting insmoother, quicker delivery, and fewer bugs;</li>\r\n	<li>better visibility for technical and non-technical team members on the state of the project;</li>\r\n	<li>automating the deployment process &mdash; get your software into the hands of the testers and the end users faster, more reliably, and with less effort.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>CI will be a continuous topic!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>I finally sat down this week, cleared my head, closed my screens, and started reading the PDF...</p>\r\n', '<p>I finally sat down this week, cleared my head, closed my screens, and started reading the PDF...</p>\r\n', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/introducing-continuous-integration', 'jenkins-cover-small.png', 1, 0, 0, '2011-12-23', '2011-12-23 15:00:00', 1, '2011-12-23 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(10, 0, NULL, NULL, 'The Birth of LaSalleMart', 'the-birth-of-lasallemart', '<p>The birth of LaSalleMart, a fork of Tienda, announced on my 44th &ldquo;The Bob Bloom&rdquo; podcast.One of the more heavily edited shows, better to hear the MP3 than read the transcript.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2012/tbbs44\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2012/tbbs44</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A good podcast to read (and hear!) is the podcast previous to it, &ldquo;Hackerprenomics with Rastin and Ash of Anahita&rdquo; at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2011/tbbs44\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2011/tbbs43</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>The birth of LaSalleMart, a fork of Tienda, announced on my 44th &ldquo;The Bob Bloom&rdquo; podcast.One of the more heavily edited shows, better to hear the MP3 than read the transcript...</p>\r\n', '<p>The birth of LaSalleMart, a fork of Tienda, announced on my 44th &ldquo;The Bob Bloom&rdquo; podcast.One of the more heavily edited shows, better to hear the MP3 than read the transcript...</p>\r\n', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/the-birth-of-lasallemart', 'lasallemart_logo_lg.png', 1, 0, 0, '2012-01-09', '2012-01-09 15:00:00', 1, '2012-01-09 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(11, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart: There’s a Secret Sauce', 'lasallemart-theres-a-secret-sauce', '<p>There is a huge opportunity open to site owners and consultants, now that we are developing our own Joomla ecommerce software.There are opportunities to open up development by controlling the software development process &amp; infrastructure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s not just the code, it&rsquo;s the process &amp; infrastructure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is one aspect of the infrastructure that is the &ldquo;secret sauce&rdquo;: the Jenkins &ldquo;Continuous Integration&rdquo; server.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yup, eye glazing stuff. But there&rsquo;s nothing about putting money into your pockets, eh? About growing your revenue, eh!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>With Jenkins, we can finally stop thinking of software releases as one big huge Joomla installable ZIP file.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>We can create different versions simultaneously.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Imagine, every time we release a new LaSalleMart, a Canadian version is created automatically. Canadian-only taxes pre-set, Canadian-only shipping and payment methods included, geo-codes pre-set.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Imagine we released a California version of LaSalleMart. Illinois-only. Florida-only. EU-only.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We can even create full Joomla versions too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Even better, we could create &ldquo;White Label&rdquo; versions, with Members&rsquo; logos, RSS feeds, contact info in the Joomla &amp; LaSalleMart dashboards.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Controlling the code means controlling the software dev process &amp; infrastructure.<strong>Controlling the software dev process &amp; infrastructure means we can fashion &lsquo;em in a way that suits our purposes</strong>, not just an extension developer&rsquo;s purposes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jenkins is not exactly new. It&rsquo;s not exactly old either. But, its cloud version is new, just a year old. And, in that year, they worked out the kinks. There&rsquo;s a basic free account for anyone. Open source projects are hosted for free!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My first 2012 podcast guest is the only person I know of who&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.gnomeontherun.com/blog/8-programming/68-j-and-beyond-presentation-continuous-integration\" target=\"_blank\">presented CI at a Joomla conference</a>, and in&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2012/tbbs46\" target=\"_blank\">Part Two</a>&nbsp;we talk about the critical role of Jenkins in his new Joomla Distro.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m thinking that open source may apply to the software development process as well as the code. It&rsquo;s going to take some hard effort along with trial-and-error to figure out how to do our specific builds on Jenkins. Sharing CI scripts and techniques will be as valuable as the code we are building, so I&rsquo;m thinking of posting them. In this way, we encourage the few that are using it for their Joomla projects to share their Jenkins goodies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are opportunities to maintain your websites without intervention. That is, without going to the Joomla Administrator to update Joomla-LaSalleMart. Imagine Joomla-LaSalle updates automated without intervention on your sites. Tie this in to your backup regimen while we&rsquo;re at it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jenkins opens the door to simultaneous development, where different (yet related) development occurs simultaneously. Instead of choosing just one generic way to do something, we can program different ways at the same time, and create different versions of LaSalleMart simultaneously. Again, taxes is a great example. Instead of programming some generic method to handle taxes, we just create different LaSalleMart versions for each tax jurisdiction. Boom, no need for tax plugins &mdash; deep in my heart, I really don&rsquo;t want my clients to see in the plugins listing &ldquo;Canadian Taxes&rdquo; anyways.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The only way to get the payoffs of the secret sauce &mdash; Jenkins Continuous Integration Server &mdash; is to control the code + software infrastructure + software development process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>There is a huge opportunity open to site owners and consultants, now that we are developing our own Joomla ecommerce software.There are opportunities to open up development by controlling the software development process &amp; infrastructure.&nbsp;It&rsquo;s not just the code, it&rsquo;s the process &amp; infrastructure...</p>\r\n', '<p>There is a huge opportunity open to site owners and consultants, now that we are developing our own Joomla ecommerce software.There are opportunities to open up development by controlling the software development process &amp; infrastructure.&nbsp;It&r', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-theres-a-secret-sauce', 'secret_sauce1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-01-13', '2012-01-13 15:00:00', 1, '2012-01-13 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(12, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Critical Lessons Learned from 2011', 'critical-lessons-learned-from-2011', '<p>There&rsquo;s one thing I can say for 2011: critical lessons were learned:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>my point-of-view and focus are strictly site owners &amp; consultants to site owners &mdash; not programmers;</li>\r\n	<li>every single risk that exists using GPL software is shouldered&nbsp;<em>solely</em>&nbsp;by the user;</li>\r\n	<li>the extreme reward for shouldering the extreme risk = controlling the code;</li>\r\n	<li>the&nbsp;<em>only</em>&nbsp;way to control the code is to wield the power;</li>\r\n	<li>if you lack the time, technical skill, resources to bring such skills in-house, then you need to form &mdash; or join an existing &mdash; &ldquo;Hackerpreneur&rdquo; club;</li>\r\n	<li>you use GPL code from other projects as Raw Material;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Rastin Mehr and Ash Sanieyan, Founders and Core Architects of the Anahita Social Engine, summarized key takeaways in their blog post &ldquo;<a href=\"http://blog.anahitapolis.com/2012/01/how-we-wrapped-up-2011/\" target=\"_blank\">How We Wrapped Up 2011</a>&ldquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>With the advent of Google+ and Google Hangout we decided to try answering some of our Premium Tribe member&rsquo;s questions during video chat sessions. Very quickly many people signed up to the point that we had to schedule 3 different sessions These sessions are completely unscripted wehere Anahita Premium Tribe members can ask us any questions on the spot and Ash and I do our best to answer them. These sessions are recorded and published with minimal editing as podcasts (Subscribe to the iTunes Feed here). We often start a session as a Q&amp;A formats, but when time allows, then they turn into round table discussions where we discuss different topics regarding Anahita, Community Management, Current affairs in the technology and social networking market in general. We have produced 3 episodes so far. The next episode will be published this Monday January the 16th. We would like to have a new episode every 2 weeks. Let&rsquo;s see how that goes.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Publishing a Hangout is a great way to communicate to the public what is happening inside Club Commerce &mdash; and an opportunity to hear my fabulous Members. Kudos to Rastin &amp; Ash!</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>&hellip;using a social networking environment to deliver service and support has clearly proven to be a superior option over support tickets and traditional discussion boards that are being used by many companies these days.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s not just the social networking environment, it&rsquo;s the attitude that goes with it. There&rsquo;s a connection with the code, the techies, and peers, that is consistently lost in ticket systems &amp; forums. My Discussion site uses Anahita, but more importantly, I&rsquo;ve absorbed the attitude.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ADDENDUM:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2012/tbbs51\" target=\"_blank\">April 26, 2012 podcast with Rastin &amp; Ash continus this theme</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>There&rsquo;s one thing I can say for 2011: critical lessons were learned...</p>\r\n', '<p>There&rsquo;s one thing I can say for 2011: critical lessons were learned...</p>\r\n', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/critical-lessons-learned-from-2011', 'anahita.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-01-17', '2012-01-17 15:00:00', 1, '2012-01-17 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(13, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Toronto Joomla User Group Meet-up, January 2012', 'toronto-joomla-user-group-meet-up-january-2012', '<p>(pics courtesy of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://plus.google.com/photos/117828494665989550744/albums/5699169416246598241?gpinv=AMIXal_27IBeLrvYO3n4PCMS_p-13H5kh5ySbFjBLMcOvv2jqM4LvMQBkfptTTY-tWw7m_ysFkLYsTBi_n_vuwQNNeup_DshM5FmEsx-N0Hw_oLUGp1OWH4\" target=\"_blank\">Alan Langford</a>)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Eight of us caught up on a pleasant evening in beautiful downtown Etobicoke. Weather could be worse in January.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Karoke starts at 9:00pm, whereupon we heard a badly mangled rendition of classic Johnny Cash:</p>\r\n\r\n<iframe width=\"420\" height=\"315\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/365q2CAGyTI\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\n<p>My first face-to-face discussion with Club Members Alan &amp; Joe about LaSalleMart.&nbsp;<a href=\"https://plus.google.com/102470627690820499884/photos?gpinv=AMIXal_27IBeLrvYO3n4PCMS_p-13H5kh5ySbFjBLMcOvv2jqM4LvMQBkfptTTY-tWw7m_ysFkLYsTBi_n_vuwQNNeup_DshM5FmEsx-N0Hw_oLUGp1OWH4\" target=\"_blank\">Ian MacLennan</a>&nbsp;was there, who is on the Joomla Platform project, which uses&nbsp;<a href=\"http://southlasallemedia.com/2012/tbbs46\" target=\"_blank\">Jenkins</a>. We had quite an after-meeting meeting!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Conversation touched on shopping at Staples, techno-babble, family push-back from over-volunteering, previous jobs, and referencing technologies that reveal our age.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>See everyone at Yorkville next month!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2012jan18_pic1.jpg\">\r\n', '<p>Eight of us caught up on a pleasant evening in beautiful downtown Etobicoke. Weather could be worse in January...</p>\r\n', '<p>Eight of us caught up on a pleasant evening in beautiful downtown Etobicoke. Weather could be worse in January...</p>\r\n', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/toronto-joomla-user-group-meet-up-january-2012', '2012jan11_jugt_1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-01-18', '2012-01-18 15:00:00', 1, '2012-01-18 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(14, 0, NULL, NULL, 'An Imperfect Understanding of Where Features Come From', 'an-imperfect-understanding-of-where-features-come-from', '<p>Within an hour of publishing my latest podcast, &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2012/lasallemart4\" target=\"_blank\">The Moneyball of Joomla ecommerce</a>&ldquo;, I received a tweet asking me why anyone would &ldquo;invest&rdquo; in my thing without a &ldquo;solid development plan&rdquo;.Listening to my &ldquo;Moneyball&rdquo; podcast, it&rsquo;s obvious that I&rsquo;m not looking at my Club Commerce/LaSalleMart conventionally. This is because convention has left us frustrated, yearning for code!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If we approach our own code development conventionally, then why will we avoid the ailments and pathologies we are seeking to avoid?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chapter 1, section 1.1 of &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2012/index.php?option=com_k2&amp;view=item&amp;id=67:introducing-continuous-integration\" target=\"_blank\">Jenkins: The Definitive Guide</a>&rdquo; opens:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>In fact it is a real game changer &ndash; when Continuous Integration is introduced into an organization, it radically alters the way teams think about the whole development process&hellip; going from a simple scheduled automated build right through to continuous delivery into production.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Circumventing the Joomla installer is a liberating idea. Using &ldquo;automated builds&rdquo; to created hundreds of simultaneous versions has a lot of value. Thinking of software development as &ldquo;upstream&rdquo; and &ldquo;downstream&rdquo; processes opens up a lot of value.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My original idea was to run a club of Tienda clients, so my clients could share the costs of common modifications. The software development process extended to maintaining a custom Distro of Tienda. Since the only one working on this Distro was, essentially, just me, what process did we need? Much time was spent on Live Update, so my clients can effortlessly grab the latest and greatest version.<br />\r\nWell, here we are, at what is the logical conclusion of our journey: that we have to be in the Joomla extension business. We have to create/maintain our own Joomla ecommerce software. This is an entirely different proposition than being in the modifications business.<br />\r\nThe last thing I want to do is recreate the problems my clients and I are escaping &ndash; principally, vapourware. So, if a &ldquo;solid development plan&rdquo; means &ldquo;tell me when your features will be released&rdquo;, then I don&rsquo;t see the point.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Furthermore, our list of features is vast. Practically bottomless. We are starved for features. It&rsquo;s one thing to be the &ldquo;mouse on the wheel&rdquo; for a finite amount of customizations; but, it&rsquo;s an entirely different thing faced with practically an infinite amount of programming using a ton of programmers for a wide spectrum of site owners and consultants. The question is not &ldquo;what&rdquo; and &ldquo;when&rdquo;. The real question is &ldquo;how&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Researching &ldquo;how&rdquo; unearthed surprises. There is a world of opportunity in the &ldquo;how&rdquo;. The &ldquo;how&rdquo; is where the real value is. As consultants and site owners, we can customize the &ldquo;how&rdquo; to suit our purposes. The right to change the code has led us to owning our software development process. Which leads us to Continuous Integration, which is involves testing and building. It is the building that we will blaze a trail.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Within an hour of publishing my latest “The Moneyball of Joomla ecommerce“ podcast, I received a tweet asking me why anyone would “invest” in my thing without a “solid development plan”...', 'Within an hour of publishing my latest “The Moneyball of Joomla ecommerce“ podcast, I received a tweet asking me why anyone would “invest” in my thing without a “solid development plan”...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/an-imperfect-understanding-of-where-features-come-from', 'moneyball1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-02-11', '2012-02-11 15:00:00', 1, '2012-02-11 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(15, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Toronto Joomla User Group Meet-up: February 2012', 'toronto-joomla-user-group-meet-up-february-2012', '<p>So caught up in the discussions, I forgot to take a picture.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Doug, Joe, Alan, Zach, Andrew and Yours Truly upstairs at the Yorkville Duke. Good to meet Joe&rsquo;s son pre-meet-up. Guelph, Whitby, Richmond Hill outnumbered the 416 contingent.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All but Doug are Founding Members of my Club Commerce. But we did not talk much about LaSalleMart, which was good. It was more wide ranging, including a discussion about NASA, legacy programming languages, Joomla&rsquo;s history, the JED, and projects currently engaged.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I asked about upgrading from Joomla 1.5 to 2.5 and appreciate the answers &mdash; thank you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joe had specific problems that we talked about, which led to a discussion about the idiosyncracies of individual extensions. Especially when it comes to templating &amp; views.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Look forward to the March meet-up. Details at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/index.php?option=com_k2&amp;view=item&amp;id=85:toronto-joomla-user-group-meet-up-february-2012\" target=\"_blank\">http://toronto.joomla.ca</a>.</p>\r\n', 'Doug, Joe, Alan, Zach, Andrew and Yours Truly upstairs at the Yorkville Duke. Good to meet Joe’s son pre-meet-up. Guelph, Whitby, Richmond Hill outnumbered the 416 contingent...\r\n                        ', '                        ', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/toronto-joomla-user-group-meet-up-february-2012', 'jugt-cn-logo.png', 1, 0, 0, '2012-02-15', '2012-02-15 15:00:00', 1, '2012-02-15 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(16, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Late Night Thoughts on LaSalleMart', 'late-night-thoughts-on-lasallemart', '<p>I caught the &ldquo;Scarborough Fair&rdquo; scene in The Graduate today, as Dustin Hoffman is driving across the Golden Gate Bridge. With the Academy Awards coming up, Oscar winning movies are de rigour this month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That long drive over the bridge summed up my feeling today as I dug into Jenkins and builds. A long journey over a very long bridge high above the water. It&rsquo;s not as if I&rsquo;m going to make a u-turn, or swerve to the side.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/7Y_EMhWIcy4?rel=0&amp;start=236\" width=\"640\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>That long drive over the bridge summed up my feeling today as I dug into Jenkins and builds. A long journey over a very long bridge high above the water. It&rsquo;s not as if I&rsquo;m going to make a u-turn, or swerve to the side.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you think CSS is mind-numbing, then you&rsquo;re really going to glaze-eye on me about software builds. It is uber-geeky. There is no pretense that a non-techie will use it. It&rsquo;s a journey into geek-land.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Surveying the dev@Cloud Jenkins service, I asked myself &ldquo;What the hell am I doing?&rdquo;. I&rsquo;ve had no occassion to get into this stuff &rsquo;til now, so what am I doing here? Can this really be the Moneyball of Joomla ecommerce?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ladies and gentlemen, it really is the Moneyball of Joomla ecommerce. This is where the techies see real value. This is techie stuff created by techies for techies for the express purpose of creating value in the development process. It&rsquo;s to make things easier, to avoid doing repetitive tasks, to reduce bugs, to increase the quality of the code, to deploy code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The thing is, it&rsquo;s a techie thing. The last thing this part of the techie world expects is &ldquo;users&rdquo;. But that&rsquo;s exactly what we are doing. We, site owners and consultants, are driving our Alfa Romeo&rsquo;s across that great bridge into the golden roadway to RoI. They are not expecting us there, where the shock on the faces of the techies will be clear on their faces. The last thing they expect here are users from the wrong side of the bridge usurping the very technology that creates immense value for their software development process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like many tools of the trade, these tools are FOSS. The Jenkins Server is licenced under the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.opensource.org/licenses/mit-license.php\" target=\"_blank\">MIT Licence</a>:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Permission is hereby granted, free of charge, to any person obtaining a copy of this software and associated documentation files (the &ldquo;Software&rdquo;), to deal in the Software without restriction, including without limitation the rights to use, copy, modify, merge, publish, distribute, sublicense, and/or sell copies of the Software&hellip;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Jenkins is available for free to anyone and everyone. It needs&nbsp;<em>a lot</em>&nbsp;of elbow grease though!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Continuous Integration technology used by lowly &ldquo;users&rdquo;, put together by lowly &ldquo;users&rdquo;, for the benefit of lowly &ldquo;users&rdquo;, is the heart of unlocking RoI for us.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And what I thought as I went travelled through software build technology, having crossed the bridge, was that this is a land that we have to live in. And, by living in it, there really is no border between &ldquo;extension purveyor&rdquo; and &ldquo;user&rdquo;. We are in the extension business, even though we are &ldquo;users&rdquo;. So, from code origination to our individual production websites, it&rsquo;s one big integrated process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I thought that the demarcation between &ldquo;upstream&rdquo; and &ldquo;downstream&rdquo; in the software development process is that point where it crosses into the individual website. Ah, but we are the extension purveyor! So, it&rsquo;s moot. We are Vertically Integrated. We are engaged in all aspects of the software development process. Origination, testing, building, deploying&hellip; there&rsquo;s no &ldquo;they&rdquo;. It&rsquo;s all &ldquo;we&rdquo; now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You know, it takes my breath away. Controlling the code, which is the underlying premise of the GPL, is just part of it. To truly control the code, you have to hold the software development process in the palm of your hand. That means crossing the bridge into geek-land for Continous Integration, the soul of the software development process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Github.com does not release software!&nbsp;<a href=\"http://scottchacon.com/2011/08/31/github-flow.html\" target=\"_blank\">They deploy continuously, daily</a>:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>We don&rsquo;t really have &ldquo;releases&rdquo; because we deploy to production every day &ndash; often several times a day. We can do so through our chat room robot, which is the same place our CI results are displayed. We try to make the process of testing and shipping as simple as possible so that every employee feels comfortable doing it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a number of advantages to deploying so regularly. If you deploy every few hours, it&rsquo;s almost impossible to introduce large numbers of big bugs. Little issues can be introduced, but then they can be fixed and redeployed very quickly. Normally you would have to do a &lsquo;hotfix&rsquo; or something outside of the normal process, but it&rsquo;s simply part of our normal process &ndash; there is no difference in the GitHub flow between a hotfix and a very small feature.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another advantage of deploying all the time is the ability to quickly address issues of all kinds. We can respond to security issues that are brought to our attention or implement small but interesting feature requests incredibly quickly, yet we can use the exact same process to address those changes as we do to handle normal or even large feature development. It&rsquo;s all the same process and it&rsquo;s all very simple.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Hotfix is really a Very Small Feature? Well, there is a true understanding where ecommerce profits come from! Profits come from features. Features come from code. That code must actually exist and reside &mdash; and work! &mdash; on your website. Your focus should be on buying revenue; and, in order for you to buy revenue, you buy features. To buy features, you buy code. Moneyball: You don&rsquo;t buy players, you should be buying wins. And to buy wins, you need to buy runs. Value is not planning or having star programmers, which are over-valued (Alan will disagree). Value is having real code working for real on your actual website. No technology, no profit! Deploying every day &mdash; it&rsquo;s a culture shock!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The implications! If you deploy everyday, then do you run big massive discrete projects? Wouldn&rsquo;t we be running a continuous stream of small projects? Wouldn&rsquo;t we want to run a ton of concurrent small projects? We&rsquo;d have to find a way to start and finish projects, as we&rsquo;d be starting and concluding projects all the time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Theoretically, at least, revenue from the sites under our purview would be growing incrementally, as features were added incrementally every day. A portion of this growing revenue would be, theoretically, re-invested into software development, resulting in more features that create more revenue.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the things I learned at tonight&rsquo;s Toronto Joomla meet-up is that there&rsquo;s some Continuous Integration skill amongst my Founding Members.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We really are crossing the bridge. No u-turns, no swerving. The technology techies rely on to impart value to their software development process: here we come!</p>\r\n', 'I caught the “Scarborough Fair” scene in The Graduate today, as Dustin Hoffman is driving across the Golden Gate Bridge. With the Academy Awards coming up, Oscar winning movies are de rigour this month. That long drive over the bridge summed up my feeling today as I dug into Jenkins and builds. A long journey over a very long bridge high above the water. It’s not as if I’m going to make a u-turn, or swerve to the side...\r\n                        ', '', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/late-night-thoughts-on-lasallemart', 'the_graduate_alfa_romeo.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-02-15', '2012-02-15 15:00:00', 1, '2012-02-15 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(17, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Testing: Value Galore', 'testing-value-galore', '<blockquote>\r\n<p>Automated testing is a key technology being incorporated into the workings of the Joomla Bug Squad. At the present, this is a somewhat<strong>specialized skill</strong>&hellip;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>(<a href=\"http://docs.joomla.org/Automated_Testing_Team\" target=\"_blank\">http://docs.joomla.org/Automated_Testing_Team</a>)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Specialized, indeed!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is no glory in testing. There is no glamour in testing. But, there is tremendous value in testing. And extracting that value is what attracts us to testing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Testing is a major PITA. It&rsquo;s easier to be casual about it. The problem with casual is that your live site becomes one huge test facility. Live sites cannot be fully simulated in tests, but doing as much testing as possible before the code hits your live site increases your chances of enjoying a smooth running, money-making live site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As Alan Langford told me, it takes time and effort to set up testing. You have to code so that your code is test-able. The reward is two-fold: quality increases hugely which reduces your operational risk; and, subsequent testing becomes easier as the initial testing set-up is done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since testing is not glamourous, is not glorious, is usually thankless, and delays code getting to market, it&rsquo;s not only glossed over but it&rsquo;s a skill that only a subset of programmers have. Indeed, a &ldquo;somewhat specialized skill&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>As of February 2010, a tests folder has been added to the Joomla! SVN download. This folder contains a growing library of unit and system (or functional) tests. The unit tests use PHPUnit and the system tests use PHPUnit and Selenium. The unit tests perform tests primarily on the Joomla! framework. The Selenium system tests actually run Joomla! from a browser and test it as a user would.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://docs.joomla.org/Running_Automated_Tests_for_Version_1.6\" target=\"_blank\">http://docs.joomla.org/Running_Automated_Tests_for_Version_1.6</a>x</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Hmmm, does this mean that such testing was not part of Joomla 1.0 &amp; Joomla 1.5? The implication is that the value of such testing is recognized to exceed its costs only recently. Regardless of when this recognition occurred, we should take the hint at Club Commerce!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I cannot emphasize enough that controlling the software development process offers massive RoI. Open source software gives us the right to control the code. But the huge value resides in the development process. That&rsquo;s the &ldquo;Moneyball&rdquo; aspect &mdash; the conventional wisdom is that the value is with the code. But the true value is the development process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With a testing regimen, we can hire a ton of different programmers for a ton of different projects. The programmers code, and then we run their code through our tests. Code that passes is integrated into our codebase.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We need an explosion of features. So, our software development process must allow us to program an explosion of features. Up-front investment in testing allows us to achieve an explosion of testing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Testing is a road less travelled, but rich in value. The Jenkins Server is mostly about testing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I had no idea how deeply Alan Langford, a Founding Member, is involved with testing:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Ground work on the implementation of unit testing has been done by Enno Klasing during the Summer of Code 2007 project and has been&nbsp;<strong>perfected by Alan Langford</strong>&nbsp;from the Joomla! Development Team.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://docs.joomla.org/index.php?title=Development_Working_Group&amp;oldid=62385\" target=\"_blank\">http://docs.joomla.org/index.php?title=Development_Working_Group&amp;oldid=62385</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is going to make your eyes glaze over:<a href=\"http://permalink.gmane.org/gmane.comp.php.pear.devel/43667\" target=\"_blank\">http://permalink.gmane.org/gmane.comp.php.pear.devel/43667</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last week, after we&nbsp;<a href=\"http://southlasallemedia.com/2012/tbbs47\" target=\"_blank\">recorded our &ldquo;The Bob Bloom Show&rdquo; interview</a>, we chatted for a half hour about LaSalleMart and testing. Alan agreed to do a special one-on-one podcast on testing and LaSalleMart, which we&rsquo;ll do in March. What prompted this post-show interview was something Alan said off-the-cuff at the recent Toronto Joomla meet-up about testing &mdash; which had nothing to do with Club Commerce or LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Testing is something I did in a former life as a Business Analyst. Use-case testing, mostly, where you dream up phony numbers, manually calculate what the computer is supposed to spit out, then see if the system actually outputs those numbers. Well, we can do &ldquo;use case&rdquo; testing in automated tests, saving the hassle of foisting it onto end users.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, we have a valuable testing skill-set here at Club Commerce. As much as I yearn for all the pet projects that are piling on already to be coded, I am going to devote myself to constructing the test environment. If this takes a couple of months, so be it, because the payoff is massive. We are going to be leaders in testing and Continuous Integration, with the payoff being the ability to accomodate an explosion of features &mdash; and getting this quality code to your sites so you can make money with these features.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s going to be very interesting, and exciting, to put other extensions through our testing before you install them on your site. This is completely in keeping with the idea that GPL software is Raw Material.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m rushing this blog post, because I want to squeeze it in before publishing my already-late&nbsp;<a href=\"http://southlasallemedia.com/2012/lasallemart5\" target=\"_blank\">February Hangout podcast</a>. So a few observations&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In order to bring an explosion of features to your live site, we need a software development process that accomodates a massive amount of programming.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This software development process, by definition, cannot be like the process other extension purveyors use &mdash; because those processes have left us yearning for features.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If the road well travelled has left us frustrated, then the road less travelled is where the pot of gold is.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most people do not like to travel on the roads less travelled.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My Club Commerce is for site owners and consultants who realize they need to travel on the road less travelled. With 140 memberships available, this is not a mass marketed club.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The &ldquo;Moneyball&rdquo; attitude leads us to probe where the value really resides. We identify where the value really resides; and, then we become skilled at these things that build value.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Believe it or not, we&rsquo;ve concluded that coding is over-rated!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The software development process is where the value is. And, the soul of value is Continuous Integration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Continuous Integration = test + build.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Testing is a &ldquo;somewhat specialized skill&rdquo; &mdash; relatively few coders are skilled at testing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Build&rdquo; has led us to the shocking conclusion of abandoning the Joomla installer!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Fallacy of the One Big Zip file!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We have a surprising competency in testing at Club Commerce. The Toronto Joomla Group, of which we participate, has an unusual competency in testing. So, Club Commerce will be a leader in testing; and, in building ( = Continuous Integration).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, despite an initial up-front investment of time/effort creating a CI environment, the payoff will be an explosion of features for you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a lot of programmers. Hiring programmers should be easy. We will need money to hire programmers to code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Club Commerce is a funding model to hire programmers!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s an article about GitHub.com called &ldquo;Lord of the Files&rdquo; (clever!) at<a href=\"http://m.wired.com/wiredenterprise/2012/02/github/all/1\" target=\"_blank\">http://m.wired.com/wiredenterprise/2012/02/github/all/1</a>. My favourite quotes: &ldquo;They weren&rsquo;t the only developers chafing under that Trusted Gatekeeper model of open source&rdquo;, and &ldquo;It&rsquo;s the startup&rsquo;s outright hostility toward corporate command-and-control that really sets it apart&hellip; yet it&rsquo;s the most productive software development team he&rsquo;s ever worked on,&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My favourite quote from an article about how GitHub.com&rsquo;s software development,<a href=\"http://scottchacon.com/2011/08/31/github-flow.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://scottchacon.com/2011/08/31/github-flow.html</a>&nbsp;is, &ldquo;we deploy all the time&hellip; We don&rsquo;t really have &lsquo;releases&rsquo; because we deploy to production every day &ndash; often several times a day&rdquo;. Yikes! How&rsquo;s that for &ldquo;continuous&rdquo;? No version numbers!</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n', '                            \r\nThere is no glory in testing. There is no glamour in testing. But, there is tremendous value in testing. And extracting that value is what attracts us to testing...', '                            \r\nThere is no glory in testing. There is no glamour in testing. But, there is tremendous value in testing. And extracting that value is what attracts us to testing...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/testing-value-galore', 'binary_eyes.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-02-25', '2012-02-25 15:00:00', 1, '2012-02-25 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(18, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Jenkins Presentation and New Book', 'jenkins-presentation-and-new-book', '<p>Zach sent me the URL to a Jenkins presentation during our&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2012/lasallemart6\" target=\"_blank\">2-1/2 hour private Hangout</a>. I sent him the URL to a new book I found on Amazon called&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.amazon.ca/Integrating-Projects-Jenkins-Sebastian-Bergmann/dp/1449309437/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8\" target=\"_blank\">Integrating PHP Projects with Jenkins</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The presentation is called &ldquo;<a href=\"http://koansys.com/tech/jenkins/jenkins-ci-pdf/view\" target=\"_blank\">Continuous Integration using Jenkins</a>&ldquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This pdf is also&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/resources/pdf/continuous_integration_using_jenkins_presentation.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">on my site (9Mb)</a>, as is the pdf of &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/resources/pdf/jenkins-the-definitive-guide.pdf%20(400+%20pages,%2025Mb,%20read%20intro!)\" target=\"_blank\">The Definitive Guide to Jenkins</a>&ldquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Slide 13 took me by surprise by using the word&nbsp;<strong>&ldquo;Profit!&rdquo;</strong>. Slid that in there, eh! Read the slides after this one. This presentation is not for you, the site owner and consultant. It&rsquo;s for other programmers! This is where the value is, and it&rsquo;s not expected that non-technical people will exploit this technology because it&rsquo;s just too technical. What I notice is this presentation is a sell job to get programmers to use CI.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At some point, CI will be mainstream. We&rsquo;re not there yet, but we are on our way. We aren&rsquo;t waiting for CI to be mainstream, we are all over this thing now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using CI means doing Joomla differently. We&rsquo;re blazing this trail. It&rsquo;s called Leadership!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The book&rsquo;s author is described as:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>The computer scientist (Diplom-Informatiker) is a co-founder of thePHP.cc and a pioneer in the field of quality assurance in PHP projects. His testing framework, PHPUnit, is a de facto standard.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>I can&rsquo;t get over the comments!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s unfortunate, however, that the book is so brief, because much more detail could&rsquo;ve been provided about the way the tools are best used, especially the meaning of the different metrics included in the various static code analysis tools.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>I admit freely that I get frustrated many times by the needless fluff to tech books that appears to be added to books for additional page count. This book has been stripped of almost all fluff, and there needs to be some fluff to provide readers with padded surface to guide them through new information. Readers may benefit from reading the conclusion first.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Rushing a book to market to stake first claim to technical bona fides to bolster a consulting business? Maybe &mdash; I can be rather cynical.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To me, this is a nascent area that is growing: CI and PHP. Soon to be CI and Joomla. There is no book on this. We will write this book ourselves. What is different is that our point-of-view is site-owners, and not extension purveyors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As I said in my &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2012/index.php?option=com_k2&amp;view=item&amp;id=86:late-night-thoughts-on-lasallemart\" target=\"_blank\">Late Night Thoughts on LaSalleMart</a>&rdquo; post (with pic of Dustin Hoffman driving on the Golden Gate Bridge):</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Surveying the dev@Cloud Jenkins service, I asked myself &ldquo;What the hell am I doing?&rdquo;. I&rsquo;ve had no occassion to get into this stuff &rsquo;til now, so what am I doing here? Can this really be the Moneyball of Joomla ecommerce?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ladies and gentlemen, it&nbsp;<strong>really is the Moneyball of Joomla ecommerce</strong>. This is<strong>where the techies see real value</strong>. This is techie stuff created by techies for techies for the express purpose of creating value in the development process. It&rsquo;s to make things easier, to avoid doing repetitive tasks, to reduce bugs, to increase the quality of the code, to deploy code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The thing is, it&rsquo;s a techie thing.&nbsp;<strong>The last thing this part of the techie world expects is &ldquo;users&rdquo;. But that&rsquo;s exactly what we are doing. We, site owners and consultants, are driving our Alfa Romeo&rsquo;s across that great bridge into the golden roadway to RoI. They are not expecting us there, where the shock on the faces of the techies will be clear on their faces. The last thing they expect here are users from the wrong side of the bridge usurping the very technology that creates immense value for their software development process</strong></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Remember who told you about this, before it was fashionable!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Slide 13 took me by surprise by using the word “Profit!”. Slid that in there, eh! Read the slides after this one. This presentation is not for you, the site owner and consultant. It’s for other programmers! This is where the value is, and it’s not expected that non-technical people will exploit this technology because it’s just too technical. What I notice is this presentation is a sell job to get programmers to use CI...', 'Slide 13 took me by surprise by using the word “Profit!”. Slid that in there, eh! Read the slides after this one. This presentation is not for you, the site owner and consultant. It’s for other programmers! This is where the value is, and it’s not expecte', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/jenkins-presentation-and-new-book', 'jenkins_headshot.png', 1, 0, 0, '2012-03-15', '2012-03-15 12:00:00', 1, '2012-03-15 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(19, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Toronto Joomla Users Group Meet-up, March 2012', 'toronto-joomla-users-group-meet-up-march-2012', '<p>I want to take a moment to thank everyone who attended this evening&rsquo;s Toronto Joomla Users Group meet-up at Yonge/Sheppard.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Eight of us were there, from Vaughan, Richmond Hill, Toronto West, Guelph, Whitby, and downtown. Quite a distance spanned.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I don&rsquo;t know exactly how it happened, but tonight was one of the most satisfying JUGT experiences I&rsquo;ve had. Maybe it was the summer like weather, I don&rsquo;t know.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I had 4 distinct meetings tonight spanning 5-1/2 hours. Zach came down early and we huddled about LaSalleMart. Then a group of us talked about the state of Joomla ecommerce with an overview of the most popular extensions. Then Joe &amp; I caught up, while taking me on a tour of the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.ustream.tv/channel/joomla-chicago-south\" target=\"_blank\">South Chicago Joomla User Group ACL presentation</a>, with the Black Hawks/Canucks playing on the big screen &mdash; seemed symbolic! Then, some of us stuck around for the &ldquo;after-meeting&rdquo; talking about the Joomla project, JAB2012, and other tidbits. Lots of really good information.</p>\r\n', 'I want to take a moment to thank everyone who attended this evening’s Toronto Joomla Users Group meet-up at Yonge/Sheppard.\r\nEight of us were there, from Vaughan, Richmond Hill, Toronto West, Guelph, Whitby, and downtown. Quite a distance spanned...', 'I want to take a moment to thank everyone who attended this evening’s Toronto Joomla Users Group meet-up at Yonge/Sheppard.\r\nEight of us were there, from Vaughan, Richmond Hill, Toronto West, Guelph, Whitby, and downtown. Quite a distance spanned...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/toronto-joomla-users-group-meet-up-march-2012', '2012mar22_jugt_joe_sonne_alan_langford.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-03-20', '2012-03-20 12:00:00', 1, '2012-03-20 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(20, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Case Study of Why Users Banding Together is so Lucrative', 'case-study-of-why-users-banding-together-is-so-lucrative', '<p>Included on my to-do list this weekend is figuring out&nbsp;iDev Affiliate&nbsp;for a beloved client.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While banging my head against the wall with this thing, I realized here is a classic reason why us consultants and site owners banding together is so darn lucrative.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Way back when, my client wanted Virtuemart to track affiliates. Since VM does not have this feature, we needed a program, and chose iDev. When someone buys in VM, the thank you page throws off a URL to iDev, which then inserts a record into the idevaff_sales table.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>First of all, my client is paying $29.99USD per month for the hosting, which is just a reseller account. You can get the Hostgator &ldquo;Business&rdquo; hosting with SSL for $15USD/month. Or, just use your current Hostgator account, add-on a new domain, spend $50/year for SSL, and you have $250 left over. Now, this is not insignificant, you&rsquo;ll see!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>iDev is&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;open source. Nothing I did touched iDev. Instead, I used external PHP with CRON to modify the &ldquo;payment&rdquo; field in the &ldquo;idevaff_sale&rdquo; table. That is, I over-wrote the iDev commission calculations with my custom calculations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By the time we mess around on the margins of this program, we could have put that energy into a real commission program of our own. How many hours did it take me to figure out iDev, and how to run my own &ldquo;API&rdquo; script against the database? Lots. And, now, how much time have I spent investigating and testing a problem. The problem is the lack of usability of my handiwork, because there are no admin for what I did.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I spend 10 hours in total messing around, and instead we could have started our own affilate program. The time saved by not using someone else&rsquo;s reseller account, plus what I bill, plus what a few other Club Commerce Members chip in, and voila, we have $2,000.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are open source affiliate solutions out there, so we can modify what&rsquo;s there, or just absorb ideas. It would be very interesting to attach the payout features with the payment step in checkout &mdash; en route to making an ecomm platform of sorts, rather than each individual thing have all the elements of checkout. Anyways, the point is that there are open source affiliate software that can potentially save us time/money building our own custom affilate LaSalleMart solutions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Attaching this affilate solution to our Continuous Development process means we don&rsquo;t have to build all features all at once. As new features are in demand, we build those. Not for fWhile banging my head against the wall with this thing, I realized here is a classic reason why us consultants and site owners banding together is so darn lucrative.ree, new features need paid programmers. But, you got the basics and that provided RoI. Now, new incremental features bring incremental revenue.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But the thing that I am really trying to get across is that &ldquo;upstream&rdquo; modifications are brutally expensive. For what we spend on post-installation feature building, we could build our own thing from scratch, bring the bulk of development back &ldquo;downstream&rdquo;, have a bunch of people share the cost of development, and make more money.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For all the effort we are lavishing on an itty bitty piece of the affiliate software, we could have asked a bunch of people needing affiliate software to chip in top-up money and built a more powerful, more friendly, more relevant affiliate features. So there!</p>\r\n', 'While banging my head against the wall with this thing, I realized here is a classic reason why us consultants and site owners banding together is so darn lucrative.                     \r\n                        ', 'While banging my head against the wall with this thing, I realized here is a classic reason why us consultants and site owners banding together is so darn lucrative.                     \r\n                        ', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/case-study-of-why-users-banding-together-is-so-lucrative', 'united_states_dollar_bill1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-03-25', '2012-03-25 12:00:00', 1, '2012-03-25 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(21, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Imagine No Software Releases, It’s Easy If You Try [song]', 'imagine-no-software-releases-its-easy-if-you-try-song', '<p>imagine no software releases<br />\r\nit&rsquo;s easy if you try<br />\r\nno waiting on gatekeepers<br />\r\nabove us only sky</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>imagine all the software going live today<br />\r\nimagine there&rsquo;s no limit<br />\r\nit isn&rsquo;t hard to do<br />\r\nnothing to delay or wait for<br />\r\nand no pre-planning too</p>\r\n\r\n<p>imagine all the software going live today<br />\r\nyou may say i&rsquo;m a dreamer, but i&rsquo;m not the only one<br />\r\nembracing continuous software concepts<br />\r\nwith software promoted live at once</p>\r\n\r\n<p>imagine no barriers<br />\r\ni wonder if you can<br />\r\nno need to wait for QA<br />\r\npromoting code to live</p>\r\n\r\n<p>imagine all the software going live today<br />\r\nyou may say<br />\r\ni&rsquo;m a dreamer, but i&rsquo;m not the only one<br />\r\nembracing continuous software concepts<br />\r\nwith software promoted live all day</p>\r\n', 'imagine no software releases, it’s easy if you try, no waiting on gatekeepers...', 'imagine no software releases, it’s easy if you try, no waiting on gatekeepers...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/imagine-no-software-releases-its-easy-if-you-try-song', 'john_lennon_imagine1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-03-27', '2012-03-27 12:00:00', 1, '2012-03-27 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(22, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Changes to Club Commerce', 'changes-to-club-commerce', '<p>Changes are coming.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In typical style, I thought it would take a day or so to effect the changes. Wrong!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am absolutely convinced that changes must result in more of my peers participating, not less.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At first, it seemed logical to shop my Club Commerce idea to a cabal of big money outfits. The problem is that the incentive to disseminate powerful Continuous technology &amp; techniques to you is somewhere between zero and never.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Code itself is a powerful asset.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However,&nbsp;<strong>the ability to create code is the sublime asset</strong>, because code itself has a limited useful-life.&nbsp; Continuous technology &amp; techniques introduces a powerful value-added potential: creating code on a massive scale. Volume and scale open up tremendous new revenue opportunities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, tell me: why would someone with such power in their hands simply give that power to&nbsp; you?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Y&rsquo;know, the code may be GPL, but the software development process that created that code is proprietary. There is no legal obligation for anyone to give you their Continous technology &amp; techniques over to the public domain. Anyone with skill in Continuous technology &amp; techniques will hoard it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You &ndash;&nbsp; the independent freelance consultant, the small-shop consultant, and the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Small_and_medium_enterprises\" target=\"_blank\">SMB</a>&nbsp;entrepreneur &mdash; will never see it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, what I am saying is that the power to create&nbsp; (and maintain) a massive volume of code is more valuable than the code itself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Today&rsquo;s weird ideas become tomorrow&rsquo;s hot money-making technology. &nbsp;You know how these things work, stuff seems to come out of nowhere and then bam! That&rsquo;s what&rsquo;s going to happen here.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I need my peers in on this thing with me. I literally cannot bring Continuous technology &amp; techniques for Joomla ecommerce without you. Well, I can&rsquo;t assure that it&rsquo;s going to get &ldquo;out there&rdquo; into your hands, without you coming in with me at Club Commerce.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More precisely, I need my peers to help figure out the Continuous techniques that accomodates volume. The only way to blaze a trail is to have us band together soooner than later. I could have pushed to figure out techniques that accomodate just my handful of wonderful Founding Tribe. However, I doubt that whatever process we created would scale at all, and we&rsquo;d be starting from scratch anyways.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, I am broadening out my Club Commerce, on purpose.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The money is nominal, by design. Your active participation can remain nominal, by design.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By design, I&rsquo;m making it as attractive as I can for my peers to get in on this with me, so that we may all have our hands firmly on the powerful Continuous techniques that we build, so that we may &ldquo;lift all our boats&rdquo; together.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My Founding Tribe of seven will now enjoy free lifetime Membership. They&rsquo;ve paid their dues big time, allowing my Club Commerce concept to develop to this point.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My Primary&nbsp; Tribe will be the next 200 Members, at $17 CDN per month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My Angel Plus Tribe will be the next 300 Members, at $19 CDN per month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My&nbsp; Angel Tribe will be the next 500 Members, at $21 CDN per month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My Regular Tribe will be Members 1,000+, at $25 CDN per month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I may cap Membership at 1,000.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is one Honourary Member, with the possibility of a second being offered. There won&rsquo;t be a third!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>April&rsquo;s LaSalleMart News and Hangout podcasts are cancelled, during &ldquo;Makeover Month&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My blog is now here, at www.southlasalle.com. My main site is now for sign-up only.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will install Anahita 1.6 as our fresh private Members-only social site. I am leaving our original Anahita 1.5 site open during the transition, as some of the threads I&rsquo;ll end up pasting to our new site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once I launch my site makeover, and install Anahita 1.6 so that it&rsquo;s functional, I will post the plan on the LaSalleMart&rsquo;s Assembla.com page. As well, I will blog about more technical things here.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My site makeover will be done before I set out to the April Toronto Joomla Meet-up this Wednesday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'At first, it seemed logical to shop my Club Commerce idea to a cabal of big money outfits. The problem is that the incentive to disseminate powerful Continuous technology & techniques to you is somewhere between zero and never...', 'At first, it seemed logical to shop my Club Commerce idea to a cabal of big money outfits. The problem is that the incentive to disseminate powerful Continuous technology & techniques to you is somewhere between zero and never...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/changes-to-club-commerce', 'change1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-04-16', '2012-04-16 12:00:00', 1, '2012-04-16 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(23, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Toronto Joomla User Group Meet-up, April 2012', 'toronto-joomla-user-group-meet-up-april-2012', '<p>On a sunny spring mild spring day, we met up at Yorkville. Great day to be downtown.We were all immersed in our own discussion, no Round Table talking this time. You never know, sometimes we all together, sometimes not. I had to change my seating to remain sociable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m not even sure what everyone was talking about. I think it was Project night at JUGT. It didn&rsquo;t help that I was late! There was a short overview comparing Drupal to Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There was talk about different business models in the Joomla world, which I always enjoy.Great to see how everyone is progressing.The May meet-up will be in beautful downtown Etobicoke.</p>\r\n', 'On a sunny spring mild spring day, we met up at Yorkville. Great day to be downtown.We were all immersed in our own discussion, no Round Table talking this time. You never know, sometimes we all together, sometimes not. I had to change my seating to remain sociable...', 'On a sunny spring mild spring day, we met up at Yorkville. Great day to be downtown.We were all immersed in our own discussion, no Round Table talking this time. You never know, sometimes we all together, sometimes not. I had to change my seating to remai', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/toronto-joomla-user-group-meet-up-april-2012', 'jugt-cn-logo.png', 1, 0, 0, '2012-04-19', '2012-04-19 12:00:00', 1, '2012-04-19 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(24, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart 1.0', 'lasallemart-10', '<blockquote>\r\n<p>&hellip;so we started to build it ourselves. As we were building, people who heard about our project, they were interested to use it as well. So,&nbsp;<strong>they ended up paying us</strong>&nbsp;to get: access to the code; to get access to our chatroom; and, everything [else]. That&rsquo;s how the First Tribe of Anahita was formed and that&rsquo;s how we raised funds.&nbsp;<strong>We raised quite a bit a funds for Anahita to fund the development hours</strong>. After that, we started the premium plans. That&rsquo;s how the community grew.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Rastin Mehr explaining the genesis of Anahita</strong>, on my <a href=\"http://southalsallemedia.com/2012/tbbs52\" target=\"_blank\">TBBS #52</a>, April 26, 2012, podcast (1min 24sec)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2012/toronto-joomla-user-group-meet-up-april-2012\" target=\"_blank\">last week&rsquo;s Toronto Joomla meet-up</a>, Zach told me that we need to get LaSalleMart 1.0 done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My reply was that LaSalleMart is as much about the software creation process as it is about the software itself &mdash; and, which is first? The software; or, the process that creates it?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He responded with: the software!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To which I said, &ldquo;you are more right than me!&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We need something to install for our clients, now.&nbsp; We need to kick-start conversion to Joomla 2.5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We have my two tax components, along with my Distro &amp; my Control Centre component.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have Akeeba Live Update set-up with its dedicated website.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, we&rsquo;re going to bootstrap everything together. So much for a linear path.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&rsquo;re starting with my Tienda 0.8.2 Distro. The first thing I&rsquo;m doing is getting checkout back to &ldquo;First Principles&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Checkout has caused me a lot of grief, and it needs some fixing before proceeding. I&rsquo;m taking it back to basic, step-by-step &ldquo;First Principles&rdquo;. I&rsquo;ve created a separate view for each step, and a separate display function in the controller for each view. It&rsquo;s a good foundation for the changes I know are coming!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then, there are things to delete. A motivator to get Tienda lean-and-mean is converting to Joomla 2.5. The less code that exists, the less code to convert. So, all references to Dioscouri extensions will be deleted. All modules and plugins will be omitted from the base installation, so we can delete the Tienda installation routine. We&rsquo;ll review the code to see what else we can jettison; or, separate out to convert later.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There will be a California package, and a Canadian package. The Canadian package will include Canada Post.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>BTW: LaSalleMart Canada is created and maintained by Canadians for Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Everything will be installable via the Joomla installer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, what are we going to do with LaSalleMart 1.0?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, we, who are bootstrapping LaSalleMart, are Joomla ecommerce consultants frustrated with traditional cart extensions. We don&rsquo;t want to merely recreate what is already out there. All we&rsquo;ll achieve is recreating our frustration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We want massively huge amounts of features. We want a software development process that can accomodate massively huge amounts of features. We want to accomodate a huge amount of investment &mdash; as feature sponsorship is attracted to LaSalleMart, we must have the ability to properly absorb that investment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We want to get our new features onto our live sites fast. No, really! This is a major reason for undertaking LaSalleMart in the first place. There are ways!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We want to produce multiple simultaneous versions of LaSalleMart &mdash; one size does not fit all, so why should we limit ourselves to just one version?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We want to get your development efforts and dollars back downstream into core development. There&rsquo;s far too much post-development, redundant &ldquo;beyond-the-install&rdquo; work being done, that could and should be pushed back downstream.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, what will I do with LaSalleMart? Ha! How &rsquo;bout what I will&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;do with LaSalleMart: give it away.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You are interested to use LaSalleMart. So support it with a subscription. Sponsor features, in whole or in part. Canada Post needs feature sponsors. Converting to Joomla 2.5 will need sponsorship. And know that everyone else involved is contributing too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We are on our way, bootstrapping everything together instead of proceeding linearly. Looking forward to having you&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/\">join</a>&nbsp;us.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'So we started to build it ourselves. As we were building, people who heard about our project, they were interested to use it as well. So, they ended up paying us to get: access to the code; to get access to our chatroom; and, everything [else]. That’s how the First Tribe of Anahita was formed and that’s how we raised funds. We raised quite a bit a funds for Anahita to fund the development hours. After that, we started the premium plans. That’s how the community grew.', 'So we started to build it ourselves. As we were building, people who heard about our project, they were interested to use it as well. So, they ended up paying us to get: access to the code; to get access to our chatroom; and, everything [else]. That’s how', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-10', 'lasallemart_logo_lg.png', 1, 0, 0, '2012-04-24', '2012-04-24 12:00:00', 1, '2012-04-24 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(25, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart 1.0 is Progressing', 'lasallemart-10-progressin', '<p>Up at 2:00am last night unable to resolve an installation halting problem leads me to conclude that I will not get LaSalleMart 1.0 out the door today.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s been a very productive week.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank you to Founding Tribe Member Zach Atkinson, whose day-to-day involvement is of tremendous benefit to all of us. Thank you Zach!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UPDATE WHILST I INPUT MY POSTS INTO MY LARAVEL APP: And pp your ass too for going suddenly quiet and dropping off the face of the earth. But, also, thank you, because I&#39;ve been so reticent about partnering with people with my software. Which has caused me succeed even more with my own sofware -- LaSalleMart 3.0 was my from-scratch innovation. Now three months in with the Laravel Framework, my pace of independent learning has accelerated, doing a from-scratch blog app -- just the beginning!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Converting Tienda 0.8.2 to LaSallemart is forcing me to explore crevices of the code I&rsquo;ve not explored before. Thank you to everyone who brought Tienda to fruition. It&rsquo;s been an interesting experience journeying through the codebase, re-living the excitement I felt when it first came out, understanding yet again why I saw so much promise; yet, at the same time, getting a deeper perspective on my frustration too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That Dioscouri blog entry keeps popping up in my mind that says &ldquo;You can change the code&rdquo;. Yes, we can, and yes we are.&nbsp; But, I&rsquo;ll tell you something, there&rsquo;s more to changing the code than &ldquo;changing the code&rdquo;. And in my chats &amp; emails with Zach, I keep coming back to it. It&rsquo;s about control. It feels so good to get into the code! Even better, instead of worrying about &ldquo;not disturbing the core&rdquo;, it&rsquo;s great to have the core by the balls!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Diving into the core of Tienda&rsquo;s checkout felt really good. I&rsquo;ve dealt tangentally with checkout, not wanting to disturb the core, which produced frustrating results. My goal was to return checkout back to &ldquo;First Principles&rdquo;, as the foundation for further modifications. My checkout is step-by-step. No guest checkout, no one-page checkout. Nothing fancy, and try not to use javascript. A grinding experience it was to achieve this without disturbing the underlying code, but in the end got it. To achieve all the fancy changes, I think we will have to go back to &ldquo;First First Principles&rdquo;, which is a topic for another post. Now there&rsquo;s a clean step-by-step checkout.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the back of my mind is converting to Joomla 2.5.&nbsp; LaSalleMart 1.0 will be for Joomla 1.5 only. Instead of doing some prep for the conversion now, I&rsquo;m deferring all that so I can get LM1 out-the-door. As Bugs Bunny says, &ldquo;Foist things foist&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There will be&nbsp;<em>three simultaneous LM 1.0 packages</em>: Canadian (eh!), California, and regular unleaded.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Canada Post will be done after the first round is done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Each package will have it&rsquo;s own Live Update, so you can update LM in Joomla 2.5 style.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am merging elements of my Tax and Distro-Control components into the single LM component to save the trouble of installing multiple components. However, in the doing, I am becoming resistant because I&rsquo;m stuffing more things into the base admin, which I hate. The admin is busy enough without cramming more stuff in there. The way to go is be a bit expedient, b/c it&rsquo;s more important to convert to Joomla 2.5 than to add things to this Joomla 1.5 version of LM1.0.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There will be no LaSalleMart website &mdash; for now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For some reason that was not apparent at 2:00am last night, installation is halting at the plugins. So, that&rsquo;s that for getting LM1.0 out this week.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once I get my Canadian package done, I&rsquo;ll get a demo site up so you can get your kick at the can.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This month all my podcasts are cancelled, except for one &ldquo;LaSalleMart News&rdquo; podcast I want to do later this month.</p>\r\n', 'Up at 2:00am last night unable to resolve an installation halting problem leads me to conclude that I will not get LaSalleMart 1.0 out the door today.', 'Up at 2:00am last night unable to resolve an installation halting problem leads me to conclude that I will not get LaSalleMart 1.0 out the door today.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-10-progressin', 'last_spike.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-05-04', '2012-05-04 12:00:00', 1, '2012-05-04 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(26, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Announcing LaSalleMart 1.0', 'announcing-lasallemart-10', '<p>It is with a certain pride that I announce LaSalleMart 1.0.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Until we have thumbs up from real Live Site usage, we will consider LM1.0 &ldquo;beta&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are three simultaneous LM1.0 packages:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>LaSalleMart 1.0 Regular;</li>\r\n	<li>LaSalleMart 1.0 Canada;</li>\r\n	<li>LaSalleMart 1.0 California.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The Canuck &amp; Cali packages have respective taxes baked right into the core, with no generic or leftover tax calculations. The geocodes and specific configs are created during installation, so there&rsquo;s no extra install or config to do.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 1.0 is a fork ofTienda 0.8.2.&nbsp; It is Tienda 0.8.2 virtually intact. However, there are differences:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>improvements to some views/layouts from my Tienda Distro;</li>\r\n	<li>Canuck taxes baked into the core of the Canadian package;</li>\r\n	<li>Cali taxes baked into the core of the Cali package;</li>\r\n	<li>Live Update;</li>\r\n	<li>new unique clean step-by-step checkout that I did especially for LaSalleMart 1.0;</li>\r\n	<li>guest checkout disabled;</li>\r\n	<li>one page checkout disabled;</li>\r\n	<li>back-link footer disabled;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Further Improvements for LaSalleMart 1.0 underway:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>improvements to PayPal Pro payment plugin;</li>\r\n	<li>complete Canada Post shipping plugin;</li>\r\n	<li>integration of new Canada Post labelling service.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>As plugins were mysteriously not working during the install process, no plugins are installed during installation. I deleted the plugin install snippet &mdash; there, that solved that problem. So, each plugin you want needs to be installed individually. I hate having to uninstall unwanted plugins anyways, one of my pet peeves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Converting to Joomla 2.5 is definitely on the to-do list!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 1.0 software &amp; support are available to Club Commerce Members only.</p>\r\n', 'It is with a certain pride that I announce LaSalleMart 1.0...                       \r\n                        ', 'It is with a certain pride that I announce LaSalleMart 1.0...                       \r\n                        ', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/announcing-lasallemart-10', 'champagne_cork1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-05-16', '2012-05-16 12:00:00', 1, '2012-05-16 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(27, 0, NULL, NULL, 'More Profound than the Code is LaSalleMart’s Build Process', 'build-more-profound-than-the-code', '<p>There are three simultaneous versions of LaSalleMart,&nbsp;produced from the same core&nbsp;for different types of users.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, from the same core. Just as I told you it could be done, I made it happen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More profound than the code is the way I built my simultaneous packages,&nbsp;because there is huge money to the User Community in waking up to how to build code. HUGE MONEY!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s not bullshit theory, it&rsquo;s not cornball thinking, it&rsquo;s not hustling a false premise to rustle up some income.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What I&rsquo;ve been telling you for months and months, I actually did</strong>. The results speak for themselves: not one, but three simultaneous software packages. The code for each package resides in exactly one place &mdash; there&rsquo;sbuild-more-profound-than-the-code no duplicate code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, we can view code by how we create it. And in so doing, we can improve the code we create, and speed up its creation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, let me tell you the deep dark secret of how I created three simultaneous ecommerce packages:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>I installed a powerful, mature, mainstream, and FREE &ldquo;build&rdquo; program, called&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.phing.info/\" target=\"_blank\">Phing</a>;</li>\r\n	<li>I created a (nearly) FREE account at one of the world&rsquo;s most respected and popular source code repository sites, called&nbsp;<a href=\"http://github.com/\" target=\"_blank\">GitHub</a>;</li>\r\n	<li>I forgot that it was dinnertime.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>I chunked up the code into a bunch of different GitHub &ldquo;repositories&rdquo;, and Phing assembled the code into the final packages. It took me half a week to create the seven Phing files that merge the repos, process the merged PHP, create the installable zip, and upload to my server&rsquo;s download folders.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, when I finish a round of mods, I update the GitHub repos, and then run my seven Phing build files one-after-the-after. Voila, my three gorgeous flavours of LaSalleMart are sitting on my server.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One-size-fits-all zip files are complete a waste of time. Instead, using established, powerful, mainstream &mdash; and FREE &mdash; tools, I present to you a taste of personal turn-key Joomla ecommerce solutions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tell me, why shouldn&rsquo;t a bunch of enterprising consultants and site owners get together and make the most of the tools that are out there. I mean, geez, I come back to this all the time, why behave like a bunch of individuals doing one-off customizations? Why not be smart and band together instead? Do our custom coding as a team, share the code amongst ourselves, and come out ahead? Well, why not take it to massive heights, and utilize the free mainstream powerful build tools out there to create eye-popping custom kick-ass ecomm features for ourselves?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For those in the User Community who are growing our own consultancies and sites, who are engaged in custom mods already, who can rub two nickels together, the potential is stunning. Let&rsquo;s push custom coding back downstream, chunk up the code into discrete repositories, and then get Phing to assemble and upload the code to our sites. What I&rsquo;ve said all these months and months is really possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since we&rsquo;re &ldquo;chunking&rdquo; our code instead of storing it in one big blog, we can &ldquo;chunk out&rdquo; the code creation process too. We create temporary &ldquo;Feature Teams&rdquo; to create very specific features.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Phing (and the Jenkins Server) can automate code testing (well, some of it!), documentation, and deployment. We will have a potent software creation &amp; maintenance process for ourselves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Y&rsquo;know, we don&rsquo;t actually have to code. There&rsquo;s too much coding to do for any one or two or three people to do anyways. What we&rsquo;ll have is a way for lots of hired programmers to code at the same time. Creating a feature will not be a matter of deciding yea-or-nay, but a matter of gathering the Feature Team and getting started. That is, no one will be gatekeeping features that have funders.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most people in the Joomla ecommerce User Community want to consume software. They have no interest in creating or maintaining it. They just want to use it. The marketplace is serving this software-to-be-consumed group quite well. However, there is a segment of the Joomla ecommerce User Community who do not merely consume software, who are engaged in the software development process in some form. It is you whom I make this call to action.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ability for the User Community to maintain &amp; create their own software is here. To you, the enterprising consultant and site owner growing your businesses, to you I say: join. Uncross your arms, and join. The only way we can make the most out of the &ldquo;build&rdquo; software is by being on both sides of the Joomla installer &mdash; being the extension purveyor; and, owning the live web sites. The Joomla installer is the Great Divide, and we have the unique position and opportunity of being on both sides. Being on both sides is where the real money is. You see what I&rsquo;m saying.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Join my Club Commerce with the idea that in a month or two you can chip in an extra $100/month to hire programmers. 200 Club Members chipping in a mere $100/month = $240,000 in pure programming annually. That&rsquo;s major money, and you get the benefit of all that code. We do have to build up our capacity to absorb all this investment in code, and we will.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve described this already in great detail. I&rsquo;ve told you in detail how we should proceed. I&rsquo;ve told you in detail why using a social site as our Members-only site is superior to traditional ticket &amp; forum sites. Now, we have LaSalleMart 1.0, which put theory into practice. We&rsquo;re ready to rock-and-roll.</p>\r\n', 'More profound than the code is the way I built my simultaneous packages, because there is huge money to the User Community in waking up to how to build code. ', 'More profound than the code is the way I built my simultaneous packages, because there is huge money to the User Community in waking up to how to build code. ', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/build-more-profound-than-the-code', 'thinking_man1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-05-17', '2012-05-17 12:00:00', 1, '2012-05-17 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(28, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Let The Other Dumb Bastard Pay For Open Source Software', 'let-the-other-dumb-bastard-pay-for-open-source-software', '<p>Without George C. Scott, Paul Newman would not have achieved that certain blue-eyed edge in The Hustler.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Great actor was George C. Scott.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/g-0dTpzNzwo?rel=0\" width=\"640\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Now I want you to remember that no bastard ever won a war by dying for his country. He won it by making the other poor dumb bastard die for his country.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>This quote captures the gestalt of open source ecommerce software:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>No bastard ever brought open source ecommerce software to fruition by paying for its creation. He brought it to fruition by making the other poor dumb bastard pay for its creation.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, it seems that I&rsquo;m that dumb bastard!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why, people are shocked &mdash; SHOCKED! &mdash; that I harbour the notion that they are going to pay &mdash; mind you, that&rsquo;s pay with actual money &mdash; for LaSalleMart&rsquo;s creation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My Dear Bobby, may I call you that (no, you may not), that&rsquo;s not how we do things. See, however you get it done, you get it done, but the way it works is if you want to create software, then you create it. You bear the cost, you shoulder the burden. LaSalleMart is your baby, so you get it done. Then, if you&rsquo;ve come up with something we like, maybe we&rsquo;ll slip you a couple of bucks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You know, if this development model actually worked, I&rsquo;d do it in a heartbeat. But, Joomla ecommerce is not like other extensions. How so? Well, it&rsquo;s vast! This is the problem, it&rsquo;s always been the problem, and it&rsquo;s the key problem to understand. It&rsquo;s vast!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla ecommerce is unlike other extensions because of its scope. The mouse-on-a-wheel doesn&rsquo;t work. Locking a programmer or two or three in a closet and having them emerge a week later doesn&rsquo;t work. It hasn&rsquo;t worked, it doesn&rsquo;t work, it&rsquo;s not going to work. It&rsquo;s been tried again and again.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The development model of making the other bastard pay for LaSalleMart is not going to work either. The scope is just too huge, too overwhelming.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For those of you who are building successful consultancies and sites, you realize that there comes a time when you have to take control of the technology you are using. You realize that the technology itself represents enormous value; that it is itself an enormous asset.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For The Few, the epiphany that waiting for the other dumb bastard to create the ecomm software that one consumes is not smart business.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'No bastard ever brought open source ecommerce software to fruition by paying for its creation. He brought it to fruition by making the other poor dumb bastard pay for its creation.', 'No bastard ever brought open source ecommerce software to fruition by paying for its creation. He brought it to fruition by making the other poor dumb bastard pay for its creation.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/let-the-other-dumb-bastard-pay-for-open-source-software', 'patton1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-05-17', '2012-05-17 12:00:00', 1, '2012-05-17 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(29, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Mid May LaSalleMart Status', 'mid-may-lasallemart-status', '<p>LaSalleMart 1.0 Canada needs Canada Post, which I&rsquo;m working on this week to complete the package.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>PayPal Pro needs a look-see for some improvements, which I am arranging with Zach.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Beyond is getting LaSalleMart ready for Joomla 2.5. This will be a big job. The hope is that with some intensive work, and pruning some of the code, we can get LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 done. And then, from there, start building out LaSalleMart in earnest.</p>\r\n', 'LaSalleMart 1.0 Canada needs Canada Post, which I’m working on this week to complete the package.', 'LaSalleMart 1.0 Canada needs Canada Post, which I’m working on this week to complete the package.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/mid-may-lasallemart-status', 'update2.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-05-22', '2012-05-22 12:00:00', 1, '2012-05-22 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(30, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Software Releases: Continuous and Otherwise', 'software-releases-continuous-and-discrete', '<p>When there are updates, you should have them. Why not just get &lsquo;em when I have &lsquo;em, instead of waiting for me to decide it&rsquo;s time to create a software release?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Technically, it&rsquo;s possible. Phing does FTP uploads, so why not upload to&nbsp; your server? Phing also pushes to Git repos, to why not push to&nbsp; your own repo, and then you can grab it there?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The only way to figure out Continuous Deployment is to do it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The immense advantage of doing software development&nbsp;<em>and</em>&nbsp;having the live websites is the ability to implement Continuous Deployment (aka Delivery).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m thinking crazy thoughts because we are a Club; and, we have control of both the downstream and upstream. That is, we control the code, and we control the individual sites. If we have hundreds of sites, then why not have a bunch of Phing scripts launched by Jenkins to FTP upload the changes to each individual site? Unthinkable with other extensions, but we are building for ourselves, so we can do things differently. As well, we are designing our development process to deliver small pieces of code all the time, instead of delivering huge blobs of code infrequently.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m thinking that I have to bust up my &ldquo;LaSalleMart-Core&rdquo; repo into many smaller repos. If we update a language file, then we should get that on sites right away (I&rsquo;m thinking of the language file as a way of delivering more help as we go along, for instance). Other files should not be delivered instantly, b/c there should be more of a testing/QA process. But ultimately, these need to be delivered too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, there may be different delivery streams for different types of files. I look forward to figuring this out as we go along, b/c there&rsquo;s a big payoff!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For those sites where it doesn&rsquo;t make sense to set up Continuous Delivery, we&rsquo;ll have traditional Live Update updates.</p>\r\n', 'When there are updates, you should have them. Why not just get ‘em when I have ‘em, instead of waiting for me to decide it’s time to create a software release?', 'When there are updates, you should have them. Why not just get ‘em when I have ‘em, instead of waiting for me to decide it’s time to create a software release?', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/software-releases-continuous-and-discrete', 'binary_eyes.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-05-22', '2012-05-22 12:00:00', 1, '2012-05-22 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(31, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Mid June LaSalleMart Status', 'mid-june-lasallemart-status', '<p>Zach the my Founding Tribe Member who is most involved in the day-to-day progression of LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He is a programmer-slash-consultant. We think of ourselves as consultants who cross the Great Divide into development. However, on the other side of the aisle are programmers who consult.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zach is installing the first live LaSalleMart site. As such, we&rsquo;ve been collaborating to make this happen. Zach is doing a terrific job of being the first to User Test LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This inaugural installation has given us the opportunity to work more closely; and, to smooth out some rough edges that we&rsquo;ve come across. Better to work with a programmer for the first round of User Testing &mdash; I get more empathy! Probably just an illusion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://dioscouri.com/index.php?option=com_ambrasubs&amp;view=categories&amp;categoryid=46&amp;Itemid=43\" target=\"_blank\">caveat on the Tienda download page</a>:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Tienda is in production beta, which means&nbsp;<strong>YES you may use it on live sites</strong>!&nbsp; Be conscious that there are&nbsp;<strong>non-critical</strong>&nbsp;known bugs that we are working on. Also, some of the features are not 100% functional.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014):&nbsp;</strong>In hindsight, yeah, &quot;Production Beta&quot; was such bullshit. It&#39;s beta or not. Production means &quot;real&quot;. The terms do not belong side-by-side.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When we come across a problem, we don&rsquo;t know if we encountered a known &lt;100% functional feature; or, if it&rsquo;s a problem in a =100%. &nbsp;Enabling product reviews impaired site performance on pages whose products have attributes. Are in 100% or &lt;100% territory here? Well, we definitely disabled product reviews, and site performance improved.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AkeebaBackup.com&rsquo;s Akeeba Release System&rsquo;s Live Update feature failed User Testing. This is a must-have feature, so we can update LaSalleMart in the Joomla Administrator. We plan on having a lot of releases (en route to eventual Continuous Deployment), so it would sure be convenient to do the updates within Joomla. That&rsquo;s how Joomla 2.5 does it now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, I ended up re-jigging installation/update to accomodate Live Update. It&rsquo;s done. In so doing, though, I had to replicate installation/update code in all three &ldquo;flavour&rdquo; repositories, in order to accommodate the Joomla installer. This should be the only time ev-ah that we replicate code among the LaSalleMart repositories.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While I was re-jigging the installation, I took the liberty of increasing the default config options from 5 records to 215 records (give or take). I kinda Bob-i-cized the install. Hey, screw it, I hate these generic set-ups anyways &mdash; the entire philosophy is to do specific builds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was oh-so-tempting to add more geocode records each LaSalleMart edition (aka &ldquo;flavour&rdquo;). It is a major PITA to have to set &lsquo;em up cold. However tempting it was to get deeper into the payment &amp; shipping default set-up, I concluded that with all the different permutations it&rsquo;s better to impute &nbsp;the direct experiences of my Club Commerce Members; rather than guess what they want. Plus, there are build issues that I want to defer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zach found a problem with one of the product details&rsquo; drop-down options. The solution was to customize this particular drop-down for Canadian HST/PST/GST, because the generic handling made no sense at all &mdash; and the drop-down as-is introduced an error. It&rsquo;s the first time I introduced specific Canadianization to the product details form, and I love it! This is exactly what I&rsquo;m trying to achieve, a Canuck Cart! We&rsquo;ll probably have to do something similar for LaSalleMart California when we do our first install.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We now have another Toronto install on the way &mdash; Canada Post is needed for this one. Plus, two Calgary installs; and, two or three California installs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I spent a lot of time working on my Launch Article, and the &ldquo;LaSalleMart News &rdquo; podcast that complimented it. I&rsquo;m not a marketing guru and it takes me halfway to forever to do it. But, until I get to 250 to 300 Members (methinks), I have to sink time into marketing. In fact, LaSalleMart is so primed now that I have to do marketing full time (methinks) in order to get Membership from basically zero to 250-300.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although I&rsquo;ve not yet completed my Canada Post shipping plugin and my PayPal Pro tweaks, I am going to hold them in abeyance for now and spend my technical time on the Joomla 2.5 conversion. After meeting Zach in person this week &mdash; a perfect late summer afternoon at St. Lawrence Market area &mdash; we&rsquo;ve come up with our approach.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ll tell you something: if I had more Members, I&rsquo;d be aggressive soliciting ideas and stimulating discussion about this, because there&rsquo;s more than meets the eye here. Zach is basically representing future Members, and as such I wanted to meet with him personally, and flesh out a decision tree on this.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The bottom line is that we decided that TIME is the most important project element (4 basic project constraints: time, cost, scope, quality &ndash;&gt; pick 2!). This is where the Tienda caveat above entered our thinking? Why convert features that are &lt; 100%? The purpose of my Club is to create &amp; maintain our own Joomla ecommerce software, so we&rsquo;re going to DIY anyways within my Club. So, let&rsquo;s amputate code. The less code, the less to convert to Joomla 2.5, the faster we can do it. That&rsquo;s the theory!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The idea is to aggressively amputate features and code. Lean and mean. Maybe too lean. But, we&rsquo;ll rebuild LaSalleMart up in our image. The conversion to Joomla 2.5 marks the first discrete break from Tienda.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Custom fields, product comments, product reviews, subscription products, the dashboard reports, guest checkout, one page checkout are for sure to be deleted. Most of the plugins and modules will initially be ignored. The system plugin over-rides com_user, so I&rsquo;m basically hoping to ditch this plugin completely.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using multiple GitHub.com repos and Phing for building the three LaSalleMart zip files are a tremendous success. After the final commit, it takes less than 10 minutes to get the three new fresh completed zip files uploaded for downloaded AND ready for your Live Updating. With the pressure of our first live site upon us, it&rsquo;s a beautiful thing (after I did my re-jigging for Live Update). It works for real. We have multiple specific &ldquo;jurisdictional&rdquo; editions of LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart is real, is viable, is ready.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The long grinding road to get to this point is done. Now, we absolutely need to get Membership popped to 250 to 300 to realize the potential of what we&rsquo;re doing.</p>\r\n', 'WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): I cannot friggin\' believe the shit I went through to fork this overhead-laden thing -- BUT I DID. And I blogged and podcasted REGULARLY about the stuff I was doing and the shit I was getting into. This post but one example! ', 'Mid June LaSalleMart Status', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/mid-june-lasallemart-status', 'update2.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-06-15', '2012-06-15 12:00:00', 1, '2012-06-15 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(32, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Soaring with Phing and GitHub — and Akeeba Live Update', 'soaring-with-phing-github-live-update', '<p>Working on LaSalleMart&rsquo;s first live site with Zach Atkinson highlighted a problem with Akeeba Live Update.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Live Update is a subset of the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.akeebabackup.com/products/akeeba-release-system.html\" target=\"_blank\">Akeeba Release System</a>. LU allows you to update LaSalleMart from your Joomla Administrator, instead of trudging to my download site, logging in, downloading, etc etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It really works. There&rsquo;s an icon in the LaSalleMart dashboard that tells you if you have the latest version. If not, you click to the update page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On my end of things, every time I have an update, I have to go to my ARS admin and fill out forms. Which is fine if I have one new release every week or two. But, what happens when I have a new release daily? Or even &mdash; gasp! &mdash; more than one per day? Then, it&rsquo;s a major PITA to update the ARS admin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A new release per day? You betcha! If I make one small change &mdash; which I did late this afternoon &mdash; why wait to release it? Philosophically, I want all LaSalleMart sites to have my changes asap. Continuous Integration, Continuous Deployment &mdash; the key word is &ldquo;continuous&rdquo;!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>GitHub.com is great. We update the repo(s), and the code is ready for Phing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Phing is proving to be so powerful that I&rsquo;m starting to consider it a weapon. Once the LaSalleMart repositories are PUSHed, it takes mere minutes to get all three LaSalleMart flavours uploaded to the Akeeba Release System folders.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, updating my ARS admin is proving to be a bottleneck. In fact, knowing I have to update it has caused me to delay running my Phing builds. This is a Very Bad Behaviour: the antithesis of &ldquo;continuous&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Joomla installer a bottleneck. Not just physically; but, it is a nasty limiting mindset. I have Grand Plans to bypass the Joomla installer completely. However, in the here-and-now, we are using the Joomla installer; and, using ARS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, after achieving &ldquo;continuous&rdquo; with GitHub and Phing, how to I overcome the ARS bottleneck? Well, did I mention that Phing is very powerful?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Phing does databases. Phing can talk to the ARS database directly. The Phing task is called &ldquo;pdosqlexec&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, Phing UPDATEs the ARS database directly. &nbsp;Look Ma, no Administrator! Bada Bing, Phing uploads the new ZIP files, and then does the UPDATEs right after.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But, I cheated. As Nicholas will probably read this, I better fess up! Phing UPDATEs #__ars_releases only. I don&rsquo;t bother adding brand new releases, I just pretend that my latest ZIPs are the very first releases. Saves a lot of bother this way, although not what ARS intends. Well, I use ARS as a conduit between code origination and final upstream code, rather than a software release mechanism. It&rsquo;s<em>continuous deployment</em>, baby!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I ended up tweaking manifest.xml and defines.php (and a few other things). Most fun reserved for phiguring out Phing. A journey learning how-to set up the automation. But, whooooooaaaa, now that I have the automation in place, it sings!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart updates can be on your site within 10 minutes of the GitHub update. With the automation, I have no extra steps with the Phing builds, except to update the separate parameter file (which is now a single point of entry instead of 3 separate files).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Forget about waiting for releases. I do &lsquo;em as I go along. Continuously.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Even via good ol&rsquo; &nbsp;Live Update, we deploy continuously!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the modern way of doing it. Phing &amp; GitHub are powerful ways to make it happen for us.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE</strong>&nbsp;(June 26, 2012):</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From Nicholas:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>The BleedingEdge category type was designed to remedy this issue. Just create a new directory with the version number and upload the files in it. Coupled with the Automatic &nbsp;Descriptions feature it&rsquo;s upload and publish with zero clicks. I have a Phing task called ftpdeploy in all my components. Issuing a new dev release is as simple as &ldquo;phing ftpdeploy&rdquo; for me&nbsp;<img alt=\";)\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_wink.gif\" style=\"float:none\" />&nbsp;Feel free to browse my Git repos and salvage all the Phing code you need&nbsp;<img alt=\":)\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif\" style=\"float:none\" />[<a href=\"https://akeeba.assembla.com/code/akeeba-release-system/subversion/nodes\" target=\"_blank\">https://akeeba.assembla.com/code/akeeba-release-system/subversion/nodes</a>]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Nicholas, awesome! I will take a look at this Thank you!</p>\r\n', 'WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014):  I was exactly dead balls on target about Phing, Github (I prefer BitBucket just to stay on Atlassian) and Akeeba\'s Live Update & Software Release System. I succeeded in getting these \"behind the scenes\" technologies to do exactly what I set out to do, that I explicitly stated in my blog over and over again: continuous development/integration/delivery. ', 'Soaring with Phing and GitHub — and Akeeba Live Update', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/soaring-with-phing-github-live-update', 'eagle1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-06-26', '2012-06-26 12:00:00', 1, '2012-06-26 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(33, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Slice, Dice, Chop and Grate: LaSalleMart’s Conversion to Joomla 2.5', 'slice-dice-chop-grate-lasallemart-conversion-joomla-25', '<p>How do I &nbsp;proceed with the LaSalleMart conversion to Joomla 2.5?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s not going to happen in a fell swoop, as if I can hoist LaSalleMart on Joomla 2.5, do a bunch of search-replaces, then refresh browser and all is well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How will I know as I progress that the conversion is successful?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What I&rsquo;m going to do is do the conversion in pieces. I&rsquo;m going to take a piece of the LM admin, and do that first. When that works, I&rsquo;ll convert another piece.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As I take each piece, I will amputate code that relate to features we are not carrying forward to the Joomla 2.5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will initiate the conversion, and Zach will help me as we go along &nbsp;==&gt; UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Yeah, right. Another person that has come and gone.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As I gain Club Commerce membership sign-ups, we&rsquo;ll increment the resources we can devote to the conversion. But, there&rsquo;s no doubt about it, the waiting is over and this week I am starting the conversion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once I start conversion, it will be my Number One technical priority. All other technical work will be deferred, except for critical fixes. So Canada Post and the PayPal Pro tweaks will have to wait. I imagine I will be working on the conversion every evening/night.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The only other priority will be growing Club Commerce Membership.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is enough post-conversion sites &amp; development in the pipeline already, among my small little group, that the conversion itself has become a pressure point. My goal is to relieve the pressure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since time is a priority, scope is not. Any opportunity to amputate code will be taken. I want to end up with a lean-and-mean LaSalleMart &ldquo;2.5&Prime; that will be the basis of immense development efforts. We will rebuild that which was amputated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I may break up the LM admin into multiple extensions. This will help me convert LaSalleMart into discrete pieces &mdash; I&rsquo;ll know that for sure the product details works because it&rsquo;s a separate component. I&rsquo;ll know that the config works because it&rsquo;s a separate component. So, there&rsquo;s some refactoring that will take place as we go along &mdash; inexorable and inevitable, so let&rsquo;s make the most of it.</p>\r\n', 'WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Re-reading my blog posts, I cannot believe what I did with LaSalleMart due to the Joomla upgrades. Got an unfinished piece of software to work, then dumped it as Joomla 3 came out. Built a full-on from scratch innovative ecomm software and then...  ', '', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/slice-dice-chop-grate-lasallemart-conversion-joomla-25', 'food_processor1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-06-26', '2012-06-26 12:00:00', 1, '2012-06-26 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(34, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 Using Framework on Framework', 'lasallemart-for-joomla-2-5-using-framework-on-framework', '<p>Now that LaSalleMart 1.0 is a reality and on its first live site, time to convert LaSallemart to work on Joomla 2.5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Refresher:&nbsp;LaSalleMart is a fork of Tienda 0.8.2. There is no Tienda version for Joomla 2.5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Late last week, I finally sat down to start the conversion. First thing to convert: admin&rsquo;s &ldquo;General Configuration&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Within 20 minutes of sitting down, I was digging into Joomla 2.5 itself. Within an hour, I knew I&rsquo;d be using FoF sooner than later.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last night, just after 2:00am, I finished my proof-of-concept of the &ldquo;General Configuration&rdquo; admin using FoF in Joomla 2.5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The notion of somehow &ldquo;porting&rdquo; to Joomla 2.5 is out the window. No dress rehearsal, this is the real thing. We&rsquo;re essentially converting Tienda to Joomla 2.5 by doing some immediate re-writes in the admin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And, we&rsquo;re doing something else: we&rsquo;re doing the theory in practice! We&rsquo;re chopping up the admin into a bunch of separate components &mdash; and into separate repos. The theory is not bullshit! All that talk about &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2012/lasallemart4\" target=\"_blank\">Moneyball</a>&rdquo; is for real. We&rsquo;re really doing it, and I love it!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The &ldquo;Framework on Framework&rdquo; (FoF) by AkeebaBackup.com was something I was going to look at for LaSalleMart at some point. Well, the future is now!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>***</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Interjection: Nicholas emailed me that I&rsquo;m wrong. There&rsquo;s more to the history of FoF than what I know. Here&rsquo;s his verbatim email reply he asked me to publish:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>FOF is NOT &ldquo;my own version of Nooku Framework&rdquo;. It&rsquo;s not &ldquo;a distillation of what attracted us to the Nooku Framework in the first place&rdquo;. FOF is based on my ideas about a framework extension which predate my involvement with Nooku by two years. FOF began its life in August 2009 as a set of three base MVC classes written for my own use, with the goal of simplifying my life. Since then, these classes had made it into two custom projects for clients, as well as ARS and Admin Tools, all predating my involvement with NF. The repos are out there to prove my word. Naturally, I had to evolve this to a full blown library once I realised that NF wouldn&rsquo;t deliver. Naturally, I implemented some conventions which are common with NF as I wanted to make Akeeba Subscriptions work without NF as soon as possible. So, no, FOF is definitely not &ldquo;my own version of NF&rdquo;. It&rsquo;s a different kind of fruit with a similar taste.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>FOF&rsquo;s goals are very different to those of NF. I am aiming for stability, backwards compatibility, extending (<strong>not</strong>&nbsp;replacing) Joomla! Platform and giving you something which doesn&rsquo;t get in your way when you want to override it. All of that while focusing on what matters to developers in the real world: quick turnaround and minimal code maintenance.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Why don&rsquo;t I enable comments on this blog, nor on my Media site? Because I hate moderating public forums.&nbsp;&nbsp;Because I&rsquo;m contrarian.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m leaving my incorrect history-of-FoF intact below, so you know what Nicholas is responding to.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank you, Nicholas, for taking the time to send me your email. And, thank you for making FoF available as a FOSS Joomla library.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>***</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another email exchange:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>the initial&nbsp;<strong>classes</strong>&nbsp;upon which FoF&nbsp;<strong>is based</strong>&nbsp;predate&nbsp;<strong>my involvement</strong>&nbsp;with Nooku Framework by 2 years. Nooku Framework did exist as a private project at that time. When NF was first presented publicly in JaB10 (April 2010 if memory serves) I had already been working on those classes for a year and I had already written ARS based on them&nbsp;<img alt=\":)\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif\" style=\"float:none\" /></blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p></p>\r\n\r\n<p>***</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Less code, speed up turnaround. That&rsquo;s what I want from FoF. And that&rsquo;s what I get. On top of that, there are extra kickers that are kick-ass. But, the fundamental value of FoF is (1) LESS CODE; (2) FASTER TURNAROUND.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is, of course, the promise of the Nooku Framework. As you know, once I started programming with the NFW for my Tienda Distro, I concluded that I could not use it!&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2011/tbbs40\" target=\"_blank\">Here&rsquo;s my podcast announcing my un-using NFW</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nicholas was coming to the same conclusion, as I mention in my podcast. Naturally, Nicholas wrote his own version of the Nooku Framework. He called it FoF. You&rsquo;ll hear me say on occassion that a pearl is created from irritation. Well, FoF is a gem, although its genesis is frustration. FoF is a distillation of what attracted us to the Nooku Framework in the first place. The number one thing that attracted us was the promise of&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;having to code 50% to 80% of the normal Joomla code for a standard normal component. FoF delivers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>FoF is just a handful of PHP files in one single solitary folder. When I first saw it, I thought I had overlooked it! I kept digging for the plugin! Oh, boy, you know, the FoF version of the &ldquo;koowa&rdquo; plugin that remained intact after I uninstalled a NFW component and crashed my site. So, naturally, I&rsquo;m searching for the FoF plugin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Forget it. No plugin, no modules, no mimicking the Joomla folder structure. Whew, I assumed &ldquo;FoF&rdquo; stood for &ldquo;Files upon Folders&rdquo;. Nope. One folder, one handful of files. FoF is a wonderful distillation that delivers as promised.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My &ldquo;General Configuration&rdquo; proof-of-concept is weird. There&rsquo;s a controller folder, but no files in it. Same for the model folder. I spent how long trying to find out how to create the component&rsquo;s main links at the top &mdash; studying Akeeba Subs looking for the elixer! Then, light-bulb! FoF &ldquo;just does it&rdquo; when I stick to the naming conventions. It&rsquo;s the first time I programmed something in Joomla by not doing anything. Totally my cup of tea!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nicholas, thank you for:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>writing FoF;</li>\r\n	<li>converting it to a Joomla library;</li>\r\n	<li>making it FOSS;</li>\r\n	<li>creating a wonderful Assembla space for FoF;</li>\r\n	<li>creating a wonderful sample component for FoF &mdash; which uses Phing!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s a gem!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And an integral aspect of LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/sdFLEQgJ_RA?rel=0\" width=\"640\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sdFLEQgJ_RA\" target=\"_blank\">Rapid Application Development with FoF at Joomla and Beyond 2012</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://akeeba.assembla.com/spaces/fof\" target=\"_blank\">akeeba.assembla.com/spaces/fof</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://akeeba.assembla.com/code/to-do-fof/git/nodes\" target=\"_blank\">akeeba.assembla.com/code/to-do-fof</a></p>\r\n', 'WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Nicholas\' \"Framework on Framework\" for Joomla was the key to making Joomla software development do-able. ', '', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-for-joomla-2-5-using-framework-on-framework', 'tastes_great_less_filling1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-03', '2012-07-03 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-03 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(35, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Why Square One Matters to LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5', 'why-square-one-matters-to-lasallemart', '<p>LaSalleMart needs prominence in Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead of burying the LaSalleMart dashboard in a component&rsquo;s admin, we need the LaSalleMart dashboard right in the Joomla dashboard. And, we need to delete or relocate Joomla dashboard icons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We need to customize Joomla 2.5 for LaSalleMart, so LaSalleMart and Joomla are one. No more relegating ecomm to sub-menus and sub-dashboards. No more that ecomm looks like an add-on. We want one integrated whole.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Furthermore, we want a matrix of Joomla-LaSalleMart Distros. We want Distros based on geographical location + &ldquo;white label&rdquo; + vertical market specialization.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Square One CMS is a critical precedent for doing Joomla distributions. It&rsquo;s important to see that it is not a crazy idea to intermediate Joomla &mdash; that it&rsquo;s actually happening.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It will be critical for Club Commerce to intermediate Joomla. To strip it of superfluous extensions, to customize the updater as we see fit, and to use it as input into our Distro builds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another important aspect is that we will need to manage our success. We need to protect our six figure investment in LaSalleMart programming with Joomla 2.5. Joomla 3.0 may come along and have a whole new way of doing things that lack backwards compatibility. I&rsquo;m all for progress, but shame on us at Club Commerce for not managing our software investment. Should we blithely allow our software to become instantly obsolete just because a group of people running Joomla says so? When Joomla 3.0 becomes LTS, Club Commerce will have the critical mass to manage Joomla 2.5 &amp; Joomla 3.0 as we see fit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Square One matters to LaSalleMart so much that I already did&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2012/tbbs45\" target=\"_blank\">two podcasts with S1&prime;s Founder earlier this year</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jeremy just wrote a terrific post called&nbsp;<a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups#!topic/square-one-cms/\" target=\"_blank\">&ldquo;Square One 3.0 Discussion</a>&rdquo; in the S1 Google Group. He enunciates the tensions involved with planning a Joomla 3.0 distro. He also articulates the tensions involved with maintaining a simple little Joomla distro versus broadening the scope into new unique features.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At Club Commerce, the investment in our own &ldquo;Square One&rdquo; type of Joomla Distro is worth it. But, an investment it shall be as it will take time, effort, and money to make a serious go of it. We should either offer our own &ldquo;Square One&rdquo; type of Joomla Distro to the community; and/or, combine our efforts with the S1 Project in order to support this very worthy endeavour.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the same way, Club Commerce should become a sponsor of the FoF project. By sponsor, I mean that Club Members pay programmers to do work for FoF, and then offer them to Nicholas &mdash; or, perhaps, to pay programmers to do work at Nicholas&rsquo; behest.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In either case, we will see where our journey takes us.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is certainly an experience translating theory into practice. Intermediating open source software is a critical aspect of mitigating risk, and banding together to effect this intermediation is a one reason to band together. The actual Doing It may turn out better than the theory, as my Club Commerce Members contribute back to the projects with which we are intermediating! Sounds good to me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another reason to intermediate Joomla itself is hoisting Joomla onto our software development process, in order to unlock inherent value. Again, the &ldquo;Moneyball&rdquo;!. You&rsquo;ll hear references to Jenkins and other infrastructure in Jeremy&rsquo;s Joomla-and-Beyond-2012 presentation:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/9nONlUeSXKs?rel=0\" width=\"640\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9nONlUeSXKs\" target=\"_blank\">Why Square One Matters To You (JAB2012)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank you to Jeremy for leading the S1 project; and, to everyone who is participating. You are doing important work!</p>\r\n', 'WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Kind of ironic that LaSalleCMS, originally to be Joomla distros (of which I did start work), is my Laravel blog app. I had a full Atlassian open source license, proof-of-concept Phing build files, a rough kickstarter outline (!), and a plan. Within three months of switching to Laravel, my blog app v1.0 is well on its way. Jeremy did do a great job with the Square One distro.', '', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/why-square-one-matters-to-lasallemart', 'fork-in-the-road1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-03', '2012-07-03 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-03 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(36, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Why I Won’t Deep-Six Club Commerce, and Why You Should Not Either', 'club-commerce-lets-go', '<p>Deep Sixing my Club Commerce idea makes a lot of sense. It&rsquo;s going nowhere. Why fight it?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, LaSalleMart is going gangbusters. The natural growth path is to use it as a basis for consulting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are two reasons why I am not deep sixing LaSalleMart:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>I need my own Club Commerce for my own consulting;</li>\r\n	<li>Avoid introducing development pathologies.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Who forked Tienda? Consultants! Users! Do I run an extension business? No. Is LaSalleMart merely one of a portfolio of extensions I sell. No no no. I am not an extension purveyor. Geez, I don&rsquo;t even give a rat&rsquo;s ass that LaSalleMart is not listed on the JED.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For my own consulting, I want the benefits for myself that I am extolling for you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A back-of-my-mind concern is that developing LaSalleMart within my consulting business will introduce development pathologies into LaSalleMart that will start to screw it up. This reasoning is along the same lines as my resistance to seeking a few LaSalleMart Big Buck Backers. We&rsquo;ll end up with a bunch of customized features, instead of something broader. Tienda, of which LaSalleMart is a fork, has these pathologies. &rsquo;nuff said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I want Club Commerce for the same reasons as you:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>cost sharing &mdash; a biggee;</li>\r\n	<li>getting to know my peers who know LaSalleMart &nbsp;so I can farm out my overflow work;</li>\r\n	<li>directly managing and controlling the technology that underlies my consulting;</li>\r\n	<li>for those that do the code, own their own software dev process, and have the end-user sites, there is tremendous $$ potential &mdash; I want my own Club to help me harvest these $$;</li>\r\n	<li>our own funding model for innovation &mdash; leaders make the biggest money. Our ability to create software + bring software to market faster than any other Joomla ecomm outfit + fund stuff ourselves = big bucks &amp; clients clinging onto you to access our network big time.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>I wrote a big blog post explaining all this. I deleted it. You see what I&rsquo;m getting at.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Monthly vig = $36 Cdn.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Monthly contribution Members make to hired programmers = $83.33 (Cdn, I think!).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The numbers certainly add up. 300 Members (which is full Club Membership) directly paying $83.33/month (directly to the programmers, not to me) = 300 x $83.33 x 12 = an astonishing $299,988 annually. Making Club Commerce a major Joomla ecomm development house. All the money going directly to programmers &mdash; to targeted, relevant technology that &nbsp;you need to grow your consulting and online business.</p>\r\n', 'WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Obviously, I wanted to pursue my \"Club\" concept, but it never -- ahem -- took flight. The spirit does continue into my Laravel era, although I think that as a Line of Business it\'s not going to happen. ', '', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/club-commerce-lets-go', 'wings_for_victory.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-04', '2012-07-04 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-04 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(37, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Club Commerce & LaSalleMart: Rare Opportunity for GTA Consultants and Site Owners', 'incredible-opportunity-for-toronto-area-consultants-and-site-owners', '<p>There&rsquo;s an entire level of conversation that happens when physically meeting, that does not happen when working remotely. Let&rsquo;s take advantage of our living here by having half (or more) Club Commerce Members from the extended GTA.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From Newmarket (Davis Drive) to Lake Ontario, Whitby to Guelph/Waterloo, and Niagara &mdash; we have a rare opportunity to develop LaSalleMart through my Club Commerce right here at home.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Working together remotely is fabulous. Getting together, physically meeting, getting to know each other better, is even more fabulous. &nbsp;It gives us a chance to go deeper, to air out opinions, to &nbsp;understand the innovation we are leading.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Club Commerce sponsored JUGT and JUGSWO events are a definite possibility. &nbsp;How do I know? Aired the idea already. A fabulous way for Club Commerce and LaSalleMart to connect to the Joomla project. Certainly no shortage of topics.</p>\r\n', 'WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Oh, I almost did not input this post. ', '', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/incredible-opportunity-for-toronto-area-consultants-and-site-owners', 'IMG_1189.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-09', '2012-07-09 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-09 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(38, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Club Commerce-LaSalleMart vs Magento-Ebay: Keep Your Value in The Family', 'keep-your-value-in-the-family', '<p>Magento constantly comes up in conversation. This week a question posed in the Joomla User Group Toronto Facebook page referred to Magento. I responded with a detailed reply; but, I want to get across the idea here that if eBay values your contribution in their ecosystem, maybe you should realize as a user your true contribution and lever it by being in the Club Commerce-LaSalleMart family.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I nearly specialized in Magento, but I just didn&rsquo;t take to it. I had trouble installing the community version, I had trouble adding products, I crashed my site whenever I installed an add-on. The one consistent message I hear about Magento is &ldquo;it has a long learning curve&rdquo;, and I don&rsquo;t doubt it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Magento is not a panacea. It requires a serious investment of time/effort to learn. Each add-on costs. Consulting costs. It all costs. Sometimes I get the impression that people perceive Magento as the best of Joomla ecommerce plus the best that Prestacart has to offer plus the best that Opencart has to offer plus the best that Ubercart has to offer. Magento is just like any other cart: it has its pros and its cons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You&rsquo;ve seen the Magento &ldquo;Compare Editions&rdquo; page at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.magentocommerce.com/product/compare\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.magentocommerce.com/product/compare</a>?&nbsp;Prices went up considerably!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla ecommerce has tremendous potential to serve the marketplace that is not interested in paying $15,000 just to get the software.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 will be well suited to serve this marketplace. Feature sponsorship via Club Commerce will provide the targeted, relevant features that are needed to serve this marketplace. A marketplace that I think is ready to further embrace Joomla ecommerce.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I look at Magento as part of a big corporate behemoth, and not as a small open source cart project. Why? Because Magento is 100% owned by eBay. Magento is now an important element of growing a new line of business for eBay, which, personally, lessens the attraction of Magento.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The pressure to grow revenue is relentless. eBay bought PayPal to secure a payment gateway for themselves. PayPal grew into a separate line of business, contributing stable income that balanced out eBay&rsquo;s earnings variability. PayPal earns revenue from non-eBay transactions, which is the source of its stable income. To grow PayPal revenue, eBay is getting into open source ecommerce. After all, this area is contributing significant earnings to PayPal. Why not become a huge purveyor of ecommerce to drive it&rsquo;s PayPal income. And, if this area can cover its costs and add to the bottom line, all the better. At least, that&rsquo;s how I see it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>eBay&rsquo;s annual and quarterly reports are at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://investor.ebayinc.com/annuals.cfm\" target=\"_blank\">http://investor.ebayinc.com/annuals.cfm</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Page 10 of the 2011 Annual Report describes X-Commerce:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>In addition to our reportable segments, in 2011, we launched a business initiative of cloud-based commerce tools called X.commerce.&nbsp;X.commerce is a platform that provides software developers access to our APIs to develop functionality for merchants of all sizes. By bringing&nbsp;together the technology assets and developer communities of eBay, PayPal and Magento, an ecommerce storefront platform we acquired in&nbsp;August 2011, the X.commerce ecosystem provides tools that are designed to drive innovation for online, mobile, social and local commerce.&nbsp;Merchants can use these tools to create web storefronts, track sales and collect payments. We also have an application store called Magento&nbsp;Connect where developers can market and sell add-on functionality and solutions to merchants that use a Magento storefront.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Segmented information on page 55. Revenues associated with X.commerce, which was launched in conjunction with our acquisition of Magento in the&nbsp;third quarter of 2011, was $7.7Million. This is the first quarter of revenue for X.commerce, a LoB that is expected to contribute significant revenues.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My question to you is: why should we contribute to a corporate behemoth&rsquo;s value by participating in their ecosystem? This is the worst private sector economy since the Dirty Thirties, so it is as incumbent upon us, the user community, to retain the value we represent for ourselves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The money we spend on our ecommerce technology is valuable. Banding together to aggregate this spending on targeted, relevant features &mdash; utilizing continuous deployment tools and techniques &mdash; allows us to retain the value of this spending, and to lever it. Directly controlling &amp; managing our ecommerce technology we use on our sites gives us the ability to harvest extra RoI that is coveted by the corporate behemoths.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&rsquo;ll increase our income, and our wealth, faster by creating our own ecosystem instead of participating in someone else&rsquo;s ecosystem.</p>\r\n', 'WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Corporations value your participation in their eco-systems. That is your indication of your participation\'s real value. You should create your own eco-system so you can accrue that value to yourself -- especially to build asset value. Corporations are building their share value on your participation. ', '', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/keep-your-value-in-the-family', 'godfather3.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-09', '2012-07-09 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-09 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(39, 0, NULL, NULL, 'How We’re Giving Back to FoF', 'how-were-giving-back-to-fof', '<p>Last week, Nicholas Dionysopoulos corresponded with me via email about his FoF.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 and FoF are become very good friends.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nicholas, in his usual graciousness, let me publish his missives to me.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>The way I understand it, it&rsquo;s best for you to produce short developer-oriented blogs about tips &amp; tricks using FoF. I would recommend doing that in a way which allows people to comment. It&rsquo;s incredible how much useful information you can get by discussing code. A lot of FoF features owe their presence to discussions help in Joomla! conferences around the globe and discussions with the early adopters.&nbsp;From that point, once you have enough information which may be relevant for other developers, we can pull them into the main wiki at Assembla, of course giving credit where credit&rsquo;s due.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As for contacting me with ideas etc, Assembla is the perfect place. It has a wiki and a ticket system, very well integrated with its merge request facility. As you&rsquo;ll see, nobody has ever sent me a patch file. It&rsquo;s all about fork it, fix it, do a merge request. A lot of discussion took place over merge requests. It&rsquo;s the most efficient method, actually! Talking about code which is right there, spotting problems, fixing them, integrating them, within minutes or hours. It&rsquo;s a very organic process. It&rsquo;s fun, even!</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>I know Nicholas is irritated that I do not enable commenting on my blogs. However, at his urging, for my FoF articles, I shall enable!</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>Regarding commenting, it&rsquo;s one thing having public comments for a generic opinion article and a completely different thing having public comments for an article about code. The former attracts all kinds of haters and trolls and I certainly understand why you don&rsquo;t want comments. The latter, however, attracts hardcore geeks. Discussion can get passionate, but tends to lean towards the &ldquo;productive&rdquo; site.</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>On the one hand, comments are disabled on my Media and Blog sites. On the other hand, I installed a dedicated innovative social site for full blast commenting for my Club Commerce Members. This is my Yin/Yang &mdash; I do not want to deal with the public!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, I said it. The retail public is not my cup of tea.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>BTDT. At the height of my Virtuemart days, I ran a free public forum to support my free public VM downloads. Most people who contacted me were a bunch of fucking assholes. I tried to put it in a fun, non-offensive way in my&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=106&amp;Itemid=220\" target=\"_blank\">Membership is not a Trojan Horse for Free Consulting</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Due to this direct experience, I&rsquo;m not going to offer LaSalleMart for free download. Ev-ah. Heck, I took down my demo site! &ndash;&gt; UPDATE: Actually, planning a special edition of LaSalleMart for free download.<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2012/why-lasallemart-is-not-available-for-free-download\" target=\"_blank\">See newer blog post</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Commenting is really good for SEO. It adds fresh content, and it promotes more eyeballs. So, I&rsquo;m a contrarian. I publish my posts to Facebook anyways, so you can comment there. If a comment ever pops up on Facebook that inspires my passions, I will &mdash; naturally &mdash; post on my own blog.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.assembla.com/spaces/lasallemart/\" target=\"_blank\">LaSalleMart is now on Assembla.com</a>, which was always in the plans anyways. Take it from the guy who interviewed&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2010/tbbs12\" target=\"_blank\">Assembla&rsquo;s Founder in 2010</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): The FOF Google Group was the place where the threads happen.&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Last week, Nicholas Dionysopoulos corresponded with me via email about his FoF. LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 and FoF are become very good friends. Nicholas, in his usual graciousness, let me publish his missives to me.', 'Last week, Nicholas Dionysopoulos corresponded with me via email about his FoF. LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 and FoF are become very good friends. Nicholas, in his usual graciousness, let me publish his missives to me.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/how-were-giving-back-to-fof', 'blackboard1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-09', '2012-07-09 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-09 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(40, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Testimonials: It’s Happening – LaSalleMart is Making Headway', 'testimonials-its-happening-lasallemart-is-making-headway', '<p>A place where LaSalleMart interest is nascently percolating is the<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/pages/Joomla-User-Group-Toronto/145858875482603\" target=\"_blank\">Joomla User Group Toronto&rsquo;s Facebook page</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which makes sense since most Club Commerce Founding Members are JUGT regulars. It&rsquo;s a great connection to the Joomla project. Through Club Commerce, I want to give back to JUGT &mdash; and JUGSWO &mdash; and by extension (wow, am I funny today!) to the Joomla project.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Geez, it&rsquo;s through JUGT that I was introduced to Tienda. JUGT hosted a Tienda seminar. I am grateful for the wonderful connections and look forward to Club Commerce being an active JUGT and JUGSWO sponsor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ah,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/groups/Joomla.User.Group.Toronto/\" target=\"_blank\">here is the Facebook link</a>. There&rsquo;s two FB JUGT pages &mdash; Alan explained it to me but I forget why. Zach&rsquo;s June 25th post &mdash; read the comments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s happening!</p>\r\n', 'A place where LaSalleMart interest is nascently percolating is the Joomla User Group Toronto’s Facebook page...', 'A place where LaSalleMart interest is nascently percolating is the Joomla User Group Toronto’s Facebook page...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/testimonials-its-happening-lasallemart-is-making-headway', 'graph1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-09', '2012-07-09 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-09 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(41, 0, NULL, NULL, 'My Fellow Canucksters: Time to Sign-up for Club Commerce Membership', 'time-to-sign-up', '<p>Here we are. Finally. Time to sign-up Club Commerce Members.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>300 Club Commerce Members. That&rsquo;s it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Right now, beyond my handful of fabulous Founding Members, there are no further Club Commerce Members.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That means I am asking you to be first to sign up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It sure would be easier if I had 270 Members paying the $36CDN/month, and contributing a further $83.33CDN (or possibly USD)/month to hired programmers, and then asking you to be one of my last 30 Members, before I close the door to Membership altogether.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To my fellow Canadians, and particularly those in the extended GTA (Davis Drive to Lake Ontario, Whitby to Guelph/Waterloo, and Niagara area), you &nbsp;have a vested interested joining.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A critical mass of Members from the JUGT and JUGSWO &nbsp;areas justifies personal meet-up, classroom style sessions, and JUGT/JUGSWO joint event planning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No Joomla cart is made in Canada. Until now. LaSalleMart is the first, and only, full featured Joomla cart made in Canada by Canadians, and frankly, for Canadians. To honour Club Commerce&rsquo;s first meet-up, we may meet at a Timmies to really savour the milestone. Maybe we should call LaSalleMart Canada for Joomla 2.5 &ldquo;double double&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We have something very special here. Which is why I am asking you to be un-Canadian in your pursuit of it: be the first to sign up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is where the main J<a href=\"http://extensions.joomla.org/extensions/e-commerce/shopping-cart\" target=\"_blank\">oomla cart extension</a>s are located:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>JoomShopping: Germany;</li>\r\n	<li>HikaShop: France;</li>\r\n	<li>RedShop: Denmark;</li>\r\n	<li>SimpleCaddy: Texas! As it&rsquo;s listing in JED says, &ldquo;without the need of setting up a complete shop&rdquo;;</li>\r\n	<li>JoomAce: Turkey;</li>\r\n	<li>VirtueMart: Germany;</li>\r\n	<li>Tienda: New York.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>BTW, I have no intention of listing LaSalleMart on the JED. But that&rsquo;s another story&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Interestingly, only one full featured cart is made in the USA. Did I miss one? And it is this cart that LaSalleMart is forking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here is your opportunity to take care of home.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I know that I am frustrated that there&rsquo;s a lack of home-grown Canadian Joomla ecommerce; and, that I am proud to lead the way. But, alas, I am not the only one.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zach Atkinson is working very hard on LaSalleMart with me. He asks right off the bat, &ldquo;<a href=\"http://zatk.ca/2012/06/20/a-canadian-take-on-e-commerce/#more-34\" target=\"_blank\">Why is it such a pain to find a Canadian solution for Joomla online shopping?</a>&ldquo;. Forget that it&rsquo;s a pain, it&rsquo;s impossible. There isn&rsquo;t one. Again, did I miss something? Did I miss something beyond someone in Quebec ripping off my free HST/PST/GST add-on for Virtuemart 1.1.x?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My Club Commerce is meant for people like you: site owners and consultants to site owners. Club Commerce lets us vertically integrate into code development, which opens up vast business opportunities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Club Commerce is a made-in-Canada innovation, based on the &ldquo;Hackerpreneur&rdquo; ideas and site of the Anahita Social Network &mdash; two more fellow Canadians in Vancouver!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m a third generation Torontonian (don&rsquo;t hold that against me!). Half my Club Commerce Founding Members belong to Joomla User Group Toronto. I was first to bring HST/PST/GST to Virtuemart, and I was first to bring it to Tienda &mdash; and of course it&rsquo;s now built into LaSalleMart Canada. And this is just the start of the Canadianization we can bring to our full featured Joomla cart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Time is now for me to push for Membership sign-ups &mdash; especially right here in my Home and Native Land.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The time is now for you to join my Club Commerce at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/index.php?option=com_akeebasubs&amp;view=level&amp;Itemid=231\">http://www.southlasalle.com/index.php?option=com_akeebasubs&amp;view=level&amp;Itemid=231</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Looking forward to meeting you on the inside,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Bob</p>\r\n', 'No Joomla cart is made in Canada. Until now. LaSalleMart is the first, and only, full featured Joomla cart made in Canada by Canadians, and frankly, for Canadians. To honour Club Commerce’s first meet-up, we may meet at a Timmies to really savour the milestone. Maybe we should call LaSalleMart Canada for Joomla 2.5 “double double”...', 'No Joomla cart is made in Canada. Until now. LaSalleMart is the first, and only, full featured Joomla cart made in Canada by Canadians, and frankly, for Canadians. To honour Club Commerce’s first meet-up, we may meet at a Timmies to really savour the mile', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/time-to-sign-up', 'canadian_flag.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-10', '2012-07-10 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-10 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(42, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Framework on Framework: Adding Drop-Down Form Fields', 'framework-on-framework-adding-drop-down-form-fields', '<p>The sample Framework on Framework (aka FoF) &ldquo;To-Do&rdquo; component uses a helper file (administrator/components/ com_todo/helper/select.php) within the component to create drop-down form fields. Such as, a drop down &ldquo;yes/no&rdquo; form field.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Knowing that I will have a lot of small-ish components comprising the new LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 admin, it&rsquo;s preferable to have this helper file in FoF itself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, what I did was move the select.php file to /libraries/fof/, and rename it &ldquo;select.utils.php&rdquo;. The new filename reflects the fiilename convention of helper-type files already in FoF.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I changed the class to:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>class FOFSelectUtils extends JAdministratorHelper</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>As well, I added a $separator parameter to several methods, and shoehorned in IF statements, so I can omit the separator option. I do not want &ldquo;&ndash;select&ndash;/yes/no&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Furthermore, I added a new method called &ldquo;referencetable&rdquo;, to display the records of a static reference table. For example, there&rsquo;s a table listing available currencies. Which currency do you want as your Default Currency? This new method creates the drop-down form field &ldquo;US Dollar/Euro/Japanese Yen/Canadian Dollar&rdquo; based on the #__lasallemart_currencies table.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I still have that ../helper/select.php file in my component. But, now, it&rsquo;s strictly for stuff unique to my component. Since the basic form field code is gone, it&rsquo;s a lot smaller now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On deck is the multiple selection drop-down form field. Then, I&rsquo;ll&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2012/how-were-giving-back-to-fof\" target=\"_blank\">fork FoF, add my handiwork, and do a pull (merge) request</a>. By early next week. Surely, in time for the next Toronto JUG meet-up so I can blab about my exploits.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The truth is, as amazed that my file worked the first time I tried it (!), my new helper file is very mundane and based on fine work already done.</p>\r\n', 'The sample Framework on Framework (aka FoF) “To-Do” component uses a helper file (administrator/components/ com_todo/helper/select.php) within the component to create drop-down form fields. Such as, a drop down “yes/no” form field...', 'The sample Framework on Framework (aka FoF) “To-Do” component uses a helper file (administrator/components/ com_todo/helper/select.php) within the component to create drop-down form fields. Such as, a drop down “yes/no” form field...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/framework-on-framework-adding-drop-down-form-fields', 'mae_west1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-12', '2012-07-12 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-12 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(43, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Mid July LaSalleMart Status', 'mid-july-lasallemart-status', '<p>Another month already!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Through a referral, talked to a potential client about the ecomm site they want to build. For the first time ev-ah since freelancing, I felt powerful. Like the gutteral revs of a motorcycle engine type of powerful.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whatever the feature list, I knew it could be done. In-house. No more wondering if someone else&rsquo;s cart I specialize in would have a promised feature released on time. No more trying to build a missing core feature without touching the core source files.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That&rsquo;s the power of Club membership. Individually, you can&rsquo;t be in the technology. But, together, by banding together, we are in the technology business. That makes us very powerful.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This month I migrated a Tienda Canada Distro to LaSalleMart Canada. It is in a dev site, it&rsquo;s not gone live. It was a PITA, as migration is a purely manual affair. Yuck. Zach and I will now test/improve PayPal Pro.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If we can defer doing Canada Post, we will. I am conflicted, to be honest, about all LaSalleMart for Joomla 1.5 work because the need to convert to Joomla 2.5 is hu-mon-gous. Shouldn&rsquo;t we put every effort into the conversion? If we can manage to defer Canada Post, then great. If not, maybe we should pass the hat and hire a dev to do it. Something that will be worth talking about with Club Commerce Members.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My Membership Drive, so to speak, started yesterday. The thought of doing is thrilled me so much that I did more programming after publishing my final marketing blog post. I&rsquo;m at 0 new Members out of 300. Today I will post in a few sites, and start contacting people individually.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If I didn&rsquo;t absolutely completely fully understand the magnitude of the benefits derived from Club Commerce, I&rsquo;d drop it in a nanosecond.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Changing tact here to my Members-only Anahita site&hellip; I know that this site&rsquo;s template is messed up a bit. However, it&rsquo;s a dev version of Anahita Social Engine version 2.0. The final version is very nearly done &mdash; in fact there&rsquo;s a new pre-final version to install that I&rsquo;ve not installed yet &mdash; and it&rsquo;s worth it to leave alone and wait for the final version. The deeper reason is that Ash and Rastin are using Bootstrap for the first time, and with each iteration they get better with Bootstrap &amp; integrating it into Anahita. So, we&rsquo;ll bear with them all the way, and then we&rsquo;ll be using a live site with Bootstrap that we can reference for LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ok, let&rsquo;s talk about com_lmadminconfig. &nbsp;Would prefer to call it &ldquo;com_lasallemart_administration_general_configuration&rdquo;, but the shorter the better.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead of figuring out how to convert Tienda&rsquo;s admin component to Joomla 2.5, I am busting it up into a bunch of smaller components, and basically starting from scratch where possible. Starting with the &ldquo;easiest&rdquo; chunk of the admin, the &ldquo;General Configuration&rdquo;. The admin itself is purely a means to update the database. So, using Akeeba&rsquo;s &ldquo;Framework on Framework&rdquo; should be a Big Help in writing &ldquo;BREAD&rdquo; functions (browse, read, edit, add, delete records).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My assumption about who is using LaSalleMart is different than the &nbsp;usual. I assume it&rsquo;s not a consumer. Who is using LaSalleMart? People who are integrating into software development. It&rsquo;s very important to do things in a standard way, because we-the-members-of-Club-Commerce want to get software onto our sites as fast as possible. So, displaying all the config options in a single form is not a priority. Let&rsquo;s stick to what FoF was made for, and not just bull ahead with a custom form. Config records change infrequently, and the intention is to initialize them as much as possible during installation, so editing one single record at a time is not unreasonable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another things is that we have to be careful not to stuff all sorts of shit into our existing components. What I am finding is that there are so many exceptions with the configuration that the exceptions are the standard.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One thing that is irritating is that the configuration codes are not used in the language strings. It sure would be easier if the same code were used throughout the component, so it would be easy to recognize what goes with which. Not to mention, makes it easier to program! Why hard-code the name of the language string when we can use a variable?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, bet your ass there&rsquo;s refactoring going on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One thing that I am &nbsp;doing is adding reference tables in the database. I want a standard way of using codes, which is have a small static table listing the codes. This is done with currencies already: #__lasallemart_currencies is a teeny tiny table whose records are currency codes. I don&rsquo;t want to hard code codes, and I don&rsquo;t want to use the &ldquo;enum&rdquo; field type in the tables. I want to use standard reference tables, and then use FoF so I have to do a one line call to build the drop-down field. Based on fine work already done, I wrote this ability into FoF.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If we at Club Commerce really want to create decent software fast, then we better give a shit about how we construct our software. The &ldquo;I&rsquo;m a user so I don&rsquo;t care how you do it&rdquo; attitude doesn&rsquo;t cut it here, because this is completely anti-thetical to what we are setting out to achieve. We can&rsquo;t vertically integrate into software development and simultaneously not give a shit about developing software.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s not about the features! The power is in the ability to create features AND bring those features to real sites. Learning and using FoF &mdash; and getting involved in that project &mdash; now instead of later &ndash;refactoring the non-standard stuff. Well, here we go!</p>\r\n', 'WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): On a small scale I had achieved my Club concept...', '', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/mid-july-lasallemart-status', 'update2.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-15', '2012-07-15 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-15 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(44, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Free LaSalleMart Version and JED Listing', 'why-lasallemart-is-not-available-for-free-download', '<p>Today on the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/groups/Joomla.User.Group.Toronto/\" target=\"_blank\">Joomla User Group Toronto Facebook page</a>, I was asked:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>&hellip; can I get a look at LaSalleMart possibly give it a trial?</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>My eyes read &ldquo;can I get a look at LaSallemart possibly give it a trial?&rdquo;. My ears heard &ldquo;can I get a FREE look at LaSalleMart possibly give it a FREE trial?&rdquo;. My head interpreted it as &ldquo;Can I get LaSalleMart for free?&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here&rsquo;s the bottom line on a freebie version of LaSalleMart: once LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 is done, and once we figured out how we will intermediate Joomla (another blog post, but not today!), &nbsp;we will release a basic Joomla Distro of LaSalleMart called &ldquo;LaSalleMart Lite&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It will have the basic feature set.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s raison d&rsquo;etre will be to&nbsp;let the public kick the LaSalleMart tires. A segment of the marketplace will be satisfied with the feature set offered, and we&rsquo;re happy to satisfy that marketplace.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, a couple of things. First, we&rsquo;re going to have to release simultaneous versions of &ldquo;LaSalleMart Lite&rdquo; &mdash; for Canada, for the rest of the world , for California (perhaps); and, for whatever jurisdiction there is a demand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Secondly, there is little chance that an all encompassing all-in-one installation routine will be created for LaSalleMart. Why? Because the Joomla installer represents a technical and psychological bottleneck, that&rsquo;s why! LaSalleMart will be comprised of a lot of disparate pieces, and the intention is to create a matrix of custom Joomla Distros to put those pieces together. The &ldquo;LaSalleMart Lite&rdquo; series of Distros will be a subset of the entire matrix of Joomla Distros we will create/maintain within Club Commerce.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once the &ldquo;LaSalleMart Lite&rdquo; Distros are locked-and-loaded, we will solicit the JED to list LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We could do some work with the LaSalleMart 1.0 for Joomla 1.5 that we have, but to drive on the highway to Joomla 2.5 we need to resist the sideroads.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, in the here-and-now, there is no free version of LaSalleMart for download, nor a JED listing. In due time!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UPDATE: I much prefer that LaSalleMart/Club Commerce stand on its own two feet, and not depend on other sites for referrals. In particular, but not excluding, the JED.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://forum.joomla.org/viewtopic.php?f=262&amp;t=733562\" target=\"_blank\">You never know when your referrals go poof</a>.</p>\r\n', 'WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Maybe someone can point to how I am supposed to achieve ROI giving away the store (pun intended). LaSalleMart 2 never made it to the Joomla Extensions Directory...', '', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/why-lasallemart-is-not-available-for-free-download', 'foss1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-17', '2012-07-17 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-17 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(45, 0, NULL, NULL, 'In Plain English, Here’s the Gist of LaSalleMart and Club Commerce', 'plain-english-gist', '<p>UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014):</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember being accused of not being incapable of stating the &quot;Value Proposition&quot; because I am a programmer. Just because I talk slowly and pause a lot does not mean I am incapable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Just because you&#39;ve met techies who are not familiar with the business side of things, does not mean that I suffer from a similar affliction. Maybe my senior year marketing courses at one of Canada&#39;s top undergrad business programs has put too many ideas into my head that does not fit into an &quot;elevator pitch&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the age of instant gratification and permanent attention deficit. Don&#39;t have that perfect &quot;elevator&quot; pitch ready, that&#39;s it. Well, how about: the software I forked never went live, but mine did go live.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will have more to say on this!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>===================================================================</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Today in the Toronto Joomla Group&rsquo;s Facebook page, I was asked to use &ldquo;Plain English&rdquo; with my explanations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fair enough!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here&rsquo;s the gist:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Club Commerce is a co-operative of consultants who are vertically integrating into software development.<br />\r\nClub Commerce is NOT, repeat NOT, a typical Joomla club that sells software via site subscriptions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s pretty effin&rsquo; expensive doing software development. Not to mention not every consultant can do some sort of coding. Plus, there&rsquo;s a massive amount of software development to do. So, to achieve vertical integration, we band together! It&rsquo;s that simple.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Vertical integration means we create/maintain the software we use for our consulting business.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Vertical integration does NOT, repeat NOT, mean selling our software!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We are vertically integrating into software development because it is good business. Our revenues depend on technology, and we don&rsquo;t want to rely on others for that technology with which our revenues depend.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The $36/month to me is to offset the loss of consulting revenue by leading LaSalleMart/Club Commerce. Otherwise, pursuing</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart will be a side hobby. Or, I end up developing LaSalleMart for a small coterie of monied clients and the general public will not see the LaSalleMart at all &mdash; which is Very Bad.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bad because there are amazing business opportunities for us consultants (and site owners) who &ldquo;do the code&rdquo;.&nbsp;<br />\r\nThe $83.33/month extra per Club Member pays for programmers we hire. Members pay this directly to the programmers, not me. $83.33/month x 12 months x 300 Members = $250,000 in direct programming.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&mdash;-</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Did anyone play the trumpet like&nbsp;<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louis_Armstrong\" target=\"_blank\">Satchmo</a>&nbsp;before Satchmo?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, we&rsquo;re playing Joomla ecommerce, but in a completely different way than anyone has done it before.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Club Commerce/LaSalleMart is new, is different, and is the right fucking response to our unique fucking pressures as consultants in the worse private sector economy since the Dirty Thirties.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&mdash;&ndash;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are the live versions of LaSalleMart:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>LaSalleMart 1.0 for &nbsp;Canada for Joomla 1.5 only;</li>\r\n	<li>LaSalleMart 1.0 for California for Joomla 1.5 only;</li>\r\n	<li>LaSalleMart 1.0 &ldquo;Regular&rdquo; for Joomla 1.5 only.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart is available by subscribing to my Club Commerce. The cost is $36CDN per month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To the best of our knowledge, LaSalleMart Canada is the only full featured Joomla cart maintained by and for Canadians.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To the best of our knowledge, LaSalleMart is the only full featured Joomla cart maintained in North America &mdash; which seems rather incredible. Yet, the Joomla carts are mainly European.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&mdash;&ndash;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 1.0 is a fork of Tienda 0.8.2.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More precisely, LaSalleMart 1.0 is a fork of Bob Bloom&rsquo;s custom Distro for Tienda 0.8.2, which included an add-on for Canadian GST/PST/HST. This Distro was live on a handful of sites before the full fledged fork.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The main differences are:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Akeeba Live Update;</li>\r\n	<li>cleaned up back-to-basics checkout;</li>\r\n	<li>guest checkout and one page checkout deleted;</li>\r\n	<li>custom extension footer;</li>\r\n	<li>registration form layout tweaks;</li>\r\n	<li>some Tienda rough edges smoothed out during UAT for first live site.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>We put in practice the theory we&rsquo;ve been espousing about software builds with tremendous success. There are three simultaneous full featured flavours of LaSalleMart; and, we can get fixes and upgrades onto your site within 10 minutes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&mdash;&ndash;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We are currently working on LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 by converting Tienda 0.8.2 to Joomla 2.5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We assumed that we&rsquo;d do a straight conversion first. Once we had LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 in our hands, then we&rsquo;d start modifying it drastically.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is actually happening is that we are diving into changes whilst converting. I will skip completely the why&rsquo;s and wherefore&rsquo;s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&mdash;&ndash;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We are&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;extension developers,&nbsp;<em>we are consultants</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We decided to&nbsp;<em>vertically integrate</em>&nbsp;into software development because it&nbsp;<em>makes business sense</em>&nbsp;for us.&nbsp;So, we are coming at extension development from the other side, the user side, which is highly unusual! We are blessed with some programming chops, but this is the first time we actually forked a Joomla extension.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once we got into software development, we discovered that there are profound business opportunities from being involved in development.<em>&nbsp;If we had not &ldquo;crossed the line&rdquo;, we&rsquo;d never open our eyes to it.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>These profound business opportunities are based on two things:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>free uber-geeky software process tools;</li>\r\n	<li>we &nbsp;have the code,&nbsp;<em>and</em>&nbsp;the software development process,&nbsp;<em>and</em>&nbsp;the websites &ndash; a powerful edge.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&mdash;&ndash;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Who are we?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We are a very small group of consultants and users who comprise the Founding Members of Club Commerce. There are less than a dozen of us. Most of us live in the GTA, and are active in the JUGT, with a wonderful representative from JUGSWO. All are Canadians, except for an exceptional consultant living in Los Angeles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Of our tiny group of fabulous professionals, Zach Atkinson and myself are the ones doing the actual development right now. It&rsquo;s been a tremendous advantage that we are able to physically meet-up, and it is this powerful collaboration that is motiving me to urge our fellow GTA-ers to be half of the 300 Club Commerce Members &mdash; we have a heckuva opportunity here to kick major Joomla ecomm ass.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&mdash;&ndash;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The purpose of Club Commerce is to band together our peers so we can harvest these business opportunities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Cost sharing is an key component of banding together</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here&rsquo;s an example. Canada Post just announced improvements to its web services. These require fresh coding. Peers banding together to share the costs ensures that these new features are brought to our websites fast.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here&rsquo;s another example: integrating QuickBooks with LaSalleMart. I guess-timate that the inital cost will be $15,000, and yearly maintenance $5,000. QuickBooks Canada is not the same thing as QuickBooks U.S. &nbsp;So, 100 of us Canadians in Club Commerce band together with $150 each to build this integration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Will you be able to serve your local Canadian market better because you have up-to-date Canada Post features? Because you have QuickBooks integration? We know we will!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&mdash;&ndash;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Relying on ourselves, and not relying on others, will put more features in our hands with which to grow our consulting and online businesses. Our clients will make more money, and we will have more billing opportunities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&mdash;&ndash;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Additionally, because Club Commerce Founding Members are mostly people associated with the Joomla User Group Toronto and Joomla User Group SouthWest Ontario, we want at least half our Club Commerce Members to be from the extended GTA area (including Niagara). Why? So we can meet in person to maximize our learning opportunities, talk about LaSalleMart&rsquo;s development one-on-one; and, to give back to JUGT and JUGSWO which have been very good for LaSalleMart. Toronto can be on the forefront of worldwide Joomla ecommerce &mdash; why not!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Bob</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'The GIST of LaSalleMart and Club Commerce...\r\n                        ', '', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/plain-english-gist', 'foss1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-18', '2012-07-18 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-18 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(46, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Anahita 2.0 Birth Release – Why Anahita Matters to us', 'anahita-2-0-birth-release-why-anahita-matters-to-us', '<p>Anahita 2.0 is out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Read about it at the Anahitapolis blog, &ldquo;<a href=\"http://blog.anahitapolis.com/2012/07/so-what-is-new-in-anahita-2-0/\" target=\"_blank\">So what is new in Anahita 2.0</a>&ldquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My Club Members-only site, at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/members\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.southlasalle.com/members</a>, is an Anahita site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ll tell you something: my upgrade failed! I got a &ldquo;fatal error&rdquo;, and then a white screen. Yes, I took extra backups before my upgrade, on top of the usual daily backups. So, I logged into Anahitapolis.com and posted my problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Anahitapolis.com is not your usual forum support site. The entire philosophy is different. Here&rsquo;s one of the<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2011/tbbs43\" target=\"_blank\">&nbsp;podcasts</a>&nbsp;we&rsquo;ve done about it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve mentioned this before, but it really happened&hellip; I had three sites to upgrade last night. Kids sleeping, decide I can&rsquo;t put it off any longer, I upgrade my two WordPress sites &amp; my Anahita site. I do the backups, and the WordPress sites upgrade fine. Not just WordPress itself, but Genesis Framework upgrade, the usual batch of plugins, and of course have to reset WordBooker plugin. Whew, all went fine. Then, Anahita upgrade. Fail fail fail. Fatal Error. Copy error message. 500 error too! I download the upgrade package and manually upload all the files (theory: will correct copy error). Fail fail fail!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m human. I got upset. As in, really upset. So I took a breath, and reminded myself that when I post in Anahitapolis, Ash or Rastin will personally read and reply to it. You think I&rsquo;m joking, but I am not. My behavioiur in Anahitapolis.com is much much different than in regular forums (which I haven&rsquo;t bothered with in a while, now that I think of it), because it&rsquo;s a social Hackerpreneur Club website, not a support forum. Professionals participate in the site, and the developers themselves are uber-active in it. So, it&rsquo;s far far better to take a deep breath and provide an intelligent post so they can help me as best they can. Put another way, my confidence is so high that I will receive the help I need, that I did what I could to help them help me. So after calming down from my frustration hissy-fit, I posted stats on my environment and error messages and crossed my fingers that it would be an easy diagnoses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is what I want in my own Members-only Club Site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The diagnoses is not easy: migrating from version 1.6 to 2.0 is not cut-and-dried. Ok&hellip; I am contemplating doing a fresh install, since I can get away with it this one last time. This would be my third from-scratch install of Anahita. Version 1.5, version 1.6, and version 2.0. From here, there will need to be a migration&hellip; and I&rsquo;m sure to post about this after all is said and done on Anahitapolis.com.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Have you heard my &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2012/tbbs51\" target=\"_blank\">Learning from Ash and Rastin</a>&rdquo; podcast? You can read &lsquo;em as well as listen&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UPDATE: Rastin tweeted that he warned me about using an &ldquo;embryo&rdquo; release. Anahita 1.6 was an &ldquo;embryo&rdquo; release, indeed. Well, v2.0 is intended for production sites, so, fresh install this weekend-ish&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Anahita is an ongoing project at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.getanahita.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.getanahita.com</a>.</p>\r\n', 'WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): I think what I wrote and my title are different! Well, I still keep up with Anahita as it progresses. ', '', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/anahita-2-0-birth-release-why-anahita-matters-to-us', 'anahita.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-19', '2012-07-19 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-19 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(47, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Tienda Alpha for Joomla 2.5: LaSalleMart is Going Its Own Way', 'tienda-alpha-joomla-25-lasallemart-going-its-own-way', '<p>Are we going to use it to create LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Reading these blog posts, it pains me to read how I struggled with Tienda which basically stopped developing; and, then confronted the Joomla versions which kept obsoleting my software. I am sure the Joomla 1.5 obsolescence was a big part of Tienda&#39;s demise, although I suspect not the only reason. Boy, was all this software obsolescence e-x-p-e-n-s-i-v-e.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart is a fork of Tienda 0.8.2, which is a Joomla 1.5 cart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 is&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;a fork of Tienda for Joomla 2.5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&rsquo;ve&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;been waiting around for Tienda for Joomla 2.5 to roll around so we can fork it.&nbsp;&nbsp;It&rsquo;s already been forked!</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>You can go your own way!<br />\r\nGo your own way<br />\r\nYou can call it another lonely day<br />\r\nAnother lonely day<br />\r\nYou can go your own way!<br />\r\nGo your own way<br />\r\nYou can call it another lonely day</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"375\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/6ul-cZyuYq4?feature=oembed\" width=\"500\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a bunch of reasons why we are going our own way with LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 right off the bat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It took a shitload of work doing the initial fork (FYI: more precisely, we forked my custom Tienda Distro), getting Live Update going, splitting Tienda into multiple GitHub repos, and figuring out Phing to create three simultaneous flavours. Then, Zach and I worked our tushes off collaborating for the first live site&rsquo;s UAT.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Geez, I talk about Zach a lot, basically a kid who was involved in my software development, and then vanished, basically, in&nbsp;the middle of the night. Zach had very little to do with LaSalleMart uno, duo, and treize. Whatever he contributed, great. I give the impression that he contributed 50,000 lines of code or something. Very interesting reading all my four years of posts in one go, with the benefit of hindsight.</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zach and I had met personally during the UAT to discuss the live site; and, to talk about converting to Joomla 2.5. We agreed that we would strip out a ton of stuff, convert a &ldquo;lean mean&rdquo; LaSalleMart, and then we would build up feature upon feature via Club Commerce. After all, the Club is supposed to be a feature creation machine!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, once that live site was humming, I checked on the status of the Tienda for Joomla 2.5 project, as the time to convert LaSalleMart to Joomla 2.5 had come. The status: it was a work in progress. So, &nbsp;no code to study. No problemo.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, the intention was to get the massive single extension reduced to a merely huge single extension, convert it to Joomla 2.5, and then, essentially, start the &ldquo;real&rdquo; LaSalleMart development. Our goal is simply to get a LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 to get the ball rolling.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, finally, I sat down to start the conversion. It took 20 minutes to realize what a crock of shit our approach was. I asked Zach, how the hell are we supposed to know if our conversion efforts are working? Are we supposed to magically do the conversion, then install it on Joomla 2.5, and voila! Then start the debug?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Our UAT work had me returning to the Tienda download page to confirm something I remember reading. Yup, there was a caveat on that download page, warning that Tienda was a &ldquo;production beta&rdquo; and, there are things that may not work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, y&rsquo;know, we were making an assumption without realizing it. We were assuming that Tienda was &ldquo;convertible&rdquo; as-is. If something doesn&rsquo;t work, then will that introduce problems while converting? Which is faster: making Tienda production-ready first in Joomla 1.5, and then converting; or, converting and hoping there are no real obstacles to conversion? Only hindsight has the answers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s a technical term I learned in my computer science courses: &ldquo;Fuck It!&rdquo;. That was my solution. We would go our own way right away. The point of having an intermediate step was to make things easier, so we could get our foothold in 2.5. Well, there&rsquo;s no easy intermediate step, there&rsquo;s just a bunch of hard decisions to make.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zach was exactly right to kick my ass to convert my custom Tienda Distro into LaSalleMart. Exactly right that I should stop marketing Club Commerce and put sweat equity into LaSalleMart. BTW, he did so in person, in a consummate professional manner &mdash; something that motivates me to reach out to my fellow GTA-ers to form the bulk of my Club Commerce Members. However, all that time I spent enumerating how Club Commerce will work, and how there&rsquo;s supra-RoI inherent in the development process, has its effect: I have a razor sharp vision of LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the end, we are creating LaSalleMart anyways. We are not setting out to create an idyllic version of Tienda; nor, is our objective to create a Joomla 2.5 version of Tienda. Tienda is our starting point, and a great starting point. But, LaSalleMart will eventually lose all its Tienda-ness anyways. If this starts sooner than later, then it starts sooner than later.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&rsquo;re going to bust up LaSalleMart into a ton of repos &mdash; so, let&rsquo;s start that now. We&rsquo;re going to strip away all the Tienda Framework anyways, so let&rsquo;s start that now. We&rsquo;re going to remove all the cross-selling extensions, so let&rsquo;s clean it up now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&rsquo;re going our own way because we know the way we&rsquo;re going.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, I sat down and did something amazing. I took what I think is the simplest piece of the admin and<em>started from scratch</em>. And, it worked! Oh boy, did it work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You know what I did? I took Nicholas&rsquo; sample component for his Framework on Framework (aka &ldquo;FoF&rdquo;), and created a different General Configuration form. In a fell swoop, I completely sidestepped conversion, and I completely sidestepped all the clean-up. Hopefully, this approach will work through the admin, because, gee, after all, the admin is one big &ldquo;front end&rdquo; for the database. I have my doubts, but I&rsquo;ll cross the bridges as I get to them. The General Config involves some clean-up, but that&rsquo;s another blog post.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I ended up adding to the &ldquo;FoF&rdquo;. I&rsquo;ve not made a pull request yet, but I will. To be honest, I&rsquo;m wondering if I should fork &ldquo;FoF&rdquo;, start a new LaSalleMart library, or what. Although I have an idea what to do, I&rsquo;ll be putting these ideas to Zach next week when we meet for the Toronto Joomla meet-up. Although I&rsquo;ve bugged him already.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We certainly have enough material to cover already for our first Club Commerce meet-up, when local Membership grows!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Something to remember, of course, is that Tienda released an alpha. Meaning it&rsquo;s released for testing. My only interest is to study the code. And my interest doing that right now is reflected in my not having downloaded it, and have no plans to do so.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>&nbsp;You can go your own way!<br />\r\nGo your own way<br />\r\nYou can call it another lonely day</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', 'WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): It\'s not as if I set out to create my own ecommerce software. But, in painful slow motion that\'s what happened. Today (mid 2014) there is no slow motion: blog app, e-broadcasting app, CRM-ticket-project app, ecommerce apps all lined up for the rest of this year. Welcome to my Laravel era!', '', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/tienda-alpha-joomla-25-lasallemart-going-its-own-way', 'fleetwood-mac-rumours-1977-album-cover.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-19', '2012-07-19 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-19 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(48, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Toronto Joomla User Group Meet-up, July 2012', 'toronto-joomla-user-group-meet-up-july-2012', '<p>On a rainy mid-summer&rsquo;s evening, just two JUGT regulars shlepped out to the Firkin at Yonge @ Sheppard on Wednesday July 25th.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yup, just me and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.linkedin.com/pub/douglas-pickett/14/15a/984\" target=\"_blank\">Douglas</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You&rsquo;d think that it was a lousy turnout, but our Joomla meet-up was a raging success! Why? Because, the fact that we got to know each other at these JUGT&rsquo;s led to a request to help with a project.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So we spent our time well, discussing Joomla with a certain intensity over pub fare, talking about a real project. No hypothetical scenarios, no discussions about state of the JED (confession: it was a nice break!). We talked about how the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2012/how-were-giving-back-to-fof\" target=\"_blank\">Framework on Framework</a>&nbsp;(aka &ldquo;FoF&rdquo;) really does save time writing components, using reference tables, using repositories and Phing, test-driven development, and a bunch of other things specific to the project.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Attending Joomla meet-ups is as much about getting to know fellow Joomla pros as it is learning about Joomla. For me, getting to know the JUGT regulars over the years has proved a massive plus for my Joomla freelance consulting business. How satisfying it is to help a newer regular in a similar fashion that I myself was welcomed when I was a &ldquo;newer regular&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bring your problems to the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://toronto.joomla.ca/jugt-events/event-registration/details/46-august-2012-pub-night\" target=\"_blank\">August 22nd JUGT meet-up in Yorkville</a>. Hope that just a few of us make it down, so you have us all to yourself!</p>\r\n', 'On a rainy mid-summer’s evening, just two JUGT regulars shlepped out to the Firkin at Yonge @ Sheppard on Wednesday July 25th...', 'On a rainy mid-summer’s evening, just two JUGT regulars shlepped out to the Firkin at Yonge @ Sheppard on Wednesday July 25th...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/toronto-joomla-user-group-meet-up-july-2012', 'toronto_skyline_day1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-25', '2012-07-25 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-25 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(49, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Framework on Framework and Managing Joomla Versions', 'framework-on-framework-managing-joomla-versions', '<p>Something that&rsquo;s been on my mind for a while is how to manage Joomla versions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Imagine, if &nbsp;you would, Club Commerce at full membership, whose Members contributed a quarter million dollars in direct software development, and confronting the release of Joomla 3.0.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What if Joomla 3.0 makes much of that quarter-mill investment in Joomla 2.5 development obsolete? Or partially obsolete?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How do we manage these Joomla versions to protect our investment?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This question came to mind reading the Nicholas&rsquo; reply to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://akeeba.assembla.com/spaces/fof/tickets/18\" target=\"_blank\">a &ldquo;Future of FoF&rdquo; ticket</a>&nbsp;(this quote is an excertp):</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Right now the biggest challenge is Joomla!&rsquo;s MVC future. Since Joomla! 3.0 the JModel / JController / JView names are used by Interfaces and the new MVC structure which has nothing to do with the old one and pretty much screws all fools who did things the Joomla! Way. The old structure is retained in the Legacy classes, e.g. JModelLegacy. Despite no plan actually existing, I suspect that the Legacy classes will be dropped. When that happens&nbsp;<strong>I will include them inside FOF</strong>. If the other Joomla! Platform classes FOF depends on are re-fuck-tored too, I will provide my own alternatives. In other words I am going to grow FOF as the Joomla! features it depends on are spirited away between Joomla! releases. This will asymptotically lead to a new framework but, as I said, backwards compatibility is king. The only real reason for me to break it is a new PHP version making it impossible to keep it.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>FoF (FOF?!) reduces code required to write components; and, helps today&rsquo;s components work in tomorrow&rsquo;s Joomla. Very interesting, and a welcome solution to an emerging pressure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&rsquo;ll have to talk about this within my Club, as it grows.</p>\r\n', 'Something that’s been on my mind for a while is how to manage Joomla versions. ==> IN HINDSIGHT, THAT IS AN EFFIN\' UNDERSTATEMENT. Given the impossibility of the task, even the brilliant Akeeba Framework on Framework could not \"manage\" Joomla versions. ', 'Something that’s been on my mind for a while is how to manage Joomla versions. ==> IN HINDSIGHT, THAT IS AN EFFIN\' UNDERSTATEMENT. Given the impossibility of the task, even the brilliant Akeeba Framework on Framework could not \"manage\" Joomla versions. ', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/framework-on-framework-managing-joomla-versions', 'investments1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-07-28', '2012-07-28 12:00:00', 1, '2012-07-28 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(50, 0, NULL, NULL, 'What and Why is LaSalleMart and Club Commerce (video)', 'what-and-why-is-lasallemart-and-club-commerce-video', '<p>How is it that a Joomla ecommerce consultant decided to fork one of the full featured monolithic Joomla cart extensions; and, decided that the best way to fork it is with a hackerpreneur club?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead of another blog post, I did a video instead.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/W5pQT5f8Q1E?rel=0\" width=\"640\"></iframe></p>\r\n', 'How is it that a Joomla ecommerce consultant decided to fork one of the full featured monolithic Joomla cart extensions; and, decided that the best way to fork it is with a hackerpreneur club?\r\nInstead of another blog post, I did a video instead.', 'How is it that a Joomla ecommerce consultant decided to fork one of the full featured monolithic Joomla cart extensions; and, decided that the best way to fork it is with a hackerpreneur club?\r\nInstead of another blog post, I did a video instead.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/what-and-why-is-lasallemart-and-club-commerce-video', 'what_and_why.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-08-05', '2012-08-05 12:00:00', 1, '2012-08-05 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(51, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Thank you to Nicholas Dionysopoulos and a New Client', 'thank-you-to-nicholas-dionysopoulos-a-new-client-and-a-note-about-fof', '<p><strong>UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): FOF absolutely essential to LaSalleMart. LM3 was basically a FOF technology wrapped in Joomla.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nicholas was his usual speedy and thorough self responding to my Framework on Framework question (<a href=\"https://akeeba.assembla.com/spaces/fof/tickets/4\" target=\"_blank\">https://akeeba.assembla.com/spaces/fof/tickets/4</a>) .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank you, Nicholas for your usual speedy and thorough replies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank you for making FoF a framework in the first place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank you for making FoF available to all of us as FOSS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank you for your patience with me as I need your additional guidance above-and-beyond just reading your source code &mdash; which you amply comment, Thank You!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank you for your JAB12 presentation (video at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sdFLEQgJ_RA\">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sdFLEQgJ_RA</a>). This morning I shut out all distractions and focused on listening to it in its entirety &mdash; a must-listen-to video!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A special thank you to a new client, who is lavishing patience on me so I can use FoF for my first client project. I may not be charging for my learning time, but the critical thing is that I have a &ldquo;real&rdquo; project with which to learn FoF. The pressure produces more intense learning, eh!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nicholas, FoF is a gem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank you!</p>\r\n', 'Thank you to Nicholas Dionysopoulos and a New Client...', 'Thank you to Nicholas Dionysopoulos and a New Client...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/thank-you-to-nicholas-dionysopoulos-a-new-client-and-a-note-about-fof', 'thankyou1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-08-17', '2012-08-17 12:00:00', 1, '2012-08-17 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(52, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Mid August LaSalleMart / Club Commerce Status', 'mid-august-lasallemart-club-commerce-status', '<p>It&rsquo;s one thing to read about entrepreneurship. It&rsquo;s another thing to live it. Living it makes reading about it quite banal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This month I have a split personality: happy and satisfied with one aspect of what I&rsquo;m doing; and, at the same time, enormously frustrated with membership aspect.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Slugging through a ton of learning-by-doing about code-creation set-up (aka &ldquo;software development infrastructure&rdquo;), I am succeeding in figuring it out and making it work. It&rsquo;s all that I knew it would be, which is quite extraordinary.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Code goes stale. Code becomes obsolete. Code is a wasting asset. However, code creation is money. Code creation is powerful. The most important capability is creating code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The intensity of my learning is bearing fruit. It&rsquo;s enormously satisfying.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Coupled with this is the difficulty of kicking starting Club Commerce&rsquo;s membership growth. This was a major topic of discussion at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2012/toronto-joomla-user-group-meet-up-august-2012\" target=\"_blank\">yesterday&rsquo;s Toronto Joomla meet-up</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We can all learn from Zach, who has a unique ability to express himself eloquently and specifically and positively.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ok&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the last few weeks I changed my focus from &ldquo;code&rdquo; to &ldquo;code creation&rdquo; &mdash; what I call the &ldquo;Moneyball&rdquo; skills. Nearly all the tools &amp; sites are free &mdash; which is quite remarkable, so everyone anywhere has access to &lsquo;em &mdash; but learning &lsquo;em, setting &lsquo;em up, and running &lsquo;em is a bitch. It was the right time for me to dig into the &ldquo;code creation&rdquo; stuff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not a line of LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 code was written in the last while. And I think this fact is manifesting in my frustration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ll tell you something, it is hard to stay the course! But, it was absolutely essential to get into &ldquo;code creation&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the same time I dove into the software development infrastructure, a custom component gig came my way. So that was the code I developed first, ahead of LaSalleMart coding, with my new infrastructure. Then, on top of that, was digging into&nbsp;<a href=\"http://akeeba.assembla.com/spaces/fof\" target=\"_blank\">FoF</a>&nbsp;&ndash; a journey in itself!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The centrality of getting LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 done is obvious. While talking, there were many sentences that started with &ldquo;Once ___ happens&hellip;&rdquo;, and &ldquo;When we have ____ done&hellip;&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, I will now return to LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 development. With a twist! I will start with the front-end first, not the admin. Why? The centre of gravity is &nbsp;the checkout working in Joomla 2.5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With LaSalleMart for Joomla 2.5 kickstarted, Club Commerce Membership will kickstart. From there, we can commence with QuickBooks integration, full featured Canada Post, matrix rules for shipping &amp; payments, gift cards, and so on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not every step of the way is peaches and cream. No matter, I will communicate the steps, so you can follow the progress.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UPDATE, Aug 24: After a Very Good Night&rsquo;s Sleep, it doesn&rsquo;t seem as bad as all that. Just keep at it, we&rsquo;re close.</p>\r\n', 'It’s one thing to read about entrepreneurship. It’s another thing to live it. Living it makes reading about it quite banal.\r\nThis month I have a split personality: happy and satisfied with one aspect of what I’m doing; and, at the same time, enormously frustrated with membership aspect...', 'It’s one thing to read about entrepreneurship. It’s another thing to live it. Living it makes reading about it quite banal.\r\nThis month I have a split personality: happy and satisfied with one aspect of what I’m doing; and, at the same time, enormously fr', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/mid-august-lasallemart-club-commerce-status', 'update2.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-08-23', '2012-08-23 12:00:00', 1, '2012-08-23 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(53, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Toronto Joomla User Group Meet-up, August 2012', 'toronto-joomla-user-group-meet-up-august-2012', '<p>Doug, Andrew, Zach and I met up at Yorkville&rsquo;s The Duke of York &nbsp;yesterday for JUGT.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Duke closed its upstairs and downstairs, so we huddled at a table near the entrance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Our Joomla 3.0 discussion was brief, because its acceptance at the table was unanimous. The question was: do we use it? Well, it&rsquo;s alpha, so that&rsquo;s a no. Do we program with it? Well, if one accepts concurrent programming in both 2.5 and 3.0, then go ahead.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We talked about Framework on Framework, and what role it plays. The FoF wiki was updated earlier in the day, so&nbsp;<a href=\"https://akeeba.assembla.com/spaces/fof/wiki/Overview\" target=\"_blank\">take a peek</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We had quite the conversation about LaSalleMart, which I will talk about in my&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2012/mid-august-lasallemart-club-commerce-status\" target=\"_blank\">Mid August Update</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Also, I am keeping an eye out for the videos from the recent&nbsp;<a href=\"http://joomladaychicago.com/\" target=\"_blank\">JoomlaDay Chicago</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Looking forward to the Fall JUGT meet-ups.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UPDATE Aug24th:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://magazine.joomla.org/issues/Issue-Aug-2012/item/830-Debating-Migrating\" target=\"_blank\">http://magazine.joomla.org/issues/Issue-Aug-2012/item/830-Debating-Migrating</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): The subtitle for the above article:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><strong><em>Joomla 3.0 is due out next month, and if you&#39;re thinking &quot;oh no, another migration situation!&quot;, don&#39;t get your feathers all ruffled yet. If you&#39;re on Joomla 2.5 you&#39;ll be absolutely fine staying where you are, probably until 2014.</em></strong></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Yeah, our reaction is unreasonable, eh, that we should be upset of &quot;another migration situation&quot; after going through the Joomla 1.5 to 2.5 experience. It is now that 2014 and about 45% of all Joomla sites are in v2.5 -- and those sites are not likely to upgrade to v3.x. They are going to either be deleted or go onto something else (er, WordPress?) -- which is my prediction. Not only have these version changes been a disaster for me, they&#39;ve been a disaster for the Joomla project too. Follow <a href=\"http://w3techs.com\" target=\"_blank\">w3techs.com</a> to see if I am wrong...</strong></p>\r\n', 'Our Joomla 3.0 discussion was brief, because its acceptance at the table was unanimous. The question was: do we use it? Well, it’s alpha, so that’s a no. Do we program with it? Well, if one accepts concurrent programming in both 2.5 and 3.0, then go ahead...', 'Our Joomla 3.0 discussion was brief, because its acceptance at the table was unanimous. The question was: do we use it? Well, it’s alpha, so that’s a no. Do we program with it? Well, if one accepts concurrent programming in both 2.5 and 3.0, then go ahead', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/toronto-joomla-user-group-meet-up-august-2012', 'toronto_skyline_day1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-08-23', '2012-08-23 12:00:00', 1, '2012-08-23 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(54, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Building Niche Social Networks', 'building-niche-social-networks', '<p>Excellent discussion about building standalone niche social networks on the latest Anahitapolis Hangout podcast.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Discussion focused on&nbsp;<a href=\"http://beerlovers.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://beerlovers.com/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://blog.anahitapolis.com/2012/09/anahita-podcast-episode-9/\" target=\"_blank\">http://blog.anahitapolis.com/2012/09/anahita-podcast-episode-9/</a></p>\r\n', 'Excellent discussion about building standalone niche social networks on the latest Anahitapolis Hangout podcast.\r\nDiscussion focused on http://beerlovers.com/\r\nhttp://blog.anahitapolis.com/2012/09/anahita-podcast-episode-9', 'Excellent discussion about building standalone niche social networks on the latest Anahitapolis Hangout podcast.\r\nDiscussion focused on http://beerlovers.com/\r\nhttp://blog.anahitapolis.com/2012/09/anahita-podcast-episode-9', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/building-niche-social-networks', 'anahita.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-10-07', '2012-10-07 12:00:00', 1, '2012-10-07 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(55, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart News Video', 'lasallemart-news-video', '<p>Continuous software development has arrived. Users either struggle to find your specific process to create their own software; or, become software consumers. The entrepreneurial journey has again led to this trend, and the idea of an End-User Software Club is more relevant now then when first proposed. So, LaSalleMart development will continue.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/MVcCpVDc32c?rel=0\" width=\"640\"></iframe></p>\r\n', 'Continuous software development has arrived. Users either struggle to find your specific process to create their own software; or, become software consumers. The entrepreneurial journey has again led to this trend, and the idea of an End-User Software Club is more relevant now then when first proposed. So, LaSalleMart development will continue.', 'Continuous software development has arrived. Users either struggle to find your specific process to create their own software; or, become software consumers. The entrepreneurial journey has again led to this trend, and the idea of an End-User Software Clu', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-news-video', 'persist1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-10-19', '2012-10-19 12:00:00', 1, '2012-10-19 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(56, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Square One Joomla Distro Done, But Spirit Will Live on with LaSalleMart', 'square-one-joomla-distro-done-but-spirit-will-live-on-with-lasallemart', '<p>Jeremy posted that he is leaving his Square One Joomla distro (<a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups=#!topic/square-one-cms/HYjoQ8d4oV4\" target=\"_blank\">https://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups=#!topic/square-one-cms/HYjoQ8d4oV4</a>).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I recorded a two part podcast with Jeremy early this year at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2012/tbbs45\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2012/tbbs45</a>. It is transcribed, so you can skim it!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is no doubt in my mind that LaSalleMart needs to sit seamlessly within Joomla. The registration process must be seamless. The Administrator&rsquo;s default dashboard and main menu needs to be seamless/integrated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>None of this add-on attitude &mdash; LaSalleMart needs to be an intimate part of Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The only way to make this happen is to create a specific Joomla distro customized for LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Spending the bulk of this past summer learning continuous deployment tools will pay off handsomely when I start working on my Joomla Distro. There will be no way to accomplish it without these tools.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I was hoping to use Square One as the basis of my Distro. Now, I will create my own Joomla Distro from scratch, and see what I can offer to the community.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Square One is an important precedent and case study. Thank you Jeremy!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Well, that Joomla distro of mine is now actually a Laravel based blog app, which you are reading from!</strong></p>\r\n', 'Jeremy posted that he is leaving his Square One Joomla distro...', 'Jeremy posted that he is leaving his Square One Joomla distro...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/square-one-joomla-distro-done-but-spirit-will-live-on-with-lasallemart', 'fork-in-the-road1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-09-27', '2012-09-27 12:00:00', 1, '2012-09-27 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(57, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Toronto Joomla User Group Planning Meet-up, October 2012', 'toronto-joomla-user-group-planning-meet-up-october-2012', '<p>Answering Alan&rsquo;s Clarion Call to organize the Joomla User Group Toronto at the Yonge/Sheppard Firkin, we huddled in our usual main floor booths to organize &nbsp;JUGT.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Track the progression at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/groups/Joomla.User.Group.Toronto/\" target=\"_blank\">JUGT&rsquo;s Facebook page</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A new website, more events, and seeding GTA JUGs require more organization to deliver. As well, we may incorporate JUGT as a non-profit, in order to handle money that would be necessary to host an annual JoomlaDay Toronto.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A lot of action&rsquo;s happened in the few weeks after this meeting &mdash; documents, the first Google+ Hangout, a new Google Group. We are forming an informal formal group, in part as a prelude to formal incorporation, with a real executive organization.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the one hand, to me personally, it seems overblown to have such an organization. On the other hand, it is a critical mass to an explosion of activity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s a Joomla pub meet-up this Wednesday. I&rsquo;ll post a follow-up. In the meantime, keep an eye on our Facebook page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_1337\"><img src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_1337-224x300.jpg\" /></a><br />\r\n<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_1338\"><img src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_1338-224x300.jpg\" /></a><br />\r\n<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_1339\"><img src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_1339-224x300.jpg\" /></a></p>\r\n', 'Answering Alan’s Clarion Call to organize the Joomla User Group Toronto at the Yonge/Sheppard Firkin, we huddled in our usual main floor booths to organize  JUGT.                      \r\n                        \r\n                        ', '', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/toronto-joomla-user-group-planning-meet-up-october-2012', 'IMG_1336.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-10-05', '2012-10-05 12:00:00', 1, '2012-10-05 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(58, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Free LaSalleMart Packages Come With No Free Support', 'free-lasallemart-packages-come-with-no-free-support', '<p>I&rsquo;m reading the latest from Nicholas about today&rsquo;s death threat on him&nbsp;<a href=\"http://dl.dropbox.com/u/5168399/Death%20threats%2C%20Part%202.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://pbwebdev.com/blog/support-the-people-that-do-good#.UIiusW--hy3\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>, as well as on Twitter, and I&rsquo;m furious.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve spent days digging deep into Nicholas&rsquo;&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.akeebabackup.com/home/news/56-releases/1496-akeeba-release-system-2-0-3.html\" target=\"_blank\">Akeeba Release System</a>&nbsp;for use with LaSalleMart; and, am a daily benefactor of his willingness to share his knowledge via the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups=#!topic/frameworkonframework/yJT_hgIzjoQ\" target=\"_blank\">FoF Google Group</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart today, pre-launch, is better than it would otherwise be because of Nicholas. I run 50-ish regular CRON jobs to crank out unattended, unfailing Akeeba Backup Pro backups &mdash; backups that are so &ldquo;pro&rdquo; that I do my WordPress backups with Akeeba Backup. On the rare occassion that these CRONs fail, it is due to the transfer to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://aws.amazon.com/s3/\" target=\"_blank\">S3</a>. CRON Problems are clearly enunciated in the notification email. Nicholas rewards people who read, which is so ironic, with witicisms and insights.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Today I started writing my Phing files to especially build my free LaSalleMart downloads. Throughout the day I felt increasingly haunted by my experience giving away my Virtuemart add-ons way back when Virtuemart was the Hot Thing. It was an over-all crappy experience giving away software. There are a lot of people who just cannot afford, or who refuse to pay, for support. Free software became the hook for people to try to get free consulting, pure and simple.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In no small way, Nicholas&rsquo; leadership has played a part in my decision to release free versions of LaSalleMart. As the beneficiary of his handiwork, the best way to say &ldquo;Thank You&rdquo; is follow his lead. In the same way, the decision of Dioscouri to release Tienda for Joomla 2.5 &ldquo;Alpha&rdquo;, and of course Joomla is FOSS, sways me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a marketing angle to releasing the software for free, but I&rsquo;m going to tell you something: it&rsquo;s bullshit. Of all the reasons, marketing ranks way down there. I know it in my heart, regardless of what the gurus espouse. The cost of releasing free software is massive. The time involved with the emails is unbelievable. And, you know something, my old VM add-ons had my name on it. LaSalleMart has my name all over it. So I treat my emails with great care. Well, something&rsquo;s going to give, and those emails are part of it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If I needed a straw to break my camel&rsquo;s back, then Nicholas&rsquo; bad day today did it. What I&rsquo;ve been thinking, I am going to do with LaSalleMart 2.0 right out of the gate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 2.0 is the most sophisticated, most ambitious technical undertaking I&rsquo;ve done in a decade. My heavy investment in knowledge in software build infrastructure is paying off behind the scenes handsomely. With it, I am finalizing LaSalleMart 2.0 builds for:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>free version of LaSalleMart for Canada;</li>\r\n	<li>free version of LaSalleMart for California;</li>\r\n	<li>free version of LaSalleMart for Florida;</li>\r\n	<li>free version of LaSalleMart for North Carolina;</li>\r\n	<li>free version of LaSalleMart &ndash; unlocalized;</li>\r\n	<li>Club version of LaSalleMart for Canada;</li>\r\n	<li>Club version of LaSalleMart for California;</li>\r\n	<li>Club version of LaSalleMart for Florida;</li>\r\n	<li>Club version of LaSalleMart for North Carolina;</li>\r\n	<li>Club version of LaSalleMart &ndash; unlocalized;</li>\r\n	<li>separate install of the LaSalleMart framework library;</li>\r\n	<li>separate install of the LaSalleMart framework&rsquo;s system library;</li>\r\n	<li>19 modules;</li>\r\n	<li>37 plugins</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Using Nicholas&rsquo; Live Update for the extensions only, I will be able to get fixes to you in 5 minutes, down from 10 minutes for LaSalleMart 1.0.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The effort to set this up blows me away, but whoa is it ever worth it. All these packages, but code is not replicated. The lego block theory of software builds in action. And, it represent just the appetizer of what&rsquo;s to come!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The effort&rsquo;s been so all-encompassing that today I perused the Square One CMS Google Group to refresh my memory. Naturally, I zoomed in on&nbsp;<a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups=#!topic/square-one-cms/Eg147AL120k\" target=\"_blank\">https://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups=#!topic/square-one-cms/Eg147AL120k</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Y&rsquo;know, I set up two separate websites just to figure out how to use Joomla&rsquo;s and ARS&rsquo; One-Click-Update for plugins and modules. And I can&rsquo;t get it to work. So for launch, only the components enjoy Akeeba Live Updates. I&rsquo;m certainly on the other end of the spectrum, because I will not enter a help ticket to Nicholas until I&rsquo;ve dug a little more. Then, I want to be as specific as I can be. Plus, it&rsquo;s been a long sprint and I really should have packed it in hours ago and started back at it fresh.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ll be honest with you, it didn&rsquo;t hit me until I went outside and got some fresh air that what I am doing, busting up Tienda&rsquo;s one-huge-zip file + putting each individual extension into a repo + re-building each extension with Phing + using ARS extensively, is no different than taking Joomla, re-constructing each individual component/module/plugin into repos &amp; builds and overall creating a disto. BULLS-EYE!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That epiphany inspired hours of research I did not expect to do today. But it is very clear to me that busting up Tienda and busting up Joomla are pretty well the same exercise. Once I figure out the how&rsquo;s-and-wherefore&rsquo;s, I can create full Joomla Distros &mdash; exactly the vision!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the first time I&rsquo;ve invested so much, so lavishly &mdash; and just plain gave a shit, to be frank &mdash; about the build infrastructure/process. And the payoff is so magnificent, and so extraordinary, that I will dive into my version of the Square One CMS by mid-November. The theory and the vision is actually happening, with the reality meeting or even exceeding my expectations at every turn.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But, boy, all this wonderful-ness is causing me heartache already. The Freebie versions are not, nor will they ever be, fire-and-forget. Letting &lsquo;em loose is going to invite a heavy backlash. Oh, did I mention, I amputated Tienda&rsquo;s installation PHP in its entirety.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, there is not one line of installation code in LaSalleMart. The installation is pure Joomla. A base installation requires a minimum of five individual installations in the J! installer: the extension, the library, the library&rsquo;s system plugin, the user plugin, and the system plugin. Plus, you have to manually enable each plugin. How many people will rush to install, eschew all documentation (that does not magically appear, btw, it requires a certain effort, n&rsquo;est-ce pas?).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m not out to create the next Virtuemart or Tienda or anything. Pardon me, but I&rsquo;m not looking in the rear view mirror while doing this thing. I am forking Tienda, but not with the purpose to be &ldquo;Tienda, but better than Tienda&rdquo;. LaSalleMart is diverging immediately from Tienda, and will continue to do so.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is an Inside, and there is an Outside. For those on the outside using the freebie versions, you get nothing. The freebie versions will not be updated regularly, doc is whatever the hell I provide, and there is abso-tively, posi-lutely, no support of any kind. No exceptions. You are on your own. Deal with it. If you install it and your site blows up, tough shit. Email me and be ignored &mdash; yes, to hell with it. I remember how it was, when people weren&rsquo;t sure I&rsquo;d respond to emails asking for help, and then my friendly advice would stimulate all manner of gambits for hard-core consulting. NFW this go &rsquo;round.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My original vision of LaSalleMart is coming to fruition, which is an amazing statement to make given the late nights I&rsquo;ve confessed to myself that such a thing would never see the light of day. Well it is.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which is why I am sticking to my original vision, which I&rsquo;ve verbosely described with great verbiage over the last two years, to perpetual complaints by those who insist on applying proper marketing. Oh well. The perseity of persistence!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nicholas&rsquo; leadership inspires me to release my LaSalleMart packages for free along with decent, but limited, documentation/support. Today&rsquo;s death threat on Nicholas nixes any notions I had about delivering any &mdash; and I mean any &mdash; doc/support for my freebies. Fergitaboudit. You are either on the inside with me in my Club Commerce; or, you are on the outside looking in. And, oh, sticking with my original vision, Membership is limited.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UPDATE: Nicholas updated his contact page. I pretty much share his sentiments&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.akeebabackup.com/contact-us.html\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.akeebabackup.com/contact-us.html</a></p>\r\n', 'I’m reading the latest from Nicholas about today’s death threat on him here and here, as well as on Twitter, and I’m furious...', 'I’m reading the latest from Nicholas about today’s death threat on him here and here, as well as on Twitter, and I’m furious...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/free-lasallemart-packages-come-with-no-free-support', 'panic1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-10-29', '2012-10-29 12:00:00', 1, '2012-10-29 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(59, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Update on LaSalleMart 2.0 and Custom Joomla Distro', 'lasallemart-joomla-distro-status', '<p>The LaSalleMart 2.0 builds are done. Next comes testing the packages, taking &lsquo;em for a spin, and fixing/tweaking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is a build? What is a package?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A package is the final assembly of software parts, put together by an automated process (&ldquo;build&rdquo;). LaSalleMart 2.0 for Canada is an assembly of the &ldquo;core&rdquo; and the &ldquo;canada&rdquo; software parts. My automated build process assembles it all into an integrated whole, and then puts this final software product in the different places where you can access it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Never have I paid such particular attention to the &ldquo;back office&rdquo; of software development. Boy, it got more involved than I anticipated &mdash; the devil is in the details for sure &mdash; but what a payoff. Without duplicating code, we have:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>5 paid flavours of the LaSalleMart extension;</li>\r\n	<li>5 free flavours of the LaSalleMart extension;</li>\r\n	<li>the LaSalleMart Library + its system plugin;</li>\r\n	<li>19 modules;</li>\r\n	<li>37 plugins.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The extensions have the Akeeba Live Update built in &mdash; when there&rsquo;s an update, you just click from your admin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The intention is to deliver updates and new features to you super duper fast. No waiting three months for fixes and updates to bundle together into a &ldquo;release&rdquo;. If there&rsquo;s a bug fix, you get it immediately &mdash; no waiting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This speed requires an infrastructure that makes it happen. Hence, the attention to the &ldquo;back office&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A huge payoff with attending to the &ldquo;back office&rdquo; is creating packages. Without duplicating code, we build specific LaSalleMart packages. The extension itself has 10 packages right off the bat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Let&rsquo;s back track a minute. LaSalleMart 2.0 is a fork of Tienda for Joomla 2.5 &ldquo;alpha&rdquo;. Upon discovering this &ldquo;alpha&rdquo;, I stopped converting LaSalleMart 1.0 to Joomla 2.5; and, forked Tienda from scratch all over again. Why? Saved a ton of time!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tienda came in one zip file. Contained within this Joomla 2.5 installable zip file was one extension, one library, almost 40 plugins, and nearly 20 modules. I busted up this zip into all its individual parts. The divergence from Tienda happened instantly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I busted it up, and then put it back together in different packages. This is the start of what will be a matrix of LaSalleMart packages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Creating these packages was more intense than I thought it would be. So, I decided to finish the packages first, and then test &lsquo;em out after the fact. The packages are done, the uploads to the various server folders for your download pleasure are done, the download areas on my website are done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now that my packages are done, it&rsquo;s time to test them to make sure they install ok. Along the way a few bugs were encountered, so those will be fixed as well. When all is done, the downloads will be available for you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Creating a custom Joomla distro (ie, &ldquo;distribution&rdquo;) seemed low priority. However, &nbsp;while busting up Tienda and creating packages, it became clear &ldquo;in the doing&rdquo; that this was the same thing that I have in mind for Joomla &mdash; to take all the components, modules, and plugins that I never use out and end up with a lean mean Joomla. Basically, bust up Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The idea of creating full Joomla distros of LaSalleMart is pretty good. But, the reality of it is even better. Busting up Tienda became a rehearsal for busting up Joomla. After I get my LaSalleMart 2.0 packages in working order, I will dive into my custom Joomla distro. Actually, I&rsquo;ve already started.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 2.0 + customize Joomla + &nbsp;&ldquo;builds &amp; packages&rdquo; = stunning power for consultants.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Heck, forget about what can be done for consultants who join me in my Club Commerce &mdash; how &rsquo;bout for me! The ability to provide &ldquo;white label&rdquo; Joomla, with the ecomm (and my favourite Joomla toys) built right in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maintaining a custom Joomla means fusing the ecomm with Joomla, creating &mdash; finally! &mdash; an integrated experience. Seamless registration, integrated administration. And, geez, when we add features, we won&rsquo;t expand an impossibly busy and squished admin component. We will create fresh new small components to administer new features. Visually, you won&rsquo;t notice because the entire LaSalleMart admin is integrated into Joomla&rsquo;s admin anyways. But, it&rsquo;s very profound to build small niche components b/c it faciliates creating the matrix of LaSalleMart packages; and, it sets the stage for an explosion of development by freeing us up from merging everything into one big bad extension.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will go heads down on this, and update the goings-on on my November &ldquo;LaSalleMart News&rdquo; podcast, which I will target for Friday, November 09th.</p>\r\n', 'A package is the final assembly of software parts, put together by an automated process (“build”). LaSalleMart 2.0 for Canada is an assembly of the “core” and the “canada” software parts. My automated build process assembles it all into an integrated whole, and then puts this final software product in the different places where you can access it.', 'A package is the final assembly of software parts, put together by an automated process (“build”). LaSalleMart 2.0 for Canada is an assembly of the “core” and the “canada” software parts. My automated build process assembles it all into an integrated whol', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-joomla-distro-status', 'persist1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-10-30', '2012-10-30 12:00:00', 1, '2012-10-30 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL);
