(60, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Busting Up — It’s Catching On!', 'busting-up-catching-on', '<p>Gee, a massive component that&rsquo;s so big that it&rsquo;s getting harder and harder to program more features. LaSalleMart? Nope. ProjectFork, a&nbsp;project management extension for Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In their blog post Monday, &ldquo;<a href=\"http://projectfork.net/blog/projectfork-team/one-final-change-before-the-beta.php\" target=\"_blank\">One Final Change Before The Beta</a>&ldquo;, Tobias Kuhn (PF&rsquo;s Founder and Lead Programmer) writes about his big-and-getting-bigger component:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>What we&rsquo;ve done so far with Projectfork 4, we&rsquo;ve squeezed tons of different data layers into this one-dimensional architecture as possible. It works, but its also unflexible and you start to see how components are, perhaps, not meant to to be all that big and complex.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Then, he writes &mdash; perhaps he discovered my blog!</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>&hellip; it seemed that nobody else had tried it before us, so we moved on and decided to make Projectfork a single component just like you&rsquo;d normally do. Two weeks ago, we&rsquo;ve found a simple, yet effective solution to keep the modular design of Projectfork 3 by making separate components, and how to hold everything together almost seamlessly.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Oh, really? No one&rsquo;s done it before? Anahita&rsquo;s been showing the way, with the wonderful Anahita Social Engine framework powering teeny tiny components. Nicholas has paved the way with his Framework on Framework &mdash; I&rsquo;ve blogged and podcast on these things lots!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tobias continues:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>So what we have now are 9 components and a library. Each component takes care of a particular type of data: com_pfprojects is for projects, com_pfmilestones is for milestones, com_pftasks is for tasks, and so forth.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The library contains tools that are equally used and shared by all projectfork components. It also contains a tiny framework, which is really just a single file that connects all the different projectfork components, almost unifying the entire code base on demand.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>A benefit will be a quick-and-quicker ability to deliver PM technology to market, by &ldquo;smalling down&rdquo; each creature feature release &mdash; simply by virtue of messing with less code. &ldquo;Smalling down&rdquo;, lower scope releases, faster-and-more frequent features hitting our sites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I was looking forward to PF4 anyways, having it on a number of sites. Now, I am&nbsp;<em>really</em>&nbsp;looking forward to the PF4 beta!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE (2013May15):</strong>&nbsp;This article is not online now &mdash; it was a great article! Also, have a hand in another new little library&nbsp;<a href=\"https://compojoom.com/forum/116-mandrill-for-joomla/17796-using-cmandrill-in-cli\" target=\"_blank\">https://compojoom.com/forum/116-mandrill-for-joomla/17796-using-cmandrill-in-cli</a></p>\r\n', 'Gee, a massive component that’s so big that it’s getting harder and harder to program more features. LaSalleMart? Nope. ProjectFork, a project management extension for Joomla.', 'Gee, a massive component that’s so big that it’s getting harder and harder to program more features. LaSalleMart? Nope. ProjectFork, a project management extension for Joomla.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/busting-up-catching-on', 'newton_apple1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-10-31', '2012-10-31 12:00:00', 1, '2012-10-31 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(61, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Interview at AdminCredible', 'interview-at-admincredible', '<p>Steve Burge interviewed me at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://admincredible.com/blog/item/27-lasallemart\" target=\"_blank\">AdminCredible.com</a>&nbsp;this week.</p>\r\n', 'Steve Burge interviewed me at AdminCredible.com this week.', 'Steve Burge interviewed me at AdminCredible.com this week.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/interview-at-admincredible', 'interview1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2012-12-11', '2012-12-11 15:00:00', 1, '2012-12-11 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(62, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart 2.0 re-launched, new LaSalleCMS project launched.', 'lasallemart-2-0-re-launched-new-lasallecms-project-launched', '<p>Today&rsquo;s MailChimp blast had a number of links, and I see that for tracking opens they redir. The next time I do a &ldquo;hey, got something cooking&rdquo; blast to do, I&rsquo;ll do the email here and link to my post.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>LaSalleMart 2.0 is re-launched:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>new LaSalleMart.com site</li>\r\n	<li>new ticket system</li>\r\n	<li>new subscription offering @ $5.65 CDN/month</li>\r\n	<li>free &ldquo;base&rdquo; LM2 download</li>\r\n	<li>Cdn, Cali, NC, FL for subscribers only</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>New LaSalleCMS project:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Joomla distro (aka, custom Joomla version)</li>\r\n	<li>new LaSalleCMS.com site</li>\r\n	<li>new Google Group</li>\r\n	<li>new GitHub account</li>\r\n	<li>Supporters&rdquo; subscription offering @ $5.65 CDN/month</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;One Club Commerce change:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>my Anahita, Members-only site is now in the webroot, not in a subfolder</li>\r\n	<li>subscription offering unchanged @ $36 CDN/month</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>Sites, with articles on home page describing each site:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://lasallemart.com/\" target=\"_blank\">LaSalleMart.com</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://lasallecms.com/\" target=\"_blank\">LaSalleCMS.com</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/\" target=\"_blank\">www.southlasalle.com</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>New &ldquo;LaSalleMart News&rdquo; podcast:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://southlasallemedia.com/lasallemart12\" target=\"_blank\">SouthLaSalleMedia.com/lasallemart12</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>Recently interviewed by Steve Burge at:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://admincredible.com/blog/item/27-lasallemart\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.southlasalle.com/2012/interview-at-admincredible</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', 'Today’s MailChimp blast had a number of links, and I see that for tracking opens they redir. The next time I do a “hey, got something cooking” blast to do, I’ll do the email here and link to my post.', 'Today’s MailChimp blast had a number of links, and I see that for tracking opens they redir. The next time I do a “hey, got something cooking” blast to do, I’ll do the email here and link to my post.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-2-0-re-launched-new-lasallecms-project-launched', 'lasallemart_logo_lg.png', 1, 0, 0, '2012-12-12', '2012-12-12 15:00:00', 1, '2012-12-12 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(63, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Critical Lessons Learned from 2012', 'critical-lessons-learned-from-2012', '<p>Today is New Year&rsquo;s Day 2013.&nbsp;Happy New Year!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A year ago I recounted &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2012/critical-lessons-learned-from-2011\" target=\"_blank\">Lessons Learned from 2011</a>&ldquo;. Today, I want to list some lessons learned from 2012.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Marketing: appeal to your Lizard Brain</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>My biggest lesson of 2012 is not techie. It&rsquo;s marketing, an area where I need to make my biggest strides in 2013. My conclusion: appeal to your Lizard Brain.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2012, my conversations seemed to have more subtext than in previous years. I have to ask myself, what is so different? Well, the difference is LaSalleMart 1.0 became a viable Joomla ecomm technology. The underlying ideas behind Club Commerce found an audience. The conversations became more meaningful. And, I found, the conversations were not about the things we were actually talking about.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Clients, potential clients, and just good ol&rsquo; casual chit-chat, expressed fear. A few times, I had conversations where I asked myself afterwards, &ldquo;what just happened?&rdquo;. You know what happened? The person I&rsquo;m talking about is scared, and is expressing their fear in every way except to actually say it out loud explicitly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My critical lesson learned: talk to your Lizard Brain.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Persist at Persisting</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>My deep dark secret about 2012 is that I grew tired of being an agent of change. It&rsquo;s tiring dealing with people&rsquo;s resistance. It&rsquo;s tiring being a lightening rod of people&rsquo;s emotional release of their insecurities about our changing world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I can&rsquo;t tell you how many times I&rsquo;ve said &ldquo;pander&rdquo; to myself in 2012.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oh, boy, it would be so much easier to pander to the public &mdash; or so it seems. Instead of leading, just follow.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hey, isn&rsquo;t &ldquo;follow&rdquo; the ultimate catch-phrase of 2012 anyways?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Every button on my screen seems to say &ldquo;follow&rdquo;, but I do not recall seeing a button that is labelled &ldquo;lead&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why don&rsquo;t I just try to exploit every trend, every hashtag, every hot controversy as a way to sell my wares? Everyone else is fomenting and exploiting ephemeral trends to sell their stuff, so it must work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why not just pander to the &ldquo;follow&rdquo; culture?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, it&rsquo;s a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siren\" target=\"_blank\">siren song</a>.&nbsp;<em>Pandering to the &ldquo;follow&rdquo; culture is seduction into destruction, because leadership is the necessary response to a changing technological world</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite the temptations, I persisted with LaSalleMart, Club Commerce, and with the idea of creating a Joomla distro. At times it was such a grind to persist, that I had to persist and persisting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>The Money is in the&nbsp;ABILITY&nbsp;to Create Software</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>I worked my ass in off in 2012 to user test LaSalleMart 1.0 for Joomla 1.5 &mdash; what a beautiful piece of work it was. Then I watched it obsolete instantly before my eyes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What a profound experience turning a massive investment of sweat equity into zero dollars cash. I had lived&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.dead-frog.com/comedians/comic/steve_martin\" target=\"_blank\">Steve Martin&rsquo;s &ldquo;How I turned a million dollars of real estate into $25 cash</a>&ldquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Living this stale dated software experience really nailed it for me that software code itself is a wasting asset. It&rsquo;s shelf life is so compressed that it&rsquo;s practically a wasted asset.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Perhaps this is a natural progression of free open source software, that such software should encapsulate ephermal value to its users. Free can now be interpreted as value-free &mdash; as in value-less.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The value of the software is the stuff you can&rsquo;t see that brings it to fruition: the software repositories, the build processes, the methodologies employed. That is, the software development process itself is where the money is. &nbsp;Having code in your hands is not valuable anymore. Having the dev process by the balls is where the money is.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most of my effort to fork Tienda into LaSalleMart is focused on the behind-the-scenes dev process. I lavished time in 2012 journeying into the different methodologies and code-creation sites out there. It was the right investment to make, and in 2013 the payoff will be enormous.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why? Because the money is in the code creation, not in the code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Communication Matters</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>2012 reinforced my belief that &ldquo;silence is the worst response&rdquo;. LaSalleMart&rsquo;s development was not all fun and frolic, there were bumps in the road, there were frustrations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But one thing I got right was creating my monthly &ldquo;LaSalleMart&rdquo; News podcast, and persisting at it every month &ldquo;rain or shine&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Believe me, it was oh-so-tempting to go silent when things were not going to plan. But then how would you know what was happening?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Even when you don&rsquo;t listen to my podcasts, or even glance at my transcripts, at least you know that I am here persisting at persisting. Which is probably what you really want to know. Yes, I am here!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2013, I plan on stepping up communications. Videos, hangouts, podcasts &mdash; and getting out there in person in the Toronto area in two ways: through the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://toronto.joomla.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">Toronto Joomla Group</a>; and, by hosting my own Club Commerce seminars.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>2011 Lessons Still Apply</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Especially the lessons of GPL software &mdash; what the software licence is all about, and how that affects us.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2013 is shaping up to be a fabulous year for LaSalleMart, Club Commerce, and LaSalleCMS. Hope to see you on the inside of this success!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Bob Bloom</p>\r\n', 'Today is New Year’s Day 2013. Happy New Year!\r\nA year ago I recounted “Lessons Learned from 2011“. Today, I want to list some lessons learned from 2012...', 'Today is New Year’s Day 2013. Happy New Year!\r\nA year ago I recounted “Lessons Learned from 2011“. Today, I want to list some lessons learned from 2012...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/critical-lessons-learned-from-2012', 'blackboard1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-01-01', '2013-01-01 15:00:00', 1, '2013-01-01 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(64, 0, NULL, NULL, 'January 2013 Joomla Toronto “Ask the Expert” — The Rebellious Expert', 'january-2013-joomla-toronto-ask-the-expert', '<p>Upon arrival from the Joomla User Group Toronto&rsquo;s &ldquo;Ask the Expert&rdquo; panel session, I composed this blog post. Might as well have called it &ldquo;3:00am Ramblings of the Irritated&rdquo;. I keep thinking I have to stay up at night and do more posts like my &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2012/late-night-thoughts-on-lasallemart\" target=\"_blank\">Late Night Thoughts on LaSalleMart</a>&ldquo;, but in reality not such a good idea!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I thoroughly enjoyed this session at the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.oasisskillsbuilding.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Oasis Skills Building on the Danforth</a>. New venue, good turnout, excellent moderator (thank you Gilles!). We repaired to a local spot that felt like Thursday pub night at UofT that played great music, than awful ear piercing crap, then good music again.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It continues to amaze and astound me the fetish Joomla has for WordPress.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/0x-fkSYDtUY?rel=0\" width=\"640\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Well, in retrospect, I understand perfectly well. And being asked all the time, and seeing the constant references to WordPress in the Joomla-verse is attributable to the fact that WordPress was in the midst of parabolic market growth. Starting in 2012, WordPress ascended to 60% of known CMS. Joomla, once the #1 CMS, was now in a parabolic market share the other way, now at 8%. Of all websites, WordPress now has 23% market share and Joomla is at 3.0% (on the way to piercing that level to 2.99% which seems inevitable). I won&#39;t give the site yet another link, but see w3techs dot com. So, no, Joomla never &quot;snapped out of it&quot;.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tonight, apropos, the WordPress theme du jour was directed at me about doing ecommerce in WordPress. Inside, that set me off big time. Outwardly, I was just mild mannered Joomla ecommerce guy. So, naturally, all the inward stuff channeled unfiltered to my blog post. Oh boy, to just click publish &mdash; on my WordPress blog! Ha!! Oh, dear reader, I&rsquo;ve learned long ago to write first, publish later.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, something very interesting happened on the way to my upgrading two very active WordPress sites to WP3.5. The &ldquo;Know Your Rights&rdquo; page that displays after successfully upgrading. This page is sitting at&nbsp;/wp-admin/freedoms.php.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What took me by surprise was the prominence of this message. Not squirreled away in some footer tag, this was slap in your face (must be on my mind) stuff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My answer to many queries posed was &ldquo;use your power&rdquo;. The power vested in you by the General Public License. Here&rsquo;s what WordPress is telling you:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>WordPress is Free and open source software, built by a distributed community of mostly volunteer developers from around the world. WordPress comes with some awesome, worldview-changing rights courtesy of its&nbsp;<a href=\"http://wordpress.org/about/license/\">license</a>, the GPL.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>You have the freedom to run the program, for any purpose.</li>\r\n	<li>You have access to the source code, the freedom to study how the program works, and the freedom to change it to make it do what you wish.</li>\r\n	<li>You have the freedom to redistribute copies of the original program so you can help your neighbor.</li>\r\n	<li>You have the freedom to distribute copies of your modified versions to others. By doing this you can give the whole community a chance to benefit from your changes.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>Don&rsquo;t you wish all software came with these freedoms? So do we! For more information, check out the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.fsf.org/\">Free Software Foundation</a>.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Substitute the word &ldquo;power&rdquo; for &ldquo;freedom&rdquo;:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You have the POWER to run the program for any purpose; you have access to the source code, the POWER to study it, and the POWER to CHANGE IT TO MAKE IT DO WHAT YOU WISH; you have the POWER to distribute copies of your MODIFIED version to others.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I don&rsquo;t give a rat&rsquo;s ass how skilled you are, it does not matter. YOU HAVE THE POWER. USE YOUR FRIGGIN&rsquo; POWER.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>WordPress is shoving it in your face, first thing you see when you upgrade. Are you listening. Luke, USE YOUR FRIGGIN&rsquo; POWER.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla is GPL. Same deal. USE YOUR FRIGGIN&rsquo; POWER.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Study the code,&nbsp;<em>simply because you can</em>. It&rsquo;s an act of freedom and power. Using your power is enormously valuable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve learned that getting an interpretation of the code is not as valuable as understanding the code. So valuable that any understanding of the code is a plus, regardless of how deep your knowledge goes. In Star Wars, Alec Guiness&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0076759/quotes\" target=\"_blank\">says</a>:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>The Force is what gives a Jedi his power. It&rsquo;s an energy field created by all living things. It surrounds us and penetrates us. It binds the galaxy together.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>With open source, the code is what gives us our power. Don&rsquo;t settle for peoples&rsquo; interpretations of what the code does. Look at the source code directly. Joomla&rsquo;s source code represents millions of dollars &mdash; look at it!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The database is open source too. Look at it. Some tables are actually intuitively named! Don&rsquo;t worry about it being your first time launching PhpMyAdmin &mdash; just launch and look. The second time you look, it makes more sense. In fact, by the 50th time, even the field names will become familiar to you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a previous life I worked in corporate I.T. I&rsquo;d have to genuflect and beg and offer burnt sacrifices for the opportunity to be refused to see the database scripts. On one project, I was the very first business analyst to ever be granted a workstation licence for the Oracle database &mdash; the first chunks of the castle wall to fall around the DBA guys. They did it to get me off their ass &rsquo;cause I was on &lsquo;em constantly for my project.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With the GPL, it&rsquo;s all there. So take a look. You will be amazed what your eye can pick up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I was asked what Joomla ecommerce extension I thought was best. What I said, and what I thought, were of two different worlds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What I said was: &ldquo;I am biased. You realize I am an extension purveyor&rdquo; &mdash; or something like that. &nbsp;I referred to the great overview video at the JoomlaDay 2012 by Deb Cinkus:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/3CkgH6ahE8g?rel=0\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>What I was thinking was, &ldquo;Oh gee, here we go again, the consumer&rsquo;s guide to building an online business&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I just don&rsquo;t look at things like I used to. It&rsquo;s been a long grind with Joomla freelancing. Mere days before the JUGT event, I ironed out the last of my LaSalleMart 2.0 builds/downloads. It&rsquo;s been a tough grinding slog. Plus, I&rsquo;m going where the ball is being thrown, not expecting to do an inside curl and thinking the ball will be where my feet are planted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_1431.jpg\"><img alt=\"Joomla Toronto in January\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_1431-224x300.jpg\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The power goes to the code creaters. Create, do not consume, software. That&rsquo;s where the value is. So use the power vested in you by the GPL. Have a way in which you can modify/fork OSS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And, always know what you need today and what you&rsquo;ll need tomorrow. Choose the best tool for the job. Even better, create the tools yourself! Or, at least have the ability to customize.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Looking forward to our next such event.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'It continues to amaze and astound me the fetish Joomla has for WordPress...', 'It continues to amaze and astound me the fetish Joomla has for WordPress...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/january-2013-joomla-toronto-ask-the-expert', 'IMG_1432.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-01-15', '2013-01-15 15:00:00', 1, '2013-01-15 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(65, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Mid January Update: Single-Launch Packages, First Sites and Testing, Atlassian, Pricing Changes', 'single-launch-packages-and-more-during-january-2013', '<h1>Integrated Single-Launch Joomla &ndash; LaSalleMart Packages (Distros) a Reality</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>From the get-go, I wanted to create single launch integrated Joomla-LaSalleMart packages. Packages that are updated in real-time as the underlying codebase changes. No waiting around for crucial bug fixes to be bundled with other features. I want those bug fixes on your site immediately.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, getting those bug fixes and form tweaks and other creature features into my single launch packages is a challenge. Back in the day, Virtuemart threw a single launch package on its site. It really was terrific. But, it was never updated. It was a one-off that sat on the site as updates were released, and people downloaded it mistakenly thinking it had the latest releases in it. Nope. The Distros on my LaSalleMart.com site are updated with the latest bug fixes, form tweaks, and whatever else.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As you know, LaSalleMart 2.0 is a fork of Tienda&rsquo;s first Joomla 2.5 iteration. A fork is independent development of software in a different direction than pursued by its original authors. Joomla&rsquo;s license is the General Public License, which encourages forking. Well, &nbsp;the first thing I did was bust up the huge installable zip into its individual parts. The LaSalleMart component, library, modules and plugins reside in their own separate software repository, and have their own separate build files. Each individual piece now has its own separate installable zip file.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My purpose is to create lego blocks of code that I put together in different ways. Now I am able to pick-and-choose what lego blocks I want in my single launch packages. I have six single launch packages &mdash; California, Canada, Florida, North Carolina, and Standard. Each package includes the necessary component, library, and plugins; and, also has the Offline Payments plugin, the Standard Shipping plugin; and, the cart module. The basics!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My single launch packages are automatically uploaded to my LaSalleMart.com site when they are built, so the packages available are always the most up-to-date.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now that the Distros are a reality, their configurations will become more encompassing to make your set-up that much easier; and, the there will be a matrix of distros. For example, a Joomla-LaSalleMart all-in-one package for Canadians for downloadable products only.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>LaSalleCMS: A Needed Joomla Distro</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>I have no intention of forking Joomla. What I do intend to do is tweak Joomla to integrate better with LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My complaint is that LaSalleMart feels like the add-on that it is. What I want, what I&rsquo;ve always wanted, is LaSalleMart being an integrated part of Joomla. The entire Joomla-LaSalleMart experience needs to be seamless. Now that my single-launch packages exist, I can take a deeper look at Joomla for integration opportunities. What can be done with the admin menu? What can &mdash; and should be &mdash; done with the user handling? Are there rarely used parts of Joomla that we can safely excise? What extensions would we prefer to add to Joomla as permanent parts of Joomla?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Again, this is all on the up-and-up, because Joomla is released under the General Public Licence. We want to keep Joomla in all its glory, but there is some custom renovations we want to do too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, I created the LaSalleCMS project. LaSalleCMS is a public open source project. Atlassian.com has granted LaSalleCMS an open source license, so JIRA, BitBucket, Confluence, and all the Atlassian on-demand goodies are provided at no cost. There is not much at the site to see &mdash; yet. But the site is at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://lasallecms.atlassian.net/wiki/\" target=\"_blank\">https://lasallecms.atlassian.net/wiki/</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleCMS is starting slow, which is understanding considering the focus on LaSalleMart and on the single-launch packages. However, LaSalleCMS is hardly ignored, as it is ready for where-ever our journey will take it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Right now, LaSalleCMS is exactly Joomla 2.5.8. I&rsquo;ve done nothing more than set up the repository, the builds, and the website with the Akeeba Release System &mdash; not exactly trivial exercises. So, LaSalleCMS updates via the Joomla remote servers. What is coming is updates coming from LaSalleCMS, not Joomla. I will detail this more when I change the update source.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Akeeba Release System and Joomla Updater</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>Towards the end of this month, I will return to figuring out the Akeeba Release System and the Joomla Updater. I am sure that the reason I can&rsquo;t make &lsquo;em work together is my own lack of getting &lsquo;em to work together. Beyond this is the new ARS&rsquo;s API.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To be more precise, ARS already works with the LaSalleMart components. I completely ignore the Joomla Updater, because there&rsquo;s a nice version reporting mechanism within the components. However, modules, plugins, and libraries need to use the Joomla Updater. So, the Joomla Updater needs to work with ARS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using ARS means I can offer individual updates to paid subscribers only. As well, with ARS, I can offer software for download on the same site where remote update requests are managed. Furthermore, I can do one deployment to my ARS site automatically.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, inexorably, LaSalleMart&rsquo;s individual plugins, modules, and library will have their own updates in the Joomla Updater. The Joomla Updater will point to my LaSalleMart&rsquo;s ARS set-up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the same way, LaSalleCMS will also use ARS the same way. For example, if I take com_banners out of LaSalleCMS, I will put it into my LaSalleCMS&rsquo; ARS set-up so you can install it individually &mdash; and so it will update via the Joomla Updater.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I mention this because these changes are coming &mdash; slowly perhaps, but inexorably.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Pricing has Changed</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve decided that there are no free Live Updates anymore. It is still free to download LaSalleMart Standard for Everyone. However, to use Live Update you need to buy a subscription.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The reason I&rsquo;ve done this is I need you to support LaSalleMart. By support, I mean pay money into LaSalleMart. &nbsp;I&rsquo;ve priced LaSalleMart subscriptions at a donation price point: $5.65CDN per month. Not only does your subscription make a difference, but I want you to subscribe. You know why? Because it costs money to hire programmers. It costs money to hire QA techs. That&rsquo;s where LaSalleMart (and LaSalleCMS too) is going: hiring skilled people. I am not relying on the kindness of strangers to provide the technical muscle powering LaSalleMart (and LaSalleCMS). Been there, done that, and if it worked for me I&rsquo;d not have decided to fork an ecomm extension but instead would be contributing to a FOSS ecomm project.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As I&rsquo;ve stated elsewhere, as the feature set broadens, those features will be available to paid subscribers only. I will keep the cost down, but you have to have skin in this game.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Live Sites and Testing</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>Thanks to my initial band of supporters. there are about a half-dozen real LaSalleMart 2.0 sites being built. These sites are serving as the initial user test sites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We are running into issues, as expected. Where functionaity is impaired, effort is exerted to restore it. Cosmetics, refactoring, pretty-fying &mdash; these things we need to defer. First things first!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is my second fork of Tienda. The first was the Joomla 1.5 edition that became LaSalleMart 1.0. The testing and fixing up is very similar to what went on with LM1.0. It&rsquo;s all part-and-parcel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By month-end I&rsquo;ll have checkout tweaked and few rough more rough edges smoothed out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At this point, you should take a good look at LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>LaSalleMart 2.0 Listing on the Joomla Extension Directory</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>At or around month-end, I will seek listing on the JED. In preparation, I&rsquo;ve read the<a href=\"http://extensions.joomla.org/tos\" target=\"_blank\">&nbsp;requirements on the JED website</a>. There are extra requirements for extensions that are forks of other extensions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Extensions that are forks of other extensions must have features beyond the original. Such extensions must have attribution in the manifest file. While I created the distro builds, I also added this attribution. I have no idea if my handiwork will be construed as &ldquo;features beyond the original&rdquo;. Another requirement is that a fork must go down a different path of development than the original.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the summer, I blogged, &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2012/why-lasallemart-is-not-available-for-free-download\" target=\"_blank\">Free LaSalleMart and JED Listing</a>&ldquo;; and, &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2012/tienda-alpha-joomla-25-lasallemart-going-its-own-way\" target=\"_blank\">Tienda Alpha for Joomla 2.5: LaSalleMart is Going Its Own Way</a>&ldquo;. Well, there is now here. I am about to list LM2 on the JED, and with the package distros on LaSalleMart.com (and the existence of LaSalleCMS) you can see the shape of things to come.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Upcoming Features</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>With the underlying infrastructure taking shape, focus can turn to feature development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is still the aforementioned J!Updater and ARS work to do. There is already a nice little LaSalleCMS to-do list.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here is my attitude about feature development: it&rsquo;s a non-stop, never-ending, continuous way-of-life. It just &ldquo;is&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Regardless of how features are developed elsewhere, feature development here is not a big grand exercise into the wild blue yonder. Feature development is starting small, being small, keeping it small, and doing it continuously. There is no end-point.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Feature development is not an incursion into stable software, disturbing the world order, and introducing earthquakes of change. Hello! Read my blog, listen to my podcasts. WE LIVE IN A CONTINUOUS WORLD!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Feature development is a way of life. We set up projects, and we do projects. Projects turn into software builds which make their way onto our sites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Times are changing, software infrastructure is changing &mdash; for the better. Not to mention I&rsquo;m sick-and-tired of being sick-and-tired waiting and waiting for software releases. LaSalleCMS is on Atlassian for a reason, eh!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, what are the upcoming features.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, Canada Post. It&rsquo;s time to get into it, set it up as a permanent ongoing project.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Feature sponsorship will determine what gets done elsewhere. QuickBooks integration is looking good. Backend order management is looking good. Perhaps gift card &amp; loyalty rewards program as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have my own pet list, as part of a general refactoring. Conditional branching checkout, shipping per product instead of per order, advanced coupons. And this is just the beginning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, it&rsquo;s late. That&rsquo;s it for now!</p>\r\n', 'From the get-go, I wanted to create single launch integrated Joomla-LaSalleMart packages. Packages that are updated in real-time as the underlying codebase changes. No waiting around for crucial bug fixes to be bundled with other features. I want those bug fixes on your site immediately.', 'From the get-go, I wanted to create single launch integrated Joomla-LaSalleMart packages. Packages that are updated in real-time as the underlying codebase changes. No waiting around for crucial bug fixes to be bundled with other features. I want those bu', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/single-launch-packages-and-more-during-january-2013', 'atlassian_logo1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-01-21', '2013-01-21 15:00:00', 1, '2013-01-21 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(66, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart 2.0: Initial User Testing Concluding', 'lasallemart-2-0-initial-user-testing-concluding', '<p>Gotta come up for air to let you know what is happening with LaSalleMart 2.0&prime;s User Testing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A quick recap:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>started with Tienda 0.10 &ldquo;alpha&rdquo; for Joomla 2.5;</li>\r\n	<li>global name change from &ldquo;Tienda&rdquo; to &ldquo;Lasallemart&rdquo;;</li>\r\n	<li>busted up the huge Tienda installation routine into component parts;</li>\r\n	<li>created six LaSalleMart 2.0 &ldquo;flavours&rdquo;;</li>\r\n	<li>created an Akeeba Release System server, with Live Update in each &ldquo;flavour&rdquo;;</li>\r\n	<li>initial release of LM2;</li>\r\n	<li>install LM2 on half-a-dozen very friendly sites for initial User Testing;</li>\r\n	<li>resolve issues resulting from this initial User Testing.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Right now, I am finishing up the issues resulting from initial User Testing. I nearly made my month-end target, but I&rsquo;ll need Super Bowl weekend to wrap it all up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Big reason for needing extra time was my effort to create Joomla Distros this month, including setting up LaSalleCMS. Not only am I User Testing LM2, but I am also testing my Joomla-LaSalleMart Distro packages. Originally expected separate testing phases, but very glad I pushed &nbsp;for the Distros in January, and testing &lsquo;em in conjunction with LM2. The Distros are sweet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This upcoming week, I will:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>conclude the initial User Testing;</li>\r\n	<li>update my LaSalleMart home page article;</li>\r\n	<li>apply to the Joomla Extension Directory;</li>\r\n	<li>publish my podcast;</li>\r\n	<li>start, and publish ASAP, my Canada Post shipping plugin;</li>\r\n	<li>start the work, finally, to get all my plugins, modules, and the library, onto the Akeeba Release System.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>At this point:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>I will track all required issues on an ongoing basis and continually improve LaSalleMart;</li>\r\n	<li>initiate feature requests;</li>\r\n	<li>start contacting template clubs to include LM2 in their template designs (after JED listing, most likely).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, it is at this point that I&rsquo;ll likely start LM2 hangouts/webinars. Perhaps a live in-person seminar as a Joomla User Group Toronto thing &mdash; discussed already.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oh, as well, three more installs after User Testing concludes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s happening!</p>\r\n', 'Gotta come up for air to let you know what is happening with LaSalleMart 2.0′s User Testing...', 'Gotta come up for air to let you know what is happening with LaSalleMart 2.0′s User Testing...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-2-0-initial-user-testing-concluding', 'nerdfestinprogress1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-02-01', '2013-02-01 15:00:00', 1, '2013-02-01 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(67, 0, NULL, NULL, 'February 2013 Joomla Toronto “Ask the Expert” – Still the Rebel!', 'february-2013-joomla-toronto-ask-the-expert', '<p>I thoroughly enjoyed yesterday&rsquo;s Joomla User Group Toronto meet-up. It&rsquo;s not the first time I forgot to take pictures at a JUGT. Excellent to meet Allison and Sheldon. Good to put a face to Facebook!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As happens, the turnout was modest, but it gives us the opportunity to get to know each other and have deeper discussions. For the first time, we played pool (across the road) which was a nice break &mdash; certainly for me, deep into debugging this week. A good mental break.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yesterday was &ldquo;Consultants talking about their client engagements&rdquo;. It was very interesting and intriguing. Just about every extension mentioned I had &ldquo;done something&rdquo; with it over the years. I was complimented on how casual I was in mentioning this-or-that with obvious knowledge. Well, nothing casual in wrestling with the code to customize it &mdash; lots of pain!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I mentioned that I did not like the installation procedure for a small little plugin available for free by a well know Joomla template club. &nbsp;So, I built my own Joomla installable zip. My consulting peers thought that was great &mdash; thank you! But, I have to tell you, I did not program anything in doing it, since it was an exercise in excluding extraneous code. It&rsquo;s not very mysterious &mdash; the only &ldquo;trick&rdquo; involved is understanding the installation xml, (sometimes called &ldquo;manifest.xml&rdquo;), which is not even PHP. It&rsquo;s a Joomla specific thing, every single installable plugin, module, component, and library has one. Handy to understand!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A typical ecommerce scenario was posed. Up front, it was clearly stated that this was a super duper easy breezy Joomla ecomm site to set up. I like easy! I always start my questioning from the end of the checkout &mdash; what is your payment method, what are your shipping rules, etc. There were a number of modifications that came up. Also, there were different ways of accomplishing the objectives. Not as easy as advertised, but very normal when digging into the real requirements. Because I&rsquo;m all-in with the coding, including having a Joomla distro ready-to-go, all solution scenarios are possible!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A very interesting question was posed: how do you know what the good extensions are? My answer is, of course, you always have to go through the code. This is the starting point. This is the glory of open source &mdash; that the source code is there for you, and that you can do anything to it to use the code as you require for your use.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The &ldquo;Free&rdquo; in &ldquo;Free Open Source Software&rdquo; = freedom! (you thought it meant &ldquo;no money&rdquo;!)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As Michael Douglas said in &ldquo;The American President&rdquo;, &ldquo;America isn&rsquo;t easy. America is Advanced Citizenship. You&rsquo;ve got to want it bad&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open source is software freedom. But you have to want it bad. You have to exercise your freedom to benefit from it, and to make that freedom work in the real world. In fact, if we do not exercise our software freedom rights (that are enumerated in the GPL), then the software creators have, in essence, proprietary software. And, many sneak in things that impair exercising our software freedom with their code. If we do not reject their code, then we are in fact acquiescing to impairing our freedom. It&rsquo;s not easy, software freedom. It means you have to Get In The Code!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/mWRVbWMvi7c?rel=0\" width=\"640\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>I want it bad! I want my software freedom. So much so, I forked a huge full featured ecomm extension, and set up LaSalleCMS, my Joomla distro.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I keep harping on this, because it keeps coming up. Get in the code!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I was asked about Google Analytics and traversing the checkout. My perspective is so different, having revamped the cart.&nbsp;<em>We have the code</em>! Why be reactive? Why have a lag between fetching the stats and the customer who is long gone? Customer service is a huge difference in conversion. Why not &ldquo;do something&rdquo; in the code that is pro-active with cart abandonment, that redirects buyers to calls to action, so their sale is ultimately consummated? Can you imagine the RoI of this code!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m a rebel with a cause!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Looking forward to our next &ldquo;Ask The Expert&rdquo;&hellip;</p>\r\n', 'I thoroughly enjoyed yesterday’s Joomla User Group Toronto meet-up. It’s not the first time I forgot to take pictures at a JUGT. Excellent to meet Allison and Sheldon. Good to put a face to Facebook!', 'I thoroughly enjoyed yesterday’s Joomla User Group Toronto meet-up. It’s not the first time I forgot to take pictures at a JUGT. Excellent to meet Allison and Sheldon. Good to put a face to Facebook!', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/february-2013-joomla-toronto-ask-the-expert', 'jugt-cn-logo.png', 1, 0, 0, '2013-02-14', '2013-02-14 15:00:00', 1, '2013-02-14 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(68, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart 2.0: Joomla Extensions Directory Application is Imminent', 'lasallemart-2-0-joomla-extensions-directory-application-is-imminent', '<p>LaSalleMart 2.0&prime;s application to the Joomla Extensions Directory is imminent. Application will be made at or before February month-end.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The current round of testing, bug squashing, and upgrades, are near conclusion. Now that I see the light at the end of this tunnel, time to come up for some air to let you know.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As you already know, LaSalleMart 2.0 is a fork of the first Joomla 2.5 &ldquo;alpha&rdquo; version of Tienda. At the time of this writing, February 21, 2013, this is the only version of Tienda released for Joomla 2.5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Something I&rsquo;ve always wanted is a matrix of Joomla ecommerce packages customized for geographical locations and industries &mdash; or, for whatever needs that come up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Something else I want is super duper fast deployment to address my perpetual frustration waiting for releases of other OSS. LaSalleMart code should get from the kitchen to the plate while the code is still hot.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To achieve multiple live packages delivered hot, I busted up the installable zip of one component, on library, 20 modules, and 40 plugins &mdash; give or take. As LaSalleMart, each has its own software repository, its own build scripts, its own installable zip. Each is separate software.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 2.0 installation is unique: the component&rsquo;s installable zip contains just the component. The plugins and library necessary to run LM2 are&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;included! These are installed separately.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Full Joomla-LaSalleMart &ldquo;distros&rdquo; will ease the pain of installing each piece separately &mdash; unfortunately, these &ldquo;distros&rdquo; are not quite ready after much testing so I am not distributing them right now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s going to be some type of solution to the installation. At this stage, it is critical to have the &ldquo;lego blocks&rdquo; done. Oh, they are done &mdash; a huge effort has gone into the builds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It proved to be a very irritating experience, but it now works: my LaSalleMart 2.0 plugins, modules, and library are update-able via the Joomla Updater.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The components update via the Akeeba Live Update, but only the component is update-able in this way. How do you update the other stuff without downloading from my site, and installing via the Joomla installer?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Look, there was a ton of installation code in the software inherited. It&rsquo;s purpose was, in part, to support the installation of a suite of extensions. I deleted the whole thing completely. There is absolutely no installation software in LaSalleMart, except for minimal code in the update scripts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is going to be a lot of updates to LaSalleMart 2.0, by design. You will get them on your site fast, by design.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My frustration waiting for releases has manifested in my unique ground-up approach to getting LaSalleMart updates to you fast. I thought it could be done, it can be done, I did it! Making it happen took a significant amount of work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This &ldquo;alpha&rdquo; version that was forked is definitely a &ldquo;work in progress&rdquo;. A lot of effort was needed just to get it in functional form. A lot less functionality was covered than desired, for two reasons: the &ldquo;builds&rdquo; were a material investment in time and effort; and, geez, this really was truly &ldquo;alpha&rdquo; software!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The priority became: get the update delivery mechanisms in place first, worry about the actual software second. Since work on LaSalleMart will be ongoing, let&rsquo;s get the code pipeline in place first.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, a checkout with offline payments, PayPal Standard, and Standard Shipping, is the goal of LM2&prime;s &ldquo;JED Release&rdquo;. Standard Shipping needed major work. And, well, as I said in my recent &ldquo;LaSalleMart News&rdquo; podcast (oh,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2013/lasallemart14\" target=\"_blank\">here&rsquo;s the link!</a>), I can&rsquo;t stand the inherited checkout.&nbsp;So I worked on checkout, and am now very close to wrapping up my upgrades to checkout.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s coming down to &ldquo;The Last Spike&rdquo;!</p>\r\n', 'LaSalleMart 2.0′s application to the Joomla Extensions Directory is imminent. Application will be made at or before February month-end. The current round of testing, bug squashing, and upgrades, are near conclusion. Now that I see the light at the end of this tunnel, time to come up for some air to let you know...', 'LaSalleMart 2.0′s application to the Joomla Extensions Directory is imminent. Application will be made at or before February month-end. The current round of testing, bug squashing, and upgrades, are near conclusion. Now that I see the light at the end of ', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-2-0-joomla-extensions-directory-application-is-imminent', 'last_spike.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-02-21', '2013-02-21 15:00:00', 1, '2013-02-21 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(69, 0, NULL, NULL, 'The LaSalleMart 2.0 “JED Release” for Real Sites has Arrived!', 'lasallemart-2-0-edition-for-joomla-extension-directory-application-is-here', '<p>It is a thrill to announce that the LaSalleMart 2.0 &ldquo;JED Release&rdquo; is here.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I call this the &ldquo;JED Release&rdquo; because this is the point in LM2&prime;s development where I will seek JED listing. Within the last hour, I just initiated the JED listing process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Officially, this is LaSalleMart version 2.0.000.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the LM2 release that is ready for live sites. Not without some caveats, which I have yet to write on LaSalleMart.com &mdash; later this evening! The installation notes are updated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s been a loooooonnnnnnggggg time coming.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Check out my<a href=\"http://lasallemart.com/\" target=\"_blank\">&nbsp;LaSalleMart.com</a>&nbsp;for details.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Bob</p>\r\n', 'It is a thrill to announce that the LaSalleMart 2.0 “JED Release” is here.', 'It is a thrill to announce that the LaSalleMart 2.0 “JED Release” is here.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-2-0-edition-for-joomla-extension-directory-application-is-here', 'lasallemart20_dashboard.png', 1, 0, 0, '2013-02-25', '2013-02-25 15:00:00', 1, '2013-02-25 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(70, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Joomla Community Magazine Article Published', 'joomla-community-magazine-article-published', '<p>The March 2013 Joomla Community Magazine published an article about JUGT by yours truly, &ldquo;Joomla User Group Toronto &mdash; The Journey&rdquo;. Read it at:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://magazine.joomla.org/issues/issue-mar-2013/item/1116-joomla-user-groiup-toronto-the-journey\" target=\"_blank\">http://magazine.joomla.org/issues/issue-mar-2013/item/1116-joomla-user-groiup-toronto-the-journey</a></p>\r\n', 'The March 2013 Joomla Community Magazine published an article about JUGT by yours truly, “Joomla User Group Toronto — The Journey”...', 'The March 2013 Joomla Community Magazine published an article about JUGT by yours truly, “Joomla User Group Toronto — The Journey”...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/joomla-community-magazine-article-published', 'joomla_community_magazine.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-03-04', '2013-03-04 15:00:00', 1, '2013-03-04 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(71, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Joomla Extension Directory Application is Now Pending', 'joomla-extension-directory-application-is-now-pending', '<p>LaSalleMart 2.0 is now officially pending approval on the Joomla Extension Directory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Turned out that the not-trivial effort to list on the JED was&nbsp;a brutal waste of time.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n', 'LaSalleMart 2.0 is now officially pending approval on the Joomla Extension Directory...', 'LaSalleMart 2.0 is now officially pending approval on the Joomla Extension Directory...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/joomla-extension-directory-application-is-now-pending', '2013mar05_jed_pending.png', 1, 0, 0, '2013-03-05', '2013-03-05 15:00:00', 1, '2013-03-05 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(72, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart 2.0 in Flight — Code and Feature Improvements Started', 'lasallemart-in-flight-improvements-started', '<p>Now that I have LaSalleMart 2.0 to the point where it can be listed on the Joomla Extensions Directory, along with the extra articles and stuff &mdash; just last week! &mdash; and on&nbsp;<a href=\"http://gearguy.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">its first live site</a>, I am starting the work to improve LM2.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s the start of the ongoing improvements.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s a list of small things that I have in JIRA to do over time. I&rsquo;m sure this list will expand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a couple of features that I am working on this week: &nbsp;coupons and product attribute pricing. Both are core features &mdash; too bad coupons don&rsquo;t work! Product attribute pricing mostly works.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Along with getting broken features to work (you&rsquo;ve seen my article &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.lasallemart.com/index.php/straight-talk-about-lasallemart\" target=\"_blank\">Straight Talk About LaSalleMart</a>&ldquo;?), I&rsquo;m also learning what some mysterious features are. There&rsquo;s something in product attributes I&rsquo;ve not figured out yet. But, I did figure out what &ldquo;automatic&rdquo; coupons are supposed to be. I&rsquo;m not sure I like the way it is implemented, but the concept is: &ldquo;if a coupon is applicable, apply it regardless of your buyer entering it into the coupon form&rdquo;. I&rsquo;ll take another look at the code, but I will probably suppress this feature on the basis that it is incompletely implemented.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I already deleted a chunk of Joomla 1.5 code, and there is more refactoring to do as I go. None of which should impact LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Subscriptions is something that I&rsquo;m eager to excise from LM2, along with some other features. Although I did not want to amputate code initially, as LM2 further stabilizes, it will be safer to chop extraneous code. The leaner and meaner, the better.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With the push to get LM2 to a workable state for live sites, and for the JED listing, concluded, now commences the phase where the features tighten up, and the overall code gets as lean and mean as we can get it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then, there&rsquo;s feature build-out, and refactoring the core. Although it might not be a completely linear finish-to-start progression.</p>\r\n', 'Now that I have LaSalleMart 2.0 to the point where it can be listed on the Joomla Extensions Directory, along with the extra articles and stuff — just last week! — and on its first live site, I am starting the work to improve LM2.', 'Now that I have LaSalleMart 2.0 to the point where it can be listed on the Joomla Extensions Directory, along with the extra articles and stuff — just last week! — and on its first live site, I am starting the work to improve LM2.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-in-flight-improvements-started', 'airplane2.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-03-11', '2013-03-11 12:00:00', 1, '2013-03-11 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(73, 0, NULL, NULL, 'New LaSalleMart Knowledge Base', 'new-lasallemart-knowledge-base', '<p>The explanations in LaSalleMart&rsquo;s admin are nice, but frequently inadequate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The verbosity some explanations overwhelm the limited space.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What to do, what to do? Create pages on my website, on my Anahita site, or what? What I&rsquo;ve decided to do, and what I started, is maintaining a separate knowledge base site on my Atlassian.com&rsquo;s account.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When necessary, and when permissions allow, I can link to JIRA and whatever else is available in the Atlassian software development&nbsp;milieu.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As well, Confluence will be the new site where Club Commerce members comment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart&rsquo;s category and product details admin forms now have links to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://southlasalle.atlassian.net/wiki/display/lasallemartkb/Category+and+Product+Layouts\" target=\"_blank\">this knowledge base article</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the first of many knowledge base articles.</p>\r\n', 'The explanations in LaSalleMart’s admin are nice, but frequently inadequate. The verbosity some explanations overwhelm the limited space.\r\n', 'The explanations in LaSalleMart’s admin are nice, but frequently inadequate. The verbosity some explanations overwhelm the limited space.\r\n', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/new-lasallemart-knowledge-base', 'blackboard1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-04-03', '2013-04-03 12:00:00', 1, '2013-04-03 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(74, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Serious Round of LaSalleMart Improvements About to Conclude', 'serious-round-of-lasallemart-improvements-about-to-conclude', '<p>An intense round of serious improvements and fixes is concluding.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This work is a result of an extended user testing phase, and is concentrated on core features: product features, category features, standard shipping, layouts. And more!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Included in this effort is the new&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2013/new-lasallemart-knowledge-base\" target=\"_blank\">LaSalleMart Knowledge Base</a>, which I am beefing up as I go along.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Digging into the product and category details admin forms has been particularly intense. The forms themselves are hard to read. Many of the settings are mysterious. Many settings don&rsquo;t work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My Knowledge Base has turned into a terrific outlet for me to talk to you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example, I spent four hours yesterday on parent and child categories. Yup, four hours of figuring out, playing with code, whipping up menu items, and scratching notes the old fashioned way &mdash; paper meet pen, pen meet paper. I scratched out a chart &mdash; well, why not put this chart on the KB for you? Then, I &lsquo;splained that I would leave the front-end handling of categories as-is.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So this initial round of LM2 user testing &mdash; taking approx two months &mdash; will conclude over the next couple of days. Probably end up being version 2.0.005.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When LaSalleMart 1.0 for Joomla 1.5&prime;s initial (and only, as it turned out) user testing phase concluded, I knew LM1 was ready for sites. It&rsquo;s the same thing this time, only much more satisfying. Having traversed the codebase more intimately than ever, having stepped through more features, fixing and improving throughout, implementing new communications venues with you, working on more dev and live LM2 sites than I did with LM1, LaSalleMart 2 is ready for your site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not that the work is finished: broader usage will uncover more issues; further work is needed on coupons and standard shipping, among others. These things are properly deferred out of UAT&rsquo;s initial phase.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, phase one of UAT is concluding. And LaSalleMart 2.0 is ready for serious implementation on live sites.</p>\r\n', 'An intense round of serious improvements and fixes is concluding. This work is a result of an extended user testing phase, and is concentrated on core features: product features, category features, standard shipping, layouts. And more!', 'An intense round of serious improvements and fixes is concluding. This work is a result of an extended user testing phase, and is concentrated on core features: product features, category features, standard shipping, layouts. And more!', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/serious-round-of-lasallemart-improvements-about-to-conclude', 'hammering1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-04-10', '2013-04-10 12:00:00', 1, '2013-04-10 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(75, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Sitting Ducks: Joomla 1.5 Sites Getting Hacked — What To Do', 'sitting-ducks-joomla-1-5-sites-getting-hacked-what-to-do', '<p>Another recent enquiry about a hacked Joomla 1.5 site. This time, encoded javascript in a module&rsquo;s view (/modules/mod_foobar/tmpl/default.php).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Just enough J!1.5 sites have been hacked in my orbit of sites in a short period time to lead me to conclude that&nbsp;it&rsquo;s a pattern, not random.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These hacks are invasive, writing snippets of javascript at the top of some PHP files, files that are invoked often. Sometimes, but in my own experience not usually, the hack involves writing to the database encoded javascript.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once your site is invaded with an injection hack, you&rsquo;re screwed. Forget about going into each PHP file and excising the offensive javascript. This approach lacks completeness, and you will invariably miss a file. I counsel zapping your site and reconstructing it. If you have a backup(s) to restore, you must restore it on a known clean server first in order to inspect that it is indeed clean. &nbsp;Even with a known good backup, I&rsquo;m still paranoid to counsel rebuilding this site from fresh installations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla 1.5 is not supported by the Joomla Project. Hackers know that these sites are sitting ducks for hacks. There is code on these sites that is vulnerable to hacks. Joomla 1.5 sites are soft targets for hard hacking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I look back and think that I should have been extreme with my Joomla 1.5 installations. The benefit of hindsight, for sure. Instead of just taking Joomla 1.5 as-is and installing it as-is, I should have actively managed Joomla 1.5 itself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is my own checklist for going back to Joomla 1.5 sites. It&rsquo;s a list of things that can be done today, without clients thinking I&rsquo;m dreaming up excuses to invoice &lsquo;em:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>decent .htaccess file in webroot;</li>\r\n	<li>update JCE to the latest version (v2.3.1 for J!1.5) (older versions of JCE might be susceptible to hacks);</li>\r\n	<li>if you know of Joomla 1.5 updates for your extensions, update &lsquo;em;</li>\r\n	<li>delete every component that can be deleted;</li>\r\n	<li>delete unused templates;</li>\r\n	<li>delete the native Joomla banner, newsfeed, poll, weblinks components, b/c these components are delete-able;</li>\r\n	<li>make sure you are using Joomla 1.5.26 &mdash; yeah, it matters.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Keep managing your going-concern Joomla 1.5 sites!</p>\r\n', 'Another recent enquiry about a hacked Joomla 1.5 site. This time, encoded javascript in a module’s view. Just enough J!1.5 sites have been hacked in my orbit of sites in a short period time to lead me to conclude that it’s a pattern, not random...', 'Another recent enquiry about a hacked Joomla 1.5 site. This time, encoded javascript in a module’s view. Just enough J!1.5 sites have been hacked in my orbit of sites in a short period time to lead me to conclude that it’s a pattern, not random...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/sitting-ducks-joomla-1-5-sites-getting-hacked-what-to-do', 'duck1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-04-14', '2013-04-14 12:00:00', 1, '2013-04-14 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(76, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Atlassian Road Show 2013 in Toronto: First Hand Lessons', 'atlassian-road-show-2013-in-toronto-first-hand-lessons', '<p>Toronto marked the fifth of four USA cities and one Canuck city Atlassian visited on their&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.atlassian.com/roadtrip\" target=\"_blank\">Road Trip 2013</a>. San Francisco is home to their American office, so is that really a road trip? LA, Chicago, New York, and here.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Held in a swank restaurant&rsquo;s suprisingly large private meeting room at King/Spadina. Offering open bar, teriyaki meatballs, slider cheeseburgers, shrimp to mainly corporate attendees.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My interest is partaking in the rare opportunity to gain first hand knowledge of JIRA (their flagship issue tracker), Confluence (website &amp; document sharing), and a sprinkling of Bamboo (continuous integration). Enjoyed talking to the friendly Atlassian people, and enjoyed the very professional hour long presentation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Atlassian is based in Sydney, with an office in SF. They offer a software</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0078.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0078-224x300.jpg\" style=\"float:right; height:300px; margin:0px 0px 10px 10px; width:224px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>dev suite enabling collaborative software development. This is similar to what Assembla offers, which I had a great interest in. After using Assembla (and GitHub), and after being treated to a personal one-on-one webinar by &ldquo;Know where the bodies are buried&rdquo; Deb Cinkus (thank you, again, Deb), I decided to use Atlassian.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The hour long presentation was well done. Using their own experience with JIRA et al, they told a story. There were no technical difficulties, the usual pixel diffusion from an overhead was offset by tv screens along the breadth of the room p<br />\r\nIt is noteworthy that Atlassian stressed that its software dev products are collaborative. I expected to hear the wordlugged into the presentation. Videos of head office personages along with on-scene clips of everyday office life gave a sense of the company behind the presentation. JIRA itself is a decade old, its sister products more recent. Although a SaaS &ldquo;On Demand&rdquo; version of the software exists, many attendees use self-hosted versions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;distributed&rdquo;, as in distributed development. Where people located far and away from each other are brought together through web based soft</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0081\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0081-224x300.jpg\" style=\"float:left; height:300px; margin:0px 10px 10px 0px; width:224px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>ware development. Nope. People may or may not be &ldquo;co-located&rdquo;, but the software process itself is collaborative. Collaborative meaning that thou shalt work together! Moving JIRA from SVN to Git, and bring QA into the software development process as (my phrase) &ldquo;Total Quality Management&rdquo; instead of as a separate function, spurred Atlassian into a collaborative culture &mdash; and its offerings as a mechanism for collaboration as software development. In the spirit of &ldquo;The Medium is the Message&rdquo;, the Process is the Software &mdash; boy, I really need to do a post about this. The end result for the JIRA team is releasing a new build to its clients bi-weekly. Relevant, quality software released often.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are two things I found very interesting. First was having post-its and hand-written pieces of paper plastere</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The other thing that I found intriguing was the confession that design gets-in-the-way. So, to solve it, Atlassian &ldquo;put people in a room for three weeks&rdquo; (with a stack of post-its, I&rsquo;m sure), and the dev teams &ldquo;signed the contracts&rdquo; to the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.atlassian.com/design/\" target=\"_blank\">Atlassian Design Guidelines</a>. Here&rsquo;s something to bring into LaSalleMart &mdash; I&rsquo;ll be looking at this. Very interesting.d around the office. Perhaps to Digital Hipsters, paper is the new retro. But, an interesting lesson about co-locationl and, to get people to actually work together, ya gotta get &lsquo;em the heck away from the screens! White board (remember those?) and card-sized pieces of paper. And I thought eye-to-eye contact when talking to people was so Last Century!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I next log into my Atlassian on-demand instance, I will have a better idea of what I&rsquo;m using. Very glad I made it downtown for the Atlassian Road Show 2013.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UPDATE (Apr 22): I&rsquo;m on the left sitting on the couch&hellip; hard to see!&nbsp;<a href=\"http://blogs.atlassian.com/2013/04/atlassian-roadtrip-week-3-toronto-and-london/\" target=\"_blank\">http://blogs.atlassian.com/2013/04/atlassian-roadtrip-week-3-toronto-and-london/</a></p>\r\n', 'Toronto marked the fifth of four USA cities and one Canuck city Atlassian visited on their Road Trip 2013. San Francisco is home to their American office, so is that really a road trip? LA, Chicago, New York, and here...', 'Toronto marked the fifth of four USA cities and one Canuck city Atlassian visited on their Road Trip 2013. San Francisco is home to their American office, so is that really a road trip? LA, Chicago, New York, and here...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/atlassian-road-show-2013-in-toronto-first-hand-lessons', 'IMG_0080.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-04-16', '2013-04-16 12:00:00', 1, '2013-04-16 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(77, 0, NULL, NULL, 'To Joomla 3, or Not To Joomla 3?', 'joomla3-or-no-joomla3', '<p>Joomla 3.1 is out and to my surprise it is labelled &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.joomla.org/announcements/release-news/5494-joomla-3-1-0-stable-released.html\" target=\"_blank\">stable</a>&ldquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Should We Use Joomla 3.1+?</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>My understanding of Joomla 3 is:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>version 3 is for play until the Long Term Support (LTS) version 3.5 is out;</li>\r\n	<li>everything is change-able in the Joomla 3 Short Term Support (STS) versions;</li>\r\n	<li>move from 2.5 to 3.5;</li>\r\n	<li>new sites in 2.5.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>A couple of Joomla docs links:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://docs.joomla.org/Joomla_3_FAQ\" target=\"_blank\">Joomla doc&rsquo;s &ldquo;Joomla 3 FAQ&rdquo;</a>;</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2013/Release%20and%20support%20cycle\" target=\"_blank\">Joomla doc&rsquo;s &ldquo;Release and support cycle&rdquo;</a>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>This STS vs LTS stuff is taken from Linux. Just for fun, here are two Ubuntu wiki pages:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://wiki.ubuntu.com/\" target=\"_blank\">home page with chart of releases</a>;</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://wiki.ubuntu.com/LTS\" target=\"_blank\">page &lsquo;splainin&rsquo; LTS</a>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>My new understanding of Joomla 3 is:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>version 3.1+ is kosher for &ldquo;real&rdquo; sites;</li>\r\n	<li>v3.1+ has so many cool standard must-have features that it&rsquo;s a must-have;</li>\r\n	<li>v3.1+ is still STS, and therefore change-able, and when things change to our detriment, the official answer will be: &ldquo;it&rsquo;s an STS&rdquo;;</li>\r\n	<li>migrate 2.5 sites to 3.1+ -&gt; perhaps;</li>\r\n	<li>new sites in 3.1+ -&gt; perhaps.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla 3 is a moving target. You install it with your eyes open. 3.1+ represents a meld of STS + LTS. It&rsquo;s &ldquo;stable&rdquo;, but it&rsquo;s change-able. Your template works with 3.10, but breaks with 3.12 &mdash; &ldquo;TBSS&rdquo; (too bad, so sad, don&rsquo;t cry for me Argentina).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, my bottom line straight answer to the question, &nbsp;&ldquo;Should I use Joomla 3.1+&rdquo;, is: &ldquo;it depends&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>LaSalleMart 2 and Joomla 3:</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Let&rsquo;s cut to the chase here: will LM2 work in J!3? As is, no. But, no does not mean no, you know.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s a wonderful trick that I&rsquo;ve used over the years: multiple websites, one database.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;db_host&rdquo; is the same, &ldquo;db_password&rdquo; is the same, and each site uses its own &ldquo;db_name&rdquo;. So we have two Joomla sites: one the v3 site, and the other the v2.5 site. Both use the same database. So, in the code, we can use whatever table we want. Of course, we might have to hard code the db prefix for the second site, but a small price to pay. Perhaps make the second site&rsquo;s db prefix a new config parameter, eh! Hmmm&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are three areas of LaSalleMart:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>front-end;</li>\r\n	<li>cart;</li>\r\n	<li>administrator.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Use K2 or similar for the front-end. Bam. There&rsquo;s your Joomla 3 site for your products and categories. I advocate using Joomla or K2 type extension for your front-end anyways, in order to harness the full power of Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The cart needs to be in the public facing (non-administrator) part of Joomla. The cart on its own is a great candidate for porting to Joomla 3, as is the address management. But, that&rsquo;s for later. In the here and now, you need to have the cart in a Joomla 2.5 site. So, you set up your J!2.5 site in a separate child folder /store/.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The admin is Joomla 2.5. Does it matter that this is in J!2.5?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Basically, LaSalleMart is in the Joomla 2.5 site. With some modification, the LM2 &ldquo;Content&rdquo; plugin (puts the add-to-cart form on Joomla pages, and any extension that renders content plugins) and the LM2 &ldquo;Cart&rdquo; module will work in J!3.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Keep the cart area incredibly clean. Go easy on the modules. Keep the same header and footer. Most templates have J!2.5 and J!3 versions, so the look-and-feel will be similar. It&rsquo;ll be somewhat easy to set up the J!2.5 site b/c it&rsquo;s front-end is less intensive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Any synchronizing between the two websites&rsquo; databases will be do-able b/c they share the same database.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, it&rsquo;s do-able. The effort is tiny compared to converting LM2 to Joomla 3.1+.</p>\r\n', 'To Joomla 3 or not to Joomla 3, that is the question. My understanding of Joomla 3 is...', 'To Joomla 3 or not to Joomla 3, that is the question. My understanding of Joomla 3 is...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/joomla3-or-no-joomla3', 'large_hamlet_blu-ray1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-04-30', '2013-04-30 12:00:00', 1, '2013-04-30 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(78, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Take It From The Man: Make Joomla Your Joomla', 'take-it-from-the-man-make-joomla-your-joomla', '<p>From a business perspective, those who use Joomla need to manage it. Directly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why? Because Joomla left on its own represents risk. This risk needs to be mitigate through active management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Case study: Joomla 1.5 is not officially supported by the Joomla Project, but there are a lot of J!1.5 sites out there. These sites are&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2013/sitting-ducks-joomla-1-5-sites-getting-hacked-what-to-do\" target=\"_blank\">sitting ducks for hackers</a>, who are probing these sites for their soft spots.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why? Because managing Joomla represents business opportunity. Eg:&nbsp;Bundling extensions together lowers cost of technology acquisition.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Case study: Template clubs&rsquo; &ldquo;QuickLaunch&rdquo; bundles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;<a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/joomla-dev-framework\" target=\"_blank\">Joomla Framework Development&rsquo;s Google Group</a>, and the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/joomla-dev-cms\" target=\"_blank\">Joomla CMS Development Google Group</a>, are where discussions about the Joomla FW and CMS take place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The fact that there are two separate discussion groups is something you should ponder right off the bat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Busting up Joomla is a great way to increase security. The less code on your site, the less code that can be hacked. Joomla comes with a lot of extra code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Don&rsquo;t take my word for it. Listen to<a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/#!msg/joomla-dev-cms/yKSCfC15KoM/7bvtn9TToDcJ\" target=\"_blank\">&nbsp;what The Man says:</a></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>To me the point is that the one-size-Joomla-download-fits-all doesn&rsquo;t hold<br />\r\nwater. It&rsquo;s a line of best fit, and when the points are a scattergram<br />\r\n(Pearson correlation approaching zero) it&rsquo;s more like a shot in the dark.<br />\r\nSo instead of trying to please-all and pleasing-none (slight exageration<br />\r\nfor effect)&nbsp;<strong>you bust things up so people can, potentially, roll their own</strong><br />\r\n<strong>distro that better suits their need</strong>s.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>The Man is Andrew Eddie. From what I can discern, he is The Man of the Platform effort. Perhaps one of a handful of &ldquo;The Man&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Man&rsquo;s phrase, not mine: &ldquo;bust up&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Man&rsquo;s &nbsp;phrase, not mine: &ldquo;roll your own distro&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Man&rsquo;s phrase, not mine: &ldquo;suit your needs&rdquo;. Actually, it&rsquo;s part of the software licence that comes with Joomla &mdash; that you can change the program.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s been a number of efforts that have come and gone over the years to bust up Joomla. It&rsquo;s a lot of work, and a commitment is needed to sustain the effort so updates are done. This is something I want to grow as LaSalleMart grows, that we do here in-house, but make available to all.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My LaSalleCMS is for this purpose, but the demands of LaSalleMart have been too intense to kickstart work on it. This is indicative of what&rsquo;s been happening to ambitious &ldquo;bust-up, distro-out&rdquo; efforts!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here&rsquo;s another one from the same link from The Man:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>I don&rsquo;t see how this changes anything. The auto-update should be able to work with a monolithic collection of extensions (that&rsquo;s really what our Joomla distro is) or individually installed extensions. In other works [sic], auto-updating should work today (theoretically) regardless of whether, for example, &ldquo;Banners&rdquo; came with distro or was installed later from someones &ldquo;playlist&rdquo; off the JED.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla is a monolithic collection of extensions, libraries, templates. The word &ldquo;collection&rdquo; is used to describe a specific way the Joomla Updater works. However, in a turn of phrase, a &ldquo;collection of extensions&rdquo; describes Joomla as it exists today.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE:</strong>&nbsp;see my comments further to this post in my May 2013 &ldquo;LaSalleMart News&rdquo;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://southlasallemedia.com/2013/lasallemart17\" target=\"_blank\">podcast</a>(transcript available).</p>\r\n', 'From a business perspective, those who use Joomla need to manage it. Directly.\r\nWhy? Because Joomla left on its own represents risk. This risk needs to be mitigate through active management...', 'From a business perspective, those who use Joomla need to manage it. Directly.\r\nWhy? Because Joomla left on its own represents risk. This risk needs to be mitigate through active management...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/take-it-from-the-man-make-joomla-your-joomla', 'how-to-stick-it-to-the-man.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-04-30', '2013-04-30 12:00:00', 1, '2013-04-30 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(79, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Keep Your Eye on… LaSalleMart!', 'keep-your-eye-on-lasallemart', '<p>LaSalleMart has graduated to the &ldquo;Keep your eye on these&rdquo; list.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>See&nbsp;<a href=\"http://polishedgeek.com/media/checkout-your-options-joomla-ecommerce-deb-cinkus-polished-geek-april1-2013.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Checkout Your Joomla eCommerce Options (pdf)</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scroll down. Way down! Scroll down past the &ldquo;Whatever happened to&hellip;&rdquo; page that lists Tienda. Of course, LaSalleMart 2 is a fork of Tienda&rsquo;s first, and only, Joomla 2.5 build.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scroll down past the LM2 mention, and you see a picture of 2 Swiss army knives. One has two attachments, the other has a zillion attachments. Very good visual when thinking of LM2.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For those who prefer extensions that are listed on the JED, I applied at the beginning of March 2013, so it&rsquo;s 2 months now &ldquo;Pending Approval&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/polished_geek_ecomm_overview1.png\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/polished_geek_ecomm_overview1-300x260.png\" style=\"float:left; height:260px; margin:0px 10px 10px 0px; width:300px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/polished_geek_ecomm_overview2.png\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/polished_geek_ecomm_overview2-300x208.png\" style=\"height:208px; width:300px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/polished_geek_ecomm_overview3.png\"><img alt=\"So slow I forked. Best thing I ever did. \" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/polished_geek_ecomm_overview3-300x220.png\" style=\"height:220px; width:300px\" /></a></p>\r\n', 'LaSalleMart has graduated to the “Keep your eye on these” list...', 'LaSalleMart has graduated to the “Keep your eye on these” list...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/keep-your-eye-on-lasallemart', 'polished_geek_ecomm_overview4.png', 1, 0, 0, '2013-04-30', '2013-04-30 12:00:00', 1, '2013-04-30 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(80, 0, NULL, NULL, 'WonderFoodCo: Live LaSalleMart Site', 'live-lasallemart-site', '<p><a href=\"http://wonderfoodco.com/index.php/buy/shop-online\" target=\"_blank\">WonderFoodCo.com</a>&nbsp;is a Joomla 2.5 Gavick based LaSalleMart 2.0 site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many LaSalleMart improvements are inspired by this site. Such as friendlier category and product details admin forms, and user defined fields in the PayPal Standard plugin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>April was busy, culminating in yesterday&rsquo;s build of version 2.0.008.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This LM2 build is the best ever. LaSalleMart 1.0 never got this far. Things that I wanted to see are there.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 2.0 is a fork of Tienda&rsquo;s first (and only) Joomla 2.5 build. What was unusable is now used on a real site. Not every corner of what was inherited used/tested, but the key stuff is.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The cart is smooth. The site registration and address management are smooth. The checkout progression is step-by-step, logical, with cues along the way. From where we came with what we had, this is a big win. From here, we can improve things further.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Checkout looks good on an ipad &mdash; just keep the number of modules down to a minimum in the cart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart inherits the template styles &mdash; it&rsquo;s really Joomla!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Standard Shipping got a lot of love. I&rsquo;m talking, a whole lotta love! There are seven standard shipping types, and it&rsquo;s not a de-humanizing experience setting it up.<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/wf_profile_overview1.png\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/wf_profile_overview1-300x256.png\" style=\"float:right; height:256px; margin:0px 0px 10px 10px; width:300px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>PayPal Standard works. You have the power now to specify the PP Stnd images and messages that your buyers see in checkout (don&rsquo;t ask me how long that &ldquo;quick&rdquo; improvement took).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A buyer complained that the address she just entered into LM2 did not display at PayPal.com &mdash; &ldquo;why do I have to enter it again?&rdquo;. Done!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The updating is phenomenal. The component uses Akeeba Live Update, which I now use all the time, and it is fabulous. Click, baby, click, and you have the latest LM. Go to Joomla&rsquo;s extension updater, and all the LM2 plugins, modules, and its library update in two clicks (click the &ldquo;all&rdquo; box, then the &ldquo;Update&rdquo; button). Getting things set up for this smooth updating was a major PITA effort &mdash; oooh, but what a payoff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/wf_add_to_cart1.png\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/wf_add_to_cart1-300x164.png\" style=\"float:left; height:164px; margin:0px 10px 10px 0px; width:300px\" /></a>Using Atlassian.com is starting to shape up. Seeing code commits in the repositories and the JIRA issues and in my Confluence Knowledge Base &mdash; it&rsquo;s a beautiful thing. You can initiate real software issues in your LM2 administrator &mdash; there&rsquo;s a &ldquo;kvetch&rdquo; form that links to my JIRA. The dev side is looking good.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Multiple LM2 editions is a success. There are five editions, but I&rsquo;m usually using the California or Canadian editions. Wonderfoods is a California site. There are 1,700-ish municipal tax rates in my California LM2. On April 1st, about two dozen rates changed. I changed the rates, and Wonderfoods received the updated tax rate changes automatically (after doing a Live Update). Great to see it work!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/wf_checkout_step1.png\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/wf_checkout_step1-300x284.png\" style=\"height:284px; width:300px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>I improved the add-to-cart form&rsquo;s handling quite a bit. Product attributes received some lovin&rsquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am excited to see my labours bear fruit. I am excited to see concepts bear out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You have a new alternative today for your sites that need standard shipping and PayPal Standard.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We got this far, and we&rsquo;re going further.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.lasallemart.com/index.php/contact-bob\">Tell me about your site</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/wf_checkout_step2.png\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/wf_checkout_step2-300x264.png\" style=\"height:264px; margin-right:10px; width:300px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/wf_checkout_step3.png\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/wf_checkout_step3-252x300.png\" style=\"height:300px; width:252px\" /> </a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/wf_checkout_step4.png\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/wf_checkout_step4-248x300.png\" style=\"height:300px; width:248px\" /> </a></p>\r\n', 'WonderFoodCo.com is a Joomla 2.5 Gavick based LaSalleMart 2.0 site. Many LaSalleMart improvements are inspired by this site. Such as friendlier category and product details admin forms, and user defined fields in the PayPal Standard plugin. April was busy for LaSalleMart’s changelog. Culminating in yesterday’s build of version 2.0.008. This LM2 build is the best ever...', 'WonderFoodCo.com is a Joomla 2.5 Gavick based LaSalleMart 2.0 site. Many LaSalleMart improvements are inspired by this site. Such as friendlier category and product details admin forms, and user defined fields in the PayPal Standard plugin. April was busy', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/live-lasallemart-site', 'wf_category_browse1.png', 1, 0, 0, '2013-04-30', '2013-04-30 12:00:00', 1, '2013-04-30 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(81, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Important Notes About LaSalleMart 2.0', 'important-notes-about-lasallemart-2-0', '<p>My new Knowledge Base page turned into a blog post:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>reminder that LM2 is a fork;</li>\r\n	<li>why untested features are sprinkled &mdash; and duly noted &mdash; in the LM;</li>\r\n	<li>Joomla 3 and refactoring.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>See my new wiki page at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://southlasalle.atlassian.net/wiki/display/lasallemartkb/Important+Notes+About+LaSalleMart+2.0\" target=\"_blank\">https://southlasalle.atlassian.net/wiki/display/lasallemartkb/Important+Notes+About+LaSalleMart+2.0</a></p>\r\n', 'My new Knowledge Base page turned into a blog post...', 'My new Knowledge Base page turned into a blog post...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/important-notes-about-lasallemart-2-0', 'important1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-05-04', '2013-05-04 12:00:00', 1, '2013-05-04 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(82, 0, NULL, NULL, 'New Mandrill Library for LaSalleMart', 'new-mandrill-library-for-lasallemart', '<p>Ever had a customer ask you where their email went? You ask them if they checked their spam folder, and that&rsquo;s about it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Would be nice to look up some stats. Well, that&rsquo;s where Mandrill comes in. MailChimp makes Mandrill. Mandrill is how we can send our emails through MailChimp.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the midst of developing LaSalleMart&rsquo;s first app, getting Mandrill up-and-running for LM became priority. The app sends an email notification, and it absolutely positively has to get there. So, time to dig into Mandrill.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Originally, I installed the excellent&nbsp;<a href=\"https://compojoom.com/about/blog/entry/cmandrill-joomla-transactional-emails-on-steroids-thanks-to-mandrill\" target=\"_blank\">Compojoom CMandrill extension (a component and a plugin)</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My app is based on the &ldquo;command line interface&rdquo; of the Joomla Platform. Well, I could not figure out how to get my app to use CMandrill. So, I created a library, which is what I really wanted to do in the first place! It is based on CMandrill, of course.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My lib_mandrill is a library, but there are two parameters that it takes from LaSalleMart&rsquo;s config. Libraries do not have a door in Joomla&rsquo;s Administrator, so if there are any parameters, one has to create a plugin or a component. Since I want lib_mandrill to work with LaSalleMart, it seems natural to add the new library settings to LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background:rgb(244, 244, 244); border:1px solid rgb(221, 221, 221); padding:5px 0px 0px 1px\"><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/lasallemart_mandrill_config1.png\"><img alt=\"Mandrill Library Settings in LM\'s Config\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/lasallemart_mandrill_config1-300x73.png\" style=\"height:73px; width:300px\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<p>Mandrill Library Settings in LM&rsquo;s Config</p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is also a special status in LM&rsquo;s Dashboard. It is imperative that your Mandrill API Key exists. Just installing lib_mandrill is no help &mdash; we need the API Key! So, I added a sub-status for the API Key as well:</p>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background:rgb(244, 244, 244); border:1px solid rgb(221, 221, 221); padding:5px 0px 0px 1px\"><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/lasallemart_mandrill_status1.png\"><img alt=\"Mandrill Status in LM\'s Dashboard\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/lasallemart_mandrill_status1-300x74.png\" style=\"height:74px; width:300px\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<p>Mandrill Status in LM&rsquo;s Dashboard</p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No, I am not an MailChimp affiliate. I see the merits of Mandrill for us, I am a happy MC user, so ta-da: meet our new lib_mandrill!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://southlasalle.atlassian.net/wiki/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=2457667\" target=\"_blank\">Knowledge Base Page</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>P.S. &nbsp;lib_mandrill installs successfully in Joomla 3.1. Haven&rsquo;t tested it in 3.1, but certainly had my eye on 3.1 whilst programming.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>P.S.S. &nbsp;Looks like I&rsquo;m being forked! See if we can get it on GitHub&hellip;&nbsp;<a href=\"https://compojoom.com/forum/116-mandrill-for-joomla/17796-using-cmandrill-in-cli#20680\" target=\"_blank\">https://compojoom.com/forum/116-mandrill-for-joomla/17796-using-cmandrill-in-cli#20680</a></p>\r\n', 'In the midst of developing LaSalleMart’s first app, getting Mandrill up-and-running for LM became priority. The app sends an email notification, and it absolutely positively has to get there. So, time to dig into Mandrill.', 'In the midst of developing LaSalleMart’s first app, getting Mandrill up-and-running for LM became priority. The app sends an email notification, and it absolutely positively has to get there. So, time to dig into Mandrill.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/new-mandrill-library-for-lasallemart', 'Mandrill_Logo_Dark-Background-aa1c0aa4.png', 1, 0, 0, '2013-05-15', '2013-05-15 12:00:00', 1, '2013-05-15 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(83, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Joomla 3, LaSalleMart 2, and the Wrong Side of Midnight', 'joomla-3-lasallemart-2-and-the-wrong-side-of-midnighta', '<p>LaSalleMart 2 is not made for Joomla 3.1. The solution is to put the ecommerce front-end in a separate Joomla 3 site in the webroot; and, install a Joomla 2.5 site in a sub-folder off the webroot for the cart and LM admin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The reason to push for Joomla 3.1 is primarily for the mobile capabilities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The separation of LaSalleMart into &ldquo;front&rdquo;, &ldquo;cart&rdquo;, and &ldquo;admin&rdquo; is natural. The &ldquo;front&rdquo; comprises what is usually the category and product pages. A reason to use Joomla for ecommerce is for its powerful &ldquo;front&rdquo; &mdash; the menus, the templating, the modules, the third party extensions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is no way that LaSalleMart can, or should, be so chock full of front-end capabilities anyways. A lot of what we see in LM&rsquo;s config is related to its front-end presentation. Hey, just remember that for product presentation, you have the full power of Joomla at your disposal &mdash; which is a prime reason for using Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Seeing how this solution works out practically, I set up the third LaSalleMart site in just this way. Technically, it is do-able. Practically, I think the effort to achieve the technical pieces are not worth it at this point. The concerns are the integrations needed. There are actually minimal technical integrations required to achieve this dual site set-up &mdash; this is actually do-able right now. However, building a kick-ass customer experience requires achieving beyond the minimum.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Technically, no integration is required, except to link from the J!3.1 product pages to the corresponding J!2.5 LaSalleMart product pages. Users have no reason to register on the J!3.1 site &mdash; big PITA side-stepped. What we end up with are two separate and distinct sites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A big plus is that templates are built for both J!3.1 and J!2.5. So creating a uniform look is do-able.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your customers want a seamless experience, regardless of the number of sites they need to traverse. So, there must be just one single add-to-cart button &mdash; which is in the J!3.1 site. There must be a cart module on the J!3.1 site as well as the J!2.5 site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using a common database, and having the J!2.5 site in a subfolder off the root, we have a good basis for the integration. The fun is in the details, and diving headlong into the technical issues would take more time than its worth. The issues seem similar to the web app I started, where one site calls the web app where LaSalleMart is installed. I foresee having to create a CLI app that grabs the data and layout for mod_app. The add-to-cart would be fun, having to add to a cart that resides on a separate (yet accessible) site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If we ever need to create this set-up, we know it&rsquo;s do-able. By, essentially, keeping the sites separate and distinct, yet related.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I do wonder, though, if we can yank J!3.1&prime;s /media/jui/ and plunk it into J!2.5. We already have Akeeba&rsquo;s &ldquo;Strapper&rdquo; if we need it as a way to get Bootstrap onto our J!2.5 site. Maybe transplanting JUI is another way &mdash; it looks like a library like any other library. If the essential issue is using Bootstrap for uber-responsive sites, then we probably don&rsquo;t have to jump to Joomla 3.1 yet. Just bolster J!2.5. &nbsp;Something to keep in mind.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE (May 27, 2013):</strong>&nbsp;Yes, definitely can yank JUI from 3.1 to 2.5. Gantry does it &mdash; see the&nbsp;libraries/gantry/assets/jui/ folder.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla 3.1 is a short-term release. I confess a touch of apprehension building a J!3.1 site knowing that it can change, with the risk that this change is unknown so who knows how these changes would impact my front-end site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But, do not get the wrong idea. I want to transition to Joomla 3.x, en route to J!3.5 &mdash; the Long Term Release. To this end, my new programming uses the Akeeba Framework-on-Framework (version 2), which intermediates between my component and Joomla. So I can program once, and my component will work on both J!3.1 and J!2.5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am in the midst of creating four &mdash; count &lsquo;em! &mdash; new components. I&rsquo;ll talk more about this on my blog, or in my next podcast. So far, it is working that FoF is letting me create one component for both Joomlas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I want all my new LM work to be ready for Joomla 3, so using FoF is critical. When I modify the source code I frequently end up in Joomla&rsquo;s doc, to see if this code will likely work in J!3.1, or what tweaks are needed. It&rsquo;s a fine line between tweaking for J!3.1; and, screwing up existing code. The same decision when I originally forked into LaSalleMart: do I amputate code to ahieve a lean-and-mean codebase; or, do I defer in case I break something.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All this forward work on Joomla 3 has been putting me on the wrong side of midnight. The learning is good, pushing the technology is good. But, some core work&rsquo;s been put on hold as a result. Now that we&rsquo;ve peered into the future, it&rsquo;s time to spend my midnight hour back on more core issues &mdash; and on my webapp(s).</p>\r\n', 'LaSalleMart 2 is not made for Joomla 3.1. The solution is to put the ecommerce front-end in a separate Joomla 3 site in the webroot; and, install a Joomla 2.5 site in a sub-folder off the webroot for the cart and LM admin.', 'LaSalleMart 2 is not made for Joomla 3.1. The solution is to put the ecommerce front-end in a separate Joomla 3 site in the webroot; and, install a Joomla 2.5 site in a sub-folder off the webroot for the cart and LM admin.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/joomla-3-lasallemart-2-and-the-wrong-side-of-midnighta', 'clock1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-05-22', '2013-05-22 12:00:00', 1, '2013-05-22 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(84, 0, NULL, NULL, 'The Long Term Has Arrived', 'the-long-term-has-arrived', '<p>The long term has arrived. It is now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Concepts underlying LaSalleMart&rsquo;s development are coming into play this month, manifesting directly into the code and into daily development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, there is a vision with LaSalleMart. What makes this month of May 2013 different from other months is the extent to which this vision is tangible-i-fying into real development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An underlying concept is: Get Small.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Get Small&rdquo; means no more huge monolithic components. LaSalleMart inherited a monolithic monstrosity of an admin. An impenetrable mass of code. &nbsp;The file that was forked had about 60 plugins/modules/library/component.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is no one-size-fits-all LaSalleMart. That&rsquo;s not what it&rsquo;s about. LaSalleMart is not conceived to be a hyper-consumer-friendly Joomla extension to install and configure. It&rsquo;s not fire-and-forget software. LaSalleMart is conceived to be hyper-code-creation friendly, unlocking the vast potential of using Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Get Small&rdquo; means fast turnaround, quick fixes, and near instant transmission of updates to live sites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Get Small&rdquo; means lots of separate components that stick to narrow purposes. As opposed to a huge component that does everything.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve explained it, somewhat in jest, as having the power of Magento, the flexibility of Joomla, the programmable power of Drupal, and the ease-of-use of WordPress, all together.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What pissed me off enormously was waiting forever for updates for the Joomla ecomm extensions I&rsquo;ve used in the past. No way I would recreate that which angered me to viscerally. So I did things differently.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And, in so doing, I learned a valuable lesson:&nbsp;<em>the process is the code.</em>&nbsp;Akin, methinks, to Marshall McLuhan&rsquo;s &ldquo;<a href=\"http://individual.utoronto.ca/markfederman/article_mediumisthemessage.htm\" target=\"_blank\">The Medium is the Message</a>&ldquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s not about the code. It&rsquo;s about code creation. My long term goal with LaSalleMart was to have the ability to create code. Create lots of code. Create lots of code fast. Deliver that code to live sites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is the sound of a feature that never makes it to a real site? It&rsquo;s the sound of money that can&rsquo;t be made.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A massive component only gets more massive. Get small, get &ldquo;nichy&rdquo;, release fast.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the short run, it hardly made sense to get so caught up in the process of creating code. But, get caught up in the process I did. And this month, it is starting to pay off. What an investment in time and energy &mdash; and learning!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This month I tried something I&rsquo;ve never done before: could I create four components from scratch in one single day? How&rsquo;s that for putting &ldquo;code creation&rdquo; to the test.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Each component has a strictly niche purpose. Each component uses just one database, an unusual luxury. Each component will use the Akeeba Live Update to update on real sites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are two tricks: basing each component on a generic set-up; and, using the Akeeba Framework-on-Framework.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The generic set-up includes build scripts, update processes, file and folder structure, pre-fabricated manifest files &mdash; all the overhead is baked right in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The awesome Framework-on-Framework relieves us of the necessity of creating standard Joomla stuff that all components require. Parsing URLs, creating forms, etc etc. &nbsp;The FoF takes a huge burden off our hands, speeding development in so doing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>FoF did not come into the LaSalleMart picture for the longest time. To many antecedents. Standard build scripts needed to happen first. Standard Git workflows &mdash; however rudimentary given how many people are working on the code right now! &mdash; had to be figured out. So many things had to happen first, so many concepts, great and small, had to be brought into technical reality, before FoF would realize its explosive potential.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This month it was finally time to bring on FoF, in the context of &ldquo;Get Small&rdquo; &mdash; with fast turnaround and delivery.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I created com_generic. Then, based on this generic component, I created com_lasallemart_address, com_lasallemart_creditcard, com_lasallemart_manufacturer, and com_foobar_address (a custom component for a custom client project).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oh, this was the first time I used FoF in a while. And, did I mention, each component is supposed to work in Joomla 3.1?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We program for FoF, and FoF intermediates Joomla. So, using FoF&rsquo;s built-in &ldquo;let me figure out how to do things in the different Joomla version&rdquo; magic, it&rsquo;s possible to build one component that works on both Joomlas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, did I produce four new components in a day? Well, no. It turns out that, well, this is the first time I&rsquo;ve done such a thing, and so &nbsp;there are details to figure out. Such as Bootstrap, and the usual doing-for-the-first-time-means-learning-stuff-you&rsquo;d-not-know-if-you-had-not-used-it with FoF. Meaning, my generic component was not finished. But, I am getting there.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Boy, it&rsquo;s a while ago in 2010. I did a podcast called &ldquo;The Emergence of Nooku Framework Based Joomla eCommerce&rdquo;. Substitute &ldquo;FoF&rdquo; for &ldquo;Nooku&rdquo;. In this podcast I describe the scenario that is now coming to fruition. It&rsquo;s incredible to finally see it come to fruition with LaSalleMart!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Y&rsquo;know, not that we need &ldquo;com_lasallemart_manufacturer&rdquo; right now. However, for LaSalleMart 3 for Joomla 3, we will need it. A nice compact little component that manages the &ldquo;#__lasallemart_manufacturers&rdquo; &nbsp;table (oops, the &ldquo;#__lasallemart_manufacturer_items&rdquo; table &mdash; refactor alert!). If we decide we need a new feature for this component, we can Get It Done without touching any other component. How&rsquo;s that for streamlined workflow!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 3 will be a suite of small individual components. As well, it will have a broadened-out library. &ldquo;Getting Small&rdquo; means we can create LM3 over time, instead of as one big bang release.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which leads me to into &ldquo;Distros&rdquo;. Joomla has a fantastic potential to create customized distributions that cater to specific needs. &ldquo;Getting Small&rdquo; has the added benefit of being a part of future future distros. We already have a taste of this by the existence of five LM packages. If you live in Canada, you&rsquo;ll want LM Canada. What about a Joomla-LaSalleMart distro for sellers of software? A distro with no shipping, no manufacturer/vendor info &mdash; essentially a slimmed down package. Yes we can! &ldquo;Getting Small&rdquo; makes this very do-able.</p>\r\n', 'The long term has arrived. It is now. Concepts underlying LaSalleMart’s development are coming into play this month, manifesting directly into the code and into daily development. Yes, there is a vision with LaSalleMart. What makes this month of May 2013 different from other months is the extent to which this vision is tangible-i-fying into real development...', 'The long term has arrived. It is now. Concepts underlying LaSalleMart’s development are coming into play this month, manifesting directly into the code and into daily development. Yes, there is a vision with LaSalleMart. What makes this month of May 2013 ', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/the-long-term-has-arrived', 'clock2.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-05-23', '2013-05-23 12:00:00', 1, '2013-05-23 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(85, 0, NULL, NULL, 'What is Apache and htaccess?', 'what-is-apache-and-htaccess', '<p>I thought I&rsquo;d reply to an email with this blog post.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://httpd.apache.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Apache</a>&nbsp;is the world&rsquo;s most used webserver software.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is free open source software licenced under the &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.apache.org/licenses/\" target=\"_blank\">Apache License</a>&ldquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is a project of the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.apache.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Apache Software Foundation</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla sits on Apache (and Apache sits on Linux &mdash; I&rsquo;ll leave that for another blog post!).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, Joomla can sit on IIS, but that&rsquo;s a rarity for me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apache is Joomla&rsquo;s &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.thefreedictionary.com/maitre+d\'\" target=\"_blank\">Maitre D</a>&ldquo;. When someone clicks to your site, Apache says, &ldquo;Hello, Joomla site, table for one!&rdquo;. Joomla says, &ldquo;this way, dear visitor&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apache controls the web server aspects of Joomla. The way the URL&rsquo;s look, communication between your visitor and Joomla &mdash; it&rsquo;s all Apache.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla comes with a file called &ldquo;htaccess.txt&rdquo;. This file contains Joomla specific stuff Apache needs to know about. We are supposed to rename it &ldquo;.htaccess&rdquo;. It&rsquo;s easier to edit as a &ldquo;TXT&rdquo; file.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The commands in this .htaccess file are called &ldquo;directives&rdquo;. Here&rsquo;s what&rsquo;s in the htaccess.txt that comes with Joomla 2.5:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>##<br />\r\n# @package Joomla<br />\r\n# @copyright Copyright (C) 2005 &ndash; 2013 Open Source Matters. All rights reserved.<br />\r\n# @license GNU General Public License version 2 or later; see LICENSE.txt<br />\r\n##</p>\r\n\r\n<p>##<br />\r\n# READ THIS COMPLETELY IF YOU CHOOSE TO USE THIS FILE!<br />\r\n#<br />\r\n# The line just below this section: &lsquo;Options +FollowSymLinks&rsquo; may cause problems<br />\r\n# with some server configurations. It is required for use of mod_rewrite, but may already<br />\r\n# be set by your server administrator in a way that dissallows changing it in<br />\r\n# your .htaccess file. If using it causes your server to error out, comment it out (add # to<br />\r\n# beginning of line), reload your site in your browser and test your sef url&rsquo;s. If they work,<br />\r\n# it has been set by your server administrator and you do not need it set here.<br />\r\n##</p>\r\n\r\n<p>## Can be commented out if causes errors, see notes above.<br />\r\nOptions +FollowSymLinks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>## Mod_rewrite in use.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>RewriteEngine On</p>\r\n\r\n<p>## Begin &ndash; Rewrite rules to block out some common exploits.<br />\r\n# If you experience problems on your site block out the operations listed below<br />\r\n# This attempts to block the most common type of exploit `attempts` to Joomla!<br />\r\n#<br />\r\n# Block out any script trying to base64_encode data within the URL.<br />\r\nRewriteCond %{QUERY_STRING} base64_encode[^(]*\\([^)]*\\) [OR]<br />\r\n# Block out any script that includes a &lt;script&gt; tag in URL.<br />\r\nRewriteCond %{QUERY_STRING} (&lt;|%3C)([^s]*s)+cript.*(&gt;|%3E) [NC,OR]<br />\r\n# Block out any script trying to set a PHP GLOBALS variable via URL.<br />\r\nRewriteCond %{QUERY_STRING} GLOBALS(=|\\[|\\%[0-9A-Z]{0,2}) [OR]<br />\r\n# Block out any script trying to modify a _REQUEST variable via URL.<br />\r\nRewriteCond %{QUERY_STRING} _REQUEST(=|\\[|\\%[0-9A-Z]{0,2})<br />\r\n# Return 403 Forbidden header and show the content of the root homepage<br />\r\nRewriteRule .* index.php [F]<br />\r\n#<br />\r\n## End &ndash; Rewrite rules to block out some common exploits.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>## Begin &ndash; Custom redirects<br />\r\n#<br />\r\n# If you need to redirect some pages, or set a canonical non-www to<br />\r\n# www redirect (or vice versa), place that code here. Ensure those<br />\r\n# redirects use the correct RewriteRule syntax and the [R=301,L] flags.<br />\r\n#<br />\r\n## End &ndash; Custom redirects</p>\r\n\r\n<p>##<br />\r\n# Uncomment following line if your webserver&rsquo;s URL<br />\r\n# is not directly related to physical file paths.<br />\r\n# Update Your Joomla! Directory (just / for root).<br />\r\n##</p>\r\n\r\n<p># RewriteBase /</p>\r\n\r\n<p>## Begin &ndash; Joomla! core SEF Section.<br />\r\n#<br />\r\nRewriteRule .* &ndash; [E=HTTP_AUTHORIZATION:%{HTTP:Authorization}]<br />\r\n#<br />\r\n# If the requested path and file is not /index.php and the request<br />\r\n# has not already been internally rewritten to the index.php script<br />\r\nRewriteCond %{REQUEST_URI} !^/index\\.php<br />\r\n# and the request is for something within the component folder,<br />\r\n# or for the site root, or for an extensionless URL, or the<br />\r\n# requested URL ends with one of the listed extensions<br />\r\nRewriteCond %{REQUEST_URI} /component/|(/[^.]*|\\.(php|html?|feed|pdf|vcf|raw))$ [NC]<br />\r\n# and the requested path and file doesn&rsquo;t directly match a physical file<br />\r\nRewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} !-f<br />\r\n# and the requested path and file doesn&rsquo;t directly match a physical folder<br />\r\nRewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} !-d<br />\r\n# internally rewrite the request to the index.php script<br />\r\nRewriteRule .* index.php [L]<br />\r\n#<br />\r\n## End &ndash; Joomla! core SEF Section.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s a good idea to add things for extra security. AkeebaBackup.com&rsquo;s Admin Tools component has an htaccess &ldquo;maker&rdquo; that makes even my eyes glaze over. Warning: one wrong move and &nbsp;your site turns into a &ldquo;500&Prime; error machine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have my own standard &mdash; but not too crazy &mdash; set of htaccess &ldquo;directives&rdquo; that I like to add to my sites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I recommend using an .htaccess password for your Administrator. This means that anyone who &nbsp;wants to access your http://myjoomlawebsite/administrator has to have the id and password that is set up in Apache &mdash; *not* in Joomla &mdash; to see the Administrator login page. Yes, this means that you end up with two login screens for your Administrator. The extra security is worth it.</p>\r\n', 'I thought I’d reply to an email with this blog post...', 'I thought I’d reply to an email with this blog post...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/what-is-apache-and-htaccess', 'apache1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-05-23', '2013-05-23 12:00:00', 1, '2013-05-23 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(86, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart State of the Union', 'lasallemart-state-of-the-union', '<p>LaSalleMart 2.0 is my Joomla ecommerce extension for Joomla 2.5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LM2 is my fork of a free open source Joomla ecomm extension that I grew more and more frustrated with. I decided to take this huge monolithic extension as my own to &ldquo;do something&rdquo; about my frustration. Best thing I ever did!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last month, LaSalleMart 2.0 for California went live on&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2013/live-lasallemart-site\" target=\"_blank\">WonderFoods</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Two New LaSalleMart 2.0 sites</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>This month, sweet-heart deals were made for two new LM2 sites. These sites should be live by month-end. By &ldquo;sweet-heart&rdquo;, I mean I am putting in free labour. This is it, no more freebies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The second site is a client of one of the Toronto Joomla Group consultants. There&rsquo;s some good user testing going on, which is very gratifying. One of the things being tested is the new layout feature developed for the first LM2 site! Without this new feature, Site#2 would be screwed. My own&nbsp;<a href=\"https://southlasalle.atlassian.net/wiki/display/lasallemartkb/Category+and+Product+Layouts\" target=\"_blank\">Knowledge Base page on my new feature</a>&nbsp;helped me remember what the particulars were &mdash; plus, I realized I left something important out. Designers have a lot more control over the layouts now &mdash; including the add-to-cart form.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The third site is a very unique site. Long ago we installed Tienda 0.5, one of the first working versions of Tienda. Well, it&rsquo;s not working on this site. So, we (meaning, mostly me) is doing up an entirely new Joomla 2.5 site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Originally, I set up this third LM2 site as a dual Joomla 3.1 &amp; Joomla 2.5 site. The 3.1 site would act as the front-end, for the purpose of utilizing the juicy mobile features. The 2.5 site would house just LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The template we are using has both a 2.5 and 3.1 version, so getting a uniform look is easy (Famous Last Words).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, in doing this set-up, the integrations between the sites to accomplish a seamless customer experience require too much work for the benefit received. Technically, no integration is necessary beyond just a link from the 3.1 product pages to the 2.5 LM product pages. So, we can always set-up a dual site in the future. However, mod_cart and the add-to-cart form are just two integrations that &ldquo;trick&rdquo; the buyer into thinking they are on one site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart does not work in Joomla 3.1. However, perhaps instead of bringing LM2 to Joomla 3.1, we should bring Joomla 3.1 to LM2. Bring JUI or Akeeba&rsquo;s &ldquo;Strapper&rdquo; or just plain ol&rsquo; Bootstrap into Joomla 2.5 to get juicy mobile goodness into LM today. We won&rsquo;t do this with Site #3, but we are certainly mindful of it now. Setting up the dual sites was very educational &mdash; absolutely no regrets. Have to push to learn, eh!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Site #3 will sell, among other things, downloadable files.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>New Mandrill Library</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Wanting upcoming LaSalleMart work to take advantage of MailChimp&rsquo;s Mandrill API, I created a<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2013/new-mandrill-library-for-lasallemart\" target=\"_blank\">Mandrill Library for Joomla</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Mobile</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Most of the ecomm action is happening on the tablets. It&rsquo;s imperative that LaSalleMart provide a kick-ass customer experience on the tablets.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As well, people behave differently on different devices. On smartphones they may respond to a link in an email. People do not go through checkout on smartphones. So, your customers will order with a coupon on their phones, but they won&rsquo;t consummate the sale on their phones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>People will watch videos on their tablets. A video with a link to a pre-coupon&rsquo;d &ldquo;buy now&rdquo; button will work on the tablet. Your customers will go through checkout if the experience is easy and pleasant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Responsive&rdquo; is not enough, because your customers behave differently on different devices. LaSalleMart has to meld with this behaviour, above and beyond the site adjusting to the &ldquo;viewport&rdquo; size.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla has something called &ldquo;CLI&rdquo; (command line interface). CLI is Joomla without the site! Akeeba Backup has a CLI &ldquo;app&rdquo; that uses the power of Joomla, and specific Akeeba Backup functions, without launching the site &mdash; and without invoking it via the browser. This is how the automatic backups (via CRON jobs) are done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla&rsquo;s CLI allows for the creation of Joomla based &ldquo;Web Apps&rdquo;. &nbsp;A &ldquo;client-side&rdquo; app is installed on the mobile device. A web application is accessed via a URL on a browser &mdash; nothing is installed on the mobile device. See&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/guide/webapps/overview.html\" target=\"_blank\">https://developer.android.com/guide/webapps/overview.html</a>&nbsp;for more info.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the urging of wonderful client, I started building an app to cope with a two staged mobile-driven checkout: the first step is order placement; and, the second step is going through checkout later to pay for the order. I want to create a new LaSalleMart library that can access different aspects of the checkout to cope with this new mobile-based checkout flow. This new library is part of getting LaSalleMart onto Joomla 3. What was many months in the future is now a necessity to respond to the demands of mobile. The future is now, eh!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mandrill for use with CLI became must-have, as we need to track out-bound emails with our Joomla apps.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The fact that we control the code puts us at a huge advantage to respond to mobile.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>On Deck for June</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>On deck for development next month:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>wrapping up coupons;</li>\r\n	<li>PayPal Pro;</li>\r\n	<li>streamlined checkout;</li>\r\n	<li>guest checkout;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>On top of the new LM library (on top of the one we already have), I want to wrap up coupons, as it&rsquo;s coming up in conversation now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am working on PayPal Pro, which prompted a new component (com_lasallemart_creditcard).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Streamlining and guest checkout are related. There are too many steps, especially at the address management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;Generic components and the Framework on Framework</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>I have a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2013/the-long-term-has-arrived\" target=\"_blank\">separate blog post about these</a>, as long term investments are starting to pay off in terms of ability to crank out features faster. Building LM for Joomla 3.x will be ongoing as new development will be as Joomla 3.x friendly as possible. I note this again so you know Joomla 3 (and mobile) is top-of-mind.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>New Home Page</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve not had a front page article for about a month now. Time to gather my notes together and get my new home page article together. I mention it here so you know that my site is not broken!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Bringing Club Commerce up to its 300 Members</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>In June, I want to do something I&rsquo;ve not done yet: broadening out the tight little group that has brought LaSalleMart to life. &nbsp;LaSalleMart is humming on its first site, with two more upcoming. Development is primed for expansion. It&rsquo;s time &mdash; finally! &mdash; to broaden our tight little group, that I call &ldquo;Club Commerce&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>JUGT Presentation</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>On May 30th, I&rsquo;m putting on a Joomla ecommerce presentation at the Joomla User Group Toronto&rsquo;s seminar. My presentation will be available on my LaSalleMart.com site.</p>\r\n', 'LaSalleMart 2.0 is my fork of a free open source Joomla ecomm extension that I grew more and more frustrated with. I decided to take this huge monolithic extension as my own to “do something” about my frustration. Best thing I ever did!', 'LaSalleMart 2.0 is my fork of a free open source Joomla ecomm extension that I grew more and more frustrated with. I decided to take this huge monolithic extension as my own to “do something” about my frustration. Best thing I ever did!', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-state-of-the-union', 'state-of-union1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-05-23', '2013-05-23 12:00:00', 1, '2013-05-23 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(87, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Mozilla’s WebFWD accelerator helping Anahita become ‘the Linux of social’', '/2013/mozillas-webfwd-accelerator-helping-anahita-become-the-linux-of-social', '<p>There&rsquo;s an article about Rastin, Ash, and their Anahita Social Framework.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Keep your eye on them. I would not be surprised if LaSalleMart and Anahita made their acquaintance down the road.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Great pics of Ash &amp; Rastin. Although it was a bit hard to &nbsp;recognize &lsquo;em initially without a coffee mug in their hands&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://venturebeat.com/2013/05/29/mozillas-webfwd-accelerator-helping-anahita-become-the-linux-of-social/\" target=\"_blank\">http://venturebeat.com/2013/05/29/mozillas-webfwd-accelerator-helping-anahita-become-the-linux-of-social/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE (June 06, 2013):</strong>&nbsp;See &ldquo;WebFWD Cohort III Graduation Day&rdquo; video, at the 42 minute mark.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://air.mozilla.org/webfwd-cohort-iii-graduation-day/\" target=\"_blank\">https://air.mozilla.org/webfwd-cohort-iii-graduation-day/</a></p>\r\n', 'There’s an article about Rastin, Ash, and their Anahita Social Framework. Keep your eye on them...', 'There’s an article about Rastin, Ash, and their Anahita Social Framework. Keep your eye on them...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca//2013/mozillas-webfwd-accelerator-helping-anahita-become-the-linux-of-social', 'ash.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-05-29', '2013-05-29 12:00:00', 1, '2013-05-29 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(88, 0, NULL, NULL, 'My May 2013 Joomla User Group Toronto eCommerce Presentation', 'may-2013-joomla-group-toronto-presentation', '<p>Thank you to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://toronto.joomla.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">Joomla User Group Toronto</a>(JUGT) for inviting me to do an ecommerce presentation at its May 2013 workshop.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I decided to specialize in Joomla in fall 2005. In 2009 I discovered JUGT, and made my way to their Sheppard-Yonge Pub Night.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>JUGT provides me with non-stop benefits:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>connection to the Joomla Project;</li>\r\n	<li>education;</li>\r\n	<li>meet Toronto area Joomla professionals;</li>\r\n	<li>clients know I am part of a Joomla network.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Being an independent Joomla ecommerce &ldquo;sole practitioner&rdquo; is great. But keeping up with the Joomla technology and trends, swapping stories, sharing knowledge is nay difficult without connecting with other pros. JUGT plays a key role in my professional life, and I&rsquo;ve made terrific friends along the way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank you JUGT!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I split my presentation into two parts:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>building website asset value;</li>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;how-to&rdquo; Q&amp;A.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0218.jpg\"><img alt=\"Bob Bloom at Joomla Toronto ecommerce workshop\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0218-300x224.jpg\" style=\"float:right; height:224px; margin:0px 0px 10px 10px; width:300px\" /></a>Devoting a Joomla ecommerce presentation to an exposition of website asset value is unconventional. So why do so? It is central to the reason why I forked Tienda into LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2010, I grew increasingly frustrated with Joomla ecommerce extensions. The pattern I observed was these extensions ebbed and flowed. They had their day in the sun when it was great to specialize in &lsquo;em, and then they had a sunset. I was starting to flit from ecommerce extension to ecommerce extension. When an extension was hot, I was there. Riding the popularity of the extension du jour is hardly a way to build long-term consulting revenues.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0221.jpg\"><img alt=\"Bob Bloom at Joomla Toronto ecommerce workshop\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0221-300x224.jpg\" style=\"float:left; height:224px; margin:0px 10px 10px; width:300px\" /></a>Just as my revenues were about to take-off, that extension&rsquo;s hotness faded and so did my revenues.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A major decision I made was to not become a generalist. I would&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;recommend to clients the best ecommerce solution that fit their needs, and then build this solution or outsource its implementation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I would specialize in an ecommerce technology. But which one? It came down to two ecommerce technologies:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Magento:</li>\r\n	<li>Something Else.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0216.jpg\"><img alt=\"IMG_0216\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0216-224x300.jpg\" style=\"float:right; height:300px; margin:0px 10px 10px; width:224px\" /></a>So, if not Magento, then I had more figuring out to do, because I did not know what that &ldquo;Something Else&rdquo; was.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By far, Magento was the obvious choice. Obvious!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In my estimation, Magento was the only &mdash; ONLY! &mdash; ecommerce technology that I had confidence would last in the long term. In five years, which ecomm technology would be standing? How could I build my revenue and business asset value over the long term without an ecomm technology that would stand the test of time?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Magento was the only &mdash; ONLY! &mdash; technology that had a real reseller program. This is very meaningful to me, because there is a real relationship between the technology providers and those who provide value-added services to clients in implementing this technology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Look, in a fundamental way, in my own eyes, Magento smoked Joomla, WordPress, Drupal, and the bevy of independent PHP carts. It was not even close.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The accountant in me, the project manager in me, the business analyst in me, the programmer in me &mdash; the sum total of my professional life told me to run, not walk, to Magento. A very cold ruthless calculation spoke to me clearly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0217.jpg\"><img alt=\"IMG_0217\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0217-224x300.jpg\" style=\"float:left; height:300px; margin:0px 10px 10px; width:224px\" /></a>Yet, I walked away from Magento and ran to Joomla!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Choosing Joomla was a very significant and profound decision for me!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, the benefits of choosing Joomla, and the terms in which I would choose it, underlie all that I do with Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Getting up in front of people that I know &mdash; hey, it&rsquo;s a JUGT presentation, not a JoomlaDay presentation &mdash; and not getting to The Real Story &mdash; I don&rsquo;t think so!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are two reasons why I walked away from Magento:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>could not run the community edition;</li>\r\n	<li>a visceral reaction to eBay buying out its founders.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Why is it that I just couldn&rsquo;t get Magento community edition to work? I tried and tried and tried. Installation was cumbersome. Using the sample data was cumbersome. Updating was impossible for me &mdash; each update crashed my install. With Magento, I had a reverse Midas Touch: I turned gold into lead, not lead into gold.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If memory serves, eBay already had an equity interest in Magento when they decided to buy out the founders completely. My reaction was visceral &mdash; I found it quite revolting. My Spidey-sense told me this was bad for me long-term. It wasn&rsquo;t one thing, it was a bunch of things.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0222.jpg\"><img alt=\"Bob Bloom at Joomla Toronto ecommerce workshop\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0222-300x224.jpg\" style=\"float:right; height:224px; margin:0px 10px 10px; width:300px\" /></a>I was convinced that I&rsquo;d be just like a ton of other consultants: chasing down clients. We&rsquo;d all be Magento resellers. We&rsquo;d all be assigned the same Support One techs. We&rsquo;d all get letters every quarter from the same Assistant Executive Vice-President in Charge of the Colony of Eastern Canada. We&rsquo;d all know where the Magento Bodies are Buried, so we knew revenue-versus-costs of the main scenarios we&rsquo;d be implementing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;d be a commodity. I&rsquo;d be just like everyone else. Commodities compete on one thing in the end, and you know what that is: price. And no way I could compete on price. You know why? Because the other consultants would have either 15 year old geniuses paid in Apple Store gift certificates, along with a slew of behind-the-old-iron-curtain coders they&rsquo;ve been dealing with for 10 years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ok, so I&rsquo;m exaggerating. But, how would I differentiate myself? Well, Joomla. I already knew Joomla, and there&rsquo;s a Joomla-Magento bridge.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ah, always back to Joomla. And, well, of course, I couldn&rsquo;t get Magento to work. Oil-meets-water!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, I was gravitating away from Joomla, but in so gravitating, I was coming back. When I was looking at &ldquo;Something Else&rdquo;, I was always comparing to Joomla. The templating, the CMS features, the ease-of-use. The ability to add a social site, or a subscription site&hellip; always &ldquo;coming home&rdquo; to Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The thing is, I had to face up to the fact that the Joomla ecomm extensions were damaging my business. So, how to &ldquo;come home&rdquo; to Joomla yet advance my business.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How did I reconcile the &ldquo;returning to Joomla&rdquo; with the &ldquo;walking away from Joomla&rdquo;?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s called &ldquo;The General Public Licence&rdquo;!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Basically, &nbsp;I didn&rsquo;t really believe what the GPL really means. Coming from the Corporate IT world, it did not really &ldquo;click&rdquo; with me. Ah, then it did!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I made an astounding leap: instead of using other peoples&rsquo; ecommerce software,&nbsp;<em>I&rsquo;d use my own</em>!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Building my own ecommerce software turned into quite the journey, and quite the investment! And certainly looking at the Joomla ecommerce world a lot differently than I ever did.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An unconventional story, but a story of the path I pursued.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A path I wanted to convey at the presentation.</p>\r\n', 'Devoting a Joomla ecommerce presentation to an exposition of website asset value is unconventional. So why do so? It is central to the reason why I forked Tienda into LaSalleMart. Moneyball of e-business!', 'Devoting a Joomla ecommerce presentation to an exposition of website asset value is unconventional. So why do so? It is central to the reason why I forked Tienda into LaSalleMart. Moneyball of e-business!', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/may-2013-joomla-group-toronto-presentation', 'JUGT_email_blast_image.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-06-05', '2013-06-05 12:00:00', 1, '2013-06-05 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(89, 0, NULL, NULL, 'June 2013 Joomla User Group Toronto Bootstrap Workshop', 'june-2013-joomla-user-group-toronto-bootstrap-workshop', '<p>This evening&rsquo;s Bootstrap Workshop, hosted by the Joomla User Group Toronto, was exceptionally good.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Doug outdid himself arranging and outfitting the Conference Room 2 at the North York Civic Centre. The conference room was magnificent, with ample space, terrific lighting, equipment, tables, and neither too hot nor too cold. Washrooms were easily findable in the foyer, there were ample coat racks had this been January, directly accessible from the subway.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Doug also provided wi-fi via a brilliant set-up eminating from his Blackberry. Score one for LTE!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Vic did a great job promoting this workshop. The graphics, emails, and alerts were well done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Niv worked his butt off for this workshop and it showed. Prepared with a detailed Powerpoint presentation devoid of any transitions, backgrounds &mdash; pure content! Prepared with files. Obviously passionate about Bootstrap. It was a thorough hands-on interactive workshop.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 10 people in attendence (4-ish known regrets) had a great range of skills and experience with Bootstrap &mdash; and Bootstrap for Joomla. There were questions from the floor &nbsp; non-stop, and great cross conversations too &mdash; thank you Niv for your patience! The regulars are certainly getting to know each other as there was a lot of participation and chatter. It was lively, informal, and very informative.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To get to the hands-on stuff as fast as possible, and to keep the lessons on point, Niv purposefully focused on just the Bootstrap Framework. A few of us attendees, me included, kept yapping about Bootstrap working with Joomla. Niv did the exact right approach keeping the hands-on lessons purely Bootstrap, since that&rsquo;s what we were there to learn. However, we certainly made it know how relevant all this was to Joomla!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In fact, I think it&rsquo;s time JUGT hosted a &ldquo;Tour of Joomla&rdquo; workshop. I get the impression from this evening that many people are not aware of JoomlaCLI &mdash; and its potential for creating Joomla web applications. I am not sure that some attendees are aware of the Joomla media folder, where JUI resides.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Having done quite a number of workshops this fall-winter-spring, the experience is starting to show. The rough edges are starting to smooth out. The venue was very very good, and without the eariler efforts we&rsquo;d not have found our way to Conference Room 2 this evening.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My goal was to understand what &ldquo;responsive&rdquo; really means with the Framework, and how the Framework achieves &ldquo;responsive&rdquo;. Mission accomplished. I realized that I was tripping over the terminology. I also understand that Bootstrap is a templating framework as well as a responsive framework. It was good to see it in action! We definitely need a follow-up workshop about LESS (and Mix-ins) &mdash; but this time let&rsquo;s use LESS in Joomla context!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well done, Alan, Niv, Vic, Doug, et al!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Powerpoint is on my&nbsp;<a href=\"https://southlasalle.atlassian.net/wiki/display/lasallemartkb/Bootstrap\" target=\"_blank\">LaSalleMart Knowledge Base</a>.</p>\r\n', 'This evening’s Bootstrap Workshop, hosted by the Joomla User Group Toronto, was exceptionally good.', 'This evening’s Bootstrap Workshop, hosted by the Joomla User Group Toronto, was exceptionally good.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/june-2013-joomla-user-group-toronto-bootstrap-workshop', 'IMG_0327.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-06-19', '2013-06-19 12:00:00', 1, '2013-06-19 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(90, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Resubmitting LaSalleMart Application for JED Listing', 'resubmitting-lasallemart-application-for-jed-listing', '<p>The&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/tag/joomla-extension-directory\" target=\"_blank\">Joomla Extension Directory</a>&nbsp;has turned into an ongoing topic (see my&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2013/lasallemart18\" target=\"_blank\">latest LaSalleMart News</a>&nbsp;podcast as well).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart is my first JED submission, and it&rsquo;s certainly been a journey. An education too, especially after viewing the Joomla and Beyond 2013 video (in one of my links below). The JED is totally volunteer run, there are 250 submissions in the queue on average, and the JED site is undergoing an extensive overhaul.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): You want to know something? Until I got to inputting this blog post, I never really thought about it. But,<span class=\"marker\"> Laravel packages are uploaded by the people who create Laravel packages.</span> LaSalleCMS will be one such package! No gatekeepers, no whining how busy the volunteers are, no waiting to be approved (pick me pick me!). Here&#39;s the Laracast vid (I think this one describes how devs can upload their own handiwork):&nbsp;https://laracasts.com/lessons/package-development-101. Here&#39;s the kicker: there is no quality assurance simply because something is listed on the JED. There&#39;s no quality assurance on Packagelist, although there is one thing I have noticed: there is a certain peer pressure not to post bullshit. I have read a lot of caveats about what the package really is -- not quite confessionals, mind you. So, yes, indeed, when LaSalleCMS is ready, I will post it to packagelist-GitHub -- because I can!</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My first submission in early March ended up being zapped around the end of May.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am resubmitting LaSalleMart for listing on the JED this evening. It is officially version 2.0.010 (not 2.0.009).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This version has the GPL canned text at the top of the PHP headers, something that was missing in my first submission. After seeing the video, I thought I ought to add the header.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I created a special page for additional notes to the JED volunteers at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.lasallemart.com/jed/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.lasallemart.com/jed/</a>&nbsp;&ndash; my first Bootstrap page too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As I noted on my home page, the reason for listing LaSalleMart on the JED are:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>public expects &ldquo;real&rdquo; Joomla extensions will be listed on the JED</li>\r\n	<li>public tends to perceive non-listing as &ldquo;something-is-wrong&rdquo; with the extension</li>\r\n	<li>Joomla&rsquo;s been good to us, we want to be good to Joomla</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ll keep you updated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE (Aug 11, 2013):</strong>&nbsp;After a very speedy reply to my JED ticket, I figured out that pressing the &ldquo;Edit&rdquo; button reveals my sins. The JED team had already put LaSalleMart through their washer. But (!), no email was sent; nor, are there visual cues on the site that the JED team had, indeed, done their thing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/lm_jed_pending_2013aug11.png\"><img alt=\"LaSalleMart JED listing 2013Aug11\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/lm_jed_pending_2013aug11.png\" style=\"height:325px; margin:0px auto 10px; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Clicking &ldquo;Edit&rdquo; displays the &ldquo;EDIT EXTENSION&rdquo; page. Here it is in 2 images to show you the 19 cosmetic changes enumerated (click for full size):</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/lm_jed_edit1_2013aug11.png\"><img alt=\"LM JED Edit1, 2013Aug11\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/lm_jed_edit1_2013aug11.png\" style=\"height:325px; margin:0px auto 10px; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/lm_jed_edit2_2013aug11.png\"><img alt=\"LM2 JED Edit2, 2013Aug11\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/lm_jed_edit2_2013aug11.png\" style=\"height:346px; margin:0px auto 10px; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ahead of making these changes, I am re-building LaSalleMart.com from scratch with Joomla 3.1 and Bootstrap. With this re-build nearly done, I will make these changes to LaSalleMart, run the build as<a href=\"https://southlasalle.atlassian.net/wiki/display/lasallemartkb/Change+Log+and+Version+Planner\" target=\"_blank\">version 2.0.012</a>, and submit this updated version to JED.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE &nbsp;(Aug 2013):</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2013/lasallemart20\" target=\"_blank\">Podcast: Nyet to JED</a></p>\r\n', 'LaSalleMart is my first JED submission, and it’s certainly been a journey. An education too, especially after viewing the Joomla and Beyond 2013 video (in one of my links below). The JED is totally volunteer run, there are 250 submissions in the queue on average, and the JED site is undergoing an extensive overhaul.', 'LaSalleMart is my first JED submission, and it’s certainly been a journey. An education too, especially after viewing the Joomla and Beyond 2013 video (in one of my links below). The JED is totally volunteer run, there are 250 submissions in the queue on ', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/resubmitting-lasallemart-application-for-jed-listing', 'groundhog_day1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-08-11', '2013-08-11 12:00:00', 1, '2013-08-11 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(91, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Just Wrote a WooCommerce Tax Plugin', 'woocommerce-florida-tax-plugin', '<p>Yes, it&rsquo;s true. I&rsquo;m involved in a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://wordpress.org/plugins/woocommerce/\" target=\"_blank\">WooCommerce</a>&nbsp;installation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No was not an option when a wonderful client asked for help. &nbsp;Kind of scratched an itch anyways, as I&rsquo;ve been curious about WooCommerce.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the process, wrote a private WordPress Florida taxes by county plugin for WooCommerce.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s a private plugin for clients, not available on the WordPress Plugin Directory. For the simple reason that I will not spend time buffing and polishing it for such listing. Rather be working on LaSalleMart 3.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A long long time ago I installed an ecomm plugin in WordPress for a client. My first major site was WordPress! Boy, I took a theme and with custom fields customized the yowza out of it. &nbsp;Grafted an ecomm plugin to another WordPress site. My first impression of that plugin was the extent to which it just took over the wp-admin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, I&rsquo;m a Joomla ecomm guy with my own Joomla ecomm extension. So, naturally, I&rsquo;m about to bash WordPress ecommerce. No I will not.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Actually, it&rsquo;s been quite instructive working on WordPress-WooCommerce at this juncture. I am absorbing lessons to bring to LaSalleMart 3.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This blog site is WordPress. My media site is WordPress. Great to have a finger in the WordPress pie, to maintain a first-hand feel for what is happening with WordPress. I do enjoy WordPress for blogging.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But, y&rsquo;know, setting up my WordPress sites was not easy. It took a concerted effort to make my around the Genesis Framework. There was a learning curve. I customized my child themes quite a bit. Substitute &ldquo;Gantry&rdquo; and &ldquo;template&rdquo;, and it&rsquo;s the same conversation about Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is pretty much my impression of WooCommerce. There&rsquo;s a learning curve. There&rsquo;s documentation to read. There&rsquo;s the getting used to the screens. I&rsquo;ve been to a number of Toronto Joomla Group meet-ups where I&rsquo;m told, in stentorian tones, that WordPress is so much easier to use than Joomla. Yeah, well, WooCommerce is like any other ecommerce thingy that I&rsquo;ve ever used. Magento, Presto, GO, etc. There&rsquo;s a learning curve, there is no escaping looking stuff up in the documentation, there are idiosyncracies. Easier to use than Joomla? Yes; and, also no.</p>\r\n', 'No was not an option when a wonderful client asked for help.  Kind of scratched an itch anyways, as I’ve been curious about WooCommerce. In the process, wrote a private WordPress Florida taxes by county plugin for WooCommerce. It’s a private plugin for clients, not available on the WordPress Plugin Directory. For the simple reason that I will not spend time buffing and polishing it for such listing. Rather be working on LaSalleMart 3...', 'No was not an option when a wonderful client asked for help.  Kind of scratched an itch anyways, as I’ve been curious about WooCommerce. In the process, wrote a private WordPress Florida taxes by county plugin for WooCommerce. It’s a private plugin for cl', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/woocommerce-florida-tax-plugin', 'wordpress-logo-notext-bg.png', 1, 0, 0, '2013-10-01', '2013-10-01 12:00:00', 1, '2013-10-01 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(92, 0, NULL, NULL, 'KISS LaSalleMart 3', 'kiss-lasallemart-3', '<p>Keeping it simple is becoming my mantra with LaSalleMart 3. After years of playing &ldquo;find that code&rdquo;, I don&rsquo;t want to play anymore.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I did a ridiculous thing today:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>I created an add-to-cart view &mdash; filename = addtocart.php;</li>\r\n	<li>I create an add-to-cart controller &mdash; filename = addtocart.php;</li>\r\n	<li>I put my test add-to-cart code in the controller file, using the task name (wait for it!): addtocart();</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Then I rebelled:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>no helper files;</li>\r\n	<li>no firing up any plugin events.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>In order to get the add-to-cart form on the product details page, I used the Framework on Framework &ldquo;loadanyTemplate&rdquo; statement in the spot where I want the form to display.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not only does it work, but:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>I know where the code is;</li>\r\n	<li>I can read the code;</li>\r\n	<li>All the code is in the controller&rsquo;s &ldquo;addtocart()&rdquo; task.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>I love it so much that I could just kiss my code! So straightforward.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Excited with straightforward code so much that I decided to keep trying to keep my code straightforward and &mdash; dangerous word here &mdash; &ldquo;intuitive&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The FoF does keep a ton of Joomla overhead out of my component. It&rsquo;s conventions impart a nice discipline to the filenames. Not building in plugin events (gasp!), refusing to do helper files unless forced to, and doing whatever else I can to keep LaSalleMart 3 mean, lean and clean is exactly the way I&rsquo;m going to proceed.</p>\r\n', 'Keeping it simple is becoming my mantra with LaSalleMart 3. After years of playing “find that code”, I don’t want to play anymore.', 'Keeping it simple is becoming my mantra with LaSalleMart 3. After years of playing “find that code”, I don’t want to play anymore.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/kiss-lasallemart-3', 'simple_is_beautiful.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-10-01', '2013-10-01 12:00:00', 1, '2013-10-01 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(93, 0, NULL, NULL, 'To Use Or Not To Use LaSalleMart', 'to-use-or-not-to-use-lasallemart', '<div class=\"alert alert-success\" role=\"alert\">\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Boy, I haven&#39;t read this post in a while. I just did as I am nearing the conclusion of inputting years of blog posts in this little homemade Laravel blog app. My initial reaction to this post was anger!&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>As I&#39;ve said before, my only regret changing technology specialties from Joomla and the superb Akeeba Framework on Framework, is that I did not drop Joomla before starting on LaSalleMart 3. Hindsight is perfect, eh! </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Who develops a distro and dumps it in favour of a fork because the original software development slows to a crawl, then forks the software into a kick-ass extension in its own right -- then has to drop it like a sack of shit because the underlying software obsoletes? Then forks a crappy but just workable enough ecomm software and through sheer force of will creates a glorious working technology before the underlying software releases a working version (which it never did)? Then, drops that massive investment to create an innovative Joomla ecommerce technology from-scratch? Of course had to drop that! Is there an award for best serious of software never released (of course, LM2 was released -- before it wasn&#39;t released!).&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>My one regret is that on October 20, 2013, the date of this blog post, I did not give Joomla the ol&#39; heave-ho. On the other hand, in the scheme of things seven odd months is not a huge time frame?!</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I can live the rest of my life not agonizing over version releases. I can live the rest of my life not explaining version releases. Oy!</strong></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After a much longer gestation period than I ever imagined, detailed in my October 2013 podcast, pretty well the moment LM2 became site-ready, I feature-froze it. &nbsp;There are four main reasons for this painful decision to stop working on LM2, and start fresh with LaSalleMart 3:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>LaSalleMart 2 is made for Joomla 2.5, not Joomla 3;</li>\r\n	<li>LaSalleMart 2 is based on software that makes it difficult to build out features relative to starting from scratch;</li>\r\n	<li>LaSalleMart 3 is based on the kick-ass Akeeba Framework-on-Framework, that will actually be included with Joomla 3.2;</li>\r\n	<li>LaSalleMart 2 is written for the desktop, but not so hot for mobile.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>Given that LM2&prime;s development is done, I&rsquo;ve not done a whole lot to promote it. Don&rsquo;t expect the same passivity with LM3.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So: to use LM2, or not to use LM2, that is the question.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since there is no LM3 to use, this question is moot for LM3.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, LM3 is in real development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am close to the point where your participation in its development is warranted. Currently, I am deep into figuring out how best to incorporate the FoF, which is having a profound, and immensely positive, influence on LM3. FoF is bringing my vision of what Joomla ecommerce should be.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, in the meantime, do you install LaSalleMart 2?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LM2 is for low-scope ecommerce sites for Joomla 2.5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a lot of things LM2 does not have, and will not have. There are just two tested payment methods: PayPal Standard, and Offline Payments. For shipping, there exists just manual (aka &ldquo;Standard&rdquo;) shipping.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Downloadable product, Canadian HST/GST/PST work, coupons work. See my&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.lasallemart.com/index.php/lasallemart-2\" target=\"_blank\">LM2 page at LaSalleMart.com</a>&nbsp;for details.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t mind using Joomla 2.5, then my LaSalleMart 2 is absolutely free. Install it and see if it is ok for your specific needs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Is LM2 a stepping stone to &nbsp;LM3? No. Migration will not be trivial; nor, will there be tools available to ease this migration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 3&prime;s first release will replicate LM2&prime;s functions. Whereupon, the question &ldquo;to use or not to use&rdquo; will be a resounding yes!</p>\r\n', 'After a much longer gestation period than I ever imagined, detailed in my October 2013 podcast, pretty well the moment LM2 became site-ready, I feature-froze it.  There are four main reasons for this painful decision to stop working on LM2, and start fresh with LaSalleMart 3...', 'After a much longer gestation period than I ever imagined, detailed in my October 2013 podcast, pretty well the moment LM2 became site-ready, I feature-froze it.  There are four main reasons for this painful decision to stop working on LM2, and start fres', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/to-use-or-not-to-use-lasallemart', 'question-mark-sign2.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-10-20', '2013-10-20 12:00:00', 1, '2013-10-20 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(94, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Long Held Vision of Joomla eCommerce is Coming to Fruition with LaSalleMart 3', 'long-held-vision-of-joomla-ecommerce-is-coming-to-fruition-with-lasallemart-3', '<div class=\"alert alert-success\" role=\"alert\">\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Despite my kvetching that I should have developed LaSalleMart 3 in Laravel 4, I succeeded in bringing a wonderful vision to Joomla ecommerce. It was not easy. There was no manual. Much of it will, indeed, be helpful in authoring LaSalleMart 4 in Laravel.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>If there was an upside to LaSalleMart 3, it was the intensity of the experience to bring a vision of clean, sane, keep-it-simple but not simplistic, code to Joomla ecommerce.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>I also built a knowledge base site (<a href=\"https://southlasalle.atlassian.net/wiki/display/lasallemart3/LaSalleMart+3+Knowledge+Base+Home\" target=\"_blank\">https://southlasalle.atlassian.net/wiki/display/lasallemart3/LaSalleMart+3+Knowledge+Base+Home</a>) along with my software.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Ultimately, I did it. I built LM3 from scratch with the vision I had.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chatting tonight with attendees of my Joomla User Group Toronto ecommerce presentation, I mentioned that my long held vision of Joomla ecommerce is starting to come to fruition with LaSalleMart 3.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You can trace my vision developing over the years in my podcasts and blog posts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Perhaps the stand-out podcast, though, is&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2010/tbbs21\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2010/tbbs21</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With the Framework-on-Framework, my vision is coming true: lots of small components, using pieces of components in other components, auto updates&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Right now, I am still testing the FoF concepts, because I have never used an ecommerce extension that does what I am doing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My initial prototype worked. Now I am building the first suite of the &ldquo;real&rdquo; LaSalleMart 3 components, plugins, and module. But in so building, I have discovered that I am prototyping again with the &ldquo;live&rdquo; LM3, in order to see if the concepts will work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So far, they do, especially using views in one component in another component. This one FoF feature is having profound effects on LaSalleMart 3. Or, perhaps, I should put it this way: HMVC is enabling a long-held vision of Joomla ecommerce to come to life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 3 is initially comprised of a suite of nine components, three plugins, and one module.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The idea is to stick to FoF conventions in order to build a clean, straight forward, and deeply powerful Joomla ecommerce technology, which I call LaSalleMart 3. So far, it is working.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have a component devoted solely to products, called com_product (ok, it&rsquo;s called &ldquo;com_lmproduct&rdquo;). This component&rsquo;s view that displays a single product on the website contains a view from the &ldquo;com_lmcart&rdquo; cart component. Specifically, the &ldquo;addtocart&rdquo; view, which displays perfectly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>HMVC means it is possible to have a ton of small limited-scope components. So far it is working very well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There really is less code. The usual coding overhead that Joomla requires for custom components is missing. It is practically a culture shock keeping to the FoF&rsquo;s mandated MVC structure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 3 is becoming something very very different than what I&rsquo;m used to for Joomla ecommerce. Something that gives it a shot at not becoming obsolete so quickly. Something that is terrific for mobile. Something that is readable by the human eye. Something that follows a consistent discipline based on Joomla&rsquo;s own MVC. Something that is condusive to huge development effort instead of bottlenecking it.</p>\r\n', 'Chatting tonight with attendees of my Joomla User Group Toronto ecommerce presentation, I mentioned that my long held vision of Joomla ecommerce is starting to come to fruition with LaSalleMart 3...', 'Chatting tonight with attendees of my Joomla User Group Toronto ecommerce presentation, I mentioned that my long held vision of Joomla ecommerce is starting to come to fruition with LaSalleMart 3...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/long-held-vision-of-joomla-ecommerce-is-coming-to-fruition-with-lasallemart-3', 'periscope_with_hand1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-10-23', '2013-10-23 12:00:00', 1, '2013-10-23 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(95, 0, NULL, NULL, 'My October 2013 Joomla User Group Toronto eCommerce Presentation', 'my-october-2013-joomla-user-group-toronto-ecommerce-presentation', '<p>My peers on the Joomla User Group Toronto (JUGT) Steering Committee graciously invited me back to lead another ecommerce presentation,<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2013/may-2013-joomla-group-toronto-presentation\" target=\"_blank\">having done one last May</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That presentation was not conventional, and there was frustration that I had not either surveyed available Joomla ecommerce solutions; nor, shared my experiences about the mechanics of creating a Joomla ecommerce website. &nbsp;So my intention with this presentation was to emphasize the mechanics of creating a Joomla ecomm website.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I started at 6:40pm, and finished non-stop at 8:15pm. Thereafter, was solid Q&amp;A until we had to vacate the premises at 9:00pm. We had a fabulous turn-out of over a dozen attendees, most of whom were friends who come out every so often; and, people new to JUGT &mdash; welcome!<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0490.jpg\"><img alt=\"2013 Oct 22 JUGT eComm Presentation\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/IMG_0490-300x224.jpg\" style=\"float:right; height:224px; margin:0px 5px 10px; width:300px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Doug Pickett did his usual superb job setting up the North York Civic Centre&rsquo;s conference room &mdash; thank you, Doug! Sheldon did a terrific job expanding on topics, providing another perspective. The JUGT regulars did a great job yielding the floor to our new attendees, each of whom related their specific projects in an impromptu round table session at the end of Q&amp;A.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My over-arching message was to go about your ecomm website backwards. Start with the last steps of checkout work your way backwards &mdash; mainly payment methods and shipping methods, along with SSL. Checkout takes time to implement, so you need to get your hands around it when you start your ecomm site. Most clients obsess about products and eye-candy and leave checkout towards the end of their site development &mdash; big mistake!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I emphasized that SEO stops at checkout; and, that once in checkout the issue of cart abandonment becomes the key driver of development decision making. Unfortunately, the emphasis on the &ldquo;front-end&rdquo; eye candy leaves little budget left over for checkout customization, which is another big mistake.&nbsp;I displayed an info-graphic on cart abandonment to emphasize typical abandonment issues.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>eCommerce is not just a cart &mdash; it&rsquo;s running a subscription site, events, and courses. It&rsquo;s combining a bunch of front-end e-marketing &nbsp;+ sales into a cohesive whole &mdash; like email marketing, blogging, white papers, SEO, AdSense, and the cart. There is also &ldquo;back-end&rdquo; processing &mdash; offline order processing, QuickBooks integration, refund administration, etc. We barely touched on these aspects of ecommerce &mdash; which&nbsp;&nbsp;speaks to the wide scope of ecommerce.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Remember: backwards!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/bbloom9/2013-oct22-jugtecommerceworkshop\">http://www.slideshare.net/bbloom9/2013-oct22-jugtecommerceworkshop</a></p>\r\n', 'So my intention with this presentation was to emphasize the mechanics of creating a Joomla ecomm website.', 'So my intention with this presentation was to emphasize the mechanics of creating a Joomla ecomm website.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/my-october-2013-joomla-user-group-toronto-ecommerce-presentation', 'jugt_listing1.png', 1, 0, 0, '2013-10-23', '2013-10-23 12:00:00', 1, '2013-10-23 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(96, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Dear Clients – Progressive Billing Only', 'progressive-billing-only', '<p>This Halloween month-end featured a haunting accounts receivable: would my client pay his final payment?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I was haunted by the pins-and-needles feeling of wondering if a significant amount would actually be paid. Reminded me of my earlier days of freelancing, especially one guy who took that final payment hostage. This final payment situation turned into a hostage situation, and I decided that no more would I do a deposit-plus-final-payment engagement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are two aspects to this: the human-nature aspect; and, the criminal aspect.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is human nature to not want to accept a project.&nbsp;No one wants to sign-off. In my corporate IT days, and in my freelancing, people hate having to explicitly decide that yes, indeed, the thing is done .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What works is doing things smaller. Clients understand fixes: the thing is broken, I fix it, they see it for themselves, they are happy, they pay. &nbsp; Clients understand tweaks: the thing needs an improvement, I improve it, the see it for themselves, they are happy, they pay.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The problem comes when there are too many things going on. With a new site, there are a lot of things going on. The client is not comfortable with blessing everything, so is hesitant. At the end of site development, clients are &nbsp;nervous. So, they are hesitant to pay.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Criminal behaviour goes beyond a natural hesitation. It&rsquo;s just exploitation. It&rsquo;s extracting free labour. The proposition is: I will pay you after you do these extra things. Of course, the successful extraction of free labour begets further rounds of extortion. And, at the end, why even pay the final invoice?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, no more deposit-plus-final-payment engagements.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Only&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.investopedia.com/terms/p/progress-billings.asp\" target=\"_blank\">Progressive Billing</a>&nbsp;from now on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My big policy decision is not going to change a thing when it comes to fixes and tweaks. I do the work first, and then I bill at the end</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What will change is how I do soup-to-nuts website development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Frequently, it&rsquo;s not deposit-plus-final-billing that is the &ldquo;real&rdquo; problem. The underlying problem is that<em>scope is never known beforehand</em>. And, or,&nbsp;<em>the work required to achieve that scope is under-estimated</em>. Either way, more work is required.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Basically, deposit-plus-final-payment becomes a fixed price arrangement. The problem for me is that the potential work I do is open-ended. Which incentivizes my client to get me working as much as possible. So there&rsquo;s the crescendo of BTW &mdash; &ldquo;by the way, do X&rdquo;, &ldquo;by the way, do Y&rdquo;. It does not take long for it to become &ldquo;by the way, do Z, or else I will not pay the final payment!&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Progressive billing means that I complete a chunk of work, and then you pay me for that chunk of work. Then, I do another chunk of work, and you pay me for that chunk of work. If we get tired of each other, we do not schedule another chunk of work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Look, I&rsquo;m not going to be your mouse-on-the-wheel. I&rsquo;m not going to be held to a fixed cost while faced with unbounded work. I may be freelance, but I&rsquo;m more &ldquo;lance&rdquo; than &ldquo;free&rdquo;!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We will &ldquo;chunk&rdquo; your new site development, and you&rsquo;ll pay as we go.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', ' I may be freelance, but I am more “lance” than “free”!', ' I may be freelance, but I am more “lance” than “free”!', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/progressive-billing-only', 'interview1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-11-03', '2013-11-03 14:00:00', 1, '2013-11-03 14:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(97, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Dear Clients: Value Is What Value Does', 'dear-clients-value-is-what-value-does', '<p>I make more money from money-making sites than from not-making-money sites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, yes, I want your site to do well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which is why I want you to&nbsp;<em>think of your site as software development, not as software consumption</em>. Why? Because there is more money in software creation than software consumption.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Software is a wasting asset. You have a money making Joomla 1.5 site? How much can you sell your site for? It&rsquo;s on Joomla 1.5, so subtract the cost of upgrading the site to Joomla 3 from its asset value.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As well, open source software is made to be modified. It is valuable to customize open source software &mdash; in fact, the GPL license explicitly allows you to do so. Managing your modifications so that you can still merge native upgrades with your customizations is very important to unleashing value. To do so, you have to set your site up with software development infrastructure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I urge my clients to own their domain registration &amp; management, own their website hosting account (not with their domain registrar), and own their own site. Separate your consultants from your domain and hosting. I am very insistent on this, and very different from other consultants who are only too glad to be in control of your domain and your website. You have to own and control that which will accrue value to you. If I effectively control your site, then its value accrues to me first! In fact, if the address associated with your domain is me &mdash; not you! &mdash; then I effectively own your domain because you can&rsquo;t sell it without my permission. Keep this in mind when you sign up for a SaaS ecomm site, the relationship between code consumption and creation &amp; control and value.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I also urge my clients to sign up and use basic software infrastructure sites. At the very minimum, sign up for GitHub.com. It is no secret that I prefer Atlassian. com: their BitBucket.org software repositories, their JIRA issue tracker, their Confluence collaboration offering, and their HipChat offering, among their other offerings. Why? Because these tools add value to your website. It means you can create software to meet your needs. It means you can manage open source software over time to extract the most value from &lsquo;em. It also means you have a form of built-in disaster recovery/business continuity. It also means you have a way of scaling out your site with project &amp; development infrastructure that will accommodate more people working on your site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My clients repeatedly say no to using Atlassian.com, GitHub.com, Assembla.com, or any other site. It is a &ldquo;tough sell&rdquo; &mdash; no, it is an impossible sell! Despite exquisitely explaining the rationale on my podcasts and blog, despite the insanely nominal cost signing up for these value-adding offerings, despite the unbelievable amount of free development software in the Linux world, I cannot convince my clients. It is too technical, I am told. It feels too much like a way of passing site control into the hands of the consultants.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, I will continue to insist! Because it&rsquo;s &nbsp;really about learning a new technical area. An area that I am learning about all the time. But the value that can be imparted to your website is so potentially huge that it is worth it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I want your site to do well!</p>\r\n', 'I make more money from money-making sites than from not-making-money sites.\r\nSo, yes, I want your site to do well. Which is why I want you to think of your site as software development, not as software consumption. Why? Because there is more money in software creation than software consumption.', 'I make more money from money-making sites than from not-making-money sites.\r\nSo, yes, I want your site to do well. Which is why I want you to think of your site as software development, not as software consumption. Why? Because there is more money in soft', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/dear-clients-value-is-what-value-does', 'united_states_dollar_bill1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-11-06', '2013-11-06 15:00:00', 1, '2013-11-06 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(98, 0, NULL, NULL, 'November 2013 Joomla User Group Toronto Jen Kramer Workshop', 'november-2013-jugt-jen-kramer', '<p>Thank &nbsp;you to Jen Kramer who delivered a fabulous workshop on Bootstrap and Foundation responsive frameworks. A special thank you to Doug and Alison who worked hard to make this evening happen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ironically, two founding members of JUGT were en route to Boston for the Joomla World Conference while Jen was en route to Toronto for the PHP conference.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We had a good turnout, and the North York Civic Centre is a very good venue. JUGT has come a long way. As this evening progressed, I thought that we are ready to arrange a JoomlaDay Toronto.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was great to talk about Joomla with others in person, with Joomla 3.2 just released and so many Joomla-LaSalleMart ideas dancing in my head.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was a question Jen asked me that galvanized my thoughts about Joomla 3.2. The latest Bootstrap Framework version is version 3. But Joomla 3.2 comes with Bootstrap v2. How can one use the latest Bootstrap in the latest Joomla? My answer is that you keep the existing Bootstrap in the &ldquo;media/jui&rdquo; folder, and put the new Bootstrap in a new &ldquo;/media/bv3&Prime; folder, and use &lsquo;em side by side. There may be issues with different javascript libraries and perhaps loading too many css files, but these are things best delved into with a fresh install and a test custom component. I pointed out that anyone using Akeeba Backup already has side-by-side Bootstraps installed &mdash; notice the installation of &ldquo;Strapper&rdquo; the next time you do an AB update.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While explaining this, I realized how truly excited I am about Joomla 3.2. This version of Joomla is the first&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/jenkgraphic560jugt.jpg\"><img alt=\"jenkgraphic560jugt\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/jenkgraphic560jugt-300x199.jpg\" style=\"float:right; height:199px; margin:0px 0px 10px 10px; width:300px\" /></a>version, in my mind, to be seriously kick-ass as a development platform. It took a long while to get to this point, a very steady progression, and now we are at Joomla 3.2. The Framework on Framework is included. There is Ajax built in &mdash; that I have to learn about (hopefully the JWC workshop on this will be on video). There are a lot of goodies to dig into that contribute to this version of Joomla being very good for dev work. In a sense, in my opinion, Joomla&rsquo;s turned a corner where building custom Joomla extensions will be the smarter choice rather than customizing an existing extension.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Put another way, I&rsquo;d not have put it to clients to build from scratch in the past. I&rsquo;d recommend tweaking an existing extension and templates exclusively over building from scratch. But now, for the same effort, you could have just built a fresh custom extension.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I thought again that now is the perfect time to be building a Joomla Distribution. A &ldquo;distro&rdquo; is a custom version of Joomla that retains the integrity of Joomla; and, includes the Joomla updates.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I mentioned my already starting work on my Joomla 3.2 distro, Jen asked me about the now defunct Square One distro. I really appreciate you asking me to &ldquo;compare and contrast&rdquo; with Square One, Jen! Thank you! Really really good question.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2013-11-07-19.12.52.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2013-11-07-19.12.52-224x300.jpg\" style=\"float:right; height:300px; margin:0px 0px 10px 10px; width:224px\" /></a>Square One was a terrific effort to create a custom Joomla 2.5 distribution. One of the goals was to create a &ldquo;lean and mean&rdquo; version of Joomla, where the optional Joomla extensions that come with Joomla become separate installable extensions like any other third party extension. Then, the idea was to add features to Joomla that were not in native Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My LaSalleCMS will be a Joomla that works hand-in-hand with LaSalleMart to provide a holistic unified Joomla-ecommerce experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My LaSalleCMS will make the Joomla development experience even better. Especially with creating development for web apps. Square One was about the user experience. My distro is more for the development experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which goes hand in hand with Joomla becoming a premier development platform. At the time, improving Joomla for users was the thing to do. Now, I see it as kicking up the development experience &mdash; which in turn improves the user experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This evening was not Joomla from a user perspective. It was about Joomla from a development perspective. This is part-and-parcel of the way Joomla is progressing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I really do believe that there is a greater value to being a software producer, not a software consumer. Joomla itself is, in my opinion, &nbsp;a terrific platform for producing software. As opposed to the Joomla project delivering something that solely satisfies the user experience. Joomla 3.2 is made for custom development &mdash; which is where significant website value resides.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Really good workshop this evening!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"356\" src=\"//www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/28044124\" width=\"427\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://www.slideshare.net/jen4web/twitter-bootstrap-vs-zurb-foundation\" target=\"_blank\">Twitter Bootstrap vs ZURB Foundation Version 3</a> </strong> from <strong><a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/jen4web\" target=\"_blank\">Jen Kramer</a></strong></p>\r\n', 'Thank  you to Jen Kramer who delivered a fabulous workshop on Bootstrap and Foundation responsive frameworks. A special thank you to Doug and Alison who worked hard to make this evening happen.', 'Thank  you to Jen Kramer who delivered a fabulous workshop on Bootstrap and Foundation responsive frameworks. A special thank you to Doug and Alison who worked hard to make this evening happen.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/november-2013-jugt-jen-kramer', '2013-11-07-20.50.17.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2013-08-13', '2013-08-13 16:03:19', 1, '2013-08-13 16:03:19', 1, NULL, NULL),
(99, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Announcing My LaSalleCMS Joomla Distribution', 'announcing-my-lasallecms-joomla-distribution', '<div class=\"alert alert-success\" role=\"alert\">\n<p><strong>UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014): Great that I never called my Joomla stuff &quot;Joomla&quot; in the name. The Joomla LaSalleCMS never happened despite years and years mulling the idea. </strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>My Laravel blog app to be called LaSalleCMS and this blog is done with LaSalleCMS -- four months into my switch to Laravel. </strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>One of the greatest challenges -- actually, let&#39;s be truthful, ok --&gt; impediments to getting my Joomla distro off-the-ground was devolving Joomla itself into its component parts. Let me be even more frank: reverse engineering the database and component/module/plugins into separate installable pieces was beyond my patience. Plus, every time there was a new Joomla version (!), the complete reverse engineering exercise had to be repeated. The Square One project devolved Joomla into about 150 separate installable pieces -- an enormous achievement. What I ultimately concluded was that to devolve Joomla, which was a critical aspect of creating distros, was really a pseudo fork-ish exercise, something I really was not in the mood to undertake.</strong></p>\n</div>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>LaSalleCMS, my Joomla Distribution, is live at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://lasallecms.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://LaSalleCMS.com</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Joomla 3.2 is a great version to bring my Joomla Distribution to fruition, mainly due to the Framework on Framework&rsquo;s inclusion. With my own Joomla Distribution, I can bring FoF updates to my clients whenever we need them, instead of waiting for the Joomla project to release its next Joomla version with these updates.UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014):</p>\n\n<p>My long-held intention was to create and maintain my own Joomla &ldquo;Distro&rdquo;.</p>\n\n<p>The lead-up took a while, ideas were tried, and then the decision to hold off until Joomla 3.2.</p>\n\n<p>My Atlassian Open Source License long secured for LaSalleCMS and lying fallow for most of the year, a period when I attended the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2013/atlassian-road-show-2013-in-toronto-first-hand-lessons\" target=\"_blank\">Toronto stop of the Atlassian Road Show</a>, and honed my JIRA, BitBucket, &nbsp;and Confluence skills with LaSalleMart. My LaSalleCMS domain and website have been set-up and ready for much of this year.</p>\n\n<p>So all was ready for the day Joomla 3.2 was released. The day it came out (<a href=\"http://www.joomla.org/announcements/release-news/5516-joomla-3-2-0-stable-released.html\" target=\"_blank\">last week</a>), I dropped everything and began creating my first LaSalleCMS Distro package from it. The first round goal: &nbsp;just initialize everything: the builds, the repo, and whatever is required to set it up. There is just one Distro package, and it is exactly Joomla, with nary a change. Ah, but LaSalleCMS now exists! The builds work, the update works (mostly), the Atlassian suite is set-up, LaSalleCMS is modified. This journey has taken its first step.</p>\n\n<p>There is barely a hint in the Administrator that you are even using LaSalleCMS. You&rsquo;ll notice the version is &ldquo;3.2.0000&Prime; instead of &ldquo;3.2.0&Prime;. The Joomla Updater says &ldquo;LaSalleCMS&rdquo;. Well, I decided to heck with any branding, let&rsquo;s just get this thing set up technically, as (surprise!) it needed more work and TLC than I anticipated.</p>\n\n<p>Now that it is set-up, I can start working on pet issues. I will create JIRA issues for these. Before I get moving on these, I will turn my focus back to LaSalleMart 3. Doing LM3 from scratch, I need to get it to a stage where development can explode. Not quite there yet, but I want to get there in the next month or so &mdash; did you listen to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2013/lasallemart23\" target=\"_blank\">my latest podcast</a>?</p>\n\n<p>The first LaSalleCMS Distro package is &ldquo;LaSalleCMS series 3.2 based on the full version of Joomla 3.2&Prime;. &nbsp;This version is the full version of Joomla. At some point there will be Distro packages that omit some components/modules/plugins that ship with Joomla. But it&rsquo;s too early for that! I am also intrigued that there may be separate repositories for these extensions maintained by Joomla &mdash; but we&rsquo;re getting ahead of ourselves.</p>\n\n<p>The open source license Joomla uses allows people to create and distribute Distro packages.</p>\n\n<p>The essence of a Distro is: the integrity of the underlying software is preserved.</p>\n\n<p>Joomla updates will be merged into LaSalleCMS.</p>\n\n<p>I&rsquo;m not turning Joomla into something else &mdash; it&rsquo;s always Joomla.</p>\n\n<p>Why do Distros?</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>To actively manage Joomla for security and added functionality;</li>\n	<li>To pair it with LaSalleMart to create a holistic Joomla ecommerce experience;</li>\n	<li>Deeper understanding of Joomla;</li>\n	<li>Moneyball: value is producing software, not consuming it. &ldquo;Producing&rdquo; Joomla opens up opportunities my clients &amp; I would not otherwise enjoy.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>UPDATE WHILE INPUTTING MY WORDPRESS POSTS TO MY LARAVEL BLOG APP (Aug 2014):These are things you&rsquo;ve heard me talk about on my podcasts for a while. Now, it&rsquo;s coming to fruition.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>LaSalleCMS has four sites!</p>\n\n<ol>\n	<li>LaSalleCMS.com;</li>\n	<li><a href=\"https://lasallecms.atlassian.net/wiki/display/LASALLECMS/LaSalleCMS\" target=\"_blank\">Atlassian Confluence</a>&nbsp;site = the collaboration and knowledge base site;</li>\n	<li><a href=\"https://lasallecms.atlassian.net/browse/LSCMSCFULL-2?jql=project%20%3D%20LSCMSCFULL\" target=\"_blank\">Atlassian JIRA site</a>&nbsp;= the issue tracker;</li>\n	<li><a href=\"https://bitbucket.org/lasallemart\" target=\"_blank\">Atlassian BitBucket site</a>&nbsp;= software repositories.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>LaSalleCMS is set-up to be a real open source project.</p>\n\n<p>The Atlassian Open Source License offers tremendous power for collaboration and development. Yet, for the here-and-now, I&rsquo;m more concerned with just getting everything set-up, and &ldquo;dogfooding&rdquo; it on my own sites and on a very select few client sites.</p>\n\n<p>Launching LaSalleCMS is part of my longer-term plans. It is thrilling to actually launch it after a long considered lead-up.</p>\n', 'Announcing My LaSalleCMS Joomla Distribution...', 'Announcing My LaSalleCMS Joomla Distribution...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/announcing-my-lasallecms-joomla-distribution', 'lasallecms.png', 1, 0, 0, '2013-11-14', '2013-11-14 15:00:00', 1, '2013-11-14 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(100, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart 3: The Project', 'lasallemart-3-the-project', '<p>To get a handle on the scope of LaSalleMart 3, I conjured up a Work Breakdown Structure this evening.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Took a roll of masking tape, blank paper, pens and markers, and walked away from the screens. Found a board to create an old fashioned pen-and-paper WBS. Which turned into pages of written plans.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With the successful launch of LaSalleCMS, and with clearing things off my to-do list last weekend, time to dive into LaSalleMart 3 development. Except that these last two days became quite frustrating, with not much to show for it, except for some superb learning about FoF HMVC (thanks Nicholas!). It is becoming all-too-easy to become immersed in the details, despite my goal of keeping this first version KISS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Taking my frustration as an indicator, I took a step back. With pen, paper, and masking tape.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What I came up with is a plan to get &ldquo;Alpha&rdquo; versions of LaSalleMart 3 done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first iterations of LaSalleMart 3 will not be production versions. They will not even be &ldquo;beta&rdquo; versions &mdash; versions that need some &ldquo;real world&rdquo; use to discover the rough edges that need ironing before releasing as &ldquo;stable&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The goal of the initial &ldquo;Alpha&rdquo; LM3 is to get checkout flowing. This requires the basics to be in place: products, add-to-cart, cart, shipping, payment, order creation. For a low-scope alpha, there&rsquo;s quite a bit of scope just to establish a cart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, the initial &ldquo;Alpha&rdquo; will have a single database product table; a basic views to support the admin &amp; display of the products; a bare-bones shipping and payment step; and order processing. These need to flow in checkout.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This initial &ldquo;Alpha&rdquo; version needs a data model! Probably a partial source of today&rsquo;s frustration is my lack of a data model, so will take some time out from the PHP to do a ERD, which will turn into SQL.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am not set on the order, but for now&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Alpha 2&Prime;: cart management using database tables (&ldquo;Alpha 1&Prime; will use session variables).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Alpha3&Prime;: site registration and address management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From here on, there are feature sets to build out to get to the &ldquo;Beta&rdquo; version of LM3. I anticipate cutting scope to get a beta done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Products: manufacturers; integrating com_content tables; downloads; inventory; price; attributes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Orders: taxes; detailed views; order administration; email notifications &amp; Mandrill.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Buyers: Shopper&rsquo;s groups (ACL) &mdash; and perhaps rounding out a partially implemented address management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shipping: manual shipping rates; allow multiple shippers per order.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Payments: manual.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From here, development can really take off.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s no need to do a &ldquo;big bang&rdquo; initial release. &nbsp;The concepts have worked! Using lots of small components, being able to run builds as often as needed&hellip; it&rsquo;s better to get small, release often, and for the immediate timeframe, bring LaSalleMart 3 into existence!</p>\r\n', 'To get a handle on the scope of LaSalleMart 3, I conjured up a Work Breakdown Structure this evening. Took a roll of masking tape, blank paper, pens and markers, and walked away from the screens. Found a board to create an old fashioned pen-and-paper WBS. Which turned into pages of written plans...', 'To get a handle on the scope of LaSalleMart 3, I conjured up a Work Breakdown Structure this evening. Took a roll of masking tape, blank paper, pens and markers, and walked away from the screens. Found a board to create an old fashioned pen-and-paper WBS.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-3-the-project', 'wbs_diagram1.png', 1, 0, 0, '2013-11-20', '2013-11-20 15:00:00', 1, '2013-11-20 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(101, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart3 Initial Alpha Release Achieved', 'lasallemart3-initial-alpha-release-achieved', '<p>In my&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2013/lasallemart-3-the-project\" target=\"_blank\">previous post</a>&nbsp;I described moving to package milestone releases to get a handle on the scope of LaSalleMart3&prime;s development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am thrilled to tell you that LaSalleMart3&prime;s initial Alpha release is achieved.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As expected, it is hardly a production-grade release, nor even a client testable release.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, it is a critical Alpha1, representing tangible development progress; and, a certain &ldquo;it&rsquo;s out of the lab&rdquo; status.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So much of this Alpha1 involves using concepts in a production-like environment, as opposed to the proof-of-concepts done up to this point. Yes, the proof-of-concept affirmed the concept. But, now it&rsquo;s time to use these concepts &ldquo;for real&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Something I&rsquo;ve never done before is developing a family of related components, modules, and plugins. How are these relations actually effected using the superb Akeeba Framework on Framework &mdash; which now ships with Joomla starting with J!3.2. Are there issues related to relating extensions?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LM3 Alpha1 is comprised of nine components, one module, and three plugins:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>com_lmaddress (address management component);</li>\r\n	<li>com_lmcart (cart component);</li>\r\n	<li>com_lmcheckout (checkout component);</li>\r\n	<li>com_lmcoupon (coupon component);</li>\r\n	<li>com_lasallemart (flagship component);</li>\r\n	<li>com_lmorder (order processing and management component);</li>\r\n	<li>com_lmpayment (payment engine component);</li>\r\n	<li>com_lmproduct (product component &mdash; will be integrated with Joomla&rsquo;s article (content) component);</li>\r\n	<li>com_lmshipping (shipping engine component);</li>\r\n	<li>mod_lmcart (cart module);</li>\r\n	<li>plg_content_lmaddtocart (add-to-cart content plugin);</li>\r\n	<li>plg_system_lmsystem (LaSalleMart3&prime;s system plugin);</li>\r\n	<li>plg_user_lmuser (LaSalleMart3&prime;s user plugin).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>A lot of effort went into creating the builds, installation, and update routines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An unexpected outcome of Alpha1 was the new concept of The Flagship Component.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ironically, the LaSalleMart component was about to be deleted as, true to the idea of not having a single massive component; but, instead, having a lot of targeted components, there was no identifiable function for com_lasallemart. I nearly ended up having LaSallemart3 not having a com_lasallemart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the config and database became issues.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Do I really want each component having its own settings? Well, yes and no. For &ldquo;no&rdquo;, I needed one place for all LaSalleMart3-wide settings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A component always has the database tables it requires. Right? Wrong! For the first time ever in my Joomla experience, components are installed without their database. Instead, only the LaSalleMart3 flagship component installs the database &mdash; for all of LaSalleMart3. Breaking up the integrated data model is going to introduce complexity and errors for no payoff, just so each component can install &amp; maintain its own piece of LaSalleMart3.&nbsp;The data model is going to become quite involved, so it needs to be managed as a single entity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thus was born the flagship component, com_lasallemart! Now, its inherent lack of identity is a plus, being available for the config, LaSalleMart3 specific reporting, and database management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A new requirement that cropped up was the need for com_lasallemart to be installed first, but uninstalled last, amongst all LaSalleMart3 extentions. That database needs to exist first! And an involved, populated, database can&rsquo;t be deleted just because its attendent component was mistakenly deleted. Having worked with a list of thirteen components starting with &ldquo;LM3&Prime; in Joomla&rsquo;s Extension Manager, I can see all too clearly clicking the wrong box at oh-dark-hundred and instantly zapping the entire database.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So the flagship component must be installed first, and uninstalled last.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I also built in a history of LaSalleMart3 extensions&rsquo; installation, upgrading, and un-installation. With so many extensions I will need this history to diagnose problems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So a dominant feature of Alpha1 is its unexpected installation routine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alpha1&prime;s overall functionality is limited. Products can be entered, and viewed in the front-end. The views are rudimentary, yet it&rsquo;s all done in FoF. The product component fetches the add-to-cart view from the add-to-cart component &mdash; no plugin needed! It&rsquo;s very exciting to see this work &mdash; well, it is for me! The add-to-cart form within the product layout uses the add-to-cart component to process. At first, cart info was stored in session variables, but that was dropped in favour of using new cart database tables. So the add-to-cart form saves to the database tables, using FoF all the way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My defining experience using FoF is deleting code. And files. And folders. It astounds me how much code is&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;needed. As long as I stick to FoF conventions, FoF will take care of the heavy lifting. It&rsquo;s always tempting to pull a Frank Sinatra and do it &ldquo;My Way&rdquo;, but it&rsquo;s a very costly indulgence. There&rsquo;s a lot of goodness packed into FoF, so why subvert it? A part of learning The FoF Way was deleting files. Yes, FoF really does require less code &mdash; if you stick to its conventions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another defining FoF experience was adding the term &ldquo;MVC Triad&rdquo; to my Joomla lexicon. Never has such joy been encapsulated by such a dry technical label. Thank you, FoF!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alpha1 was originally supposed to flow through the entire checkout sequence, to include the shipping and payment components. With the expanded installation routine, and the success of the add-to-cart piece (without the plugin!), scope was truncated and Alpha1 was wrapped up. Hello continuous development mentality! Sometimes, just use time as the cut-off. The essential outcomes were achieved.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All thirteen extensions install, even though most don&rsquo;t do anything. And, the administrator side is not even tested &mdash; I know that I have an Akeeba Strapper issue, but given the front-end focus of Alpha1, why worry about it right now? I would love to use Bootstrap 3 anyways&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Indeed, the flagship component must be installed first, and the others must un-install ahead of it. The database installs &mdash; and uninstalls. The installs work on LaSalleCMS, my Joomla 3.2 Distro &mdash; but there is a pending versioning issue that cropped up, but can wait.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oh, the initial order processing works. As a stand-alone process, the FoF-based order processing works. Order processing requires intensive database updating, so I wanted to get a sense in Alpha1 what FoF requires for multiple table INSERTs. I&rsquo;ll tell you this: I had to delete code!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alpha1 excludes address management, because this is a sub-system, not just a one-off form to whip up. Addressing it (pun intended) would have distracted away from the key Alpha1 outcomes. Basically, Alpha1 is the first &ldquo;getting out of the lab&rdquo; release, with the focus on using FoF in the practical production environment. It&rsquo;s a bit early to worry about address management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alpha2 will use rudimentary shipping and payment checkout steps in order for LaSalleMart3 to flow through checkout. There will be no address management. This may end up being all of Alpha2.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alpha3 will focus on the add-to-cart subsystem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alpha4 will focus on address management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At this point, development is ready to explode. The goal to achieve LaSalleMart3&prime;s first Beta release is to replicate the functions in LaSalleMart2, which included a detailed standard shippping, integrated site registration/address management/checkout workflow, product attributes, PayPal Standard, and more.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alpha3 and Alpha4 can be done concurrently, so the time to step on the gas is now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2013/lasallemart24\" target=\"_blank\">LaSalleMart News #24 (Dec 2013): LM3 Alpha One Achieved</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.lasallemart.com/index.php/lasallemart3-vision\" target=\"_blank\">Vision of LaSalleMart3</a></p>\r\n', 'I am thrilled to tell you that LaSalleMart3′s initial Alpha release is achieved. As expected, it is hardly a production-grade release, nor even a client testable release. However, it is a critical Alpha1, representing tangible development progress; and, a certain “it’s out of the lab” status...', 'I am thrilled to tell you that LaSalleMart3′s initial Alpha release is achieved. As expected, it is hardly a production-grade release, nor even a client testable release. However, it is a critical Alpha1, representing tangible development progress; and, a', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart3-initial-alpha-release-achieved', 'lm3_bitbucket_alpha1_sm.png', 1, 0, 0, '2013-12-05', '2013-12-05 15:00:00', 1, '2013-12-05 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(102, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Progressing Down the LaSalleMart Road', 'progressing-down-the-lasallemart-road', '<p>The problem with going heads-down with programming is that I go dark.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My tweets go to zero, my Facebook participation declines &mdash; if that&rsquo;s even possible given my usual Facebook aversion. The last few weeks of Holidays were the perfect time to go dark. Although I came up for air to do a little podcast, I need to compliment it with a blog post. Then, I&rsquo;m going dark a little bit more.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This afternoon was devoted to LaSalleMart&rsquo;s add-to-cart plugin. A necessary adjunct to the Joomla article and LaSalleMart product tables integration, this plugin displays LaSalleMart&rsquo;s add-to-cart form in a Joomla article. The twist is using the Framework on Framework, which allows the plugin to act as a conduit &mdash; a pipeline if you will &mdash; between Joomla&rsquo;s article and LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am trying very hard to avoid using plugins, and am succeeding so far. One reason is what I perceive as abuse and overuse in general. Another reason is favouring the use of components as the full flower of Joomla is truly available when programming with components. Taking plugins back to first principles, plugins should &ldquo;fire events&rdquo; when necessary; and, should act as conduits.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart has, hopefully, the only suite of plugins that it needs: a system plugin; a user plugin; a content plugin; and the add-to-cart content plugin. The three other plugins are essentially placeholders, set-up now as a convenience if (when) they are needed. The user plugin will likely have events associated with user login to deal with session_id&rsquo;s in LaSalleMart&rsquo;s cart table.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This afternoon I knew I was onto something when I&nbsp;<em>deleted code</em>&nbsp;in my add-to-cart plugin. Deleting code is a frequent exercise as I program with the Framework on Framework (which now ships with Joomla 3.2). Today I created a template for my plugin. Then, later on, I deleted it. &nbsp;Instead, I finally got a view in my component to render in my plugin, to display in a Joomla article:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<code>// Output buffering<br />\r\n@ob_start();<br />\r\necho $view-&gt;loadAnyTemplate(&#39;site:com_lmcart/addtocart/default&#39;);<br />\r\n$output = @ob_get_clean();</code></p>\r\n\r\n<p>// Get the add-to-cart form in the Joomla article!<br />\r\n$article-&gt;text = str_replace($matches[0][0], $output, $article-&gt;text);</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Exactly what I was trying to achieve! The layout in my cart component renders directly in my plugin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With this key linkage achieved, the build-out will include layouts built exclusively for my plugin, controlled administratively from my component. Instead having a ton of plugin parameters that need manual specification within the plugin code (that sits in the Joomla article), my hope is that one lonely parameter is all that&rsquo;s needed. The multitude of parameters will instead reside within the component (not the plugin), and rendered through rules the component&rsquo;s controller carries out. A build-out that will not happen by this current month-end, mind you! Getting there.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step-by-step, my vision is working out. This plugin is extraordinarily lean, the code is exceptionally readable. It helps that I am deleting code, not adding to it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart displays products from its product table. Alternatively, Joomla articles can represent products. Both options have a working add-to-cart form. Furthermore, right now, the add-to-cart form is the exact same form! Although this has a nice symmetry, you&rsquo;re eyes will appreciate using different layouts later on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The product and add-to-cart nexus are functionally done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What has cropped up is the use of different Bootstrap versions. Joomla uses Bootstrap 2.3.2. The newer templates properly use Bootstrap 3. So, I am in the process of having LaSalleMart use both.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The project plan I have is a good basis for going off on twists and turns. When I created the plan of what features would encompass which Alpha release packages, I had not the slightest thought about the two Bootstrap versions. However, in the doing I realized I had to &ldquo;do something&rdquo;. &nbsp;These things take time, but it&rsquo;s time well spent.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Overall, I still see a good chance of releasing LaSalleMart3 version one point oh at the end of January.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Basis of optimism is seeing LaSalleMart staying lean and clean &mdash; so far! As I am building the basics right now, I am keeping close to the Framework on Framework conventions, straying as little as I can in order to get the most FoF benefits. &nbsp;I will build the administration forms along these lines, so you will see what seem like a lot of little forms that could be bundled up for convenience. That convenience is not worth the programming right now. It&rsquo;s better to build the forms along FoF lines first anyways to get a stronger feel of how FoF works. We can consolidate forms later, if need be. I suspect that the real issue is workflow, not form consolidation, so: first the forms, then the workflow. If I can somehow keep the administration forms XML based, instead of writing PHP based forms, I can speed up the creation of these admin forms, freeing up time on the other stuff.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That other stuff is features I was hoping to deal with after doing a bare-bones production release. But, alas, what seemed fine on paper when I first put my release packages together is not looking realistic in the doing. Without building out the product heft a little more, a production LaSalleMart site will be too bare-bones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I need to pretend I am a user and give the LaSalleMart I&rsquo;ve accomplished so far a whirl. So I will create a new site from scratch, using the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://t3-framework.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Base Joostrap template</a>&nbsp;to see LaSalleMart in a real Bootstrap 3 set-up. I am very sure there will be a number of rough edges to smooth out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once smoothed out, I will do the product quantity feature set; and, the product attribute feature set. Originally, I was to omit these product feature sets. But, I&rsquo;d rather build these features, rather than the hooks in anticipation of these features coming. These are showstopper features anyways, so I figure if I stick close to the Framework, I can still meet a January month-end production release.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My hope is that the product feature sets will be complete by Friday, January 17th. The product and cart components, the cart module, and the add-to-cart plugin. The #__content and #__lmproduct_items tables are integrated, the add-to-cart works, the cart itself works. Looking forward to a quick user-styled test of what I have, and then move on to product quantity and product attributes. These relate intimately with price, which is a Big Reason to get these done now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At this point, I will call this &ldquo;LaSalleMart3 Alpha2&Prime;. I will create a private demo site for a specific private audience, and then progress to address management, shipping, payment, order processing, and order management. Somewhere in there I have to sneak in taxes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By address management, I mean billing and shipping addresses. Nothing fancy!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By shipping, I exclude all shipping companies. Right now, I am talking strictly manual shipping methods. In part, I want to test using components for shipping, rather than plugins. So a few shipping components. Digging into shipping is not for this month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By payments, I mean &ldquo;purchase order&rdquo; payment and PayPal Standard. That&rsquo;s it. Again, I will use components for each payment method, not plugins. Digging into payments is not for this month. Not that doing PayPal Standard is exactly trivial&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Order processing will be involved. So, order management will be minimal. I am hot to have back-end order initiation, which is something that is not realistic to have in the first production release.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart is progressing. My social life and social media life may not progress as much this month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Look for a progress report not this weekend, but the weekend next.</p>\r\n', 'This afternoon was devoted to LaSalleMart’s add-to-cart plugin. A necessary adjunct to the Joomla article and LaSalleMart product tables integration, this plugin displays LaSalleMart’s add-to-cart form in a Joomla article. The twist is using the Framework on Framework, which allows the plugin to act as a conduit — a pipeline if you will — between Joomla’s article and LaSalleMart.', 'This afternoon was devoted to LaSalleMart’s add-to-cart plugin. A necessary adjunct to the Joomla article and LaSalleMart product tables integration, this plugin displays LaSalleMart’s add-to-cart form in a Joomla article. The twist is using the Framework', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/progressing-down-the-lasallemart-road', 'under_construction1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-01-07', '2014-01-07 15:00:00', 1, '2014-01-07 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(103, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart: Revised Alphas', 'lasallemart-revised-alphas', '<p>Last week I posted on my blog:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>That other stuff is features I was hoping to deal with after doing a bare-bones production release. But, alas, what seemed fine on paper when I first put my release packages together is not looking realistic in the doing. Without building out the product heft a little more, a production LaSalleMart site will be too bare-bones.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, I discovered this week that even more build-out is needed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The success of using small targeted-scope components that talk to each other (thank you, Akeeba Framework on Framework!) has resulted in&hellip; well, a bunch of components! I created icons in each components&rsquo; admin cpanel to make it easy traversing the various LaSalleMart components. Not scheduled work, but one of those things discovered &ldquo;in the doing&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart&rsquo;s&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2013/lasallemart3-initial-alpha-release-achieved\" target=\"_blank\">flagship component</a>&nbsp;has icons linking to each component. Great! But, um, I made a mistake: regardless of a LaSallemart component&rsquo;s existence on a website, its icon appears in the flagship component. So&hellip; have to programmatically confirm the existence of each component first. Good thing I took the time to create a LaSalleMart installation history database table, eh! I am pretty sure that I cheated, putting calls to the model in the actual view file &mdash; but, it is direct and human-readable!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I also took a nice little tour of Joomla&rsquo;s JSession and #__session table. Not having occassion to delve into sessions in my regular Joomla experiences, this tour represented a new learning opportunity. Maybe not one I wanted! I have set (and get) custom session variables before, but this is the first time I ended up going through the source code, and studying the database table. All this in pursuit of managing the cart database table.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another little expedition was triggered by an interesting question in the Akeeba Framework on Framework Google Group. The question asked about the new Joomla profile plugin. What is a &ldquo;profile plugin&rdquo;? Is this something that can help me with my upcoming LaSalleMart Address Management component? More studying source code. No, this plugin will not be part of LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Building LaSalleMart is turning into an ongoing journey of learning and discovery. &nbsp;In part because Joomla never stays still. The Framework on Framework is not staying still. Implementing innovation is sometimes about the deep dark details.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I like to tell myself that LaSalleMart development can start to really hum along now, as the bulk of the implementation style of FoF et al is now established. Well, hopefully, this is mainly true. Then, it&rsquo;s just a &ldquo;mere matter&rdquo; of the sheer volume of development to achieve!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, I have revised my LaSalleMart project schedule.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Alpha 2:</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>wrap up what I&rsquo;ve done up &rsquo;til now into Alpha 2;</li>\r\n	<li>create an Alpha2 demonstration site;</li>\r\n	<li>give the password to a dozen people for initial comment.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Alpha2 is a bit too &ldquo;raw&rdquo;, really. But if Alpha1 was an exercise of bringing LaSalleMart &ldquo;out of the lab&rdquo;, then Alpha2 is an exercise of taking LaSalleMart &ldquo;out of the shop&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alpha2 and its demo site will be completed by this weekend.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE: Done January 23, 2014. Demo site =&nbsp;<a href=\"http://lasallemart.com/alpha2\" target=\"_blank\">http://LaSalleMart.com/Alpha2</a></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Alpha 3:</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a bunch of unresolved issues that have accumulated. Alpha 3 is just taking the time to go over everything now. Nothing earth shattering, but important to get done before getting deeper into development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE: Bulk of Alpha3 done.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Alpha4:</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>From this point forward, I&rsquo;ll be using JIRA extensively. Which means a bit more of a learning curve learning how to do basic &ldquo;Release Management&rdquo; with JIRA. The advantages are significant, including gaining more JIRA expertise with which to manage a team of devs &mdash; that day is coming, of that I am sure. I look forward to a real changelog. Associating individual commits (pushed to BitBucket.org git repositories) to issues. Hooking onto Atlassian was always the plan, so here we go.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alpha4 is a build-out of the product: product attributes, and product quantity; and, bringing these build-outs to bear on the cart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Originally, I included taxes in this Alpha, and perhaps I still will. Depends if I need to build hooks into the price calculations immediately, or if I can defer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Alpha5:</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Customer address management;</li>\r\n	<li>Three tax handling components: Florida, Canada, California;</li>\r\n	<li>Update the cart, where-ever necessary;</li>\r\n	<li>Do the cart module.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Alpha 6:</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>One manual shipping method;</li>\r\n	<li>One manual payment method;</li>\r\n	<li>Optional: PayPal Standard payment method;</li>\r\n	<li>Order processing;</li>\r\n	<li>Checkout steps.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Alpha7:</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>This is essentially a pre-Beta version;</li>\r\n	<li>Smooth out the front and back end order details forms;</li>\r\n	<li>Wrap up issues deferred from Alpha4 until now.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Beta1:</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Wow, Beta already!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m not putting dates to anything, except to say I&rsquo;ll be hard at it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UPDATE (March 02, 2014):&nbsp;</strong>After putting Alpha2/3 together, I doubt I&rsquo;ll be doing any other official Alpha versions at all. In the push to get the first LaSalleMart3 out-the-door, there&rsquo;s little utility getting distinct alpha versions done. As well, with all the pieces inter-related &mdash; which is a big reason getting a base production done in the first place &mdash; it is not really practical thinking of bringing independent feature sets to fruition independently.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thinking in terms of alpha releases was very helpful getting a handle on the initial feature set. It was a bit like a zero-budget process, brining the feature set down to a very sparse bare-bones level; and, then, justifying each subsequent feature-creep.</p>\r\n', 'I discovered this week that even more build-out is needed...', 'I discovered this week that even more build-out is needed...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-revised-alphas', 'alpha1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-01-16', '2014-01-16 15:00:00', 1, '2014-01-16 15:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(104, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Cutting Edge, Kicking Ass, and The Times A-Changed On You Again', 'cutting-edge-kicking-ass-and-the-times-a-changed-on-you-again', '<p>After attending this evening&rsquo;s Joomla User Group Toronto&rsquo;s workshop on blogging, I returned in the mood to, well, blog!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s been a while, what with LaSalleMart, squeezing in some monthly podcasts, and whatnot, since I&rsquo;ve blogged. Getting the first production release of LaSalleMart3, built from scratch using the best ev-ah Joomla version 3.2 with the superb RAD framework for Joomla (the Akeeba Framework on Framework), takes precedence over blogging. Well, tonight is the exception.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Do you know that when the question was asked to about the dozen-plus attendees this evening &ldquo;who blogs &mdash; who maintains a blog?&rdquo;, I was the only hand &mdash; the ONLY hand &mdash; that went up. The question of &ldquo;who podcasts&rdquo; was not even mentioned, although later is was acknowledged that I was the sole podcaster in the room. No one questioned how the presenters could present on blogging when they don&rsquo;t blog, but I kept my counsel (until now, I suppose).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I cut my freelance computer consulting teeth with WordPress, my first major client site. This blog and my media site are in WordPress. I use a framework specific to WordPress, along with a heavily customized child theme (of course customized!).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Professionally, I found it necessary to keep a hand in WordPress all these years, even though my specialty is Joomla. Good move. With the advent of WordPress 3.9, my attitude to WordPress has changed hugely &mdash; not that I&rsquo;ve blogged about it (much, if at all). However, I will defer (the bulk of) this topic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Blogging and ecommerce go together like chocolate and peanut butter. So much so that I take it as axiomatic that ecommerce site owners blog. So much so that I&rsquo;ve made great efforts to use Joomla&rsquo;s native article facility for LaSalleMart product pages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And barely any ecommerce client I&rsquo;ve had since I started freelancing has actually blogged. I will hazard a guess that 10% of my ecomm clients blogged in any way, shape, or form.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Google loves original content. So, blogging is a must &mdash; a must!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How many clients of my clients over the years look to SEO as an instant fix pill to &ldquo;fix&rdquo; sales? Most. But blogging? Feh! That&rsquo;s effort!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I took immense joy at hearing the presenters tell us how the old SEO tricks are falling by the wayside. I do like the tidbit that Google updates its search algorithm multiple times per day. How&rsquo;s that for an ode to continuous software development!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Blogging is more than that, you know. &nbsp;Blogging is your strategic advantage. Blogging is how your potential buyers get to know you. It&rsquo;s how you build your credibility as an expert. It&rsquo;s how you tell the story of your products and services. This is the internet! Why are you treating your ecomm site like a Sears catelogue, listing your stuff for sale with a little blurb. Geez! You and 150,000 other sites selling Widget X look all the same.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, the world is changing. Blogging is so last decade. I cannot stress enough on the eve of LaSalleMart3 being released, that those who use LaSalleMart3 e-broadcast. So much so that I have in mind so create a Joomla e-broadcasting platform to work hand-in-glove with my ecommerce. Especially for ecommerce sites &mdash; and especially for the client profile I expect to serve with LaSalleMart3 &mdash; e-broadcast is &ldquo;the new blog&rdquo; and is a m-u-s-t for ecommerce. You have espied my&nbsp;<a href=\"http://lasallecast.com/\" target=\"_blank\">LaSalleCast</a>?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Until last week, I just had not grasped what this thing called &ldquo;The Joomla Framework&rdquo; really is. I was not paying attention, and I have my hands full with this from-scratch ecommerce technology for the Joomla CMS.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last week as the Big Debate over the Joomla Framework&rsquo;s open source licensing. Which led me to discover&nbsp;<a href=\"http://framework.joomla.org/\" target=\"_blank\">The Joomla Framework</a>. LaSalleMart work slowed so I could dive into the J!FW, and am I ever glad I did.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>THE JOOMLA FRAMEWORK IS MAGNIFICENT.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Go forth, Dear Reader, and discover the J!FW.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The J!FW is technologically topical right now, and magnificently so. It is so far ahead technologically that it is a separate technological entity than the Joomla CMS that we all know and love. Well, except for a tiny little sliver of a sliver of the J!FW that does exist in the Joomla CMS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are intriguing and interesting possibilities with the J!FW and LaSalleMart. And, of course, with e-broadcasting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a sample J!FW web app that I installed. After the fourth try to get my install to work, it worked (mostly!) &mdash; and immediately I exclaimed &ldquo;aaaahhhhhh yyyeeessss!&rdquo;. Now I Get It!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank you to the few persevering and independently minded souls who forged ahead to create this magnificent gift to all of us.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am S-O-L-D completely on the J!FW.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The J!FW is a completely new area of learning &mdash; nearly everyday I pursue this journey.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tonight I was asked if my LaSalleMart &ldquo;can do ____&rdquo; like Virtuemart. Let me tell you something: for my clients and I, LaSalleMart is ours! We control the whole darn thing completely. WE CAN DO ANYTHING WE WANT!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is a hugely liberating fact: it&rsquo;s ours + we can do what we want.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No submitting support requests, no playing mother-may-I, no nibbling around core code. LaSalleMart is ours!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And, baby, I&rsquo;m gonna confess something to you right here and now: if all you want to do behind the wheel of LaSalleMart is turn off the add-to-cart form to &ldquo;just have a catalogue&rdquo;, then you do not deserve to drive LaSalleMart. Go back whence you came. Pick up your marbles and go home.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart will be obviously lacking in features of your usual Mega-PHP-Cart you download from megaphpcart-dot-com, but as I scolded a workshop attendee over a brew, &ldquo;I am developing a cutting edge ecommerce technology from scratch with Joomla 3.2 and FoFv2, and these are the questions you are asking me?&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart is designed to scale in the mobile world. Check!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart is designed to work with Joomla, exposing the strategic power of Joomla for ecommerce. Check!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart is intimately developed with the superb Framework on Framework. Check!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart happens to be perfectly positioned for the Joomla Framework. Check!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It will not take my development group (future tense) much time to scale features into LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now that I&rsquo;ve blogged, I will not do so again until I get LM3&prime;s first production release done. It&rsquo;s getting close, and there&rsquo;s a lot of detail work to do.</p>\r\n', 'Meanwhile, the world is changing. Blogging is so last decade. I cannot stress enough on the eve of LaSalleMart3 being released, that those who use LaSalleMart3 e-broadcast. So much so that I have in mind so create a Joomla e-broadcasting platform to work hand-in-glove with my ecommerce. Especially for ecommerce sites — and especially for the client profile I expect to serve with LaSalleMart3 — e-broadcast is “the new blog” and is a m-u-s-t for ecommerce. You have espied my LaSalleCast?', 'Meanwhile, the world is changing. Blogging is so last decade. I cannot stress enough on the eve of LaSalleMart3 being released, that those who use LaSalleMart3 e-broadcast. So much so that I have in mind so create a Joomla e-broadcasting platform to work ', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/cutting-edge-kicking-ass-and-the-times-a-changed-on-you-again', 'eagle1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-03-12', '2014-03-12 12:00:00', 1, '2014-03-12 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(105, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Four Software Freedoms Described By The Man Himself', 'four-software-freedoms-described-by-the-man-himself', '<p>He does a lot of interviews and appearances. Here is a very recent one&nbsp;<a href=\"http://stallman.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Richard Stallman</a>&nbsp;did where he describes in his own words his Four Software Freedoms that is the heart of the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://gnu.org/licenses/gpl.html\" target=\"_blank\">General Public License</a>&nbsp;that Joomla (and WordPress et al) uses:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The full interview is&nbsp;<a href=\"http://rss.infowars.com/20140311_Tue_Alex.mp3\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>, starting at 1:24</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://gnu.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Free Software</a>:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><strong>Free software is a matter of the users&rsquo; freedom to run, copy, distribute, study, change and improve the software.</strong>&nbsp;More precisely, it refers to four kinds of freedom, for the users of the software:</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<blockquote>\r\n	<p>The freedom to run the program, for any purpose (freedom 0).</p>\r\n	</blockquote>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<blockquote>\r\n	<p>The freedom to study how the program works, and adapt it to your needs (freedom 1). Access to the source code is a precondition for this.</p>\r\n	</blockquote>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<blockquote>\r\n	<p>The freedom to redistribute copies so you can help your neighbor (freedom 2).</p>\r\n	</blockquote>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<blockquote>\r\n	<p>The freedom to improve the program, and release your improvements to the public, so that the whole community benefits (freedom 3). Access to the source code is a precondition for this.</p>\r\n	</blockquote>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>0:37 &ldquo;Freedom to work together and exercise collective control&rdquo; &mdash; Well, that means people of differing skills can get together to do as a team what they cannot do individually. A &ldquo;Hackenpreneur&rdquo; group could progress software quite effectively.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are not familiar with these Freedoms (nor the GPL), do take a moment.</p>\r\n', 'He does a lot of interviews and appearances. Here is a very recent one Richard Stallman did where he describes in his own words his Four Software Freedoms that is the heart of the General Public License that Joomla (and WordPress et al) uses...', 'He does a lot of interviews and appearances. Here is a very recent one Richard Stallman did where he describes in his own words his Four Software Freedoms that is the heart of the General Public License that Joomla (and WordPress et al) uses...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/four-software-freedoms-described-by-the-man-himself', 'richard_stallman.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-03-14', '2014-03-14 12:00:00', 1, '2014-03-14 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(106, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart: Breaking Radio Silence Later This Month', '/2014/breaking-radio-silence-later-this-month', '<p>LaSalleMart 3 will launch later this week.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One more week of nose-to-the-grindstone; and, then, launching.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Punch line: LaSalleMart 3 will&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;be production ready. Close! But, no matter,&nbsp;<strong><em>it&rsquo;s time to break radio silence</em>.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&mdash;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 3 is Joomla ecommerce technology&nbsp;built from scratch with Joomla 3.2 and with the fabulous Framework on Framework that ships with Joomla (and, yes, will not ship with future versions of Joomla &mdash; a story for later). Yes, LM3 will work with Joomla 3.3 (the revised versioning is also a story for later).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first production release is a nice cart package to run a basic clean cart in Joomla. LM3 is designed to further greater ambitions, but laying down the basics in a new innovative form is the imperative for the first production release. And, wow, there are a lot of basics to lay down. Something about being innovative&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&mdash;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This week&rsquo;s been especially productive: Canadian PST/GST/HST, wrapping up the cart summary, coupons (managed to sneak in some tweaks sooner than later), tweaked admin product views, and lots of work on the cart. Already refactoring some cart code, after last week refactoring some add-to-cart coding.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite working hard on an ajax powered cart, I put ajax on the back burner. Frankly, I was getting upset at ajax subverting the Framework on Framework&rsquo;s HMVC. It is more important at this point to understand all that I am setting out to do, so I understand how ajax fits in. The coding structure started to fall into place once I removed the ajax-ness; but, yeah, it necessitated some re-coding.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I knew this week that this re-coding would clobber my hope of getting LM3&prime;s first production release done next week. But, no regrets, because the structure, the use of the Framework on Framework, the flow is what I envisioned it would be. This re-coding is absolutely essential.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What I see happening now is finishing the cart, finishing the checkout and registration, and then testing it all with a mock site. This site will likely form the basis of a demo site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The remainder of the checkout process will be ongoing, but it is definitely time to break radio silence about LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A bit more heads-down, and then time to tweak LaSalleMart.com, do videos, blog posts, and communicate!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&mdash;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another week and the time will be right to break radio silence.</p>\r\n', 'LaSalleMart 3 will launch later this week. One more week of nose-to-the-grindstone; and, then, launching.', 'LaSalleMart 3 will launch later this week. One more week of nose-to-the-grindstone; and, then, launching.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca//2014/breaking-radio-silence-later-this-month', 'radio1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-04-11', '2014-04-11 12:00:00', 1, '2014-04-11 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(107, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Atlassian Road Show 2014 Toronto', 'atlassian-road-show-2014-toronto', '<p>Toronto is again on the map for this year&rsquo;s Atlassian Road Show, which is up to eight cities worldwide this year. Glad to see Toronto as a hotbed!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Atlassian is the software code-in-the-cloud infrastructure that I use: BitBucket (Git software repositories), JIRA (issue tracking), and Confluence (<a href=\"https://southlasalle.atlassian.net/wiki/display/lasallemart3/LaSalleMart+3+Knowledge+Base+Home\" target=\"_blank\">public facing knowledge base</a>).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have enjoyed the luxury of not creating JIRA issues and linking BitBucket &ldquo;Smart Commits&rdquo; to these JIRA issues while getting the first production release of LaSalleMart 3 done. However, after keeping a tight linkage for LaSalleMart2, I can tell you that it&rsquo;s much better to have the linkage. Even as a one-person shop bootstrapping software, LaSalleMart3&prime;s codebase is growing, and the linkage is beneficial. Having kept the formal issue tracking, and then letting it go, I am surprised how I&rsquo;d have preferred to have stuck with it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ability to produce code is the &ldquo;MoneyBall&rdquo; of e-value, so Atlassian is critical software development infrastructure. LaSalleMart is about to involve more people than just me, so Atlassian is indispensible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2013/atlassian-road-show-2013-in-toronto-first-hand-lessons\" target=\"_blank\">last year&rsquo;s Toronto Road Show</a>, I really didn&rsquo;t know what to expect. This year, I went with a mission: to ask about&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.atlassian.com/software/bamboo\" target=\"_blank\">Bamboo</a>, their continuous development offering. I did enjoy the opportunity to talk about Bamboo. Subsequently, I learned that Amazon Web Services offers free EC2 instances to new accounts, so this is going to help.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014apr22_atlassian2.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014apr22_atlassian2-300x225.jpg\" style=\"float:left; height:225px; margin:0px 10px 10px 0px; width:300px\" /></a>I am on the right track as the keynote presentation focused on their new &ldquo;Git Essentials&rdquo; offering, which combines JIRA, BitBucket, and Bamboo. I had not known of &ldquo;Git Essentials&rdquo; prior.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I attended their Toronto Road Show because it gives me a chance to guage Atlassian as a company, to ask questions, to meet people who work for Atlassian. This year there was a big difference: there was a $16 charge to attend. So those attending were serious about using Atlassian or seriously kicking the tires.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Atlassian is clearly for the corporate market. Atlassian is not cheap beyond the first pricing tier, and clearly it is corporations using Atlassian. But, as said in the keynote, Atlassian is made to scale, and that is clearly what I have in mind for LaSalleMart&rsquo;s development. I would not have spent upwards of two years learning Atlassian by using it if I was not bullish &mdash; I need to know it to scale it to underlie software development growth. Let&rsquo;s be honest, learning Atlassian&rsquo;s been a bit of a PITA, so if there wasn&rsquo;t a tremendous future payoff why would I bother. But there is a tremendous future payoff, and as usual I chased the learning by using it before I really had to.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ll tell you something, if all I had to learn was JIRA right now, then having a long lead-in period to get comfortable with it wouldn&rsquo;t be a problem (and there&rsquo;s a lot I still have to learn, but at least I have the base). But I have an explosion of learning right now that is unbelievable: getting into real continuous development with Bamboo, designing tests that meld well with Bamboo, Laravel, Laravel + WordPress, the new features in the recently released PhpStorm, etc etc etc. The learning gets deeper and deeper! So, having Atlassian under my belt as I do already is big comfort.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If I was worried about Atlassian as a company, that was taken care of pretty quickly. Atlassian is growing. 30,000 customers, 800 employees, opening new offices, and new offerings.<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014apr22_atlassian1.png\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014apr22_atlassian1-300x212.png\" style=\"float:right; height:212px; margin:0px 0px 10px 10px; width:300px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There were local Atlassian partner companies in attendence &mdash; think of &lsquo;em as resellers &mdash; which is good to know &mdash; I may have training needs later this year. Yes, I am bullish! I&rsquo;m sure this fall LaSalleMart breakout as a start-up. Very good to know of the local Atlassian partner companies to reach out to when the time comes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank you, Atlassian, for coming to Toronto.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>PS: I found this Forbes article from 2011 &ndash;<a href=\"http://www.forbes.com/sites/tomtaulli/2011/06/14/atlassian-100m-business-with-no-sales-people/\" target=\"_blank\">Atlassian: $100M+ Business With No Sales People</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>PS:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://fora.tv/2014/06/03/Atlassian_RoadTrip_2014\" target=\"_blank\">Roadtrip 2014 Webinar</a>:</p>\r\n', 'Toronto is again on the map for this year’s Atlassian Road Show, which is up to eight cities worldwide this year. Glad to see Toronto as a hotbed! Atlassian is the software code-in-the-cloud infrastructure that I use: BitBucket (Git software repositories), JIRA (issue tracking), and Confluence (public facing knowledge base)...', 'Toronto is again on the map for this year’s Atlassian Road Show, which is up to eight cities worldwide this year. Glad to see Toronto as a hotbed! Atlassian is the software code-in-the-cloud infrastructure that I use: BitBucket (Git software repositories)', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/atlassian-road-show-2014-toronto', '2014apr22_atlassian3.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-04-23', '2014-04-23 12:00:00', 1, '2014-04-23 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(108, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Akeeba Backup For WordPress is Kick-Ass', 'akeeba-backup-for-wordpress-is-kick-ass', '<p>Akeeba Backup For WordPress is Kick-Ass. My Media and Blog sites are done in WordPress. My first major client as a freelance consultant was in WordPress (whilst cutting my Joomla ecomm teeth with Virtuemart). I&rsquo;ve always kept a hand in WordPress.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I backed up my two WordPress sites with&hellip;. Joomla! I created stub Joomla sites in order to use Akeeba Backup. Well, no more as I now have&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.akeebabackup.com/products/akeeba-backup-wordpress.html\" target=\"_blank\">Akeeba Backup for WordPress</a>(AKWP) installed, configured, and CRON&rsquo;d.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, yesterday I backed up this blogging site with ABWP. I then restored it to this domain &mdash; it&rsquo;s not on &ldquo;blog.southlasallecommerce.com&rdquo; anymore.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Having used Akeeba Backup for years, it was love at first site seeing it in WordPress. It is essentially the Joomla extension living in the WordPress admin. Glorious! I understood everything right away. Excellent placement of the CRON command, before I forget, very handy to copy-paste it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My database-only and full-site-backup profiles work. Uploads to Amazon S3 work. CRON &mdash; well, I messed up my overnight CRONs but I am very sure they will work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The restoration worked as well, although in my particular case I had to do manual stuff beyond the scope of Kickstart/ABWP. What ABWP does do is update the relevant records in the #__options table &mdash; well done!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Amazing that ABWP is considered beta.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After yesterday evening&rsquo;s Joomla User Group Toronto workshop, I told the guys that ABWP was a bit &ldquo;raw&rdquo;, in that some of the language strings still say &ldquo;Joomla&rdquo;. They laughed, but I said that it is a rare glimpse at getting a Joomla extension into WordPress. This, ladies and gentlemen, has had a profound effect on yours truly, who is developing a major Joomla ecommerce technology. Where Joomla intersects WordPress is more overt than it will likely be over time &mdash; which I want to emphasize that in my two days experience with ABWP has no effect on the functionality. It is clear, though, that this is the Joomla extension (that I know and love) in WordPress. It installs exactly like a WordPress plugin. But the folder structure is very unique! And there it is, &ldquo;AWS&rdquo; which is slated for official release this fall. I have to deep dive into the coding of ABWP, but it is brilliant. Brilliant! So now I know that a Joomla extension can live in WordPress &mdash; more precisely: the WordPress admin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bravo, Nicholas!</p>\r\n', 'Akeeba Backup For WordPress is Kick-Ass...', 'Akeeba Backup For WordPress is Kick-Ass...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/akeeba-backup-for-wordpress-is-kick-ass', 'thumbs_up1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-04-24', '2014-04-24 12:00:00', 1, '2014-04-24 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(109, 0, NULL, NULL, 'WordPress — Yes I Do! — Actually, No I Do Not!', 'wordpress-yes-i-do', '<p>As of now, I do WordPress. For my clients; and, coming, for LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve always done WordPress, been doing it for years and years. My media and blog sites are both done with WordPress. My first major ongoing client was a WordPress site. I helped develop a WooCommerce site last fall, including developing a small WordPress plugin for it.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Whoa, just saw this new blog post:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.dionysopoulos.me/the-interesting-effects-of-losing-a-pro-bono-job/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.dionysopoulos.me/the-interesting-effects-of-losing-a-pro-bono-job/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>No more will WordPress remain my &ldquo;Quiet Competency&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>WordPress is now a tool in my professional toolbox.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As well, I will pursue a LaSalleMart-Laravel-WordPress package.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I use the Genesis Framework, which I recommend.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I use a wonderful plugin for iTunes (my podcasts are on iTunes).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I use a wonderful plugin for Facebook.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I tend to customize themes with the user-defined-field a bit too much.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This year I plan on combining blogging/e-broadcasting with e-commerce. Originally, I planned on bringing blogging/e-broadcasting to Joomla-LaSalleMart. I am revising my approach by bringing LaSalleMart to WordPress&rsquo; native blogging/e-commerce strength.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart will not reside within WordPress as a plugin, though, as I see this as a very low value proposition for me and for my clients. Instead, LaSalleMart providing &ldquo;web services&rdquo; to WordPress while housed in an independent PHP framework (Laravel, most likely) opens up enormous opportunities. That I can leave the bulk of the blogging/e-broadcasting to WordPress while pursuing LaSalleMart-Laravel-WordPress is a huge plus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Creating a LaSalleMart as a WordPress plugin is not going to work. There&rsquo;s a reason LaSalleMart exists right now as a Joomla/Framework-on-Framework technology. WordPress&rsquo; codebase is getting long-on-the-tooth. However, I&rsquo;m pretty sure there is a way to get LaSalleMart into the WordPress front-end. Along these same lines, LaSalleMart can reside within Joomla&rsquo;s front-end &mdash; so the opportunities open up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>WordPress: yes I do!</p>\r\n', 'My original plan coming from Joomla was to get into WordPress. Now, yes, I will help you with WordPress. But, as my prime professional specialty, no...', 'My original plan coming from Joomla was to get into WordPress. Now, yes, I will help you with WordPress. But, as my prime professional specialty, no...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/wordpress-yes-i-do', 'wordpress-logo-notext-bg.png', 1, 0, 0, '2014-04-24', '2014-04-24 12:00:00', 1, '2014-04-24 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(110, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Not Mass Marketing LaSalleMart', 'not-mass-marketing-lasallemart', '<p>Although thoughts of thousands of subscribers paying $19.99 per month dance through my head, I am&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;mass marketing LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;selling LaSalleMart to the general public.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;listing LaSalleMart on the Joomla Extensions Directory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why? LaSalleMart and mass marketing are not a good fit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are lots of free and commercial open source ecommerce Joomla extensions and independent PHP projects.&nbsp;This market is well served. Does the marketplace need yet another entrant?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart was not really conceived to serve the mass market anyways. LaSalleMart was conceived to serve my power user clients, consulting clients; and, even to serve as the technological base for my own e-businesses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart does not shield the user from the technicals, by design and without apology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The installation is a PITA because each component must be installed separately. I refuse to package up all the components, plugins and modules because I want the freedom of choice what to install and what not to install.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Joomla&rsquo;s front-end power is exposed by design</em>, for the purpose of designing engaging websites. Web designers, start your engines! Intense customer engagement does not come out of a canned template.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart may not be for the end user, but it is for the power user. And it is definitely made for other consultants. Both groups active in&nbsp;advancing the technology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Besides, I think mass marketing as a Joomla extension is pretty moot now. LaSalleMart will spread its wings beyond Joomla, so it&rsquo;s going to stay &nbsp;nascent for a little while longer to contemplate selling $19.99/month subscriptions to the multitudes. If it ever does.</p>\r\n', 'Although thoughts of thousands of subscribers paying $19.99 per month dance through my head, I am not mass marketing LaSalleMart.', 'Although thoughts of thousands of subscribers paying $19.99 per month dance through my head, I am not mass marketing LaSalleMart.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/not-mass-marketing-lasallemart', 'corn-flakes1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-04-28', '2014-04-28 12:00:00', 1, '2014-04-28 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(111, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart, Web Apps, and the Laravel Framework for PHP', 'lasallemart-web-apps-and-the-laravel-framework-for-php', '<p>My original idea was to create web applications using Joomla CLI (just nod your head and let it pass), for use alongside Joomla-LaSalleMart sites. LaSalleMart is designed so that it is easy to pull the pieces you need into CLI (&ldquo;Comman Line Interface&rdquo; &mdash; sort of an oxymoron&hellip;).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then, when I realized that the Joomla Framework is an actual Joomla Framework akin to other independent PHP frameworks (like Zend, Cake, Symfony), it looked like it would be even easier to whip up adjunct web apps for LaSalleMart sites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What I did not anticipate was an aha moment while I was refactoring (read: re-writing) pieces of LaSalleMart earlier this month. To cut to the chase here, the &ldquo;aha&rdquo; was that the way I was (re)writing LaSalleMart lends itself to re-doing LaSalleMart as &ldquo;web services&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart is comprised of multiple, small, targeted-scope Joomla components&nbsp;<em>that talk to each other</em>. It has been a journey of discovery putting the right functionality into the right component (not always as obvious as it seems). This is the first time I&rsquo;ve programmed Joomla like this &mdash; ah, but it&rsquo;s terrific! When a component needs something from another component, it asks that component for what it needs. Usually data or template.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So the internal LaSalleMart functionality can set the stage for moving LaSalelMart into a &ldquo;web services&rdquo; thing. Where LaSalleMart back-end functions exist in a separate entity &mdash; within an independent PHP framework (Laravel, most likely), which are then called via a URL (like any URL) from Joomla, WordPress, or from something else &mdash; especiall web apps.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla and WordPress do have one thing in common: they are actually two websites in one. There&rsquo;s the public facing &ldquo;front&rdquo;; and, then there is the private &ldquo;admin&rdquo; that is resides in a sub-folder (Joomla = /administrator/; WordPress = /wp-admin/).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The LaSalleMart administrative back-end can realistically reside in a separate software entity completely. The product detail forms, coupon management, order management, etc &mdash; can all exist external to Joomla and WordPress. Front-end views that need a product price, price ranges, quantity restrictions, etc can interrogate the external software via &ldquo;RESTful API&rdquo; for this information.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This means that the bulk of LaSalleMart can exist separate of the &ldquo;front-end&rdquo; software. This opens enormous opportunities. Theoretically, the actual Joomla and WordPress specific front-end programming development is a minimal effort since the bulk of action occurs outside of the front-end. Oh, I talk a brave game, eh! But, the theory is pretty sound; and, I&rsquo;ve spent a lot of Quality Time programming in Joomla-Framework-on-Framework recently &mdash; there is something to the theory. Oh, I&rsquo;ve also taken a good look at my own WordPress Genesis-Framework-based theme, on top of my recent WooCommerce engagement (when I took a Good Look at the WC code), and there is something to the theory with WordPress too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The fall release of a new Akeeba Framework that is slated to work with Joomla and WordPress (if I am understanding it properly) (called &ldquo;AWF&rdquo;) certainly intrigues me &mdash; especially if it can help with front-end work!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The opportunity to create LaSalleMart web apps from this scenario is huge. I see things like whipping up landing page web apps and single product with express checkout web apps.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then we&rsquo;d have Joomla and WordPress and web apps that can be built, theoretically, from varied independent PHP frameworks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wow.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is an independent PHP framework that I will start using:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://laravel.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Laravel</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laravel is a framework focusing on web apps. It seems to lend itself well to web apps. It is in its fourth version, has come out of its initial releases with good overall acceptance and adoption.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I may have to figure out the Joomla-Laravel integration, and the WordPress-Laravel integrations. Welcome to innovation, without which we could not cope with the universe of mobile devices.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is no manual giving step-by-step instructions on how to use Laravel with Joomla and WordPress &mdash; and for something that will use both! Just like using Joomla 3.0 and the Framework on Framework to achieve specific goals meant diving being the one figuring it out, same with this. Intrepid people who want to join me on this journey, and enjoy the profit potential so derived instead, should contact me about joining my little family of clients.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laravel for LaSalleMart using a web services (RESTful API) + native WordPress for e-broadcasting + web apps = YOWZA!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, yes, time to spread our wings!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>P.S. Found this blog post:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://maxoffsky.com/code-blog/top-5-trends-laravels-rise-2014/\" target=\"_blank\">http://maxoffsky.com/code-blog/top-5-trends-laravels-rise-2014</a></p>', 'My original idea was to create web applications using Joomla CLI (just nod your head and let it pass', 'My original idea was to create web applications using Joomla CLI (just nod your head and let it pass), for use alongside Joomla-LaSalleMart sites. LaSalleMart is designed so that it is easy to pull the pieces you need into CLI (“Comman Line Interface” — s', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-web-apps-and-the-laravel-framework-for-php', 'laravel1.png', 1, 0, 0, '2014-04-28', '2014-04-28 12:00:00', 1, '2014-04-28 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(112, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Growing my Technology and Consultancy with the Club Concept', 'growing-consultancy-with-club-concept', '<p>At the height of my Virtuemart era, individual clients came together to sponsor features they wanted. Not only did these clients share costs, but they shared testing and feedback. My clients banding together to bring features to fruition was a fantastic success.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My observation is that it is not usual for the user/client community to band together to create software. Usually, it is developers who band together, with a &ldquo;user community&rdquo; orbiting around the controlling group of developers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yet, in my own experience, my clients banding together to create software was a tremendous success. Custom features were created, no single client paid full price, features created were high ROI features, testing quality rose because motivated individuals actually tested (imagine that!). The outcomes were tremendous.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although I toyed with many ideas, I never really deviated from the idea that LaSalleMart would be developed by my clients banding together.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My clients agree up-front that they are actively involved in LaSalleMart&rsquo;s development, and so we would organize ourselves for that purpose.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My clients would not be passive consumers of LaSalleMart. No!&nbsp;<strong>My clients will be active producers of LaSalleMart ecommerce technology</strong>. And in so doing,&nbsp;<em>will be able to build value in their e-businesses that they would otherwise not have built.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>If technology stood still, if devices customers use did not change, if we were still at the stage where having your own ecomm site was still considered a novelty, then maybe we&rsquo;d not have such an intense need to be in the software creation business. But, that&rsquo;s not the world we live in, and e-businesses that are actively engaged in software creation are going to kick the ass of their competitors who are not so engaged. We need sites that are engaging. We need sites that have high ROI features. And this is Just for starters.j</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Software creation is enormously expensive. It sure would be nice if I could create software per client on an a la carte basis. But, the clients that I serve are not in this position. Even monied clients balk at paying for a la carte software.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My clients banding together is a terrific response to the software creation barriers.&nbsp;<em>By sharing costs of software that return high ROI, we create an eco-system for ourselves where we are progressively able to devote more dollars into further high ROI software</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My professional consultancy is itself an innovative response to do something for my clients that is simply not available in the traditional open source projects (free and commercial) they&rsquo;ve been participating in. We create our own eco-system, instead of latching on to someone else&rsquo;s eco-system that is really designed to take money from end-users who buy software.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your business opportunity is not with consuming software. You consuming someone elses&rsquo; software is just that someone elses&rsquo; business opportunity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yeah, you remember Citizen Kane. In the movie, John Foster Kane never invested in anything. He just bought things (scroll to 1min 50seconds if the video is not jumping to that time):<br />\r\n<iframe allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/WTmVlDh2V2g?t=1m50s&amp;rel=0\" width=\"420\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, are you just buying other peoples&rsquo; technology? Shouldn&rsquo;t you be investing in your own?</p>', 'At the height of my Virtuemart era, individual clients came together to sponsor features they wanted', 'At the height of my Virtuemart era, individual clients came together to sponsor features they wanted. Not only did these clients share costs, but they shared testing and feedback. My clients banding together to bring features to fruition was a fantastic s', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/growing-consultancy-with-club-concept', 'groucho_marx1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-04-28', '2014-04-28 12:00:00', 1, '2014-04-28 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(113, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Joomla’s New Versioning', 'joomlas-new-versioning', '<p>Joomla posted the new versioning&nbsp;<a href=\"http://developer.joomla.org/news/586-joomla-development-strategy.html\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://developer.joomla.org/news/587-faq-s-for-joomla-s-improved-release-cycle.html\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This new versioning applies to the Joomla CMS,&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;to the Joomla Framework &mdash; in case you were wondering!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since the FAQ mentions WordPress, it&rsquo;s fair for me to post the WordPress&nbsp;<a href=\"http://wordpress.org/about/roadmap/\" target=\"_blank\">Roadmap</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which one is easier to understand? Which one is easier on the eyes?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One thing I do know: Joomla changed its versioning&nbsp;<em>again</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla 3.5 was supposed to be&nbsp;<em>THE</em>&nbsp;Joomla 3.x version. Version 3.0, 3.2, 3.3, and 3.4 were &ldquo;training wheel&rdquo; versions to get the kinks out and do whatever under-the-hood stuff that was to be done. What mattererd was that 3.0, 3.1, 3.2, 3.3, and 3.4 were all pointing to a terminus called &ldquo;3.5&Prime;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla 3.5 was going to be s-t-a-b-l-e, with all the wonderful-ness that that entailed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, it has changed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I fully understand that all series 3.x Joomla versions will be backwards-compatible, so upgrading will not (should not?) be an issue. Except that v3.3 requires PHP 5.3.10 (if memory serves), which should not provide barriers for my LaSalleMart clients.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You know worries me? That this versioning system will be changed&nbsp;<em>again</em>, and in so doing will negatively impact LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You know what worries me? That there&rsquo;s an effort to replace the Joomla Platform with elements of the Joomla Framework; and, that ipso facto will violate backwards compatibility.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You know what worries me? That the superb Akeeba Framework on Framework is designed to work with the Joomla Platform, not the Joomla Framework, so it will not necessarily intermediate Joomla changes. So introducing elements of the Joomla Framework in future Joomla 3.x versions could really eff up LaSalleMart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I just want to direct your attention to&nbsp;the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/joomla-dev-cms/9A57dQ8pA_k\" target=\"_blank\">Google Group thread</a>&nbsp;entitled &ldquo;According to new Development Strategy, are we dropping simple upgrades from 3.x to 4.0 ? (aka migration again?)&rdquo;. There are a number of extension developers communicating things&nbsp;<a href=\"https://groups.google.com/d/msg/joomla-dev-cms/9A57dQ8pA_k/dGhJrER7r-cJ\" target=\"_blank\">like</a>:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>I&rsquo;d add to Beat&rsquo;s post that smooth upgrades between versions &ndash; even major versions &ndash; is essential to retaining people using Joomla. I have a number of people who just still refuse to upgrade from J1.5 because of the level of effort and the number of things that break. For those that went through the effort of 1.5 to 2.5, they did so on the promise that 3.5 would offer a smooth upgrade (NOT migration) from 2.5. With the 3.4 release strategy announcement, does anyone in this group know if that changes whether 3.5 will provide a smooth upgrade from 2.5 or not?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a large community of, perhaps silent, Joomla users who care more about stability and smooth migration paths than any amount of new features. They are you [sic] non-technical Joomla users who really just want a stable web site for their content (whether business, nonprofit, hobby, personal interest, blog or whatever).</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>I very much agree with this one. &nbsp;I&rsquo;ve been following this thread, and a few others, and my sense of insecurity goes up. Really wish this was an open and shut case with dead-balls simple declarative statements like &ldquo;Joomla 3.x series core updates will never break&rdquo;. Oh well, whatever. I thought Joomla was on a terrific track with Joomla 3.5 &ldquo;LTS&rdquo;. Now&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is a recent article:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://pbwebdev.com/blog/wordpress-trends-vs-joomla-trends\" target=\"_blank\">WordPress Trends vs Joomla Trends</a>.&nbsp;The comments are very very good.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, I can control what I am going to do, so here&rsquo;s my game plan:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The current Joomla version is 3.2. LaSalleMart works on 3.2 &mdash; it should, as the bulk of the programming is done on 3.2.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For the time being, Joomla 3.2 is, for my purposes, is the &ldquo;real&rdquo; Joomla version.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla 3.3 just came out (April 30, 2014).&nbsp; Once I complete LaSalleMart&rsquo;s first production release, I will then test it on Joomla 3.3. If it works; and, if Joomla 3.3 is accepted by the community (as opposed to having post-release caveats/issues), then for my purposes it will be the &ldquo;real&rdquo; Joomla version. I will post when this happens.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When Joomla 3.4 comes out, I will approach it with the same attitude. Based on the promise (premise?) that backwards compatibility is preserved, I expect that no issues will stand in the way as my considering it the &ldquo;real&rdquo; Joomla version.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is no indication that FOF, which is&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;included with Joomla starting with v3.3, will have issues that prevent upgrading. But, FOF may not intermediate Joomla changes that come from the Joomla Framework. There&rsquo;s been a clear statement on this (I&rsquo;m not hunting for it, it&rsquo;s already the wrong side of midnight). It would be ironic if we had to use Akeeba Solo to back up our Joomla 3.x sites!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, if it turns out that a Joomla 3.x series is not working for us, then we&rsquo;ll adopt that version of Joomla as our own and support it on our own if need be. This is an advantage of operating my professional consultancy as a Software Development Club. We&rsquo;ll cope. I already have ideas how to handle supporting Joomla solo (helps that I&rsquo;ve experimented with doing my own Joomla distributions).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which means that Joomla-LaSalleMart sites will be supported for years regardless of the zigs and zags of the Joomla 3 series from this point on.</p>', 'Joomla posted the new versioninghereandhere.\r\n\r\nThis new versioning applies to the Joomla CMS,notto', 'This blog post represents the desire *not* to dump months and months of intensely intense work on building a from-scratch innovative ecommerce technology. But, at some point the insanity of building superb software that obsoletes has to end -- I am not ge', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/joomlas-new-versioning', 'version1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-04-29', '2014-04-29 12:00:00', 1, '2014-04-29 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(114, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Reseller Concept', 'reseller-concept', '<p>A reseller is typically a local company that provides value-added services for a technology provider. Does not really have to be a technology provider, but it sure fits with LaSalleMart!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The technology provider provides training and support to the reseller, ensuring that the reseller has all that they need to service their customers. The technology provider does not directly contact the reseller&rsquo;s customers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In exchange, the reseller typically contracts to buy a certain minimum amount from the technology provider &mdash; making it worth the provider&rsquo;s while to invest in the reseller. The reseller than goes out and sells to a certain geographic area.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this arrangement, the reseller gets a direct connection to the technology. If something goes wrong, the technology provider fixes it. If there&rsquo;s a new feature idea &ldquo;from the field&rdquo;, the reseller has a direct line to get that into the pipeline. When there are questions about programming add-ons, the reseller has support people to contact. The end-customers are assured that the reseller is connected to the technology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I estimate that 75% of my clients will be other consulting professionals; and, that 25% will be end-user customers. I want my consulting professional clients to be &ldquo;dialed in&rdquo; to LaSalleMart; to have their questions answered; to enjoy ongoing training and support. I want end-user customers to be assured that the LaSalleMart eco-system is abundant with high level professionals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>LaSalleMart ecommerce technology will&nbsp; thrive because of the outstanding professionals who install, train , and develop it</strong>. And this success comes from the<em>&nbsp;reseller-like approach we take with LaSalleMart, using a Club concept</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>BTW: there will not be any contractual minimum purchasing agreements. Ha! My clients pay the &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2014/why-the-vig\" target=\"_blank\">vig</a>&rdquo; and download to their hearts content.</p>\r\n', 'A reseller is typically a local company that provides value-added services for a technology provider. Does not really have to be a technology provider, but it sure fits with LaSalleMart!', 'A reseller is typically a local company that provides value-added services for a technology provider. Does not really have to be a technology provider, but it sure fits with LaSalleMart!', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/reseller-concept', 'worldwide-resellers1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-04-29', '2014-04-29 12:00:00', 1, '2014-04-29 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(115, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Encapsulating E-Asset Value', 'encapsulating-e-asset-value', '<p>I want my clients to build asset value, not just build revenues.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Set your site up so you can sell it. Whatever you sell it for is &ldquo;asset value&rdquo; &mdash; well, that&rsquo;s the way I see it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Canada, if you set up your site as a &ldquo;Canadian Controlled Private Corporation&rdquo;; and, your first $750,000 in small business capital gains are exempt. Here&rsquo;s an&nbsp;<a href=\"http://business.financialpost.com/2013/10/16/plan-to-take-full-advantage-of-business-owners-capital-gains-exemption/\" target=\"_blank\">article from the National Pos</a>t.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, yes, you have to set your site up as a corporation &mdash; of course, I urge you to consult your legal and accounting professionals. But, as well, you have to set up your site itself in a way that you can sell it to someone else.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the years I&rsquo;ve actually had arguments with people about setting up their sites so they can sell it. Arguing with my what is completely in their best interests.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, I refuse to &ldquo;take care&rdquo; of your domain on your behalf. Really! My having any control over your domain is &mdash; well, I consider it a huge conflict of interest.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will help with DNS settings for only my most trusted clients, followed by a suggestion to change their password.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Clients who value convenience over learning to use the GoDaddy domain management system make me nervous, if you want to know the truth.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&mdash;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you do not iron-balls control over your &ldquo;DNS&rdquo; &mdash;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://support.godaddy.com/help/article/1497/domain-name-faq\" target=\"_blank\">domain name server&nbsp;</a>&ndash; you are setting yourself up to be effed up over royally.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Never ever settle for the &ldquo;convenience&rdquo; of having someone else &ldquo;do&rdquo; your DNS. Ever.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You give me control over your DNS, you give me your site. You become my vassal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not only can I control where your site is hosted, I can put my name in as the &ldquo;address&rdquo; of the site. That makes me the effective owner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You cannot encapsulate value of something that you do not own. So never ever delegate domain management to anyone. This is a do-it-yourself thing, end of story, period, discussion over.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Frankly, anyone refusing to do so is not really a client I really want anyways. At some point, I&rsquo;m going to be blamed for things I never do &mdash; BTDT &mdash; and eff that crap, baby.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you want to build asset value, then you do it right. You own the domain. You separate the domain from hosting &mdash; never combine the two (belt and suspenders approach). You consider the tax impact of different forms of ownership. Your address is in all the domain address listings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You can&rsquo;t sell what you can&rsquo;t control.</p>\r\n', 'I want my clients to build asset value, not just build revenues. Set your site up so you can sell it. Whatever you sell it for is “asset value” — well, that’s the way I see it. In Canada, if you set up your site as a “Canadian Controlled Private Corporation”; and, your first $750,000 in small business capital gains are exempt...', 'I want my clients to build asset value, not just build revenues. Set your site up so you can sell it. Whatever you sell it for is “asset value” — well, that’s the way I see it. In Canada, if you set up your site as a “Canadian Controlled Private Corporati', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/encapsulating-e-asset-value', 'timber-investment-increasing-asset-value1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-04-29', '2014-04-29 12:00:00', 1, '2014-04-29 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(116, 0, NULL, NULL, 'E-Value Equals Ability to Create Software', 'e-value-equals-ability-to-create-software', '<p>Here I go harping on this again. But, as I re-ignite my consulting, I want to be clear about my philosophy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Did you see the MoneyBall movie? &ldquo;MoneyBall&rdquo; refers to, the way I see it, identifying where value really comes from (yeah, the audio sucks):</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/qd1aZb4ORmw?rel=0\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Value, to me, is monthly revenue; and, year-end asset value.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What underlies e-business value?&nbsp;<strong>Ultimately, it is the ability to create software.</strong>&nbsp;It is&nbsp;<em>not the software itself</em>, which has a best-before date. It the ability to create software.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>I want to deliver this ability to my clients</em>. To achieve it, I want my clients to band together.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Who is Favio?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/GF3GZwo0vGc?rel=0\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Here I go harping on this again. But, as I re-ignite my consulting, I want to be clear about my philosophy.\r\nDid you see the MoneyBall movie...', 'Here I go harping on this again. But, as I re-ignite my consulting, I want to be clear about my philosophy.\r\nDid you see the MoneyBall movie...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/e-value-equals-ability-to-create-software', 'moneyball1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-04-29', '2014-04-29 12:00:00', 1, '2014-04-29 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(117, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Software Creation is Power', 'software-creation-is-power', '<p>LaSalleMart 3.0 is Joomla ecommerce technology that I am developing from-scratch.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the first time I&rsquo;ve ever developed ecomm software. Such a different feel from customizing other peoples&rsquo; software!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am used to &ldquo;nibbling at the edges&rdquo; of other peoples&rsquo; software, because usually I am trying&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;to modify their core codebase, lest my changes be over-written when next updated. If I do modify core code, I am mindful to merge my changes with the next core update.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One thing I am very used to is waiting for other people to update their software. With promised features. With fixes. And waiting and waiting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 3.0 represents a culture shock of sorts. If I wanted to do something, or not do something, then that was up to me. There was no forum, no support ticket, no one to email. It was weird! No more asking permission!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I wanted to use foreign key constraints in my MySQL CREATE statements, and I did. What an incredible learning experience, by the way. I thought I would ease my burden by using a GUI database tool. They stunk, so I hand crafted LaSalleMart&rsquo;s entire database &mdash; about 40 tables so far.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I wanted to achieve a lot of things, and &mdash; many times to my surprise &mdash; achieved them. In so doing, I innovated. And am glad I did because I set the stage to bring<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2014/lasallemart-web-apps-and-the-laravel-framework-for-php\" target=\"_blank\">&nbsp;LaSalleMart to the Laravel Framework</a>&nbsp;&mdash; in part to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2014/wordpress-yes-i-do\" target=\"_blank\">bring LaSalleMart to WordPress</a>&nbsp;(gonna be different than WooCommerce, I guar-an-tee that). Something that I was not contemplating when I started LaSalleMart 3.0, but am very much contemplating it now!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At some point in building the pieces of LaSalleMart I started to feel powerful. It&rsquo;s a feeling that I&rsquo;ve not experienced before, because I&rsquo;ve never built something like LaSalleMart before. It&rsquo;s a great feeling!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I decided I wanted to add a few extra features now to coupons. So I did. The core code base is mine, so changing whatever in the core needed changing to accomodate my features I just changed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My clients will get a sense of this power. It may take time, but I know the moment will happen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s the power of YES.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>New features becomes an expression of will and resources. No &ldquo;feature voting&rdquo;. No &ldquo;feature request forms&rdquo;. No waiting for Godot for promised features. We are in control. There is no &ldquo;them&rdquo;, just &ldquo;we&rdquo; &mdash; remember the Club!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I am asked &ldquo;can LaSalleMart do X&rdquo;, I always reply: &ldquo;We can do anything we want&rdquo;. &nbsp;We do not need to ask permission, we can just Make It Happen. That&rsquo;s the power of YES. That&rsquo;s the power of creating your own software.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You wonder if I had those middle-of-the-night moments where I questioned why I was programming ecomm software from scratch when there&rsquo;s Magento, PrestaCart, and tons of other PHP based ecommerce software. Bet your ass I did! All the time. But, as LaSalleMart started to take shape, and take shape in the way I wanted it to, these moments abated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sure, it seems idiotic to recreate features that exist in mature feature-rich offerings. But, I got LaSalleMart to a certain point, and it did not look so idiotic anymore. &nbsp;LaSalleMart is real, and offers a tremendous strategic advantage. For you, and for me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We will design features that are not designed for the mass market, but are designed for our specific needs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You know what I think? I think doing tradition ecommerce sites is sometimes the wrong response to today&rsquo;s mobile devices.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You know what I think? I think that it&rsquo;s practically criminal how people squander the strategic advantages of websites when they do their ecommerce sites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With our own software, with our ability to create our own software, we can explore responses that we&rsquo;d otherwise not contemplate. Technological responses to business opportunities. And do it ahead of everyone else, on our own.</p>\r\n', 'At some point in building the pieces of LaSalleMart I started to feel powerful. It’s a feeling that I’ve not experienced before, because I’ve never built something like LaSalleMart before. It’s a great feeling!', 'At some point in building the pieces of LaSalleMart I started to feel powerful. It’s a feeling that I’ve not experienced before, because I’ve never built something like LaSalleMart before. It’s a great feeling!', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/software-creation-is-power', 'weight_lifting_arnold1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-04-30', '2014-04-30 12:00:00', 1, '2014-04-30 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(118, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Why The Vig?', 'why-the-vig', '<p>The&nbsp;<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vigorish\" target=\"_blank\">vigorish</a>, or &ldquo;vig&rdquo;:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Vigorish, or simply the vig, also known as juice, the cut or the take, is the amount charged by a bookmaker, or bookie, for taking a bet from a gambler&hellip;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>I am referring to a charge outside usual invoicing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Regardless of the ebbs and flows of invoicing, regardless of the extent to which invoicing is earmarked to sub-contractors, a modest monthly amount is charged that is not attributable to any direct client work. Each client &mdash; and clients of clients perhaps &mdash; pay a &ldquo;vig&rdquo; for participating in active LaSalleMart software development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve concluded that to deliver the lowest cost software creation eco-system to my clients I need to charge a base monthly amount to my clients. And perhaps not just to my clients, but to my clients&rsquo; clients who are part of our eco-system.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>pay for common software infrastructure &mdash; it ain&rsquo;t cheap!</li>\r\n	<li>ensure that everyone is paying the lowest amount;</li>\r\n	<li>equality: regardless of invoices, there are not clients who are shouldering this burden more than other clients who are equally benefitting;</li>\r\n	<li>pay for get-togethers, starting in the GTA. Perhaps quarterly &ldquo;LaSalleCONs&rdquo;. And pay for video-ing the sessions;</li>\r\n	<li>pay other developers for common features all my clients use &mdash; and for some R&amp;D that no client may want to shoulder.</li>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;vig&rdquo; is $36.00CDN/month (almost forgot to mention);</li>\r\n	<li>minimal barrier to entry into Club &mdash; you know everyone else on the inside is paying.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Vigorish, or simply the vig, also known as juice, the cut or the take, is the amount charged by a bookmaker, or bookie, for taking a bet from a gambler…', 'Vigorish, or simply the vig, also known as juice, the cut or the take, is the amount charged by a bookmaker, or bookie, for taking a bet from a gambler…', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/why-the-vig', 'cost-risk-benefit-dice1.png', 1, 0, 0, '2014-05-01', '2014-05-01 12:00:00', 1, '2014-05-01 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(119, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart 3.0 Status', 'lasallemart-3-0-status-may-first-2014', '<p>LaSalleMart 3.0 is built from scratch with the Joomla 3 series and with the superb Akeeba Framework on Framework.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The initial production release is close. Instead of waiting to re-write code until after the first production release, I took the time to get it done last month. LaSalleMart is comprised of small targeted-scope components that talk to each other, the first time I&rsquo;ve ever authored such components in Joomla. It took a few rounds of code re-writes to settle into this wonderful way to approach Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Products are done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The integration of Joomla native articles with LaSalleMart products is done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Coupons is done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The cart is done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Knowledge Base is up-to-date.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The admin is set-up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All the things are in place except the checkout.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The registration and address management is not done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shipping is not done &mdash; only a basic manual shipping is planned for the first production release.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Payments are not done &mdash; only a basic manual payment is planned for the first production release.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Order processing is not done. The cart&rsquo;s database tables are nearly identical to the order tables, by design, so there is a big head start there.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Getting this stuff done in a few weeks is do-able. But I would be remiss if I neglected to let you know that I have&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2014/lasallemart-web-apps-and-the-laravel-framework-for-php\" target=\"_blank\">Laravel</a>&nbsp;on my mind. I am toying with trying&nbsp;my basic manual shipping method in Laravel right away. I am not really interested in the shipping method being in Laravel! I am interested in taking what is a relatively &ldquo;easy&rdquo; LaSalleMart function as the excuse to dive into setting up Laravel for RESTful API that LaSalleMart-Joomla can use. This and authentication. Which means &mdash; get this&hellip;. that there is a possibility that a little piece of LaSalleMart 3.0&prime;s first production release will not be in Joomla. We&rsquo;ll see&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will be posting updates here later this month.</p>\r\n', 'Instead of waiting to re-write code until after the first production release, I took the time to get it done last month. LaSalleMart is comprised of small targeted-scope components that talk to each other, the first time I’ve ever authored such components in Joomla. It took a few rounds of code re-writes to settle into this wonderful way to approach Joomla...', 'Instead of waiting to re-write code until after the first production release, I took the time to get it done last month. LaSalleMart is comprised of small targeted-scope components that talk to each other, the first time I’ve ever authored such components', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-3-0-status-may-first-2014', 'boeing_787_factory1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-05-04', '2014-05-04 12:00:00', 1, '2014-05-04 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(120, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Big Opportunities in eCommerce Right Now', 'big-opportunities-in-ecommerce-right-now', '<p>A powerful aspect of creating our own ecommerce software is busting out of the idea of just &ldquo;building websites&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead, my clients and I can think in terms of &ldquo;doing start-ups&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This infographic is absolutely terrific (click to enlarge, or see its original at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://blog.referralcandy.com/2014/05/01/the-biggest-opportunities-in-ecommerce-right-now-as-revealed-by-retail-experts-infographic\" target=\"_blank\">http://blog.referralcandy.com/2014/05/01/the-biggest-opportunities-in-ecommerce-right-now-as-revealed-by-retail-experts-infographic</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Conversion rate optimization, number three, is something I harp on. The infographic is correct: most retailers focus on traffic generation, not conversion. To finally have our own technology instead of wrestling with off-the-shelf software that is sooo difficult to modify &mdash; yeah, go ahead, modify the checkout process to your custom workflow! Since when was I able to modify checkout without invading the core codebase of other peoples&rsquo; software? Like, never! Checkout tends to be an intimate aspect of the code &mdash; break something, and that&rsquo;s it, the checkout halts and the entire ecomm software is useless. Or, yeah, there&rsquo;s a plugin event, so just write a plugin. Why, just go about writing a new piece of software off the core, but relates to the core &mdash; sure&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Number five, improving customer experience, is so important. I term it as &ldquo;intense customer engagement in an attention deficit world&rdquo;. The device itself is critical to the experience &mdash; research shows that people research on smart phones but buy on tablets. Although I think this will change with the ascension of mobile payments. Melding shopping behaviour to device is something we can model in our software &mdash; instead of taking generic off-the-shelf software that resides in traditional websites. It is time to get into web apps &mdash; a whole different ball of wax.</p>\r\n', 'A powerful aspect of creating our own ecommerce software is busting out of the idea of just “building websites”...', 'A powerful aspect of creating our own ecommerce software is busting out of the idea of just “building websites”...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/big-opportunities-in-ecommerce-right-now', 'biggest-opportunities-ecommerce-right-now-retail-experts-infographic.png', 1, 0, 0, '2014-05-05', '2014-05-05 12:00:00', 1, '2014-05-05 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(121, 0, NULL, NULL, 'ANNOUNCEMENT: SWITCHING FROM JOOMLA TO LARAVEL & WORDPRESS', 'moving-to-laravel-wordpress', '<p>To abandon the huge investment in LaSalleMart-Joomla, something major must have happened.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Actually, one major shock happened, with a number of affirmative follow-up events.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>To be explicit, I am abandoning Joomla; and, I am moving to WordPress and to the Laravel PHP Framework.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ah, I am&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;merely switching to WordPress. I am doing something I&rsquo;ve not done before: I am specializing in a PHP framework:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://southlasalle.atlassian.net/wiki/display/technicalnotes/Laravel\" target=\"_blank\">Laravel</a>. Why? To do web applications. General purpose sites are, in many situations, giving way to functionally specific web application sites. The web apps I do will be based on the Laravel framework.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>About a month ago, Joomla announced that is will abandon the explicitly termed Joomla 3.5 &ldquo;Long Term&rdquo; version. In its place, it announced&hellip; nothing. The version policy to replace it was not announced simultaneous to the &ldquo;Long Term&rdquo; abandonment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That non-announcement shook me up viscerally. As I said in my latest&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasallemedia.com/2014/lasallemart29\" target=\"_blank\">podcast</a>,</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>Every major Joomla version has obsoleted the Joomla ecommerce extension I specialized in</em>, which has had, shall we say, a negative impact on my growing professional consultancy. The Joomla 3.5 &ldquo;Long Term Version&rdquo; that is upcoming is a critical assurance to me that my family&rsquo;s&nbsp;<em>huge investment in developing LaSalleMart will produce ROI</em>.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 3.0 was built from the ground up, from scratch, with Joomla 3.2 and the superb Akeeba Framework for Joomla. Successfully bringing to fruition the vision of modern Joomla ecommerce, LaSalleMart 3.0 was a labour of months and month and months of tender loving programming. Mere weeks away from its first production release, LaSalleMart 3.0 represents the culmination of a three year journey.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 3.0 represents my confidence, and my commitment, to Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla was moving beautifully towards its version 3.5 &ldquo;Long Term&rdquo; version. Each version 3 release was a concrete step towards the &ldquo;Long Term&rdquo; terminus that LaSalleMart 3.0 would base itself on for two years &mdash; actually, my timeframe was three years although officially the &ldquo;Long Term&rdquo; version would be officially supported for two years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The superb Akeeba Framework on Framework was included with Joomla, in Joomla 3.2. further solidifying what was to be a very solid &ldquo;Long Term&rdquo; Joomla 3.5. Although FOF&rsquo;s donation to Joomla has now ceased.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Abandoning the &ldquo;Long Term&rdquo; Joomla 3.5 brought fear, but not enunciating what would take its place produced a deep visceral reaction from which I never recovered. I did not know it at the time, but that was it for me with Joomla.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Seven years I&rsquo;ve been working with Joomla. Five years involved with the Toronto Joomla Group. Two odd years on its Steering Committee. A podcast mostly devoted to Joomla that won an Honourable Mention at a Joomla conference. A monthly podcast devoted to my Joomla projects. A huge investment in modern Joomla ecommerce. So, yeah, it&rsquo;s a major thing that I am switching technologies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not having a replacement versioning policy shook my confidence to the core. The replacement policy that was published about two weeks later was dense with text and poorly formatted &mdash; really, you think clients are going to wade through that?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have read a lot of threads on different sites about the new versioning policy. None have produced any illumination, nor contributed to restoring my confidence. The repeated claims that the Joomla versioning policy is just like WordPress&rsquo; version policy is bullshit. WordPress&rsquo; latest version is THE version, end of story. Joomla has three ongoing versions:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/w3techs_2014may15_joomla_usage_stats_mkt_share.png\"><img alt=\"W3Techs.com Usage statistics and market share of Joomla for websites\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/w3techs_2014may15_joomla_usage_stats_mkt_share.png\" style=\"height:392px; margin:0px auto 10px; width:547px\" /></a></p>', 'To be explicit, I am abandoning Joomla; and, I am moving to WordPress and to the Laravel PHP Framewo', 'To be explicit, I am abandoning Joomla; and, I am moving to WordPress and to the Laravel PHP Framework [subsequently: WordPress only upon request]', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/moving-to-laravel-wordpress', 'change1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-05-19', '2014-05-19 12:00:00', 1, '2014-05-19 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL);
