(122, 0, NULL, NULL, '2014 May 22 Laravel Toronto Workshop', '2014-may-22-laravel-toronto-workshop', '<p>Thank you to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://soapboxhq.com/\" target=\"_blank\">SoapBoxHQ</a>&nbsp;at Queen@Spadina for opening their fabulous office space to the Toronto Laravel community; and, for leading LaravelTO.&nbsp;A thank you to<a href=\"http://vehikl.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Vehikl</a>&nbsp;as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is their fifth meetup since November/December 2013, and my first. Twenty-ish were on hand this evening for shmooze, and three really good presentations. If you are kicking Laravel&rsquo;s tires; or, getting deep into Laravel like me and many others there tonight,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.meetup.com/Laravel-Toronto/\" target=\"_blank\">get yourself down next time</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first presentation was a review of last week&rsquo;s Laracon 2014 in NYC.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The second presentation was a look at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.fabfile.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Fabric!</a>, a tool for deployment (based on Python, not PHP). Really appreciate seeing the code in action!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The third presentation was a look at a database factory for testing at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/vehikl/faktory\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/vehikl/faktory</a>. The side discussion about mocks and Mockery was very interesting, as was the focus on database tables with UNIQUE and FOREIGN KEY constraints &mdash; something I spent some time on with LaSalleMart 3.0.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There was plenty of time for chit-chat, the people were very warm and informal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tonight confirms to me that Laravel has hit an inflection point in its growth. I am all-in with Laravel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No one asked how to do a &ldquo;website&rdquo; this evening. The talk was of &ldquo;apps&rdquo; and &ldquo;start-ups&rdquo;. The discussions were deeply technical, in a way I&rsquo;ve not experienced, but enjoyed greatly, in this my third Toronto meet-up group of the 2013-&rsquo;14 season.<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014may22_laravelto_1.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014may22_laravelto_1-225x300.jpg\" style=\"float:right; height:300px; margin:0px 0px 10px 10px; width:225px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is those who think of their e-businesses as start-ups; and, as e-businesses; and, not just &ldquo;I want to do an ecommerce website&rdquo; whom I want to help. There are good reasons to integrate some touch-points of WordPress with LaSalleMart-Laravel, but there are exceptional opportunities beyond the CMS sphere that Laravel can access.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, it&rsquo;s been a month of second thoughts, of second guessing, of learning modern PHP app building. This evening brought a certain closure to my decision to move on, and renewed motivation to continue intensive learning.</p>\r\n', 'Thank you to SoapBoxHQ at Queen@Spadina for opening their fabulous office space to the Toronto Laravel community; and, for leading LaravelTO. A thank you to Vehikl as well...', 'Thank you to SoapBoxHQ at Queen@Spadina for opening their fabulous office space to the Toronto Laravel community; and, for leading LaravelTO. A thank you to Vehikl as well...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/2014-may-22-laravel-toronto-workshop', '2014may22_laravelto_2.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-05-23', '2014-05-23 12:00:00', 1, '2014-05-23 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(123, 0, NULL, NULL, 'App Economics Changing: More E-Biz Power To You, Brother!', 'app-economics-changing-more-e-biz-power-to-you-brother', '<p>There&rsquo;s a difference, I am realizing, between programming ecommerce in a content management system, and programming ecommerce as a web application. A huge difference.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The web application is more powerful. It&rsquo;s not even close.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sure, I could do this and that in Joomla &mdash; but, and I&rsquo;ve made this abundantly clear over the last year especially with LaSalleMart 3.0 development, without the superb Akeeba Framework on Framework programming &ldquo;this and that&rdquo; in Joomla is much less attractive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sure, there are some amazing plugins for WordPress that extend WordPress quite a bit. But, look, ask around about WordPress&rsquo; codebase.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The times are a-changing, and the economics are a-changing too. What once seemed like the purview of the start-up is going to be more accessible to the less funded. Web application framework is changing things.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Drupal is drastically changing itself.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://symfony.com/blog/symfony2-meets-drupal-8\" target=\"_blank\">http://symfony.com/blog/symfony2-meets-drupal-8</a>. Perhaps a meld of CMS and app. A form of Creative Destruction perhaps?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Laravel Framework also has a Symfony base. Laravel was born for web application development, and has hit an inflection point, of which I am a part. And you should be a part of it as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I had a frustrating moment with Laravel when I put my contact page together. For my LaSalleMart.com site, I deleted my Joomla site. I put together a site with Laravel, in part for a real learning experience with Laravel. I was really pissed off at Laravel, because email does not &ldquo;just work&rdquo;. Why, we have to set up the actual email function. Stupid me, I kept thinking I was using Joomla. Just fire up the contact component and that&rsquo;s it. Well, there is no contact component. And there is no email thingee either. So, I set up my contact form, and the email never happened. First was anger, because if Joomla has email &ldquo;just work&rdquo;, then why can&rsquo;t Laravel do such a basic thing? Then, was intense frustration at figuring out the email!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My intense frustration at Laravel&rsquo;s lack of email functionality was the demarcation line of moving from CMS to apps. Web applications are not the same thing. I persisted and figured out how to actually send an email with Laravel. Why, gee, the best way to send an email in Laravel is to use a transactional email service. There are two that come out-of-the-Laravel-box, of which one I am familiar. Oh, how familiar? You want to know the power of blogging? Why, I have a blog post from a year ago on this web service:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/2013/new-mandrill-library-for-lasallemart\" target=\"_blank\">New Mandrill Library for LaSallemart</a>. I already have a Mandrill account set up doing absolutely nothing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mandrill signed up its 250,000th user this month. MailChimp, which owns Mandrill, has 6,000,000 users.&nbsp;The thing a</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>You might think most of those 250,000 users come from MailChimp&rsquo;s 6 million users. We thought the same thing! When Mandrill started, we expected a lot of crossover. Turns out the audiences are completely different, and we had to re-think our entire approach. Mandrill&rsquo;s a team that likes challenges though: this one just meant Mandrill had to earn these users on our own.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>(from&nbsp;<a href=\"http://blog.mandrill.com/250000.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://blog.mandrill.com/250000.html</a>).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, I got Mandrill to work. I found where to put the Mandrill API, set my email hosting keys with HostGator (this is how I knew I was setting up &ldquo;real&rdquo; email!), and my contact form sent email. And I thought, the power, the magnificent power! Never in my wildest dreams did I contemplate building a MailChimp type app in Joomla. You don&rsquo;t build apps in Joomla! You need serious firepower for such a thing. Even with the superb Akeeba Framework for Joomla, forget it. But, if not build a MailChimp type app that uses Mandrill (hows that for irony, but Mandrill is built upon MailChimp&rsquo;s email &ldquo;engine&rdquo;, at least originally), then build INTEGRATED WORKFLOW that includes transactional email (I am already mulling SMS too).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With this type of blog post, I&rsquo;d normally want to enumerate the reasons why apps are so inherently powerful than the CMS. Well, I really don&rsquo;t want to this post. Maybe another time&hellip; it&rsquo;s enough to know that I&rsquo;m spanning new vistas and realizing why the start-up community talks of &ldquo;frameworks&rdquo; and &ldquo;apps&rdquo; instead of &ldquo;content systems&rdquo; and &ldquo;websites&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At this point, my own personal experience is enjoying the nakedness of Laravel. No menu system, no theming, no article handling, no permissions scheme, no administration. Laravel is not a ready made website, where you add-on your own stuff after-the-fact. Laravel is a set of tools with which to make whatever the heck you want.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, what is the website? Whatever you make IS the site. There is nothing else there!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s not a case where you just decide you are not going to use the menus. There are no menus with which to ignore!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which at first is scary. Which did not last long! Now that I am faced with a blank slate, I feel liberated from the awful bloat that has become template frameworks, component creep, etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laravel has&nbsp;queuing. I&rsquo;ve not done it yet, but the significance is that thousands of processes can be done in the background so the site stays fast. If you want tens of thousands of customers on your site &mdash; or millions! &mdash; then you&rsquo;ll want queuing. Laravel is designed for such a load (you also have to ensure you design your Laravel app to properly accommodate such activity &mdash; queueing is not going to happen auto-magically).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead of having rss to email, now it&rsquo;s totally feasible to maintain a list within my site (or, perhaps, keep the list in MailChimp and fetch it) and send emails out everytime I publish an article. Built right into the app. Lots of possibilities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have not looked, but what if there was a Laravel app &ldquo;out there somewhere&rdquo; that had the double opt-in form sequence done, had the unsubscribe form and confirmation done, and a few other email list housekeeping things done, in a nice little installable package?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wouldn&rsquo;t that be kind of like having a content system and looking for add-ons? Well, yes, kind of!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://getcomposer.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Composer</a>&nbsp;is how one would add a mail list package to their Laravel app. Already, there are a number of contact form packages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m thinking about LaSalleMart 4.0 differently with Laravel than I did with LaSalleMart 3.0 in Joomla. The potential is so much greater; and, app frameworks are different beasts than content systems. Integrating customer management with ecommerce is one possibility. Workflows &mdash; yowza!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If there was a way to somehow break LaSalleMart 4.0 into real small installable pieces, to keep sites very lean, and to be more like a framework than an end-use type of software.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Should &ldquo;product type&rdquo; be a separate package? Or should there be just one &ldquo;product&rdquo; package?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Where this is all going is making apps accessible to those who would normally build high-ish end CMS sites. Where you would need $25,000 to build an app, will soon be $5,000.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Start-up power at CMS prices.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ll be blogging more about this!</p>\r\n', 'There’s a difference, I am realizing, between programming ecommerce in a content management system, and programming ecommerce as a web application. A huge difference...', 'There’s a difference, I am realizing, between programming ecommerce in a content management system, and programming ecommerce as a web application. A huge difference...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/app-economics-changing-more-e-biz-power-to-you-brother', 'the-times-a-changing-again1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-06-11', '2014-06-11 12:00:00', 1, '2014-06-11 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(124, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart 4.0: The Approach', 'lasallemart-40-the-approach', '<p>LaSalleMart 4.0 is starting, rightly so, with LaSalleMart 3.0, where I separated the major ecommerce areas into separate components: product, checkout, cart, coupon, orders, etc. These Joomla components talked to each other. Laravel is made for breaking up ecommerce into &ldquo;domains&rdquo;, so I am looking at what I already achieved with an eye to improving it with LM4.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which means that I am starting LaSalleMart 4.0 just as I started with LaSalleMart 3.0: struggling with the approach. With LM3, I created something I had never done before; nor, had I ever seen before: one extension comprised of multiple small targeted-scope components. So the struggle with LM3 was figuring out how to get from the proof of concept to the &ldquo;real&rdquo; LaSalleMart development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With LaSalleMart 4.0, the struggle is of a very different character: at what point is my field of dreams too idyllic? Maybe, it would be enough to recreate what I achieved with LM3 with my Laravel based LM4 &mdash; why struggle with the approach at all? Let&rsquo;s just get to it!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, for one thing, I am unsatisfied with the answer to the question, &ldquo;What is a product?&rdquo;, in LM3.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another thing is the concept of &ldquo;engine&rdquo;. Should there be a checkout &ldquo;engine&rdquo; that determines on-the-fly what the checkout steps should be?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s fine to be ambitious, but there is this matter of being on the early portion of the Larvel Learning Curve. Why not Keep It SSimple, and dig right into Laravel?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, while surveying the Laravel 4 landscape, I decided to stay on my Field of Dreams more than practicality counsels.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are Laravel ecommerce projects. It was studying these projects that convinced me to dream a little ecommerce dream. Let&rsquo;s see how it goes, shall we!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/moltin\" target=\"_blank\">Moltin</a>&nbsp;is strictly a cart &ndash;&gt; WRONG! It is an ecomm API only &ndash;&gt; see&nbsp;<a href=\"http://molt.in/\" target=\"_blank\">http://molt.in</a>. Basically, you send it an array of inputs and it creates a &ldquo;cart&rdquo; in the session &mdash; am I reading this one right? Actually, there&rsquo;s no actual cart &mdash; there&rsquo;s no view where you can actually see the cart. The cart exists in memory only. The rest of it you have to create for yourself. A great reminder to build ecommerce &ldquo;services&rdquo;. A product is just a product_id with a price &mdash; I thought that on the one hand this frees up what the definition of a product is to be whatever you associated with product_id; but, on the other hand, maybe this is a strict definition of a product that there is a product_id and a price, and little else.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You can get the product name and description from the product table (I almost said #__lmproduct_items table!), but&hellip; when there are attributes, the cart needs to hold the selected attributes. Did the customer select a white, red, or blue t-shirt? LM3 used database tables for the cart, not session variables.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is an interesting set of ecommerce packages at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://cartalyst.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Cartalyst</a>. These packages are &ldquo;cart agnostic&rdquo; and are supposed to serve as the basis for building ecommerce apps. Why not just grab these packages and get a head start? Well, I am haunted by two things: not having my own ecommerce technology; and, having my base technology prematurely go obsolete. In this case, it seems tempting to dig into these packages and get a heckuva head start on things. Maybe even be spared the trouble of creating Laravel ecommerce technology from scratch. Well, BTDT. I would rather be a stubborn S.O.B. and stick with LaSalleMart 4.0; and, later, see if Cartalyst provides added value. Here&rsquo;s a case of the app economics change in action: a set of packages that still require development, but provide a huge head start at nominal cost &mdash; that&rsquo;s how I read it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://bundles.laravel.com/bundle/cartify\" target=\"_blank\">Cartify</a>&nbsp;is a Laravel 3 cart. Well, I&rsquo;m pretty sure it&rsquo;s for Laravel 3! Here is&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/brunogaspar/cartify\" target=\"_blank\">the GitHub repo</a>. Oooh, I like the product definition including attributes:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n$item = array(\r\n   &#39;id&#39; =&gt; &#39;sku_123ABC&#39;,\r\n   &#39;qty&#39; =&gt; 1,\r\n   &#39;price&#39; =&gt; 39.95,\r\n   &#39;name&#39; =&gt; &#39;T-Shirt&#39;,\r\n   &#39;options&#39; =&gt; array(\r\n      &#39;size&#39; =&gt; &#39;L&#39;,\r\n      &#39;color&#39; =&gt; &#39;Red&#39;\r\n   )\r\n);\r\n\r\nCartify::cart()-&gt;insert($item);\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s also&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/Crinsane/LaravelShoppingcart\" target=\"_blank\">Crinsane</a>&nbsp;and the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/Crinsane/LaravelWebshopAdmin\" target=\"_blank\">Crinsane admin</a>. And&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/rktaiwala/Shpcart\" target=\"_blank\">ShpCart</a>. Of course, Cashier comes with the now released&nbsp;<a href=\"http://laravel.com/docs/billing\" target=\"_blank\">Laravel 4.2</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s great to have these Laravel carts to look at.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am thinking that each product type has its own installable package. If you want to use subscription products, then you have to grab the package with the product tables, admin forms, associated cart and order tables, and whatever other stuff you need. Which I doubt will quite work this way, since order management will be a separate package, so how can a product package update a separate order package? If I could, would I want to?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Would someone have the patience to click a separate subscription product admin? Product detail forms have been all-in-one forms to accommodate the various product types. I cannot stand these busy all-in-one product detail forms &mdash; they are so confusing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Something I did with LaSalleMart 3.0 was let the administration mimic the programming conventions. So, the forms dealt with one database only. In the end it was not so bad, mainly because the product details forms were minimalist and clean. There was one Knowledge Base page for each product details page &mdash; easy to link to from the LM3 admin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I had more product forms in LM3, but the forms were small and understandable. Based on this success (you can see LM3 screencasts at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://lasallemart.com/lasallemart3\" target=\"_blank\">LaSalleMart.com/lasallemart3</a>) I want to step on to my LM4 Field of Dreams and really segregate product types. A base product will have a product_id and product_type. Right now, I think a base product will also have Y/N fields for &ldquo;shipping&rdquo;, &ldquo;downloads&rdquo;, etc &mdash; although I am not sure exactly which tables these definitions should reside.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With LM3, I started defining products strictly, manifesting in the decision to not have inventory for product attributes. You buy the product_id, and whatever attributes that are associated with that product_id. If you keep inventory levels for attributes, then the product is of a different product type than a &ldquo;product with attributes&rdquo;. If a client were to ask for inventory for attributes, I had already decided to turn them down; instead, we&rsquo;d have to build the proper product profile.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A big reason for my&nbsp;obstinacy is the spaghetti programming that comes out of it. Can you add inventory? Ok&hellip;. hack hack hack done. Oh, nice, can you add rules if one attribute inventory is zero, then the product is not available for sale&hellip; hack hack hack hack done. Oh good, but I don&rsquo;t keep inventory for all attributes, so can I have both inventory and non-inventory for attributes of the same product? Forget it! Let&rsquo;s do it right with Laravel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I developed the LaSalleMart 3.0 product and cart views right away. But, with LaSalleMart 4.0, creating the UI is not critical to building the product and cart. Sounds weird, but build the functions first, then the UI. This should make development faster &mdash; and build a RESTful cart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As much as I want to dig into Laravel-LM4, I could waste a lot of time with Ready, Shoot, Aim. So, I will mull my approach over a little more.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are Laravel based Content Management Systems on the way. Two are OctoberCMS, which is out, and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/PongoCMS\" target=\"_blank\">Pongo for Laravel 4</a>, which is in active development. Interesting&nbsp;<a href=\"http://octobercms.com/blog/post/building-a-blog-and-forum\" target=\"_blank\">OctoberCMS screencast here</a>. I should design LaSalleMart 4.0 so it can use either, and whatever else comes out. This&nbsp;<a href=\"http://codecanyon.net/item/laravel-cms-crud-builder-administrator/7194641\" target=\"_blank\">CRUD Builder/CMS/Admin</a>&nbsp;looks interesting. &ldquo;CRUD&rdquo; refers to the database actions &ldquo;Create&rdquo;, &ldquo;Read&rdquo;, &ldquo;Update&rdquo;, and &ldquo;Delete&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>App as CMS is both fascinating and repulsive to me at the same time! I like the idea of having user management, authentication, pages, and menus &ldquo;built-in&rdquo;. But, right now, I do not want to deal with something that is bloated, tries to do too much, and&hellip; well, where the site becomes the CMS first and not &ldquo;the thing that you are building&rdquo;.&nbsp;I still harbour the idea of integrating WordPress as the product front-end with LM4-Laravel, so there&rsquo;s definitely a place/need for CMS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ll be mulling my LaSalleMart 4.0 Field of Dreams a bit more before settling down with Laravel 4.2 and my IDE.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'LaSalleMart 4.0 is starting, rightly so, with LaSalleMart 3.0, where I separated the major ecommerce', 'LaSalleMart 4.0 is starting, rightly so, with LaSalleMart 3.0, where I separated the major ecommerce areas into separate components: product, checkout, cart, coupon, orders, etc. These Joomla components talked to each other. Laravel is made for breaking u', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-40-the-approach', 'fork-in-the-road1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-06-14', '2014-06-14 12:00:00', 1, '2014-06-14 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(125, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Music to my Ears: Going to Stick With Laravel 4.x For A While', 'music-to-my-ears-stick-with-laravel-4-for-while', '<p>The videos for the Laravel Conference last May just came out. The keynote address was delivered by the Founder and Keeper of Laravel. He said that &ldquo;we&rsquo;re going to stick with Laravel 4 for a while&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stability is a red hot button for me right now, so hearing this is music to my ears.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you&rsquo;ve not heard of Laravel, here&rsquo;s a great introduction from the Founder.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/YKWHQnXcEB4\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ve been building apps for 16 years but building good apps for 5 months&rdquo;. Love that quote at 1:30:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/2_380DKU93U\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nice brief history of Laravel in this session:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/eqN-rt-D9KQ\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ah&hellip; ok, nice to see an&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.sitepoint.com/6-reasons-move-laravel-homestead/\" target=\"_blank\">article</a>&nbsp;state what I like about Laravel&rsquo;s Benevolent Dictator:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Homestead being official, as in, made by Taylor Otwell, the father of Laravel, means it&rsquo;s automatically assumed to hold to certain standards. While the Laravel community isn&rsquo;t&nbsp;<a href=\"https://gist.github.com/anonymous/8565929\" target=\"_blank\">without its drama</a>&nbsp;(who cares what a class is called? If a revolutionary new framework calls a model a potato, a facade, or a rocketship, it&rsquo;s perfectly fine as long as the potato/facade/rocketship works), it&rsquo;s the exclusivity of Taylor&rsquo;s involvement with it that gives it a note of simplicity and quality that&rsquo;s much needed in today&rsquo;s PHP world. We&rsquo;ve seen far too many open source projects ruined by team egos, zealous contributors, or incompetent jacks-of-all-trades and&nbsp;<strong>it&rsquo;s my personal opinion that Taylor&rsquo;s almost exclusive involvement in Laravel&rsquo;s betterment is what makes it shine above the rest and truly allows it to compete with Phalcon in quality</strong>.</p>\r\n</blockquote>', 'The videos for the Laravel Conference last May just came out. The keynote address was delivered by t', 'The videos for the Laravel Conference last May just came out. The keynote address was delivered by the Founder and Keeper of Laravel. He said that “we’re going to stick with Laravel 4 for a while”...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/music-to-my-ears-stick-with-laravel-4-for-while', 'laracon2014_keynote.png', 1, 0, 0, '2014-06-29', '2014-06-29 12:00:00', 1, '2014-06-28 13:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(126, 0, NULL, NULL, 'My Opinion of WordPress Has Not Changed Through the Years', 'my-opinion-of-wordpress-has-not-changed-through-the-years', '<p>Now that I am looking at Joomla in the rear-view mirror, has my opinion of WordPress changed?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The answer is no. In fact, if anything, I am rediscovering why I have not embraced WordPress as the be-all-and-end-all.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>WordPress has kicked ass with market share and man-on-the-street awareness. There are a zillion plugins for a zillion things. But, my opinion has not changed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I still think that WordPress is the wrong platform for serious e-business. You just do not build your e-business with WordPress. I thought that years ago and I still think that now. The reasons why Joomla was the better platform with which to build ecommerce technology still exist. It&rsquo;s just that Joomla is not the alternative platform with which to build it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>WordPress is a kick-ass blogging platform. For pure blogging and ebroadcasting, I use WordPress myself and have for years.bourne identity soundtrack</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you want to sell some products, run an ecommerce site as a hobby or as a side business, then, sure, use WordPress. But, if you have ambitions, then no way I would recommend using WordPress for it. Use WordPress as your product front-end &mdash; yes, something to consider.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But, I absolutely refuse to build my ecommerce technology on WordPress today just as I&rsquo;ve refused years ago. Laravel is the right place for LaSalleMart to be.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are so many buyers of WordPress software and services that sellers gravitate to the WordPress marketplace simply because that&rsquo;s where the money is. Hey, you go where the money is, right? Buyers love WordPress because there are millions of dollars of WordPress technologies available for a song. If you want to build the absolute lowest cost website, then WordPress is hard to beat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>WordPress&rsquo; massive market share has not changed the fact that menus are still not in their own database table. Or that the codebase is ancient. Yes, I see there are &ldquo;intra&rdquo; changes where code changes look like under-the-hood add-ons. Well, I see that there are clever ways a developer can skirt around the WordPress codebase to get some modern goodness whilst fully participating in the lucrative WordPress marketplace.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is tempting to just try to carve myself a slice of that WordPress marketplace by creating LaSalleMart for WordPress. But that&rsquo;s just bullshit, because I never saw WordPress as the platform of choice for ecommerce. If I developed LaSalleMart for WordPress, it would be solely to ride WordPress&rsquo; market share.&nbsp; And you know something, I cannot do that. As tempting as it is; well, it seemed tempting, but no way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart was never conceived to be the consumers choice for ecommerce anyways. That&rsquo;s not how I pursued it. I knew full well whilst developing LaSalleMart 3 that it would piss off the &ldquo;I&rsquo;m a web designer, not a web developer&rdquo; crowd. Which meant that an army of web designers would not choose LaSalleMart. My reaction: so what! I was not going to worry about reconciling the technical advantages of how I developed LaSalleMart with the &ldquo;hide the technology&rdquo; requirements of technology consumers. WordPress is all about hiding the technology, which is perfectly encapsulated by its auto-update feature that can only be suppressed in the wp-config.php file. Well, that&rsquo;s not the mentality that went into LaSalleMart 3, which was not designed for the feint of heart. However, if you wanted the technology &ldquo;kick&rdquo; that Joomla 3 + FOF offered, LM3 was for you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You know what I love about WooCommerce? It so WordPress-ian! The hooks, the filters. But, oh, the database! I love how it uses posts for transactions and customers. That is precisely how a WordPress ecommerce plugin should operate. That is precisely what you should get with a WordPress ecommerce plugin. What a pure expression of WordPress ecommerce. And I hate it! No normalized customer tables, no normalized order tables, etc etc. Since when do I need to go to Stack Exchange to learn where my orders are in the database?In my eyes, that&rsquo;s the price of being in WordPress ecommerce: you suck it up and live with it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I can live with the fact that menus are not in their own database tables, because it is a small price to pay for using a kick-ass blogging and e-broadcasting platform. The database makes sense for blogging, which is what it was originally designed for.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But, despite WordPress&rsquo; massive market share, Laravel is the place to be for ecommerce. And that&rsquo;s exactly where LaSalleMart 4 is going.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Now that I am looking at Joomla in the rear-view mirror, has my opinion of WordPress changed? The an', 'Now that I am looking at Joomla in the rear-view mirror, has my opinion of WordPress changed? The answer is no. In fact, if anything, I am rediscovering why I have not embraced WordPress as the be-all-and-end-all...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/my-opinion-of-wordpress-has-not-changed-through-the-years', 'thinking_man1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-07-02', '2014-07-02 22:39:42', 1, '2014-07-02 22:39:42', 1, NULL, NULL),
(127, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart 4 Approach, Part Deux', 'lasallemart-4-approach-part-deux', '<p>As I just posted, I love this quote from the Laracon 2014 NYC session: &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve been building apps for 16 years, but I&rsquo;ve been building good apps for 5 months&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/2_380DKU93U\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>That sums up the general sense that Laravel embodies PHP modernity. That a challenge with Laravel is not in using it, but in using it properly to build good apps.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If all I wanted to do was put as much of my LaSalleMart 3 code into Laravel, then I&rsquo;d be on my way. But, why use Laravel like that? Why ignore the Laravel Value Proposition? Obviously, LaSalleMart 4 is not about shoving LaSalleMart 3 code someplace to crank out a new software release.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve enjoyed an end-of-school and extended Canada Day mental break. Oh, does that mean that I&rsquo;ve not worked on LaSalleMart 4? Hardly! It means that I stopped prototyped but continued reading and watching videos &mdash; mainly the excellent Laracasts.com videos. The Laracon 2014 videos were just published, so I&rsquo;ve been watching them. As well, I now watch the Laravel on GitHub and so have followed the substantial daily issue posts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have especially enjoyed the posts by Laravel&rsquo;s Founder. It is clear who is in charge. One word replies abound: &ldquo;No&rdquo;. And no arguments follow! If you want your pull request accepted you need a compelling reason. It is not what I am used to with Joomla, and let&rsquo;s leave the comparison at that. It is ironic that &ldquo;building community&rdquo; is based on an obvious benevolent dictator. The community is exploding. So there you go. But right now I see huge, and I mean huge, benefit to the Founder protecting his vision of Laravel as it is expressed in version 4. Everyone has their own version of what they want or how to improve it, and the only way they can truly see their own vision in Laravel is by forking it. Or, create a separate package for it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think the idea of keeping Laravel lean, and then having separate packages &mdash; such as validation packages. There are so many validation packages, I am thinking that what I should really do is do<em>These</em>my own (based on other open source packages, of course!) &mdash; is a pretty good idea.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think this idea is so good that the emerging Laravel eco-system that is itself hitting an inflection will become a viable alternative to WordPress for those that want to reach for &ldquo;app power&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, part of the LaSalleMart 4 approach may include offering custom packages. Validation is one. User management is another. More prototyping is needed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Along the lines of &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve been building&nbsp;<em>good</em>&nbsp;apps for 5 months&rdquo;, I know I have to use &ldquo;command buses&rdquo; in LaSalleMart 4. Also, a validation&nbsp;<em>layer.&nbsp;</em>These are things that are part and parcel of building good apps.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So I am investing extra time to get a handle (kind of a pun) on these things. The payoff will be huge, one of which is being able to build more features upon the existing code, without disturbing existing code. Well, it&rsquo;s a new way of thinking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I know from developing LaSalleMart 3 that there is enough complexity &mdash; or perhaps it&rsquo;s really scope &mdash; to warrant embracing the structure that the Laravel Framework encourages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As I watch&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/3uV3ngl1Z8g\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&hellip; I am thinking, it does not seem professional learning programming while programming. Shouldn&rsquo;t I be learn first, and then code? What kind of LaSalleMart can I create if I am treating is as a CompSci 201 project?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, it is actually the opposite. If you are not learning, then you are being unprofessional. There is no termination point where you can stop learning and then start coding. The learning never stops. Or, as Laracasts.com motto says, &ldquo;Never Stop Learning&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is why the Moneyball of e-business is so tough: you are always struggling with software development. But, you know, value is not where it is easy. If it were easy, then everyone would be start-up millionaires. You are always struggling with software development because, in part, the learning never stops.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is dawning on me that the IOC container really is the central idea of the Laravel Framework. Dawning on me because I&rsquo;ve not used software like this before, so it is not intuitive. Yes, I read&nbsp;<a href=\"http://martinfowler.com/articles/injection.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://martinfowler.com/articles/injection.html</a>. I am certainly open to using these concepts purely on the basis that for some things in LaSalleMart 3, there has to be a better way of doing these things.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Something that took me by surprise with LaSalleMart 3 was the complexity&nbsp;of the cart. LaSalleMart 3&prime;s cart had its own set of database tables. Totals, taxes, shipping, and coupons were part of the cart. Add payments and some post-processing steps and you&rsquo;d have an order. Tax was a sub-system, not a mere calculation. The cart had to knock on the tax system&rsquo;s door and ask it to go through its algorithm. Same with coupons. Then, when an order was placed, it the same sequence occurred, with additional processing &mdash; such as deleting the cart database records, and creating the order records.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My goal is not to create a LaSalleMart 4 that will be the toast of the CompSci faculty lounge. I have to be practical. But &ldquo;Muddy Controllers&rdquo; (@ 26:20) resonates.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/eqN-rt-D9KQ\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://laracasts.com/index/event\" target=\"_blank\">https://laracasts.com/index/event</a>&nbsp;dives deep into it. Yes, it resonates.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 3 was mud, but very organized mud thanks to innovations I had never done before with Joomla thanks to the superb Akeeba Framework for Joomla. But, we&rsquo;re not in Joomla anymore, Dorothy. The Laravel Framework opens up modern ways to handle the &ldquo;What happens when a buyer places an order?&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is dawning on me is the concept of inversion. Inversion is the &ldquo;I&rdquo; in &ldquo;IoC&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>&hellip;in traditional programming, the custom code that expresses the purpose of the program&nbsp;<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_call#Main_concepts\">calls into</a>&nbsp;reusable libraries to take care of generic tasks, but with inversion of control, it is the reusable code that calls into the custom, or problem-specific, code.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>(from&nbsp;<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inversion_of_control\" target=\"_blank\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inversion_of_control</a>)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The idea is neatly summed up as the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hollywood_Principle\" target=\"_blank\">&ldquo;Hollywood Principle</a>&ldquo;:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>The Hollywood principle is a software design methodology that takes its name from the clich&eacute; response given to amateurs auditioning in Hollywood: &ldquo;<strong>Don&rsquo;t call us, we&rsquo;ll call you</strong>&ldquo;. It is a useful paradigm that assists in the development of code with high cohesion and low coupling that is easier to debug, maintain and test.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most beginners are first introduced to programming from a diametrically opposed viewpoint. Programs take control of the running environment and make calls on the underlying system to do their work. A considerable amount of successful software has been developed using the same principles, and indeed many developers need never think there is any other approach. After all, programs with linear flow are generally easy to understand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As systems increase in complexity, the linear model becomes less maintainable. Consider for example a simple program to bounce a square around a window in your favorite operating system or window manager. The linear approach may work, up to a point. You can keep the moving and drawing code in separate procedures, but soon the logic begins to branch.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The key to make this possible is to sacrifice the element of control.&nbsp;<strong>Instead of your program running the system, the system runs your program</strong>.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>In LaSalleMart 3, the add-to-cart controller was very muddy, despite the fact that I had done a terrific job of organizing it within the Joomla context. There are a number of things that happen when a product is added to the cart, but, boy, those add-to-cart tasks really start piling up.&nbsp;I have no recollection of ever seeing interfaces in a Joomla component; nor any dependency injection as is done in Laravel. Laravel is modern, in part, because it is newer. And, not having delved into frameworks before the Akeeba Framework for Joomla, dependencies is new.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Adding products to the cart represents a number of tasks that have to be done. Placing an order represents even more tasks that have to be done. Executing these tasks in &ldquo;muddy&rdquo; controllers that grew ever-larger started causing problems in LaSalleMart 3. So, I may not be familiar with Inverted Containers and Dependency Injection, but I am certainly softened up to be receptive to these notions!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The notion of representing the individual tasks as events is quite appealing. See the &ldquo;&hellip; building good apps for five months&rdquo; video. That the controller that requests these tasks does not even have to know what these tasks are is weird and appealing at the same time. Weird because it is not intuitive how a task can be accomplished; and, appealing because it helps organize the code better. That developers&nbsp;can actually traverse LaSalleMart 4&prime;s code and understand it without requiring a separate set of documentation &mdash; hey, how good is that! The number beneficiary of this organization will be me, as I will be able to come back to code months after touching it and actually understand what the heck I was doing. Don&rsquo;t laugh &mdash; you ever write down a recipe, then dig it up later only to realize you wrote in some short-hand that made total sense at the time but is now indecipherable. Well, welcome to the club. I comment the heck out of LaSalleMart 3, but for the code itself to be organized to the point of being intuitively understandable &mdash; nirvana!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A big payoff of doing it these new ways is the ability to add new tasks easily. How &rsquo;bout notifying the site owner that someone is in checkout (say, via SMS with&nbsp;http://www.twilio.com). Sure is easier to add one more task to the list than cracking open a muddy controller.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another big payoff is being able to test the tasks, as they are independent creatures that can be tested on their own.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A very intriguing payoff is something that I&rsquo;ve not used before: queueing tasks.&nbsp;Tasks are executed&nbsp;in the background, so people are not waiting around for the processing to finish. Queueing is important for high volume web apps. Having proper tasks with which to queue becomes a necessity so queueing is practical.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Laracasts.com motto is &ldquo;Netflix for Developers&rdquo;. Right now, I am more like the Netflix tagline&nbsp;&ldquo;you need to get it to get it&rdquo;. I need to make sense of the Laravel jargon by &ldquo;getting it&rdquo;. For me, the &ldquo;it&rdquo; to get is the IoC container &amp; injection: that Laravel controls the app, not the thing I am developing. LaSalleMart is not in control, Laravel is in control. So, let Laravel control! Hey, Laravel, someone just placed an order, so go forth and make that order happen. Very unlike LaSalleMart 3 which would quarterback everything.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s not just a journey into The Laravel Framework, but into PHP frameworks. My introduction to PHP frameworks is mostly working with the Akeeba Framework for Joomla, which incorporates ideas from the general PHP framework world. But, it is specifically meant to work with Joomla, so it is very constrained. I took very little notice of&nbsp;<a href=\"http://symfony.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Symfony</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"http://ellislab.com/codeigniter\" target=\"_blank\">CodeIgniter</a>, not to mention ignoring&nbsp;<a href=\"http://framework.zend.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Zend</a>. Maybe I should have had a greater interest in at least one of these frameworks before. Working hard with the Akeeba Framework for Joomla, dealing with its particular idiosyncracies which exist mostly to cope with Joomla, has proved a good learning ground for Laravel. Laravel itself is not like other PHP frameworks, so there&rsquo;s new learning to do anyways. Some of Laravel is not so mysterious, as I&rsquo;ve worked with MVC already. So, as I kick myself for not getting into the frameworks earlier, at the same time it does not matter as switching to Laravel involves new learning anyways. Like the quote says, &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve been building good apps for five months!&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ll tell you this: I sense my Laravel learning is happening far faster than with my learning Joomla/Akeeba Framework. One reason I am sure is the complete lack of &ldquo;users&rdquo; in the Laravel community, in the sense that &ldquo;users&rdquo; is recognized in Joomla (and WordPress). There is only one Laravel &ldquo;user&rdquo;: the developer. There are no end-users. No one ever claims that Laravel is &ldquo;too technical, and as a &lsquo;regular&rsquo; Laravel user one should not have to deal with Laravel&rsquo;s technicals!&rdquo;. On the contrary, actually. All the learning resources are focused on developers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laravel is unified. The code is obviously under the auspices of one person. Joomla is under the auspices of multiple people/groups of people, which manifests very much in the code. Right now, for me, Laravel being so controlled by one person is very welcome, in part because what it augurs for code stability; and, in part for learning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Learning Laravel is a cottage industry. There is a lot out there devoted to teaching Laravel. The Laracasts videos are an absolute must.&nbsp;That this site (made with Laravel) is viable is a tangible indicator of Laravel&rsquo;s growth. I must be making progress, because I&rsquo;m starting to argue with the videos&nbsp;while I am watching. Acceptance is not an issue with Laravel anymore &mdash; it is accepted. The issue, now, is education. The Laravel community is responding by creating educational resources. Dig in! These resources are hugely effective in my learning Laravel. Including all the code available at GitHub.com, such as the Laravel website sitting in a GitHub repo.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Having just viewed the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n9H6pqC5t_A\" target=\"_blank\">&ldquo;Break the Mold&rdquo; talk at Laracon 2014 NYC</a>, I see that the app folder is highly modificable. Seeing it in action, a few lightbulbs went off.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, there&rsquo;s more videos, more articles, and more learning to do. The IoC container is key, but there are other ideas to absorb. There are a lot of others in the same boat as me, learning the specific Laravel concepts that make it so unique and compelling. Although I wanted to have more LaSalleMart 4 code prototyped in Laravel at this time, my little summer mental break has proved very refreshing and productive, as all the time digging into Laravel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is really helping is having worked hard building a from-scratch, innovative LaSalleMart 3. At every step of my Laravel learning, I am constantly referring to my LaSalleMart 3. There are a lot of people who relate Laravel to their CodeIgniter projects. There are a lot of people who relate Laravel to their Symfony projects. I imagine there are not a lot of people, relatively speaking, coming from Joomla, but that is me. LaSalleMart 3 could probably be better construed as ecommerce for the Akeeba Framework than simply as a Joomla extensions. It is my intensive use of the Akeeba Framework for Joomla that is paying off hugely right now in my transition to Laravel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'As I just posted, I love this quote from the Laracon 2014 NYC session: “I’ve been building apps ', 'As I just posted, I love this quote from the Laracon 2014 NYC session: “I’ve been building apps for 16 years, but I’ve been building good apps for 5 months”...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-4-approach-part-deux', 'approach1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-07-03', '2014-07-03 22:37:22', 1, '2014-07-03 22:37:22', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(128, 0, NULL, NULL, 'JoomLarvel!', 'joomlarvel', '<p>Took a nice little week-ish long side tour of servers, including Laravel&rsquo;s Homestead, setting up my first DigitalOcean &ldquo;droplet&rdquo; cloud server, and digging into nginx.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now that my development environment is set, I am settling into creating my own little content management system with Laravel. The reasoning behind creating my own little CMS is learning + need. I need to develop something smaller than LaSalleMart to really learn Laravel, so why not develop LaSalleCast? Well, LaSalleCast is not exactly un-ambitious, but it is a live project I want to start; and, it is smaller in scope than LaSalleMart. LaSalleCast needs stuff that all Laravel apps seem to need: user management,&nbsp;article management, etc. Well, why not create a CMS that all my projects can use. I can move LaSalleMart.com to it, so I already have my first real site! A CMS has the stuff is the subject of videos, articles, and a lot of GitHub source code, which makes it seem like a great first app to develop.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The thing about a CMS is that it is really two separate and distinct apps, separated by a common database. There is &ldquo;front-end&rdquo; that is the website that everyone sees. Then, there is the administrative &ldquo;back-end&rdquo; that only those who run the site see. There is only one database, though, that both share.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After moseying around a lot of examples and articles, I am going to explicitly delineate the front and back ends. This is something I&rsquo;ve not seen yet, and is not necessary to do with Laravel, especially with its flexibility with routing. Maybe my problem is that you can take the boy out of Joomla, but you cannot take Joomla out of the boy. &nbsp;Joomla has explicit front and back ends (yes, WordPress too). Separate folders for templates, modules, language files. About the only thing that the front and back ends shared were the libraries and plugins.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I hardly imagined when I moved to the Laravel Framework that I would develop a Joomla-ish CMS. Seems a bit ironic, eh! Well, not Joomla-ish, but how about &ldquo;Joomla inspired&rdquo;? Unlike Joomla, the entry point is shared, but from there I will separate the front and back ends with their own folders. Each will have its own layouts (templates/themes), own routes, own MVC, own folders. The database will be shared, and if other things are shared I will put &lsquo;em in a &ldquo;shared&rdquo; folder.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After all the &ldquo;Domain Driven Development&rdquo; and such learning I&rsquo;ve done, it feels almost rebellious to have a main app folder structure of &ldquo;site&rdquo;, &ldquo;admin&rdquo;, and &ldquo;shared&rdquo;. Well, there are two apps in each app, and I am finding that it is quite confusing. Why not put my intense Joomla experience to some good use? Indeed! I am still calling my little CMS &ldquo;LaSalleCMS&rdquo;. But, I&rsquo;ve already nicknamed it &ldquo;JoomLarvel!&rdquo; (removing that last &ldquo;a&rdquo; makes it more readable).</p>\r\n', 'Took a nice little week-ish long side tour of servers, including Laravel’s Homestead, setting up my first DigitalOcean “droplet” cloud server, and digging into nginx...', 'Took a nice little week-ish long side tour of servers, including Laravel’s Homestead, setting up my first DigitalOcean “droplet” cloud server, and digging into nginx...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/joomlarvel', 'aha_kid.png', 1, 0, 0, '2014-07-18', '2014-07-18 12:00:00', 1, '2014-07-18 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(129, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleCMS for Laravel will be Published!', 'lasallecms-for-laravel-will-be-published', '<p>Today is August 06th, 2014.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Development of LaSalleCMS, based on the Laravel Framework for PHP, is progressing well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So well that I am not posting any more articles on my blog until I move my blog to LaSalleCMS, which I expect will happen by Labour Day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In order to deepen my understanding of Laravel, and as important stepping stones to developing LaSalleCast, LaSalleMart, and now I am contemplating LaSalleCRM, I want to pack more into LaSalleCMS than I originally intended.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleCMS began as a learning exercise, with the idea that it would be something that only I would use for my own websites. The only way to learn Laravel is to use it, and the only way to use it is to have real projects. Since the only person using it is me, it does not matter that it&rsquo;s full of growing pains.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite the growing pains, I am enjoying putting together my own blog app from scratch. Last Sunday, I did not enjoy it, as there were a ton of frustrations. But, persevering through the frustrations, it took shape. I put in a crazy-long Monday to wrap up the essentials of my administration area. Having gone through the experience with tangible success, I am fired up to get LaSalleCMS beyond what I originally intended it to be.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I see LaSalleCMS as the starting point for my other projects. So I want to &ldquo;fill out&rdquo; the features. An hour flew by as I hand-listed the features &mdash; both great and small. So, there is more learning and features to do, before I move my blog site to LaSalleCMS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not only will SouthLaSalle dot com be my blog site, but it will be my flagship site as well. Crazy that no site of mine markets me as an independent freelance consultant/developer &mdash; how&rsquo;d that happen, I&rsquo;m not exactly sure?! Well, gotta fix that.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, no more blog posts this month. Will finish up my August podcast this week, and that&rsquo;s it for that.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m not on Facebook much as it is, so it&rsquo;ll be hard to be on it even less.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m on Twitter all the time, although I do not do a lot of tweeting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I went &ldquo;underground&rdquo; for an extended period of time when I developed LaSalleMart 3, and it was a mistake. These weeks before Labour Day is a good time to go &ldquo;underground&rdquo; anyways just because of the time of year. So, that&rsquo;s what I will do!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I was going to blog about the July LaravelTO workshop, but I will demure for now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Bob</p>\r\n', 'Development of LaSalleCMS, based on the Laravel Framework for PHP, is progressing well.\r\nSo well that I am not posting any more articles on my blog until I move my blog to LaSalleCMS, which I expect will happen by Labour Day...', 'Development of LaSalleCMS, based on the Laravel Framework for PHP, is progressing well.\r\nSo well that I am not posting any more articles on my blog until I move my blog to LaSalleCMS, which I expect will happen by Labour Day...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallecms-for-laravel-will-be-published', '2013dec24_bob_jonathon.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-08-06', '2014-08-06 12:00:00', 1, '2014-08-06 12:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(132, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Announcing the Launch of LaSalleCMS and South LaSalle Dot Com', 'announcing-the-launch-of-lasallecms-and-southlasalle-dot-com1', '<p>It is with great pleasure that I announce the launch of my flagship site, SouthLaSalle Dot Com, which uses my new Laravel blog app.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I switched my technical specialty in Apri/May of this year from Joomla to Laravel. In so doing, I abandoned the from-scratch Joomla ecommerce technology I had written, based on the absolutely superb Framework-on-Framework -- my LaSalleMart 3.0.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I chose Laravel as my new technical specialty. Five months later my first version of LaSalleCMS is done.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is the first time ever that my own sites use something other than Joomla or WordPress. And, incredibly, the first time that my own site is based on software that I myself have built.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s one thing to build an app to learn. It&#39;s another thing to use that app for real. My blog app is missing a zillion features that are taken for granted by millions of WordPress users. But there is no way I&#39;m going back. All those articles I&#39;ve written that being able to create software is powerful -- it&#39;s true. I am much more powerful with my own blog app than I am using someone elses. This is the first time I&#39;ve really lived my assertion about software creation and can feel the power. The power of software creation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Obviously, my blog app is bare bones. But it is not going to stay bare bones. Having a media manager would sure be convenient. I have plans for full user management -- right now I really don&#39;t need it. In a short period of time it will fill out. I lavished time on architecture and proper structure. My guess is that myself and my clients will end up using my blog app or the up-and-coming OctoberCMS -- a nice Laravel based choice.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laravel is the most powerful PHP thing I&#39;ve ever learned in my life. Laravel is modern. Laravel is built specifically for creating web applications. When I started using Joomla and WordPress, I was not able to program my own blogging software. My skills have definitely progressed. My powers as a programmer are really growing now. Where I got to with LaSalleMart-Joomla, I am now vaulting from that base. I have yet to peak, my programming powers are just now taking off.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After an intensive five month transitional period of changing my technical specialty, I am thrilled to launch my own flagship site using my flagship blog app.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Bob</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'It is with great pleasure that I announce the launch of my flagship site, SouthLaSalle Dot Com...', 'It is with great pleasure that I announce the launch of my flagship site, SouthLaSalle Dot Com, whic', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/announcing-the-launch-of-lasallecms-and-southlasalle-dot-com1', 'lasallecms_admin_posts_listing1.png', 1, 0, 0, '2014-09-28', '2014-09-28 10:59:57', 1, '2014-09-28 12:10:47', 1, NULL, NULL),
(133, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Finally, My Software Start-up!', 'finally-my-software-start-up1', '<p>Over these last months while going through an intensive learning of my new technical specialty -- the learning never stops -- I&#39;ve been mulling about where I want to go with my efforts and Laravel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The answer that I&#39;ve come up with is that I am going to continue to do what I was doing. Except with Laravel I have a technical specialty that will get me to where I am going. Yes, I think where I am headed is better suited with Laravel than with Joomla (or WordPress), which became apparent as my new blog app took form.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am a software start-up. Something that I did not quite feel when I created LaSalleMart for Joomla, as I saw myself as creating software for Joomla. Now, I am creating software -- no qualifying statements follow.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am going to fulfill the software ambitions I started in my Joomla era, using the Laravel Framework for PHP:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>LaSalleCMS --&gt; my blog app;</li>\r\n	<li>LaSalleCast --&gt; my e-broadcasting app;</li>\r\n	<li>LaSalleMart --&gt; my ecommerce software.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Version one of my first ever Laravel app is done, and it needs work. But, it is incredibly important that it exists! It is done. It is achieved. It is deployed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I need to wrap up my initial blog posts, add my home page &quot;About&quot; section, and then embark on pre-Larvel 5 conversion; and, then convert to Laravel 5 -- funny enough but I&#39;ll be converted to Laravel 5 before it is even released. In so doing, I plan on creating my first Laravel packages. I will start with my contact page, and then see about my own sanitizer and command-bus packages.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then, it&#39;s full-on creating LaSalleCast, which includes moving my current media site from WordPress to my own podcasting app.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleCast is pure &quot;dog food&quot; --&gt; I am creating it exclusively for my own use. In this sense, it is truly my own start-up. Based on my years of podcasting, there are a bunch of features that I need to help me do my podcasts and save me a massive amount of time. Yes, I expect to earn revenue (not much at the start), and to build up this e-asset.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleCast is not something I want to turn into a line of business. It is my ecommerce that I want to be my major line of business. However, the meld of e-broadcasting and ecommerce is especially powerful, under-appreciated, and massively under-utilized, so who knows.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleCast/SouthLaSalleMedia is something I want ready by Halloween. I am suspending my podcasts until this is up-and-running. Then, I am continuing with my monthly LaSalleMart podcasts; and, will re-start my &quot;The Bob Bloom Show&quot; podcasts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which means on November 1st at the latest I will start on LaSalleMart, my ecommerce technology for Laravel. It will be a different beast than the ecommerce I did with Joomla. Built completely from scratch, it will have an API. In fact, the API will be built first. So, by Christmas, I expect to have my LaSalleMart API version 1.0 done.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finally, the software start-up I&#39;ve always wanted!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Bob</p>', 'LaSalleCMS, LaSalleCast, LaSalleMart --> welcome to my start-up...', 'Over these last months while going through an intensive learning of my new technical specialty -- th', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/finally-my-software-start-up1', 'entering startup1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-09-28', '2014-09-28 11:47:36', 1, '2014-09-28 12:11:05', 1, NULL, NULL),
(134, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaravelTO Presentation', 'laravel-toronto-presentation-october-28-20141', '<p>At the October 28, 2014 monthly Laravel Toronto Meet-up, I presented my custom blog app, LaSalleCMS.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A special thanks to <a href=\"http://soapboxhq.com/\" target=\"_blank\">SoapBox</a>&nbsp;for organizing; and, for offering their superb facilities and hospitality to the Toronto Laravel Community.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After six months in the lab, it was great to show what I had. Not having shared it with anyone, my presentation came out as a big stream of consciousness -- methinks.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The presentation reminded me of my podcasts. I find it hard to ad-lib, so I write out my podcasts ahead of time. On the other hand, doing so removes the spontaneity of the moment. As well, I do like to go on tangents -- usually related -- where I know what I want to convey but I do not want to write it down in detail ahead of time. The first part of my presentation was fairly smooth because I had slides prepared. Going over my code was more free-form, and I do not think I performed as well. The attendees were quite patient with me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I thought the most interesting thing was using the command bus. No. What was discussed was using .env.php and .env.local.php files to specify database credentials. Which I explained very poorly. For my next presentation I need to rehearse with an audience first!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This presentation is also a launch. Four of my own sites are now based on my blog app, which is now up on GitHub.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/bbloom9/lasallecms-presentation\" target=\"_blank\">Slideshare Presentation</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Images by <a href=\"http://ca.linkedin.com/pub/sheldon-seale/32/496/515\" target=\"_blank\">Sheldon Seale</a> and <a href=\"https://twitter.com/vicmakcy/status/527260367932518400\" target=\"_blank\">Victor Mak</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.44.14.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.44.14.jpg\" style=\"height:auto; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.44.35.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.44.35.jpg\" style=\"height:auto; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.45.52.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.45.52.jpg\" style=\"height:auto; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.47.06.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.47.06.jpg\" style=\"height:auto; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.53.12.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.53.12.jpg\" style=\"height:auto; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 21.01.31.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 21.01.31.jpg\" style=\"height:auto; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 21.13.18.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 21.13.18.jpg\" style=\"height:auto; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 21.04.34.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 21.04.34.jpg\" style=\"height:auto; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.58.56.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.58.56.jpg\" style=\"height:auto; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.49.31.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.49.31.jpg\" style=\"height:auto; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.46.12.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.46.12.jpg\" style=\"height:auto; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 21.20.16.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://www.southlasalle.com/images_original_blog/2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 21.20.16.jpg\" style=\"height:auto; width:350px\" /></a></p>', 'Presenting LaSalleCMS, my custom blog app, based on Laravel 4.2. At the Toronto Laravel Group on Oct', 'Presenting LaSalleCMS, my custom blog app, based on Laravel 4.2. At the Toronto Laravel Group on Oct', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/laravel-toronto-presentation-october-28-20141', '2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/tweeted_pic.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-11-02', '2014-11-02 23:02:45', 1, '2014-11-03 00:25:48', 1, NULL, NULL),
(135, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Six Months In With New Specialties: A Retrospective', 'six-months-with-new-specialty-a-retrospective1', '<p>It is six months since I decided, in a flash of an instant of a moment, dropped Joomla; and, decided to specialize in the Laravel Framework.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Six months hence I presented my custom blog app made with Laravel to the Toronto Laravel meet-up group; and, have installed it on four of my own sites.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Technically, it&#39;s been a grand achievement these six months. The scope of learning&#39;s been vast. Can I learn new and different technicals at 50? Bet your ass I can. It&#39;s been gratifying.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although these six months have been expensive, the years preceeding my switch were lean too. The constant Joomla version changes were absolute disasters, a lesson that is germaine to the upcoming Laravel version.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not once in these six months have I regretted moving from Joomla. Not in the dead of night deep in my own thoughts. Not one shred of doubt.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My only doubt, in fact, was not switching to Laravel when I started working on LaSalleMart 3.0.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In my estimation, which has not changed one iota since writing about it extensively in my blog and podcasts, is that Joomla is already a niche CMS. Nothing more, nothing less. My regret is not seeing it for what it really was.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A guy like me would get neck deep into WordPress, right? That&#39;s where the action is, right? Well, instead, I dove further into development, which I think is a bit unusual. Actually, I&#39;ve been working with WordPress more than ever for clients.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But, ultimately, six months in, it is clear to me that I am interested in picking up where I left off. I now have my own blog app, and I am thrilled about it -- a passion that I know came through at my presentation. I have in the works my LaSalleCast app with which to run my podcasting line of business. I am actively researching developing&nbsp;LaSalleMart 4.0&#39;s API.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What I am doing is the same. It&#39;s the technology that is different. A more powerful technology.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What I will be doing is keep at what I am doing. Building LaSalleCMS, LaSalleCast, and LaSalleMart. And with it, perhaps a bit of LaSalleCRM and LaSallePM.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But something happened in last month, in October, that has made me decide again on my technology direction. Laravel itself was slated for a gentle release to verion 4.3 this month (November 2014). However, in October, all notions of version 4.3 were blown to smithereens in favour of a new backwards-compatibility breaking version 5.0.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And you know something, this course correction, has made me blistering mad.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Laravel creators and sponsors can do anything they darn well want with their Framework. It&#39;s their right, it&#39;s their decision. That they said one thing and then changed their mind is their perogative. Further, they can put in whatever feature they want, which is their perogative.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These technology version changes are a killer, eh!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;m not throwing away a very intense, and many time tense, and hardly costless, six months transition period. And, for the first time in years, I do not see a clear Value Proposition in switching to the new version of what I am using. Furthermore, for the first time, I have the ability to use multiple versions, and multiple frameworks, for my software.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In October, I decided that my software is more important than the frameworks I use.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Previously, I thought it crucial to know all I could about Laravel, in part so I could land programming gigs while developing my own software. Now, I am throwing these notions out the window. Frankly, it&#39;s been liberating, as I&#39;ve stopped worrying about becoming familiar with the latest toys and pop-features that are in vogue. Ironically, I&#39;ve become more proficient with Laravel 4.2 these last two weeks not worrying about keeping up with the latest Laracast videos or worrying about Laravel 5.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My commitment is to my software.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laravel 4.2 is kick-ass. It is not obsolete. It is powerful technology and I am glad I learned it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Does it matter that LaSalleCast is based on L4.2 or L5?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In my estimation, no. But sticking with L4.2, becoming more proficient with it, makes my software better. And gets my software into production a heckuva lot faster.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ironically, following the decisions made with L5 has increased my understanding of L4.2. Furthermore, I&#39;ve started to look at the framework that underlies Laravel called Symfony, and have gained more insight as a result.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Six months ago, if you told me that I would build my own blogging app, I&#39;d have laughed at you. But I did. I am getting fearless. The framework stuff is hugely over my head, but so what, I can still clone the repo and change it for my own purposes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Compared to the open source license Joomla and WordPress uses, the open source license Laravel uses is especially compact in its <a href=\"http://opensource.org/licenses/MIT\" target=\"_blank\">expression of software freedom</a>:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Permission is hereby granted, free of charge, to any person obtaining a copy<br />\r\nof this software and associated documentation files (the &quot;Software&quot;), to deal<br />\r\nin the Software without restriction, including without limitation the rights<br />\r\nto use, copy, modify, merge, publish, distribute, sublicense, and/or sell<br />\r\ncopies of the Software, and to permit persons to whom the Software is<br />\r\nfurnished to do so, subject to the following conditions:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The above copyright notice and this permission notice shall be included in<br />\r\nall copies or substantial portions of the Software.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>My guess is that L4.2 will be, if it is not already, in &quot;maintenance mode&quot;. It&#39;s seen all the major (and major-minor) features its going to have. So, hacking away at it to suit my own software needs is not going to deprive me of future creature features.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So for now, I am going to stick with L4.2. Actually L5 has not been released, so when it is, I will study it. But I am forging ahead with my own software with L4.2.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Right now, what I have on-deck is creating some packages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a database backup package that I want to use as the basis for my own package as I need more functionality.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I want to turn my itty bitty little Access Control code into a separate package, with which to grow into a grander ACL system.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I may similarly do the same for my image handling.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am mulling a package to handle what I will loosely call &quot;Command Bus Handling&quot;. I need a package that will simplify creating &quot;CRUD&quot; in the admin.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I really want to dive into LaSalleCast development, but it&#39;s clear to me that I&#39;m going to get bogged down if I don&#39;t clean up some things in my blog app first.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With LaSalleCast development, my goal is get operational first. I expect a lot of pet features that I want to build will not happen at first, so that I can get my new LaSalleCast Media site up-and-running by this month-end.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will divulge that I am curious if I can actually program a basic email app. Where emails can be sent and received within the app. Where threads can be saved. If so --&nbsp;and I&#39;m sure it is do-able! -- I will have the basis for the kind of CRM and PM (project management) thingee that I&#39;ve been looking for -- and can offer to my clients.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&#39;ll see... first I have to clean up LaSalleCMS and get out LaSalleCast&#39;s first version....</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Six months since changing my technical specialty. Was it the right decision? Is it a disaster?', 'Six months since changing my technical specialty. Was it the right decision? Is it a disaster? What\'', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/six-months-with-new-specialty-a-retrospective1', '2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/tweeted_pic.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-11-03', '2014-11-03 15:33:46', 1, '2014-11-03 16:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(136, 0, NULL, NULL, 'A Sense of Progression', 'a-sense-of-progression14', '<p>By Halloween I really wanted to have LaSalleCast done to the point where I could at least resume podcasting. Not having even started LaSalleCast upset me deeply. It seems so easy to get sidetracked.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ve been asking myself what the point of it all is if I can&#39;t get my darned software out the door. The past number of years I&#39;ve been programming, but where&#39;s the software? It really burns me up!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have a lot of software that I want to produce. LaSalleCMS. LaSalleCast. LaSalleMart. LaSalleProjects. LaSalleCRM?! I need to pick up the pace.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ll tell you something. I came to a startling conclusion today.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ve been asking myself for months &quot;Would I hire myself?&quot;. Have my development skills progressed to the point where someone would want to hire me? Do I perceive myself as someone whom I&#39;d hire? I figure if I know I&#39;m at a certain proficiency than I could get some programming gigs&nbsp;while en route to developing my own software.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No one is a bigger critic than me (so I think!), so naturally I do not think that I would hire myself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, I looked at it from a Moneyball perspective. To me, &quot;Moneyball&quot; (yes, referring to the movie -- see previous blog posts) means looking at where value really comes from. From a technical proficiency viewpoint, I am not there yet. From a value perspective, though, I represent huge value.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My will to learn is sky high. My ability to learn is huge. I am pushing pushing pushing all the time to learn. What I did to achieve LaSalleMart 3.0 pales to what I&#39;ve achieved in the last six months. Now, I am getting fearless, because six months ago I would never think I would create a blog app from scratch. Now I am thinking of a type of LaSalleFramework for myself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My ambition, my perserverance, my relentless push to learn -- along with a background that encompasses much more than just programming. There is tremendous value there.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, after thinking that I am un-hire-able for Laravel gigs, I have concluded that, be that as it may (and yes, my testing skills are, ahem, nascent -- but even here my skills are s-l-o-w-l-y improving), my value to a growing start-up is immense. Solving problems, delving into the unknown, etc etc.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My startling conclusion: keep this value for my family, instead of transferring it to someone else.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And so marks the end of a very short era where I ask myself, &quot;Would I hire myself?&quot;. For a deep techie gig, no. To help build a start-up, yes. My own start-up!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And so I am truly thinking of myself as a start-up, and less of a programmer. As a start-up, I need my software to come to fruition, otherwise there is no RoI. My need to be proficient in all the latest hot techniques is now superceded by the need to build my software business.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which precisely describes where I am at: build my software business.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is high time I got my software out-the-door.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I need a three-to-four (-to-five) year outlook for my software. I need underlying software that supports a longer term. Which is impossible since software changes over in a shorter timeframe. So the shorter timeframe needs to be manage-able. And, sometimes, change needs to be avoided.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laravel 4.2, the current version, the version I learned and really like, is not obsolete. It works, the PHP version(s) it uses is new, its modern ways that I found so attractive are still modern.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ve come to the conclusion that if I have to learn a new revamped version of Laravel, then why don&#39;t I put that learning effort into learning something else? There is actually a something else: the framework upon which Laravel is built: the Symfony Framework. Instead of keeping up with the upcoming Laravel 5&#39;s happenings -- and I just turned off my Laravel GitHub notifications today -- I am delving into Symfony.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The more I delive into Symfony, the more I understand Laravel. It&#39;s a double payoff. The Symfony documentation is very good.&nbsp;I am reading up on Events in the Components PDF (http://symfony.com/doc/current/components/index.html).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Symfony has a very explicit <a href=\"http://symfony.com/doc/current/contributing/community/releases.html\" target=\"_blank\">Road Map</a>. Their change management appears very stated, very measured.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maybe I&#39;ll try Symfony&#39;s templating system called Twig. I have a PhpArchitect article about using Twig in Laravel, so I know it&#39;s do-able.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maybe I&#39;ll see if I can use Symfony&#39;s Event system instead of Laravel&#39;s.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think Laravel 5 is going to have an active post-launch period where it is still subject to change, as a result of mass use. Given how active the GitHub repository is already, IMO there&#39;s going to be an active &quot;settling down&quot; period. So, I&#39;ll see what transpires and assess to what extent I think L5 should be in my software&#39;s future.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I need to settle down into a prolonged period of software development for the sake of the software business I am building. It is important to actually get software out-the-door -- otherwise, this is all moot.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I also want to point out that my proficiency in L4.2 is deepening, which is extremely valuable. At this point I&#39;d rather spend my efforts further deepening my L4.2 proficiency because with such proficiency I can get my software out-the-door. And, I can use my deepening skills to broaden my chops -- especially testing and API.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Getting LaSalleCast to a point where I can use it to re-start my podcasting is very important to me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, I am changing tact in my approach because even more important is finding ways to speed up my development! I have far too much software in mind to build for this pace of development.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are three areas that I am currently seeking, how do I put it, &quot;boilerplate&quot; solutions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first area is form processing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The second area is form building.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The third area is listing records in the Admin.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For form processing, I am building my own solution based on Laravel packages I am currently using. These packages are not providing the comprehensive solution I crave, so I am building the solution I crave.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For form building, I will survey what is out there in the hopes that I can jump on an existing canned solution that relieves me from hand-coding forms.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For listing records in the Admin, I miss this aspect of the Framework-on-Framework that I used for Joomla. My hope is that I can find a similar solution that builds the sorting and filtering and pagination automatically, akin to FoF. In my preliminary searches, there are packages out there to explore.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The idea is to get big chunks of software done in an afternoon, rather than taking days to hand-craft &#39;em. So, I am investing time now to achieve this payoff, at the cost of delaying LaSalleCast. The theory is that the time saved from getting these three areas under my belt will more than offset the delay.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I may further delay LaSalleCast by building a custom&nbsp;email package. Embedded into LaSalleCast will be a little email app, where I can send and recieve emails within LaSalleCast. The advantage is I can track threads with sponsors and guests right in LaSalleCast. Sending and receiving emails is an important aspect of a ticketing&nbsp;app (or more broadly speaking, CRM), and a project management app. So, I am thinking of building this package ahead of LaSalleCast, to have this essential feature figured out and in my back pocket.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'By Halloween I really wanted to have LaSalleCast done to the point where I can resume podcasting...', 'By Halloween I really wanted to have LaSalleCast done to the point where I could at least resume pod', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/a-sense-of-progression14', '2014oct28_laravelTO_presentation/2014-10-28 20.47.06.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-11-08', '2014-11-08 14:42:57', 1, '2014-11-08 16:51:39', 1, NULL, NULL),
(137, 0, NULL, NULL, 'SEO: Take two of these and search for me in the morning', 'search-engine-optimization-magic-pill1', '<p>Search Engine Optimization. Here&#39;s one topic that is conspicuously missing from my blog and podcasts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why would such a well known topic so integral to website success be the exact thing that I avoid talking about.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ll tell you why: I think that SEO is simultaneously complete and utter bullshit; and, is also sublime. But it&#39;s hard to discuss it out the depths of the bullshit that I am usually engaged in.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, I think the general public and&nbsp;clients have a bullshit attitude about SEO. Rare is the sublime.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think &quot;SEO&quot; is really a code word for &quot;Quick Buck&quot;. Or &quot;Quick Fix&quot;. Or &quot;Game The System&quot;. Or, naturally, &quot;Blame The Consultant&quot;. But the ultimate code word is &quot;Snake Oil&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I really do not know which came first: people clamouring for a quick fix to their website ills; or, those who proffer quick fixes. Well, I think the demand comes first. Those who demand quick-and-easy fixes are the reason there are those willing to sell those quick-and-easy fixes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the years, I&#39;ve frustrated my fair share of clients, and the general kick-the-tires crowd, because I refuse&nbsp;to proffer quick fixes to &quot;The Traffic Problem&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Look, if you want track-backs, link-backs, link bait -- the whole bag of tricks -- then get yourself another consultant, because I think that stuff is unadultered bullshit. Look, let&#39;s be honest, in my experience, these types of clients are bullshit clients. They go from one consultant to the next, they complain about each invoice, they are moan-and-woers, and the ratio of free-hours-per-billable-charged-hour is on the high side. Really.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To me, you have two choices with SEO: pay Google; or, roll up your sleeves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To which, I must interject here that I believe that before you worry about SEO, you worry about conversion. Conversion is what it is ultimately about, right? Well, the sites I&#39;ve been involved with over the last near-decade, it is about conversion. It is almost all about conversion.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;m trying a bit of shock therapy here, for a reason. The clients I want to serve are those who (mostly) agree with me about SEO. In separating the wheat from the chaff, I am kicking off my special Client Series with what I think is the most divisive issue surrounding websites. If you are adament that you pump as many &quot;visitors&quot; to your site as you can; that you &quot;drive traffic&quot;; that you &quot;maximize eyeballs&quot; (do people really still say that??), then you are likely not my cup of tea.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once we talk about c-o-n-v-e-r-s-i-o-n, then we can talk about SEO. But we&#39;ll have to dispense with the bullshit. I mean, you don&#39;t need me for that, do you? There are consultants on all four corners of the globe who are happy to dance the dance and then take your money.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And it&#39;s not like I think I am the last word on &quot;SEO Truth&quot;. It&#39;s a big SEO world. You want to run-and-gun, go ahead. You do the shake-and-fake without me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have an SEO philosophy: your site needs to be intrinsically worth being on. Google wants you to have a &quot;real&quot; site where &quot;real&quot; people read, watch, download, and buy. You celebrate that. You offer that. You strive for that. It&#39;s hard! No wonder people are attracted to the snake oil.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have an SEO philosophy:&nbsp;Google wants you to have a REAL site.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I want my clients to have real sites. Sites that have pathways to conversion. Then, I want my clients&#39; sites to look at SEO, because once you have an intrinsically &quot;real&quot; site, you can start earning Google Love.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have an SEO philosophy: real content is crucial. This is itself controversial, but this is my philosophy.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A real site with real content -- and fresh content -- is the kind of client site I want.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have an SEO philosophy: long tail keywords are kick-ass. These keywords should be a natural by-product of your content. It should seem natural to have long tail keywords in your article&#39;s title.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I never thought that obsessing about H2 tags, optimal search term sprinkling, and other tricks really meant much. The meta-tags are pretty well a waste of time. Google publishes changes to their algorithms daily (if not more frequently), so what works yesterday is ineffective today. What matters is what endures, and that&#39;s having a real site.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Building a real site is hard work. And that&#39;s really what separates the wheat from the chaff.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Search Engine Optimization. Here\'s one topic that is conspicuously missing from my blog and podcasts', 'Search Engine Optimization. Here\'s one topic that is conspicuously missing from my blog and podcasts', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/search-engine-optimization-magic-pill1', 'investments1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2014-11-13', '2014-11-13 14:34:06', 1, '2014-11-12 16:00:00', 1, NULL, NULL),
(139, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Sick for Weeks', 'sick-for-weeks1', '<p>On Friday November 14th, I was sure I was coming down with a cold thanks to my children. Usually, I just take it easy for a couple of days and it passes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oh no, not this time! I got something more than what my children had, and it knocked me out. In a week I was told I had bronchitus, and given anti-biotics. Now on my second round of anti-biotics, my verve is returning.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This turned out to be an extended hiatus from programming. Oh, I could have pushed, but my programming&nbsp;is a continuous journey of discovery and learning that is better served when I am sharper than I&#39;ve been over this last month.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I left off my programming disembowelling LaSalleMart into packages. See <a href=\"http://github.com/bbloom\" target=\"_blank\">http://github.com/bbloom</a>. The package I have not yet uploaded is still in progress called &quot;Form Processing&quot;, which handles, well, form processing in the commander style.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I had interrupted my LaSalleCMS packages to do a database backup package, which I did finish at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/bbloom/dbbackup\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/bbloom/dbbackup</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will continue with where I left off. I do want to get my podcasting platform off the ground, so I may stick to the basics before diving into the more ambitious aspects. Especially when I want to get to my ecommerce API sooner than later.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over my hiatus, I decided to cancel my &quot;Client&quot; blog series, which I think set the wrong tone. I will instead do this series with regular blog posts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over my hiatus, I decided that I really should try to promote myself better. This flagship site of mine does need some promotional aspect to it!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My hiatus is over.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'An unexpected programming hiatus due to my flu that became more than just the flu...', 'On Friday November 14th, I was sure I was coming down with a cold thanks to my children. Usually, I', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/sick-for-weeks1', 'SickSmily.gif', 1, 0, 0, '2014-12-08', '2014-12-09 06:54:29', 1, '2014-12-15 14:36:51', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(140, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Bootstrap Framework', 'boostrap-framework1', '<hr />\r\n<h3>Bootstrap is a front-end template framework (<a href=\"http://getbootstrap.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://getbootstrap.com</a>).</h3>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Created as a hobby-ish project at Twitter, now a full fledged leading mobile layout technology. Joomla 3 uses Bootstrap.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With the possibility of using Bootstrap on its own for my first LM app,&nbsp;I&#39;m creating this KB page so I have somewhere to put stuff I am finding.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Good intro at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.onextrapixel.com/2012/11/12/how-to-use-twitter-bootstrap-to-create-a-responsive-website-design/\">http://www.onextrapixel.com/2012/11/12/how-to-use-twitter-bootstrap-to-create-a-responsive-website-design/</a>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>The Joomla User Interface in Joomla 3 at /media/jui/</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>From new&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.linkedin.com/groups/Welcome-Responsive-Design-Frameworks-5050331.S.246422197?view=&amp;srchtype=discussedNews&amp;gid=5050331&amp;item=246422197&amp;type=member&amp;trk=eml-anet_dig-b_pd-ttl-cn&amp;ut=0r-3bdvjsZyRM1\">LinkedIn group</a>:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>It seems that developers really like Bootstrap, because so much styling is done for them, and the sites they can build with Bootstrap don&#39;t look totally awful. (They look similar, sure, but they don&#39;t look awful!)</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Designers seem to start with Bootstrap, and many move to Foundation because it&#39;s more flexible and powerful.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>FOUNDATION link:&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.linkedin.com/redirect?url=http%3A%2F%2Ffoundation%2Ezurb%2Ecom&amp;urlhash=haux&amp;_t=tracking_disc\">http://foundation.zurb.com</a></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Developers have grown to love Bootstrap as it provides styling for all elements, saving them from having to think about visual design.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDesigners are growing to dislike Bootstrap as it provides styling for all elements, complicating the task of visual design.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nI&#39;ve worked with Bootstrap, Foundation, HTMLBP, 320andup, Skeleton, Responsable, Inuit and others. I&#39;ve personally found there to be issues with all of them, which is why I now roll my own. Of those that I have used I strongly favour those that:&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\na) Do not provide any visual &lsquo;design&rsquo;;&nbsp;<br />\r\nb) Do not require me to litter my markup with styling classes;&nbsp;<br />\r\nc) Are authored in Sass!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>--&gt; see&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/nternetinspired/OneWeb\">https://github.com/nternetinspired/OneWeb</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>--&gt; demo at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://joomlafuture.com/\">http://joomlafuture.com/</a></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>(<a href=\"http://blog.southlasallecommerce.com/2013/june-2013-joomla-user-group-toronto-bootstrap-workshop\">My blog post about this workshop</a>)</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.slideshare.net/jen4web/comparing-bootstrap-and-foundation-version-2\">Jen Kramer&#39;s Slideshare comparing Bootstrap wtih Foundation version 2</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://blog.southlasallecommerce.com/2013/november-2013-jugt-jen-kramer\">Jen&#39;s Nov 2013 Presentation to Joomla User Group Toronto</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Links:</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://twitter.github.io/bootstrap/\">The official Bootstrap site</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.joomla.org/3/en#mobile\">Joomla 3: &quot;Mobile Ready&quot;</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://bootstraphero.com/the-big-badass-list-of-twitter-bootstrap-resources\">Badass list of twitter bootstrap resources</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://builtwithbootstrap.com/\">Built with Bootstrap</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://github.com/akeeba/fof\">F</a><a href=\"https://github.com/akeeba/fof\">ramwork on Framework includes Bootstrap, in the &quot;strapper&quot; folder</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://jui.kyleledbetter.com/\">jui.kyleledbetter.com/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://hwdmediashare%20free%20bootstrap%20joomla%20template/\">http://hwdmediashare.co.uk/joomla-templates</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://wright.joomlashack.com/\">http://wright.joomlashack.com/</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://bootsnipp.com/\">https://bootsnipp.com/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.queness.com/post/11632/18-useful-twitter-boostrap-goodies-you-should-know\">18 Useful Bootstrap Goodies</a>&nbsp;|<a href=\"http://mashable.com/2013/10/20/bootstrap-editors\">&nbsp;</a><a href=\"http://mashable.com/2013/10/20/bootstrap-editors/?goback=%2Egde_5050331_member_5799254793377566720#%21\">http://mashable.com/2013/10/20/bootstrap-editors/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://semantic-ui.com/\">http://semantic-ui.com/</a></li>\r\n	<li>**&nbsp;<a href=\"http://stylebootstrap.info/\">http://stylebootstrap.info/</a>&nbsp;(Create unique web design with Twitter Bootstrap. Kw: themes, templates, styles. generator. customize) **</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.html5rocks.com/en/mobile/responsivedesign/\">http://www.html5rocks.com/en/mobile/responsivedesign/</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Bootstrap Themes:</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://bootsnipp.com/\">http://bootsnipp.com</a>&nbsp;(not themes per se, but terrific site!)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://bootstrapzero.com/\">http://bootstrapzero.com</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.prepbootstrap.com/\">http://www.prepbootstrap.com</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Bootstrap Framework', 'Bootstrap Framework', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/boostrap-framework1', 'northshoremountains1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-01-19', '2015-01-20 08:05:23', 1, '2015-01-20 08:26:28', 1, NULL, NULL),
(141, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Continuous Technology', 'continuous-technology1', '<h1>Notes about Continuous Technology</h1>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>There&#39;s a lot of RoI in Continuous Technology. Here are tidbits I&#39;ve come across.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>I&#39;ve blogged about this stuff quite a bit at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://blog.southlasallecommerce.com/\">blog.southlasallecommerce.com</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Read the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://developer.joomla.org/news/562-plt-meeting-notes-may-5-2013.html\">Joomla PLT meeting minutes</a>. Says &quot;Working on integrating Jenkins and Travis-CI&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I read up on Travis-CI and don&#39;t have an intuitive grasp why one would want to integrate. But, very noteworthy to see Joomla move towards CI.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then ended up on &quot;<a href=\"http://www.quora.com/Continuous-Integration-CI/What-is-the-difference-between-Jenkins-CI-CircleCI-Codeship-Travis-CI-Cisimple-Hosted-CI-and-Wercker\">What&#39;s the difference between Jenkins CI, CircleCI, etc</a>?&quot;. Great answer (by founder of CodeShip):</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Jenkins/Hudson (OSS) was the most common service in the past. It&#39;s a huge piece of software, very complex with a lot of features and a shitty UI.&nbsp;<strong>Therefore it&#39;s an absolute pain-in-the-ass to set up&nbsp;</strong>[I concur! -Bob]. When the trend towards cloud started, the Jenkins community tried to keep pace and added plugins. However Jenkins/Hudson never developed as a cloud-based CI&amp;CD solution, especially not for the GitHub-IAAS/PAAS stack.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Various services (mainly startups) have pushed into this space. They all have in common that they are hosted SaaS solutions. Some of them (like hosted-ci.com) are just a hosted Jenkins server, most of them not.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>CIsimple and Hosted-CI are focusing on mobile development. That means, they just support Android and iOS, but not web applications (eg. Ruby projects).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<a href=\"https://circleci.com/\">CircleCI</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.codeship.io/\">Codeship</a>&nbsp;as well as Travis-CI are mainly for web applications. They all support the big frameworks but are different in detail.<br />\r\nWercker is one of the newer services in that space (like many others) but still in beta. I haven&#39;t tried them and I don&#39;t know how their solution looks like.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><a href=\"http://blog.codeship.io/2013/06/04/Testing-Tuesday-8-Behavior-Driven-Integration-and-Unit-Testing.html\">http://blog.codeship.io/2013/06/04/Testing-Tuesday-8-Behavior-Driven-Integration-and-Unit-Testing.html</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.atlassian.com/git/workflows#!workflow-feature-branch\">https://www.atlassian.com/git/workflows#!workflow-feature-branch</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://blogs.atlassian.com/2014/04/practical-continuous-deployment\">http://blogs.atlassian.com/2014/04/practical-continuous-deployment</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'There\'s a lot of RoI in Continuous Technology. Here are tidbits I\'ve come across.', 'There\'s a lot of RoI in Continuous Technology. Here are tidbits I\'ve come across.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/continuous-technology1', 'northshoremountains1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-01-19', '2015-01-20 08:28:50', 1, '2015-01-20 08:28:50', 1, NULL, NULL),
(142, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Akeeba Framework on Framework', 'akeeba-framework-on-framework1', '<hr />\r\n<p>Framework on Framework (v2) is Nicholas&#39; superb Rapid Application Development software to create Joomla applications.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Now included with Joomla 3.2+.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Also called the &quot;RAD&quot; layer (Rapid Application Development) layer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h1>UPDATE (Nov 2014): My interest in Joomla has gone to about nil, except to support my existing clients, and to check out market share at W3Techs.com. My interest in F0F is very high, but practically speaking I am not contributing to the project. A modest little PR, posting knowledge tidbits here, blog posts, podcasts, active in the threads&nbsp;&ndash; the things I used to do I do not do. Still, this page is a good introduction.</h1>\r\n\r\n<h1>Without FoF (F0F), there would have been no LaSalleMart 3.0 development. Period.&nbsp;</h1>\r\n\r\n<h1>-Bob</h1>\r\n\r\n<h1>&nbsp;</h1>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h1>UPDATE (May 2014): My interest in Joomla may have waned, but my interest in the superb Akeeba Framework on Framework is still strong. I am still following all the F0F Google Group threads and GitHub issues. The upcoming &quot;AWF&quot; (Akeeba Web Framework??) is intriguing&nbsp;&ndash; Akeeba Solo is using an early version of AWF.&nbsp;</h1>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My&nbsp;<a href=\"http://southlasalle.com/\">blog</a>&nbsp;mentions FOF all the time. .&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My&nbsp;<a href=\"http://southlasallemedia.com/\">podcasts</a>&nbsp;include FoF chit-chat all the time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>FoF has multiple kick-ass Value Propositions.&nbsp;<strong>So much so that I consider &quot;programming with Joomla&quot; to mean using FoF</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>FoF Value Proposition: FoF mitigates future Joomla version risk;</li>\r\n	<li>FoF Value Proposition: FoF brings out the native strengths of Joomla in ways that Joomla itself lacks;</li>\r\n	<li>FoF Value Proposition: FoF is &quot;Rapid&quot; in the sense that less code is needed to program in Joomla, &nbsp;than programming in Joomla&nbsp;<em>without</em>&nbsp;FoF requires!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>FoF intermediates Joomla versions&nbsp;&ndash; mainly changes in the Joomla platform. So, FoF is a hedge against future changes in the code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you program for FoF, you are programming for&nbsp;<em>future</em>&nbsp;Joomla platform changes - to the extent that it is possible to do so. Having lived the brutal best before code expiration of LaSalleMart 1 (for Joomla 1.5) and LaSalleMart 2 (for Joomla 2.5), I am coding LaSalleMart 3 with the confidence that my Joomla ecommerce technology can glide into Joomla 4 (and beyond). As opposed to shelving the whole thing each time there is a new &nbsp;major Joomla version; and, as opposed to requiring deep rewrites to accommodate the new major Joomla version.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>FoF brings out the native strengths of Joomla, compensating for the surprising inability of Joomla itself to bring out these strengths.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I applaud Nicholas for baking HMVC into FoF. The &quot;H&quot; is bringing an awesome power to LaSallemart.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla is programmed on the &quot;Model View Controller&quot; paradigm. Which is why the folder structure has (wait for it!) &quot;controllers&quot;, &quot;models&quot;, and &quot;views&quot; folders.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The &quot;H&quot; is &quot;Hierachial&quot;&nbsp;&ndash; no, there is no &quot;hierarchial&quot; folder! The &quot;H&quot; means that one component can use another component&#39;s &quot;MVC&quot;. Peek-a-boo, I see you! Good-bye, monolithic impossibly-bloated components!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The &quot;H&quot; means that plugins and modules that need to use a view in a component can actually use that view, instead of recreating that view within the plugin/module. Modules and plugins are so often just a conduit for another component&#39;s view. With FoF, the modules and plugins can fetch the view already existing in a component.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;H&quot; is not merely a feature that LaSalleMart 3 uses here-and-there. &quot;H&quot; is not just a mere convenience. &quot;H&quot; is a deeply profound aspect of Joomla programming for LaSalleMart 3. Components, modules, and plugins are designed on purpose to embrace &quot;H&quot;. They are related!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Saying that FoF is the &quot;RAD layer&quot; is a bit of a misnomer. &quot;RAD&quot; is &quot;Rapid Application Development&quot;, which is an&nbsp;<a href=\"http://searchsoftwarequality.techtarget.com/definition/rapid-application-development\">approach to creating software</a>. Don&#39;t really know what you need for the software you want? No problem! Don&#39;t do One Big Project. Just do 100 little complete projects. Call each little complete project &quot;iteration&quot;, and then use the things you created in the last &quot;iteration&quot; as the starting point for the next &quot;iteration&quot;. FoF is &quot;Rapid&quot; for different reasons that have nothing to do with project methodology.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>FoF is &quot;Rapid&quot; in the sense that it is faster to program in Joomla with FoF than without using FoF.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Programming a Joomla component is faster using FoF than not using FoF.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Let me put it to you this way: programming in Joomla without FoF is&nbsp;<em>slower</em>&nbsp;than using FoF!&nbsp;<em>The Joomla drudgery that FoF takes care of auto-magically</em>, you then have to bake into each and every component you create because you are<em>&nbsp;not</em>&nbsp;using FoF.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>FoF makes building &amp; maintaining custom Joomla components more attractive. So much so that it changes the &quot;buy versus build&quot; proposition. For the time it takes to configure and customize a third party extension, one might as well have just built a FoF based custom extension. So, not only does Joomla have a zillion add-ons. It now offers a tremendous &quot;custom build&quot; proposition.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/TimPlummer/rapid-application-development-using-akeeba-fof-and-joomla-32\">Rapid Application Development using Akeeba FoF and Joomla 3.2 (Slideshare)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Huge thanks to Nicholas, and deep appreciation to everyone involved with FoF.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(from&nbsp;<a href=\"https://groups.google.com/d/msg/frameworkonframework/e7JdfC4BWFY/BJjD8-waBwQJ\">https://groups.google.com/d/msg/frameworkonframework/e7JdfC4BWFY/BJjD8-waBwQJ</a>)</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>&nbsp;What are the preferred naming conventions for controllers, models, tables?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Controllers: Preferred is singular, plural will work<br />\r\nModels: Preferred is plural, singular will work<br />\r\nTables: must be singular&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Google Group:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/frameworkonframework\">https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/frameworkonframework</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Doc:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/akeeba/fof/blob/development/documentation/fof-guide.xml\">https://github.com/akeeba/fof/blob/development/documentation/fof-guide.xml</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Repo:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/akeeba/\">https://github.com/akeeba/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Framework on Framework (v2) is Nicholas\' superb Rapid Application Development software to create Joo', 'Framework on Framework (v2) is Nicholas\' superb Rapid Application Development software to create Joo', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/akeeba-framework-on-framework1', 'northshoremountains1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-01-19', '2015-01-20 08:31:50', 1, '2015-01-20 08:31:50', 1, NULL, NULL),
(143, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Laravel Links', 'laravel-links1', '<hr />\r\n<table>\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th style=\"vertical-align:top\">\r\n			<p>Main Laravel Sites</p>\r\n			</th>\r\n			<th style=\"vertical-align:top\">\r\n			<p>URL</p>\r\n			</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"text-align:right; vertical-align:top\">Laravel site:</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\"><a href=\"http://laravel.com/\">http://laravel.com/</a></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"text-align:right; vertical-align:top\">Laravel forum &amp; community site:</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\"><a href=\"http://laravel.io/\">http://laravel.io/</a></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"text-align:right; vertical-align:top\">Laravel podcast:</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\"><a href=\"http://www.buzzsprout.com/11908\">http://www.buzzsprout.com/11908</a></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"text-align:right; vertical-align:top\">Laracasts:</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">\r\n			<p><a href=\"https://laracasts.com/\">https://laracasts.com</a></p>\r\n\r\n			<ul>\r\n				<li><a href=\"https://laracasts.com/series/build-a-laravel-app-from-scratch/episodes/9\">https://laracasts.com/series/build-a-laravel-app-from-scratch/episodes/9</a></li>\r\n				<li><a href=\"https://github.com/foxted/larabook/\">https://github.com/foxted/larabook/</a></li>\r\n			</ul>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td colspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:right; vertical-align:top\">Laracon Videos:</td>\r\n			<td colspan=\"1\" style=\"vertical-align:top\"><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/channel/UCRawXmZv30Vf_MivyPYb_GQ\">http://www.youtube.com/channel/UCRawXmZv30Vf_MivyPYb_GQ</a></td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2>Laravel Resources Lists:</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://github.com/abhimanyusharma003/Laravel-Resources\">https://github.com/abhimanyusharma003/Laravel-Resources</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://github.com/daylerees/laravel-resources\">https://github.com/daylerees/laravel-resources</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><a href=\"http://laravel.io/forum/02-13-2014-how-to-install-laravel-on-a-hostgator-shared-server\">http://laravel.io/forum/02-13-2014-how-to-install-laravel-on-a-hostgator-shared-server</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><a href=\"http://wiki.laravel.io/Laravel_4\">http://wiki.laravel.io/Laravel_4</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://forumsarchive.laravel.io/viewtopic.php?id=4\">http://forumsarchive.laravel.io/viewtopic.php?id=4</a>&nbsp;(Roadmap)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://taylorotwell.com/\">http://taylorotwell.com/</a>&nbsp;(founder&#39;s blog)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://maxoffsky.com/code-blog/list-cmss-built-laravel/\">http://maxoffsky.com/code-blog/list-cmss-built-laravel/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hollywood_principle\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hollywood_principle</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>From&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.derekmartin.ca/2014/02/25/laravel-at-explodecode/\">http://www.derekmartin.ca/2014/02/25/laravel-at-explodecode/</a>&nbsp;presentation&nbsp;<a href=\"https://southlasalle.atlassian.net/wiki/download/attachments/16056326/laravel.pdf?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1399940923624&amp;api=v2\">2014feb_derekmartin_laravel_presentation.pdf</a>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://southlasalle.atlassian.net/wiki/download/attachments/16056326/laravel.pdf?version=1&amp;modificationDate=1399940923624&amp;api=v2\">2014feb_derekmartin_laravel_presentation.zip</a>):</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://getcomposer.org/doc/01-basic-usage.md\">http://getcomposer.org/doc/01-basic-usage.md</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://four.laravel.com/docs\">http://four.laravel.com/docs</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://net.tutsplus.com/tutorials/php/laravel-4-mastery/\">http://net.tutsplus.com/tutorials/php/laravel-4-mastery/</a>&nbsp;&ndash; Very Good!</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://phpmaster.com/inversion-of-control-the-hollywood-principle/\">http://phpmaster.com/inversion-of-control-the-hollywood-principle/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://vimeo.com/album/2157913/video/53009943\">IoC part1 -&nbsp;http://vimeo.com/album/2157913/video/53009943</a></li>\r\n	<li>IoC part2 -&nbsp;<a href=\"http://vimeo.com/album/2157913/video/53029232\">http://vimeo.com/album/2157913/video/53029232</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://codehappy.daylerees.com/ioc-container\">http://codehappy.daylerees.com/ioc-container</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.purepixel.co.uk/2013/01/laravel-4-first-thoughts/\">http://www.purepixel.co.uk/2013/01/laravel-4-first-thoughts/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/15562528/laravel-4-ioc-container-setting-up-using-providers\">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/15562528/laravel-4-ioc-container-setting-up-using-providers</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.thenerdary.net/post/30859565484/laravel-4\">http://www.thenerdary.net/post/30859565484/laravel-4</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://driesvints.com/blog/using-laravel-4-model-events/\">http://driesvints.com/blog/using-laravel-4-model-events/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://tutsplus.com/lesson/validating-with-models-and-event-listeners/\">https://tutsplus.com/lesson/validating-with-models-and-event-listeners/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://four.laravel.com/docs/ioc\">http://four.laravel.com/docs/ioc</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://fideloper.com/laravel-4-where-to-put-bindings\">http://fideloper.com/laravel-4-where-to-put-bindings</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://net.tutsplus.com/tutorials/php/laravel-4-mastery/\">http://net.tutsplus.com/tutorials/php/laravel-4-mastery/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://github.com/symfony/symfony/tree/master/src/Symfony/Component/HttpKernel/Exception\">https://github.com/symfony/symfony/tree/master/src/Symfony/Component/HttpKernel/Exception</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://medium.com/on-coding/5963ca9d6499\">https://medium.com/on-coding/5963ca9d6499</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.developerdrive.com/2013/10/introducing-laravel-part-1/\">http://www.developerdrive.com/2013/10/introducing-laravel-part-1/</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://laravel.com/docs/facades\">http://laravel.com/docs/facades</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://laravel.uservoice.com/forums/175973-laravel-4/suggestions/3150953-more-simple-way-to-extends-core-class\">http://laravel.uservoice.com/forums/175973-laravel-4/suggestions/3150953-more-simple-way-to-extends-core-class</a></li>\r\n	<li>Great DB profiling package: bkwld on github</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://taylorotwell.com/full-ioc-unit-testing-with-laravel/\">http://taylorotwell.com/full-ioc-unit-testing-with-laravel/</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>LaraconNYC 2014 talk. #7 and #8 about how-to really do controllers; event-listener... very good vid.&nbsp;<a href=\"https://laracasts.com/lessons/laracasts-live\">https://laracasts.com/lessons/laracasts-live</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Laracon EU 2014:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laravel Tricks/Tips in-depth --&gt; fabulous!&nbsp;<a href=\"https://speakerdeck.com/anlutro/in-depth-laravel-tricks-and-tips\">https://speakerdeck.com/anlutro/in-depth-laravel-tricks-and-tips</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>TDD The Good Parts (Adam Wathan of LaravelTO)&nbsp;<a href=\"https://speakerdeck.com/adamwathan/tdd-the-good-parts-1\">https://speakerdeck.com/adamwathan/tdd-the-good-parts-1</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finding a lot of Laravel &amp; Composer related links. Not sure where to put everything, and I want these in one page. So going to throw some mix-and-match links here:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.phpclasses.org/blog/post/236-PHP-Composer-Private-Repository-Automatic-Access.html\">http://www.phpclasses.org/blog/post/236-PHP-Composer-Private-Repository-Automatic-Access.html</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://transmission.vehikl.com/\">http://transmission.vehikl.com/</a>&nbsp;--&gt; GOOD BLOG!\r\n	<ul style=\"list-style-type:disc\">\r\n		<li><a href=\"http://transmission.vehikl.com/theres-a-model-hiding-in-your-rest-api/\">http://transmission.vehikl.com/theres-a-model-hiding-in-your-rest-api</a>&nbsp;--&gt; REALLY GOOD!</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://adamwathan.me/\">http://adamwathan.me</a>&nbsp;(Works for Vehikl)</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/3616293/tdd-the-good-parts.pdf\">https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/3616293/tdd-the-good-parts.pdf</a>&nbsp;--&gt; READ THIS!</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://confluence.jetbrains.com/display/PhpStorm/Composer+Support+in+PhpStorm\">http://confluence.jetbrains.com/display/PhpStorm/Composer+Support+in+PhpStorm</a>&nbsp;(COMPOSER-PHPSTORM)</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.phpclasses.org/blog/post/236-PHP-Composer-Private-Repository-Automatic-Access.html\">http://www.phpclasses.org/blog/post/236-PHP-Composer-Private-Repository-Automatic-Access.html</a>&nbsp;(COMPOSER &amp; pvt repos)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Open source application built with Laravel, for learning!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://cribbb.com/\">http://cribbb.com</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://github.com/cribbb/cribbb\">http://github.com/cribbb/cribbb</a>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>BLOG WITH LARAVEL TIPS:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://culttt.com/code\">http://culttt.com/code</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>EXCELLENT SERIES&nbsp;&ndash; scroll to the bottom!&nbsp;<a href=\"http://culttt.com/2014/04/14/sending-email-laravel-4/\">http://culttt.com/2014/04/14/sending-email-laravel-4/</a>&nbsp;(a touch out of date, I ignore the install instructions)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DIY BLOG WITH LARAVEL WITH THEME: &nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/rufhausen/brewski\">https://github.com/rufhausen/brewski</a>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>Command Bus vs Events</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>PHP NW 2013 sessions:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3uV3ngl1Z8g\">Ross Tuck - Models and Service Layers</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ElnqUIjLWVk\">Rob Allen = Introducing Dependency Injection</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.reddit.com/r/PHP/comments/29a6qz/what_am_i_missing_with_this_whole_command_bus/cij6avo\">http://www.reddit.com/r/PHP/comments/29a6qz/what_am_i_missing_with_this_whole_command_bus/cij6avo</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://rosstuck.com/phpnw13-models-service-layers-talk/\">http://rosstuck.com/phpnw13-models-service-layers-talk/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/rosstuck/models-and-service-layers-hemoglobin-and-hobgoblins\">http://www.slideshare.net/rosstuck/models-and-service-layers-hemoglobin-and-hobgoblins</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://rosstuck.com/domain-events-on-creation/\">http://rosstuck.com/domain-events-on-creation/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Modules instead of packages:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://creolab.hr/2013/05/modules-in-laravel-4/\">http://creolab.hr/20</a>http://mattstauffer.co/blog/upgrading-from-laravel-4-to-laravel-5<a href=\"http://creolab.hr/2013/05/modules-in-laravel-4/\">13/05/modules-in-laravel-4/</a>&nbsp; and &nbsp;<a href=\"http://creolab.hr/2013/10/modules-laravel-4-part-2/\">http://creolab.hr/2013/10/modules-laravel-4-part-2/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>HOMESTEAD:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.sitepoint.com/6-reasons-move-laravel-homestead/\">http://www.sitepoint.com/6-reasons-move-laravel-homestead/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2>LINKS ADDED JAN2015 AND BEYOND:</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://mattstauffer.co/blog/upgrading-from-laravel-4-to-laravel-5\" target=\"_blank\">http://mattstauffer.co/blog/upgrading-from-laravel-4-to-laravel-5</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.maatwebsite.nl/laravel-excel/docs\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.maatwebsite.nl/laravel-excel/docs</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/thecanarycollective/station\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/thecanarycollective/station</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://blog.orchestraplatform.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://blog.orchestraplatform.com/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/orchestral/config\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/orchestral/config</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://mattstauffer.co/blog/extending-laravels-application\" target=\"_blank\">http://mattstauffer.co/blog/extending-laravels-application</a>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s seldom that we need to extend Laravel&#39;s core, and even when we do, it&#39;s most likely we&#39;re going to extend specific components, which is&nbsp;<a href=\"http://laravel.com/docs/4.2/extending\">detailed in the docs</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, all of these instructions presume you&#39;re using the core Laravel Application (IOC Container) to extend the other classes.&nbsp;<strong>What if you want to extend the&nbsp;<code>Application</code>&nbsp;itself</strong>?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Laravel links', 'Laravel links', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/laravel-links1', 'northshoremountains1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-01-20', '2015-01-20 12:17:40', 1, '2015-01-27 11:09:24', 1, NULL, NULL),
(144, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Mandrill', 'mandrill1', '<hr />\r\n<h2><strong>MANDRILL IN LARAVEL 4.2 at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://laravel.com/docs/mail\">http://laravel.com/docs/mail</a></strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2>Mandrill = sending auto-generated site emails via MailChimp&#39;s system</h2>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Your site sends out emails. So, what happens when your recipient does not get it? You are totally SoL. There&#39;s no way to track what happened.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What if I told you there was a professional reputable service that sent your website&#39;s automatically generated outgoing email, and tracked what happened. Just as if you logged into&nbsp;&ndash; well, MailChimp.com&nbsp;&ndash; and sent an email blast from MC. You get all the stats and tracking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://mandrill.com/\">Mandrill.com</a>&nbsp;is this service. It&#39;s terrific! There&#39;s only one problem: it&#39;s really really really expensive! I mean, I&#39;m talking about one of those tiered pricing... well, the first 12,000 emails per month Mandrill sends out for you is free. Then, it&#39;s borsht after that. Yeah, what I am saying is there&#39;s this new kick-ass email service by a reputable outfit that is giving the service away.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ve had my eye on Mandrill for a while. Today, the time came to get to it. Interestingly, the problem is the first LaSalleMart app I am creating. It&#39;s supposed to send out emails&nbsp;&ndash; very important emails. My clients really need these emails tracked that my app sends automatically. So, I want to use Mandrill.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Other Links:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.codecademy.com/tracks/mandrill\">http://www.codecademy.com/tracks/mandrill</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://blog.mandrill.com/\">http://blog.mandrill.com/</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Setting up your SPF record in DNS settings</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mandrill automatically adds any domain you use for sending through Mandrill. Mandrill also automatically adds authentication to all messages sent through our servers, but adding SPF and DKIM records for your sending domain(s) is strongly recommended for better deliverability.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.mail-tester.com/spf/cpanel\">http://www.mail-tester.com/spf/cpanel</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://support.google.com/a/bin/answer.py?hl=en&amp;answer=33786\">Understand SPF records (in Google Apps help)</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://help.mandrill.com/entries/22030056-how-do-i-add-dns-records-for-my-sending-domains\">Mandrill.com: how do I add DNS records for my sending domains?</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>The purpose of an SPF record is to prevent spammers from sending messages with forged From addresses at your domain. Recipients can refer to the SPF record to determine whether a message purporting to be from your domain comes from an authorized mail server.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>', 'Mailchimp.com\'s Mandrill API', 'Mailchimp.com\'s Mandrill API', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/mandrill1', 'northshoremountains1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-01-20', '2015-01-20 12:22:41', 1, '2015-01-20 12:22:41', 1, NULL, NULL),
(145, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Laravel Packages', 'laravel-packages1', '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th style=\"vertical-align:top\">\r\n			<p>Name</p>\r\n			</th>\r\n			<th style=\"vertical-align:top\">\r\n			<p>Link</p>\r\n			</th>\r\n			<th style=\"vertical-align:top\">\r\n			<p>Comment</p>\r\n			</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">Virtuoso</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\"><a href=\"https://github.com/coderabbi/virtuoso\">https://github.com/coderabbi/virtuoso</a></td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">\r\n			<p>Increase flexibility and reduce code duplication by easily composing complex View Composers from simple component Composers without unnecessary indirection or boilerplate code.</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Excellent readme!</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">Ardent</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\"><a href=\"https://github.com/laravelbook/ardent\">https://github.com/laravelbook/ardent</a></td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">Self-validating smart models for Laravel Framework 4&#39;s Eloquent O/RM.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">DB backup</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\"><a href=\"https://github.com/heybigname/backup-manager\">https://github.com/heybigname/backup-manager</a></td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">Database backup manager for dumping to and restoring databases from S3, Dropbox, FTP, SFTP, and Rackspace Cloud.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">Generators</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\"><a href=\"https://github.com/JeffreyWay/Laravel-4-Generators\">https://github.com/JeffreyWay/Laravel-4-Generators</a></td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">This Laravel 4 package provides a variety of generators to speed up your development process.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td colspan=\"1\" style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td colspan=\"1\" style=\"vertical-align:top\"><a href=\"https://github.com/laracasts/Validation\">https://github.com/laracasts/Validation</a></td>\r\n			<td colspan=\"1\" style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td colspan=\"1\" style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td colspan=\"1\" style=\"vertical-align:top\"><a href=\"https://github.com/laracasts/Commander\">https://github.com/laracasts/Commander</a></td>\r\n			<td colspan=\"1\" style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Tuts:</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th style=\"vertical-align:top\">\r\n			<p>Name</p>\r\n			</th>\r\n			<th style=\"vertical-align:top\">\r\n			<p>Link</p>\r\n			</th>\r\n			<th style=\"vertical-align:top\">\r\n			<p>Comment</p>\r\n			</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\"><a href=\"http://blog.kongnir.com/2013/09/18/laravel-4-things-to-note-when-creating-package/\">http://blog.kongnir.com/2013/09/18/laravel-4-things-to-note-when-creating-package/</a></td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\"><a href=\"http://jasonlewis.me/article/laravel-4-develop-packages-using-the-workbench\">http://jasonlewis.me/article/laravel-4-develop-packages-using-the-workbench</a></td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\"><a href=\"http://laravel.com/docs/packages\">http://laravel.com/docs/packages</a></td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">\r\n			<p><a href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/tihomiropacic/laravel-4-package-development\">http://www.slideshare.net/tihomiropacic/laravel-4-package-development</a></p>\r\n\r\n			<p><a href=\"https://github.com/orangehill/Laravel-Workbench-Walkthrough\">https://github.com/orangehill/Laravel-Workbench-Walkthrough</a></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n			<td style=\"vertical-align:top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>', 'Laravel Packages', 'Laravel Packages', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/laravel-packages1', 'northshoremountains1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-01-20', '2015-01-20 12:24:15', 1, '2015-01-20 12:24:26', 1, NULL, NULL),
(146, 0, NULL, NULL, 'PHP: Traits vs. Interfaces', 'php-traits-vs-interfaces1', '<hr />\r\n<h1>EXCELLENT ARTICLE!</h1>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/9205083/php-traits-vs-interfaces\">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/9205083/php-traits-vs-interfaces</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h1>MONEY QUOTE FROM THE ARTICLE:</h1>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Traits, on the other hand, are simply a method for re-using code. Interfaces should not be thought of as a mutually exclusive alternative to traits. In fact,&nbsp;<strong><em>creating traits that fulfill the capabilities required by an interface is the ideal use case</em></strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You should only use traits when multiple classes share the same functionality (<em>likely dictated by the same interface</em>). There&#39;s no sense in using a trait to provide functionality for a single class: that only obfuscates what the class does and a better design would move the trait&#39;s functionality into the relevant class.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<h1>SELECTED QUOTE FROM THE ARTICLE:</h1>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Public Service Announcement:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>I want to state for the record that I believe traits are almost always a code smell and should be avoided in favor of composition. It&#39;s my opinion that single inheritance is frequently abused to the appoint of being an anti-pattern and multiple inheritance only compounds this problem. You&#39;ll be much better served in most cases by favoring composition over inheritance (be it single or multiple). If you&#39;re still interested in traits and their relationship to interfaces, read on ...</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Let&#39;s start by saying this:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) can be a difficult paradigm to grasp. Just because you&#39;re using classes doesn&#39;t mean your code is Object-Oriented (OO).</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>To write OO code you need to understand that OOP is really about the capabilities of your objects. You&#39;ve got to think about classes in terms of what they&nbsp;<strong><em>can do</em></strong>&nbsp;instead of what they&nbsp;<strong><em>actually do</em></strong>. This is in stark contrast to traditional procedural programming where the focus is on making a bit of code &quot;do something.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If OOP code is about planning and design, an interface is the blueprint and an object the fully constructed house. Meanwhile, traits are simply a way to help build the house laid out by the blueprint (the interface).</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Interfaces</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>So why should we use interfaces? Quite simply, interfaces make our code less brittle. If you doubt this statement, ask anyone who&#39;s been forced to maintain legacy code that wasn&#39;t written against interfaces.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The interface is a contract between the programmer and his/her code. The interface says, &quot;As long as you play by my rules you can implement me however you like and I promise I won&#39;t break your other code.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>...This approach works great. But maybe a few weeks later you decide you want to use a file-based cache system instead of APC. Now you have to change your controller code because you&#39;ve programmed your controller to work with the functionality of the&nbsp;<code>ApcCacher</code>&nbsp;class rather than to an interface that expresses the capabilities of the&nbsp;<code>ApcCacher</code>&nbsp;class. Let&#39;s say instead of the above you had made the&nbsp;<code>Controller</code>&nbsp;class reliant on a&nbsp;<code>CacherInterface</code>&nbsp;instead of the concrete&nbsp;<code>ApcCacher</code>&nbsp;like so:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code>// your controller&#39;s constructor using the interface as a dependency&nbsp;public&nbsp;function __construct(Request $req,&nbsp;Response $resp,&nbsp;CacherInterface $cacher=NULL)</code></pre>\r\n\r\n<p>To go along with that you define your interface like so:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code>interface&nbsp;CacherInterface&nbsp;{&nbsp;public&nbsp;function fetch($key);&nbsp;public&nbsp;function store($key, $data);&nbsp;public&nbsp;function&nbsp;delete($key);&nbsp;}</code></pre>\r\n\r\n<p>In turn you have both your&nbsp;<code>ApcCacher</code>&nbsp;and your new&nbsp;<code>FileCacher</code>&nbsp;classes implement the&nbsp;<code>CacherInterface</code>&nbsp;and you program your&nbsp;<code>Controller</code>&nbsp;class to use the capabilities required by the interface.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This example (hopefully) demonstrates how programming to an interface allows you to change the internal implementation of your classes without worrying if the changes will break your other code.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Traits</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Traits, on the other hand, are simply a method for re-using code. Interfaces should not be thought of as a mutually exclusive alternative to traits. In fact,&nbsp;<strong><em>creating traits that fulfill the capabilities required by an interface is the ideal use case</em></strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You should only use traits when multiple classes share the same functionality (likely dictated by the same interface). There&#39;s no sense in using a trait to provide functionality for a single class: that only obfuscates what the class does and a better design would move the trait&#39;s functionality into the relevant class.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Consider the following trait implementation:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Unknown macro: {code here, goto article to see it}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nA more concrete example: imagine both your&nbsp;<code>FileCacher</code>&nbsp;and your&nbsp;<code>ApcCacher</code>&nbsp;from the interface discussion use the same method to determine whether a cache entry is stale and should be deleted (obviously this isn&#39;t the case in real life,&nbsp;but go with it). You could write a trait and allow both classes to use it to for the common interface requirement.</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>One final word of caution: be careful not to go overboard with traits. Often traits are used as a crutch for poor design when unique class implementations would suffice. You should limit traits to fulfilling interface requirements for best code design.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'PHP: Traits vs. Interfaces', 'PHP: Traits vs. Interfaces', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/php-traits-vs-interfaces1', 'northshoremountains1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-01-20', '2015-01-20 12:26:12', 1, '2015-01-20 12:26:12', 1, NULL, NULL),
(147, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Links', 'general-links1', '<p>API DEVELOPMENT:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.phproundtable.com/episode/all-about-web-apis-raml-oauth-hateoas\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.phproundtable.com/episode/all-about-web-apis-raml-oauth-hateoas</a>&nbsp;(RAML&nbsp;@1:06:00)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://restful-api-design.readthedocs.org/en/latest/scope.html\" target=\"_blank\">https://restful-api-design.readthedocs.org/en/latest/scope.html</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://apiary.io/\" target=\"_blank\">http://apiary.io/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://apiblueprint.org/\" target=\"_blank\">http://apiblueprint.org/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/apiaryio/dredd\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/apiaryio/dredd</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://apigility.org/\" target=\"_blank\">https://apigility.org/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/dingo/api\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/dingo/api</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/dingo/api/issues/213\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/dingo/api/issues/213</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SEO</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://yoast.com/meta-descriptions\" target=\"_blank\">https://yoast.com/meta-descriptions</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LIST OF HANDY SAAS TOOLS</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://blog.hubstaff.com/saas-growth-tools/\" target=\"_blank\">http://blog.hubstaff.com/saas-growth-tools/</a></p>', 'General links', 'General links', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/general-links1', 'northshoremountains1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-01-26', '2015-01-26 14:22:24', 1, '2015-01-26 14:22:24', 1, NULL, NULL),
(148, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Flagship Blog for All My Blog Sites', 'flagship-blog-for-all-my-blog-sites1', '<p>Seemed like a good idea to have a blog on each product site. LaSalleMart articles should appear on my LaSalleMart.com site. LaSalleCMS articles should appear on my LaSalleCMS.com site -- right!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Good in theory, lousy in practice.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, there&#39;s just one blog site, here at my flagship site.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Never mind that you have to go from site to site to see all my blog entries, on this side of the keyboard, maintaining different blogs is a pain.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But, what I did not expect, but happens all the time, is that I talk about my different projects in a single post. Hey, they are related projects -- related behind the scenes at least from a development point of view.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Right now, LaSalleMart and LaSalleCMS development are deeply related. I mention them hand-in-hand all the time. So, what to do?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Post in LaSalleMart.com and link from LaSalleCMS.com? Post in one site and then paste the article in the other site (BTW, never do this)?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then in each site have headline links to my other blog sites? Who has the patience to traverse all these sites?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Just going to have one blog with everything!</p>', 'One blog on my flagship site instead of blogging on my individual sites.', 'ipso lorum the ipso lorum the ipso lorum the ipso lorum the', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/flagship-blog-for-all-my-blog-sites1', 'server-consolidation-image1.gif', 1, 0, 0, '2015-01-26', '2015-01-27 02:03:46', 1, '2015-01-27 03:36:57', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(149, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Announcement: LaSalleMart API will be Released as Free Open Source Software', 'announcement-lasallemart-api-released-free-open-source-software1', '<p>LaSalleMart 4&#39;s API will be released as free open source software (FOSS).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 4 is the fourth version of my ecommerce technology. It is the first version that is not a Joomla add-on. LM v4 is based on the Laravel Framework. This from-scratch development is just commencing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The API will be a true API and not just an &quot;internal&quot; API as originally conceived.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The main driver for releasing LM&#39;s API as FOSS is marketing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Software development itself is now a marketing exercise as people can see progress in real-time. FOSS software affirms that the software does exist, and that there is ongoing developmental effort.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The &quot;<a href=\"http://individual.utoronto.ca/markfederman/article_mediumisthemessage.htm\" target=\"_blank\">medium is the message</a>&quot;. Do I really develop ecommerce software? Do I really have competency in this area? Have I progressed with Laravel as I keep asserting? Now, you can just see for yourself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 4&#39;s administrative back-end, and website front-end, will <em>not</em> be available as FOSS.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have zero expectations that others will be interested in contributing to my projects. Truthfully, I am not looking for contributors. Maybe later...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Closed JIRA and Confluence Subscriptions</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Having mentioned Atlassian quite a bit in my blog and podcasts, it is noteworthy that I just closed my JIRA and Confluence subscriptions. Releasing my LaSalleCMS blogging software as FOSS, and releasing LM&#39;s API as open source, I am shifting over to GitHub. I have not used JIRA in a while, and do not really plan on using it. Confluence on its own does not make sense because it&#39;s value is in its deep integration with the other Atlassian offerings. Using it just as a knowledge based website does not make sense, given that I am developing my own content system. So, I copied my Confluence content to my sites, and deleted my Confluence Spaces. Then, I reviewed my JIRA Projects and deleted each one.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Created GitHub.com Organizations</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>I just created <a href=\"https://github.com/lasallecms\" target=\"_blank\">LaSalleCMS</a> and <a href=\"https://github.com/lasallemart\" target=\"_blank\">LaSalleMart</a> organizations on GitHub.com. I&#39;ll be moving/creating repos for these orgs as I progress.&nbsp;</p>', 'LaSalleMart API will be released as free open source software (FOSS)', 'LaSalleMart API will be released as free open source software (FOSS)', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/announcement-lasallemart-api-released-free-open-source-software1', 'foss1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-01-26', '2015-01-27 03:57:56', 1, '2015-01-27 04:08:36', 1, NULL, NULL),
(150, 0, NULL, NULL, '2015 Development Road Map', '2015-development-road-map1', '<p>Although I stated my 2015 Road Map in my January 2015 podcast, I want to re-state it here with updates.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the time of my podcast, I had not decided to develop a true API for LaSalleMart, not just an &quot;internal&quot; API. As well, I am releasing this API as FOSS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The decision to develop a true API precipated an unexpected research journey. Between this research, and intense volunteer work that needed to be done (and not expected to repeat this year), January did not see much code production. Well, that&#39;s about to change.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How I develop my LaSalleMart API profoundly affects my LaSalleCMS and LaSalleCast development. It is imperative that I progress with LM&#39;s API before proceeding with any other development.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My API development represents a profound change in how I program code. Not only will I do more up-front planning; but, for the first time I will do Test Driven Development (TDD). Which may over-state things a bit, but I will be programming in conjunction with unit testing (with PhpUnit).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will refactor (re-write) LaSalleCMS. The centrepiece of this refactoring will be a new LaSalleCMS API. Same with LaSalleCast development. This API development depends on what is learned from LM&#39;s API development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, February&#39;s development will be dominated by LaSalleMart&#39;s API development. I just want to develop a basic, yet workable,&nbsp;ecommerce API.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then, I want to turn my attention to LaSalleCMS. The reason: LaSalleCMS is the predicate to other development. Unlike LaSalleMart, LaSalleCMS already has a full administrative back-end, and a front-end, both which will be re-worked. And, then, will be available to LaSalleMart and LaSalleCast development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a nice little list of things that LaSalleCMS needs: user management, login management, permissions, tag search, and on and on. I figure that I will release a renewed &quot;version one point oh&quot; LaSalleCMS in March.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a bunch of pieces that I want to build as part of LaSalleCast. Pieces that can be used anywhere, but that I have specific uses for in LaSalleCast. As I&#39;ve mentioned before, a main piece is the email handling.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I do not feel pressured to get LaSalleCast all done by a certain date, primarily as this app is really just for my use. However, I do feel a certain urgency getting the major pieces done, and getting LaSalleCast done to the point where I can migrate my existing Media site to it -- which will be a major effort. So, there&#39;s leeway with LaSalleCast, but it&#39;s something I want sooner than later. Otherwise, I could end the year with LaSalleCast and my new Media site not done.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With LaSalleMart&#39;s basic API done, and with LaSalleCMS v2.0 released (which will likely be completely FOSS&#39;d), I can then turn my attention to LaSalleMart&#39;s administrative back-end. Before this development is complete, I plan on seeking client sponsorship for this development, and for the first front-end development effort. As well, I plan on seeking client sponsorship on further LaSalleMart API development, as well as building a front-end LaSalleMart&nbsp;site. There will be plenty of LaSalleCMS resources to use at this point, and I plan on adding some hooks into LaSalleCMS.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>To Summarize...</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>basic, but workable, LaSalleMart ecommerce API done by end of February (we&#39;ll see!);</li>\r\n	<li>fully refactored LaSalleCMS 2.0, including new API, and revamped administrative back-end by end of March;</li>\r\n	<li>all my sites, except my Media site, converted to LaSalleCMS 2.0 by end of March (they are already using v1);</li>\r\n	<li>start LaSalleCMS administrative back-end in April;</li>\r\n	<li>start LaSalleCast&#39;s email feature, and other major features, in April;</li>\r\n	<li>finish LaSalleCast&#39;s API, and administrative back-end, by June;</li>\r\n	<li>build new Media site during the summer;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Laravel 5</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>I had serious reservations about Laravel 5, to the point where I decided I better just stick with the wonderful Laravel 4.2 for my Software Trio&#39;s ongoing development. And, to the point where I decided I should learn about the framework Laravel is based on -- Symfony Framework.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, Laravel 5&#39;s development changed course. So much so that the excitement I had for Laravel back in May when I dove into it has returned.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laravel 5 is looking mighty good, and is on the verge of being released as beta. Probably now it is ok to use, as it is unofficially beta now. But, once bitten, twice shy, with Laravel alpha software. I&#39;ll have to overcome my reticence, as the time to learn it has arrived.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All my development will be done in Laravel 5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleCMS is up for deep refactoring, so moving to L5 is just a part of this refactoring. LaSalleMart and LaSalleCast development has not begun, so there are no barriers to using L5.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think there&#39;s just one package I&#39;ll need to upgrade -- my database backup package. I might just refactor it anyways, for use with the new L5 &quot;CRON&quot; feature (is that what it is called?).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Before my nasty and prolonged flu hammered me, I was working on a fork of Jeffrey Way&#39;s Command Bus package. I wanted a nice little plain vanilla command bus package. Well, I can toss all that work overboard as L5 has its own implementation of the command bus; and, as well, has new event handling. I need to deep dive into this aspect of L5, and am glad I messed with the command bus package which helped me learn what it was all about. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>APIARY.IO</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>I discovered this month (January 2015) that there&#39;s a lot of tools out there for API development. It&#39;s big business. Well, I think I am going to try <a href=\"http://apiary.io/\" target=\"_blank\">apiary.io</a>&nbsp;for API documentation and prototyping.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The site found two rounds of financing totally $1.8million by 2011 (see this <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2011/07/29/apiary-aims-to-take-the-headache-out-of-api-creation-documentation-springboard/\" target=\"_blank\">TechCrunch article</a>).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2015 Road Map, as updated in late January 2015', 'Although I stated my 2015 Road Map in my January 2015 podcast, I want to re-state it here with updat', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/2015-development-road-map1', 'toronto-road-map-1970.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-01-26', '2015-01-27 04:25:19', 1, '2015-01-27 07:03:08', 1, NULL, NULL),
(151, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Artisan Files Interview', 'artisan-files-interview1', '<p>My January 2015 interview at the Artisan Files is up at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://laravel-news.com/2015/01/artisan-files-bob-bloom/\" target=\"_blank\">https://laravel-news.com/2015/01/artisan-files-bob-bloom</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Eric Barnes sent me seven questions. I wrote out answers to five of &#39;em!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'January 2015 interview at the Artisan Files, by Laravel News\' Eric Barnes.', 'January 2015 interview at the Artisan Files, by Laravel News\' Eric Barnes.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/artisan-files-interview1', 'laravel-news1.png', 1, 0, 0, '2015-01-26', '2015-01-27 07:12:22', 1, '2015-01-27 07:24:50', 1, NULL, NULL),
(152, 0, NULL, NULL, 'January 2015 Laravel Toronto Meet-up', 'january-2015-laravel-toronto-meet-up1', '<p>Made it to deep downtown last Thursday for the Laravel Toronto Meet-up. It snowed, but not as much as the radio forecasted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kudos to Graham for presenting his Laravel 4.2 code. I got a lot out of the tour, and as much from the banter of the SoapBox programmers during the presentation. The discussion about &quot;lessons learned&quot; as they progressed with building their large app was especially interesting. All of it was directly applicable to my Software Trio&#39;s development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As usual, SoapBox is very hospitable to the Toronto Laravel community:&nbsp;making their excellent facility available for these meet-ups, ordering pizzas, and many of their programmers and associates are there to talk up Laravel.</p>', 'SoapBox presented their Laravel 4.2 codebase. Very informative. Excellent discussion...', 'SoapBox presented their Laravel 4.2 codebase. Very informative. Excellent discussion...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/january-2015-laravel-toronto-meet-up1', '2015jan29_laravelTO/2015jan29_laravelTO1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-02-02', '2015-02-02 16:52:46', 1, '2015-02-02 17:06:45', 1, NULL, NULL),
(153, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Laravel 5 Package Development', 'laravel-5-package-development1', '<p>As affirmed in this recent podcast,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.laravelpodcast.com/episodes/7372-episode-22-laravel-5-laracon-announcements-live-q-a\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.laravelpodcast.com/episodes/7372-episode-22-laravel-5-laracon-announcements-live-q-a</a>, the &quot;workbench&quot; facility for Laravel 4 package development is not included in the new Laravel 5. In its place, there is... nothing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More about package development during&nbsp;the January 2015 Dallas/Fort Worth Laravel Group&#39;s hangout at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XrBoZE_jnSo&amp;t=52m10s\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XrBoZE_jnSo&amp;t=52m</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most of my development will be packages, so this L5&nbsp;&quot;development&quot; (excuse my pun) is rather profound.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Packages are add-ons. You start with your base&nbsp;app, and then you can install add-ons (aka &quot;packages&quot;).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, knowing how exactly I will go about doing my packages in Laravel 5 is an important thing. Which is why I spent some time figuring it out.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The solution I came up with is like the &quot;workbench&quot; facility. The package resides in its own folder separate from the app; and, separate from the &quot;vendor&quot; folder. The package has its own git repository in its root folder.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, it is possible to develop&nbsp;the package within a L5&nbsp;app -- very important! -- and not worry about composer updates over-writing dev files.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I suspect that my package development set-up is made possible by PSR-4 in the app&#39;s composer.json, a new thing in L5; and, likely, the main reason why &quot;workbench&quot; was scrapped.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, first I installed the L5 app as usual. I customized it a bit.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then, I set up this L5 app for package development.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My GitHub repository is at:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/bbloom/Laravel_Custom_Organization\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/bbloom/Laravel_Custom_Organization</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Please note the issues, which are also tied into the commits, which act as a &quot;step-by-step&quot; guide (mostly), at:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://github.com/bbloom/Laravel_Custom_Organization/issues\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/bbloom/Laravel_Custom_Organization/issues</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will be adding to this repo as my L5 package development progresses.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whew, glad to have this figured out!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some (related) links:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Taylor Otwell talks about <strong>L5 paths</strong> in this same hangout at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XrBoZE_jnSo&amp;t=1h12m\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XrBoZE_jnSo&amp;t=1h12m</a></li>\r\n	<li>Matt Stauffer&#39;s excellent post about <strong>overriding the Application&#39;s paths</strong> at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://mattstauffer.co/blog/laravel-5.0-environment-detection-and-environment-variables\" target=\"_blank\">http://mattstauffer.co/blog/laravel-5.0-environment-detection-and-environment-variables</a></li>\r\n	<li>Laracasts&#39;<strong> PSR-4 autoloading </strong>video (subscription required) at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://laracasts.com/lessons/psr-4-autoloading\" target=\"_blank\">https://laracasts.com/lessons/psr-4-autoloading</a></li>\r\n	<li>excellent thread:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://laracasts.com/discuss/channels/general-discussion/l5-package-configuration-file\" target=\"_blank\">https://laracasts.com/discuss/channels/general-discussion/l5-package-configuration-file</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'My custom solution for developing Laravel 5 packages.', 'My custom solution for developing Laravel 5 packages.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/laravel-5-package-development1', 'package1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-02-05', '2015-02-06 05:53:09', 1, '2015-02-13 16:20:29', 1, NULL, NULL),
(154, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Update', 'update-early-february-20151', '<h3>Laravel 5</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Laravel 5 just came out, so I&#39;ve been digging into it. I am in a great position to refactor the software I&#39;ve developed with L4.2 to L5, so that&#39;s what i will do. All new software will use L5.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>New GitHub Respositories so can use the Issue Tracking</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>I have a problem: where do I jot down little research nuggets.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I know I&#39;ll be doing a user management package, so I want to put interesting GitHub, articles, and stuff somewhere so I can refer to them when I am working on this package.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I used Confluence for this, but it was frustrating so I close my subscription. I do have knowledge bases on my sites, but even then it&#39;s a bit frustrating.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, I am trying something new:&nbsp;I am creating repositories on GitHub.com so I can use its issue tracker. I am keeping my notes and stuff in the issue tracker.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I decided to make this stuff public, so you can see the progression.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Boy, there&#39;s a lot of stuff already.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>New GitHub.com Organizations</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>I created new GitHub organizations:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://github.com/lasallecms\" target=\"_blank\">LaSalleCMS</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://github.com/lasallemart\" target=\"_blank\">LaSalleMart</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://github.com/lasallecast\" target=\"_blank\">LaSalleCast</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://github.com/lasallecrm\" target=\"_blank\">LaSalleCRM</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Repos for my L5 packages and apps will reside here.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I already created issues for research nuggets in CMS, and will do so for the other orgs as the need arises.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>LaSalleCRM</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>My Software Trio has a new addition -- I should now call it &quot;Software Quartet&quot;?: LaSalleCRM.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although developing customer relationship management software is low priority, there is a piece that I want to build into it immediately. A small piece, but a piece nonetheless. Hence, my creating LaSalleCRM.com and the GitHub organization now.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>LaSalleMart hooks into LaSalleCMS</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a couple of ecommerce hooks I want to build into my CMS right now. Not a whole lot, but this is how it starts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart 3 for Joomla had a unique integration with native Joomla content articles, so LM3 could use Joomla itself for the front-end. In the same way, I want my CMS to power the ecommerce front-end -- why build a separate ecomm front-end system that overlaps LaSalleCMS?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s a small thing, but... I will allow multiple CMS categories per CMS post. Then, we can set up a &quot;Product Category&quot; category, with a category tree structure underneath.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another small thing, that presents an interesting challenge (to me, probably not to you), is including a &quot;product_id&quot; field in the CMS&#39; article database table.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As I progress, I can build in more hooks.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>API</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Although I am enamoured with the idea of having real API&#39;s for my Software Quartet, logistically it may be too ambitious; plus, the need is not there.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Each site will have its own API; and, *not* access a remotely located API. The idea is that the store reside at https://store.com; and, its&nbsp;API reside https://api.store.com.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am contemplating putting this setup on hold, and just putting the API within the actual app, but in its own namespace. In this way, I can build the API as a separate package, which I still want to do; but, dispense with worrying about authentication, throttling (that&#39;s what it&#39;s called?), and other worries a true SaaS API have.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Update: newly released Laravel 5, updates to my GitHub repos, and more...', 'Update: newly released Laravel 5, updates to my GitHub repos, and more...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/update-early-february-20151', 'update3.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-02-08', '2015-02-09 05:28:44', 1, '2015-02-09 05:55:57', 1, NULL, NULL),
(155, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleCMS First!', 'lasallecms-first1', '<p>LaSalleCMS is the foundational app. It has the user management, login management, admin back-end, and all that type of stuff. LaSalleMart is basically a package (more likely a series of packages)&nbsp;that is installable onto LaSalleCMS.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It did not take long to realize that I better deal with LaSalleCMS first.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart&#39;s product price table has a user-group field as a foreign key constraint. But, LaSalleMart does not create any user tables in the database -- LaSalleCMS does that.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My&nbsp;content system and my ecommerce apps are made to work together, in part because I think peanut butter and chocolate are meant to be together. In part, because my CMS acts as the foundational app. LaSalleMart should not be recreating the &quot;app infrastructure&quot; that already resides in LaSalleCMS.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So I am changing the order of development, by focusing on LaSalleCMS v2.0 (built with the newly released L5) first.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My guess is that instead of diving into LaSalleMart development, I will instead take a detour first and do the bulk of LaSalleCast, including moving my Media site to it. Then, away I go with LaSalleMart.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I also created a new class of software, that I am calling LaSalleCRM: Customer Relationship Management. Having stared at LaSalleMart 3&#39;s database tables for a while, I really did not like how limiting the customer tables were set up. For example, why not use these customer database tables as the basis for my LaSalleCast guest profiles? Why have each &quot;component&quot; describe its own people -- and therefore create a stovepipe database. No!&nbsp;Why not extract the customer tables into its own package right away? Well, that&#39;s what I&#39;m doing, and placing that package into its own major class of software: customer&nbsp;management. I can build up CRM functions as I go along, starting first with this kernel: an initial set of customer tables.&nbsp;</p>', 'My ecommerce needs the foundations that my content system provides. So, focusing on LaSalleCMS first', 'My ecommerce needs the foundations that my content system provides. So, focusing on LaSalleCMS first', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallecms-first1', 'update3.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-02-13', '2015-02-13 17:29:16', 1, '2015-02-13 17:34:52', 1, NULL, NULL),
(156, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Welcome To LaSalle Software And My Own Six Web Applications', 'welcome-to-lasalle-software-and-my-own-web-applications', '<p>LaSalle Software Verision 1.0 tagged today (Nov 03, 2015).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My own six web applications, based on my LaSalle Software, deployed yesterday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Historic Day</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Today is an historic day: <em>the first time I actually released significant software, instead of deep-sixing it due to version change</em>s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Was it four years ago that I started a series of ecommerce software for Joomla that never saw the light of day? Going down memory lane, my Tienda add-ons ended up in a full &quot;distribution&quot; package; with the tapering off of Tienda development, I forked it. Then Joomla went to a newer non-backwards-compatible version so I threw out my fork and started a brand new fork. When I released that fork -- and a huge effort that was, I had to threw it out as Joomla went to another newer non-backwards-compatible version. Then, I started a completely new LaSalleMart for Joomla from scratch. When Joomla mis-managed its versioning policy announcement, opening up the possibility that my latest massive LaSalleMart undertaking might end up prematurely obsolete, I dumped Joomla. This was March-April 2014.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To where? I&#39;ll tell you this, something that is critically significant: I did not look at specializing in other content systems. Instead, I looked at becoming a <em>web application developer</em>. Which is how I decided to specialize in the Laravel Framework.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Most Code&nbsp;Learning Since I Graduated the University of Toronto</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Learning web application development and the Laravel Framework entailed the most concentrated period of computer learning since I graduated university. And it is still happening --&nbsp;likely a permanent feature of my professional existence. Not just Laravel, but a growing body of topics to dig into. LaraCasts was&nbsp;heaven sent!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>LaSalle Software: Bridging the Gap</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>It did not take long to notice a huge problem. To build web applications for myself and for my clients, there was no ready-made quick-launch software for us to hit the ground running. Laravel itself is not an app -- it is the framework that powers the app, but is not the app itself. There&#39;s no ready-made admin piece, nor blogging/article piece, nor any of the other pieces that each web app will need.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sure, there were a lot of people spinning up&nbsp;their own web app &quot;starter kit&quot;, but none out there appealed to me. Most were learning exercises, some were more serious efforts but very custom. Plus, I was gun-shy about using someone else&#39;s scaffolding software.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It seemed that anyone learning Laravel started out by coding a blog web app. I am no different. It was&nbsp;his learning exercise became a real software development effort to created the web app quick-start software that I - and my clients -- need. Basically, I just kept going.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What happened along the way was Laravel released version 5. At the same time, I realized I made a huge mistake not breaking up my web app into a series of inter-related packages. So, I took my L4.2 code as the&nbsp;springboard to creating L5.1 packages.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Today, I released three suites of packages: LaSalleCMS, LaSalleCRM, and LaSalleCAST. There is one LaSalle Flagship web app just to get our web apps going; 8 CMS packages; 4 CRM packages; and, 4 CAST packages. Moving to L5.1; and, breaking up my software into related packages was smart move.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>I Am My Own First Client</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Along the way, I had my own web application needs; plus, I wanted to use my own software as a way to ensure that it worked.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I wanted to replace my existing WordPress sites, especially my Media site as I have a long-standing list of pet features I&#39;ve always wanted. Why not use my new blogging software for my blogging site? And, as well, I could really use a little Knowledge Base app, a little To Do app, and a minimal type of base customer management web app. And, of course, always on the back of my mind is starting LaSalleMart anew.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oh boy, did this expand the scope, and timeframe, of what I was doing. More than I ever anticipated. Getting LaSalleCAST done, alone with my Media site web app, took somewhere in the neighbourhood of forever. LaSalleCAST necessitated a working LaSalleCMS and a working LaSalleCRM. So what I have now is an <em>integrated solution</em>&nbsp;that would not otherwise exist had I not pursued my own needs.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I came across an irritating problem: it took too much time and effort -- and repetition -- to create the admin forms. To create the admin input forms for my To Do, it took forever. Never mind that clients would be irritated, I was irritated! Taking days to spin up the admin basics was not acceptable. I created my own solution: admin form automation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Administrative Form Automation: Hours Instead of Days</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead of hand-crafting admin input forms, I found a way to set up a handful of files only; and, then the admin forms generate automatically. Now it takes hours instead of days to spin up the admin side. If you or me want to prototype something, it is possible to do so.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One thing I&#39;ve found, though: it takes a lot of thinking to set-up the database tables that underlie the forms.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Commitment to Long Term Development</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>My wife and children and I have invested enormously in LaSalle Software. We are committed to its long term growth and development. It took an enormous effort to get to today&#39;s historic launches -- we did it!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalle Software Version 1.0 lays the foundation for long term development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&#39;s no funny business with how I used the Laravel Framework. I stayed within the spirit and practices espoused in Laracasts, so anyone familiar with Laravel will recognize what I&#39;m doing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Only with my admin form automation did I &quot;go on my own&quot;. The reason is that in this one area I had to innovate.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Welcome!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Bob Bloom</p>', 'Welcome to my LaSalle Software Version 1.0 release; and, to my six web applications based on my Software.', 'Welcome to my LaSalle Software Version 1.0 release; and, to my six web applications based on my Software.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/welcome-to-lasalle-software-and-my-own-web-applications', 'IMG_1343.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-11-03', '2015-11-03 23:32:49', 1, '2015-11-18 20:09:43', 1, NULL, NULL),
(158, 0, NULL, NULL, 'True North PHP', 'truenorthphp2015', '<p>Dec 03rd, 2015</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I created this special page for those I met at the Nov 05-07th True North PHP Conference at Microsoft Canada&#39;s conference facilities in Mississauga.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Having a surplus of cards I made especially for the Conference, I&#39;m still handing &#39;em out to people I meet who are interested in what I&#39;m up to.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Things are coming together:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>LaSalle Software Version 1.0 is released;</li>\r\n	<li>Development is active for a Version 1.01 release by Christmas;</li>\r\n	<li>Version 1.01 will have important fixes; and, must-have features that did not make it into v1, but really should have;</li>\r\n	<li>All my six new web apps based on my Lasalle Software are live;</li>\r\n	<li>My flagship site now has a better summary of my Software, plus new articles;</li>\r\n	<li>My podcast site has the first two &quot;LaSalle Software News&quot; podcasts up;&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>My podcast site has the November&nbsp;&quot;Bob&nbsp;Bloom Show&quot; &nbsp;-- the first episode&nbsp;since 2012. Dec&#39;s episode is in the works;</li>\r\n	<li>First client project with LaSalle Software in discussion.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart, my ecommerce software, is slated to commence New Year&#39;s Day. I&#39;m doing prelim work now to pave the way for active development.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is LaSalle Software? See the summary descriptions I just published yesterday on my Home Page.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank you for checkout out my site.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>-Bob</p>', 'TrueNorthPHP landing page', 'TrueNorthPHP landing page', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/truenorthphp2015', '2015nov05_true_north_php_conference/truenorthphp_logo.png', 1, 0, 0, '2015-11-04', '2015-11-04 22:06:44', 1, '2015-12-07 03:02:17', 1, NULL, NULL),
(159, 0, NULL, NULL, 'True North PHP Conference 2015', 'truenorthphpconference2015', '<p><a href=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/images/2015nov05_true_north_php_conference/IMG_0993.JPG\"><img alt=\"Bob Bloom at True North PHP Conference 2015\'s \'Leaderboard\'\" src=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/images/2015nov05_true_north_php_conference/IMG_0993_350x261.JPG\" style=\"float:left; height:261px; margin-right:10px; width:350px\" /></a>On November 5 to 7, 2015, I went to the <a href=\"http://truenorthphp.ca\" target=\"_blank\">True North PHP Conference</a> in Toronto.</p>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"clear: both;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/images/2015nov05_true_north_php_conference/IMG_0991.JPG\"><img alt=\"About to enter the Microsoft Conference Center\" src=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/images/2015nov05_true_north_php_conference/IMG_0991_350x469.JPG\" style=\"float:left; height:469px; margin-right:10px; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Superbly organized by the <a href=\"http://www.meetup.com/GTA-PHP-User-Group-Toronto\" target=\"_blank\">Greater Toronto Area PHP User Group</a>, the venue was Microsoft Canada&#39;s Mississauga Conference Center.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My first TNPHP conference, I had a great time, learned a lot, met a lot of people. Some people I had met at the GTA PHP User Group; and, at the <a href=\"http://www.meetup.com/Laravel-Toronto/\" target=\"_blank\">Laravel Toronto User Group</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"clear: both;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/images/2015nov05_true_north_php_conference/IMG_0989.JPG\"><img alt=\"Composer tutorial\" src=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/images/2015nov05_true_north_php_conference/IMG_0989_350x469.JPG\" style=\"float:left; height:469px; margin-right:10px; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Day 1: Tutorial Day</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The first day was not a conference day, but was a tutorial day, with two morning, and two afternoon, tutorials. Each tutorial ran&nbsp;three hours. It was a shame that I could not attend all the tutorials.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Of course I was going to the <a href=\"http://lumen.laravel.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Lumen</a> tutorial. Lumen is the Laravel Framework&#39;s microframework.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I went to&nbsp;the <a href=\"https://getcomposer.org\" target=\"_blank\">Composer</a> tutorial to solidify my&nbsp;knowledge of this core technology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Before the morning&#39;s Composer tutorial started, one of the conference organizers read the riot act about the Conference&#39;s <a href=\"http://confcodeofconduct.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Code of Conduct</a>. As dire as it sounded, in the three days, I did not hear of any incidents.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Actually, what I thought would happen was hearing laptops and mobile devices during the talks.&nbsp;Everyone had their laptops open, and had their devices on during all the talks. But it did not happen.&nbsp;The ring tones et al were muted, without a word being said by any speaker to mute devices.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Composer tutorial was superb. The speaker was very prepared for the rigours of a three hour tutorial. He had a lot of slides prepared. A&nbsp;lot of ground was covered. I thought there would be hands-on exercises, but there were none, which turned into a good thing given the wide scope the tutorial covered. As well, the slides had a lot of code, so we saw Composer in action.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some Laravel artisan commands launch Composer; and, the Laravel app&#39;s composer.json launches artisan commands. This tutorial helped me understand those&nbsp;processes better.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Lumen tutorial was hands-on, and required some experience with the Laravel Framework. Some attendees were frustrated not having worked&nbsp;with Laravel before, so they walked out. Those that stayed contributed to a very interactive,&nbsp;lively tutorial.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Lumen tutorial was the only Laravel specific talk of the Conference. So I think some attendees were expecting a Laravel overview first, before the deep dive into Lumen.&nbsp;It&#39;s great to see people show up for a hands-on introduction to Laravel. So I talked to one of the organizers about doing a Lightening Talk intro at an upcoming GTA PHP meet-up.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div style=\"clear: both;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/images/2015nov05_true_north_php_conference/IMG_0995.JPG\"><img alt=\"API (Batman) Tool Belt\" src=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/images/2015nov05_true_north_php_conference/IMG_0995_350x261.JPG\" style=\"float:left; height:261px; margin-right:10px; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Conference Day One:&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Incredibly, I did not take a pic on day one, so this pic is from Day Two. On Day One, I attended:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>* opening keynote address<br />\r\n* security top ten<br />\r\n* job queues<br />\r\n* MySQL 5.7 + json<br />\r\n* tech writing primer</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All the speakers at the Conference&nbsp;were hugely knowledgeable. They&nbsp;did a great job packing a lot of material&nbsp;into an hour.&nbsp;But an hour seemed too condensed a timeframe. The speakers were very organized, traversing&nbsp;a lot of technical ground.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I stayed for the Microsoft Azure hackathon, but did not touch Azure at all (the Microsoft Azure specialist did forgive me). Instead, I lounged around, and worked on a problem I discovered with LaSalle Software, because it was such a great environment to do my own little hackathon. I did follow the real-time Azure example, which was good since I did not attend the Azure talk.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/images/2015nov05_true_north_php_conference/IMG_0996.JPG\"><img alt=\"XDebug talk\" src=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/images/2015nov05_true_north_php_conference/IMG_0996_350x261.JPG\" style=\"float:left; height:261px; margin-right:10px; width:350px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Conference Day Two</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>I missed the keynote, due to domestic chauffeuring duties. I was there for the rest of the day:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>* great API&#39;s<br />\r\n* API (Batman) utility belt<br />\r\n* debugging<br />\r\n* simple design<br />\r\n* PHP5.5 promises and generators</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I attended the API talks specifically for insights that will help LaSalleMart. I was not disappointed, especially about API versioning.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Confession: I&#39;ve always been in awe of xdebug. That someone could create such a thing, and that they would release it for free, just blows me away. The author of xdebug gave the debug talk, and it was great. I am so glad that PhpStorm 10 has xdebug zero config.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Simple Design talk was unique because&nbsp;I saw the same talk on video given at LaraConEU. Being live, I got more out of it. Of all the Day One and Two talks, this talk seemed most suited for Tutorial Day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The PHP5.5 talk lost me. Talking to some other attendees afterwards, the general idea is that PHP is offering a facility to get info from API&#39;s &quot;asynchronically&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am looking forward to next year&#39;s True North PHP Conference.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'The True North PHP Conference was November 5th to 7th, 2015, in Toronto.  It was the first TNPHP that I attended. I had a great time, learned lots, and met lots of people. I especially got a lot out of the Tutorial Day.', 'The True North PHP Conference was November 5th to 7th, 2015, in Toronto.  It was the first TNPHP that I attended. I had a great time, learned lots, and met lots of people. I especially got a lot out of the Tutorial Day.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/truenorthphpconference2015', '2015nov05_true_north_php_conference/truenorthphp_logo.png', 1, 0, 0, '2015-11-16', '2015-11-15 07:23:09', 1, '2015-12-03 21:12:30', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(160, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Overview Of Salient Client Stuff', 'overviewofsalientclientstuff', '<p>There are topics that I want to write about in a series of posts geared just for current and potential clients. This series won&#39;t happen for now, so I want to devote brief attention to the topics most on my mind right now in this single post.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>The Value Proposition of web applications: Software Creation is Power</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>What underlies the value of websites? Is it the design? Is it page views? Is it Google search rank?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>For the clients I&#39;ve served since going freelance in 2007, value is really rooted in the ability to to create software.</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And, I&#39;ll tell you this: <strong>the clients who I&#39;ve succeeded with the best have a software development mindset</strong>, whether they realized it or not.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/software-creation-is-power\" target=\"_blank\">The ability to create software is powerful</a>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Where does value come from?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the movie &quot;Moneyball&quot;, the question was: where do runs come from? The answer was: they come from getting on base. So, the way to look at baseball hitters was: do they get on base? What they conveyed in the movie was getting on base from inducing base-on-balls was just as important a factor as an ability to hit. In fact, the under-valued aspect of a player was his ability to get on base via base-on-balls.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The &quot;moneyball&quot; of our websites is the ability to create code that brings in revenue. Perahps I should amend that to say that the &quot;money&quot; is the ability to create extra code taht brings in extra revenue(?).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The thing is, the majority of clients I&#39;ve served since 2007 do not give a shit about creating code. They want a website. If there&#39;s something they need specific to their business, then somehow it just conjures up magically. Back here in RealVille,&nbsp;it does not work that way.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>The Value Proposition of LaSalle Software</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The clients I want to serve are those who want an alternative to Joomla and WordPress sites -- just as I&#39;ve transitioned out of consulting with these technologies and moved into web app consulting. Like me, you realize that you need to get into something else now.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are fabulous technologies driving down the price of getting into, and maintaining, web applications. The problem, though, is that there is a vast gap connecting you to this technology. That connection is always left to the web app owner to create -- the user management, the login management, the content handling, the admin, etc.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalle Software is this&nbsp;expensive investment in &quot;scaffolding&quot;, provided to you for free, that you need, so I can get you into your own web apps.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalle Software is also the basis for your own custom web app software development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalle Software is also the basis for you to install&nbsp;other installable packages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalle Software offers a secondary value proposition, strictly because I need this for myself: spin up administrative database forms fast. Hand crafting these forms takes forever!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For myself, LaSalle Software is fulfilling its raison d&#39;etre.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Web Applications are not for the faint of heart</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>There is absolutely no way you can escape all of &quot;the technicals&quot; of web applications. The web applications industry is not in its&nbsp;&quot;consumer friendly&quot; era right now. Things are just a bit too nascent.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The &quot;upstream&quot; infrastructure phase is behind us now. The economics of web app infrastructure has changed massively over the last few years, with the cost of web app infrastructure nose diving -- and the speed of spinning up this infrastructure has increased geometrically.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We are in the &quot;downstream&quot; phase of web applications now. Lots of progress&nbsp;about the web application itself -- but mostly it stops at the web app code. It&#39;s not consumer oriented at all. Shielding the &quot;end user&quot; from the technology is impossible, because such shielding does not exist.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Doing web applications means there will be technical things to do with along the way. I want the technicals to be as painless as possible (for the both of us!); however, I can&#39;t shield you from all the technicals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are things that clients do when they are resistant to things technical: they get angry, they become unresponsive, they become victims. People do a lot of things to convey their resistance, but most of all they adopt a &quot;technology consumer&quot; mien.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dear client: with web applications, you are part of the software development process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Subscriptions for web applications</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>This is not shared hosting anymore. I do web applications using the &quot;Best Practices&quot; that the Laravel World espouses, which means you using:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>GitHub.com <a href=\"https://github.com/pricing\" target=\"_blank\">private</a> software repositories ($7+ usd per month)</li>\r\n	<li>the Laravel Forge service for setting up and maintaining cloud servers ($10 to $20&nbsp;usd per month)</li>\r\n	<li>Digital Ocean cloud servers ($10+ usd per month)</li>\r\n	<li>possibly, for email, Google Apps ($5 usd per domain per month) OR the just launched AWS WorkMail ($4usd/user/month)</li>\r\n	<li>Comodo PositiveSSL certificates ($9 usd per year) (more expensive SSL certs are ok) ==&gt; believe it or not, maybe free!</li>\r\n	<li>Domain registrar separate from email and site hosting</li>\r\n	<li>Mandrill.com transactional email (first 2,000 emails free)</li>\r\n	<li>Amazon Web Services Simple Storage Service (AWS S3)</li>\r\n	<li>Ottomatik.io backups ($10+ usd/month)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>When the time comes, there&#39;s&nbsp;twilio.com, pusher.com, and more.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>I am under no illusions about LaSalle Software</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>I started LaSalle Software as a pedagogical exercise to learn the Laravel Framework. Just like most people who learn Laravel, my first app was a blog.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While learning, I was looking for a &quot;real&quot; Laravel based content system to use for myself and for my clients. Well, I couldn&#39;t find such a system that I was happy with, and I was building out my little blog-y thing-y until I decided that my own blog would become my &quot;real&quot; content system.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalle Software is just at Version 1.0. You don&#39;t have to tell me what it is missing. Or that it lacks polish (look mom, no javascript!). Or that there is &quot;no community&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am using my own software every day now -- and I mean every day -- and I have managed to infuriate myself by not putting in a few little creature features.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I actually have to remind myself that if I had found something &quot;out there&quot;, then I&#39;d not have had to build my own thing. That is where the industry is at right now. Not to get into a discussion about it, but just to let you know, I was digging pretty deep with Grav and OctoberCMS, and eagerly awaiting Drupal 8 -- I should tell you about it at some point, but I don&#39;t want to get sidetracked right now...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The big picture proposition of LaSalle Software -- this, I have delivered! Not only did it get me into web applications, but it got me into it in a way that I could make for myself in a timely way my own custom web apps. There a bunch of tiny little web apps, but there&#39;s a big web app that I had my heart set on: doing my own podcasting web app.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An app based on installable podcasting packages, that in turn are installed on top of the base LaSalleCMS packages. I spent a disproportionate amount of time and effort on the templating for SouthLaSalleMEDIA.com, which in itself is a case study. But no way I could do SouthLaSalleMEDIA.com without myself having LaSalleCMS (and LaSalleCRM to a much smaller degree) in my back pocket.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So I&#39;m not going to blow smoke up your ass to over-sell my software.It fulfills it&#39;s prime value proposition, for which I did it in the first place. I know, because I&#39;m &quot;dog-fooding&quot; my LaSalle Software daily.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Also, I know that right now there is no LaSalle ecommerce, or LaSalle event handling, or a lot of other packages that are sure to be needed. Well, we&#39;ll create the software ourselves, use a SaaS (eg, EventBrite.com), see what is out there that we can install/adapt for ourselves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>You have to really understand your web application&nbsp;to really make it work.</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The days of relying on your visitors to intiate site traversal are long gone.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It matters a great deal how people interact with your site on all the different mobile devices.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It does not take much to cause site visitors to abandon a site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You have to <em>really</em> understand your site. Otherwise, people will visit your site, but they will abandon it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For my own podcasting site that I did from scratch using my own LaSalle Software, the number one thing that irritated me was deleting stuff off my site. There&#39;s not a lot of room on a smartphone, so the podcasts have to be the focus. And the clutter and distractions -- extra links, menus, sidebars -- had to go. It is not easy to toss the distractions and clutter overboard!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'There are topics that I want to write about in a series of posts geared just for current and potential clients. This series won&#39;t happen for now, so I want to devote brief attention to the topics most on my mind right now in a single post.', 'There are topics that I want to write about in a series of posts geared just for current and potential clients. This series won&#39;t happen for now, so I want to devote brief attention to the topics most on my mind right now in a single post.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/overviewofsalientclientstuff', 'moneyball1.jpg', 0, 0, 0, '2015-11-15', '2015-11-17 00:17:30', 1, '2016-04-15 04:39:29', 1, NULL, NULL),
(162, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalle Software Detailed Features', 'lasallesoftwaredetailedfeatures', '<h2>LaSalle Software</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>free open source software (except three LaSalleCAST packages) under GPL</li>\r\n	<li>packages listed on Packagist.org, software repositories on GitHub.com</li>\r\n	<li>Github.com milestones, issues, and smart commits&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>based on the wonderful Laravel Framework v5.1 LTS</li>\r\n	<li>use Laravel&#39;s command bus and events to make web app customization easier</li>\r\n	<li>sticking close to Laravel best practices and tools per Laravel.com, Laracasts.com, LaravelPodcast.com, and other various Laravel resources</li>\r\n	<li>three areas&nbsp;of software</li>\r\n	<li>software comprised of Composer&nbsp;installable packages</li>\r\n	<li>the basic installable packages:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>an internal&nbsp;API package</li>\r\n		<li>an admin package</li>\r\n		<li>a&nbsp;frontend package</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>PSR-4</li>\r\n	<li>PSR-2 --&gt; will improve when I run the just-launched&nbsp;Nitpick-ci.com for&nbsp;version 1.01</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div id=\"lasallecms\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"LaSalleCMS\" src=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/images_tsltc/lasallecms-logo.png\" style=\"background-color:#450508\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalle Content Management System is&nbsp;the foundation for building your custom web application. It is comprehensive, encompassing a stand-alone ready-made blog (just add your front-end template), user/login management, an admin area, and much much more:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Version 1.2.0&nbsp;(March 31, 2016)</u>:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>send article to a LaSalleCRM list</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Version 1.0.1 (February 01, 2016) (&quot;client-ready&quot; version)</u>:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>only logged in users can see the front-end; guests see a splash page</li>\r\n	<li>two factor authorization for:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>front-end &amp; admin&nbsp;login</li>\r\n		<li>front-end registration</li>\r\n		<li>already 2FA validated logged-in users excused from 2FA via cookie</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>front-end login management: login/logout, new user registration, reset password, terms of service checkbox</li>\r\n	<li>featured image handling (<em>server browsing is still pending - sorry, I have not found a good package, and not developed one yet</em>)</li>\r\n	<li>new admin form automation&#39;s delete confirmation</li>\r\n	<li>new admin form automation&#39;s&nbsp;save-and-continue-editing button</li>\r\n	<li>pretty drop-down form fields</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Version 1.0 (November 01, 2015) (first ev-ah production-ready version)</u>:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>full featured blogging software</li>\r\n	<li>separate administration site</li>\r\n	<li>categories for listing related articles (and LaSalleMart hook)</li>\r\n	<li>tags for internal article search</li>\r\n	<li>future dated article publishing</li>\r\n	<li>auto generated with manual override&nbsp;slug</li>\r\n	<li>wysiwyg editor</li>\r\n	<li>auto generated with manual override excerpt (to display article snippet on list pages)</li>\r\n	<li>auto generated with manual override meta description (displays on Google search results)</li>\r\n	<li>auto generated with manual override canonical URL</li>\r\n	<li>featured image handling</li>\r\n	<li>explicit record locking so two people cannot modify the same article at the same time</li>\r\n	<li>extensive config options (accessed directly in the config files, not in the admin)</li>\r\n	<li>open graph (Facebook), Twitter, and Google meta tags</li>\r\n	<li>image handling</li>\r\n	<li>single post &quot;next&quot; and &quot;prev&quot; navigation</li>\r\n	<li>my admin form automation -&nbsp;most admin forms are using my admin form automation</li>\r\n	<li>command bus (oops, &quot;job&quot;) handling</li>\r\n	<li>popular third party&nbsp;backup package integration</li>\r\n	<li>popular third party rss feed package integration</li>\r\n	<li>popular third party sitemap package integration (which I&#39;ve largely ignored, so may need TLC)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleCMS is&nbsp;comprised of the Flagship app, six core packages, and two optional packages:</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>Flagship app</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>ready-made app to spin up your LaSalle Software app</li>\r\n	<li>all necessary stuff needed for the installable LaSalle packages are built-in</li>\r\n	<li>based on Laravel/Laravel</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>API package</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>normalized database tables</li>\r\n	<li>processing and database handling</li>\r\n	<li>admin form automation processing</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>admin&nbsp;package</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>runs the visual aspect of admin -- the admin that you see</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>helpers&nbsp;package</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>inspired by Laravel&#39;s helpers.php</li>\r\n	<li>all packages can use these helper functions for dates, HTML, and images</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>user management&nbsp;package</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>user management</li>\r\n	<li>login/logout management</li>\r\n	<li>user groups</li>\r\n	<li>will incorporate related user management features in Laravel Framework, recent Laravel Spark, and the new Laravel Tasks repos (which I have barely scanned) in LaSalle Software Version 1.01</li>\r\n	<li>other user related security &quot;creature features&quot;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>form handling&nbsp;package</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>form handling for admin form automation</li>\r\n	<li>special &quot;express&quot; handling of database&nbsp;lookup tables</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>front-end&nbsp;package</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>over-ride-able front-end routes and controllers&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>not include the front-end blade template (view) files</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>contact&nbsp;package</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>standalone and embedded contact forms</li>\r\n	<li>contact form processing</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>knowledge base&nbsp;package</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>basic little app for links</li>\r\n	<li>will save a site&#39;s meta-description, if it has one</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div id=\"lasallecrm\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"LaSalleCRM\" src=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/images_tsltc/lasallecrm-logo.png\" style=\"background-color:#450508\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalle Customer Relationship Management has one purpose: so LaSalle Software can integrate with a customer database. LaSalleCRM is this database, and integrates with the To-Do app, and LaSalleCAST. Soon, LaSalleMART.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>API package</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>database and processing</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>admin&nbsp;package</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>the input forms use&nbsp;my admin form automation</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>list management&nbsp;package</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>front-end list sign-up</li>\r\n	<li>front-end list unsubscribe via unsubscribe link in the footer of list send-outs</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>to do&nbsp;package</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>basic little to-do app</li>\r\n	<li>created using my admin form automation</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div id=\"lasallecast\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"LaSalleCAST\" src=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/images_tsltc/lasallecast-logo.png\" style=\"background-color:#450508\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleCAST is my e-broadcasting platform. Created specifically to power my own podcasting site.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>API package</u>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>database and processing</li>\r\n	<li>not available for public download</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>admin&nbsp;package&nbsp;</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>forms use my admin forms automation</li>\r\n	<li>episodes and forms have fields just for iTunes -- that are used in my iTunes feed package</li>\r\n	<li>transcription handling</li>\r\n	<li>content, show notes, research notes not viewable in the front-end</li>\r\n	<li>status codes to help with scheduling and publishing</li>\r\n	<li>although not on my Media site, ability to list upcoming shows. Possible to suppress non-viewable&nbsp;upcoming shows</li>\r\n	<li>not available for public download</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>frontend&nbsp;package&nbsp;</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>does nothing -- exists for future development</li>\r\n	<li>not available for public download (hide your disappointment!)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3><u>iTunes feed package</u></h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>creates the iTunes feed</li>\r\n	<li>I created this package because I want a DIY solution for my Media site, instead of having a SaaS do it</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'A detailed list of LaSalle Software \r\nfeatures.', 'A detailed list of LaSalle Software  features.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallesoftwaredetailedfeatures', 'laptop.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2015-11-20', '2015-11-18 06:49:23', 1, '2016-03-16 07:38:27', 1, NULL, NULL),
(166, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Introductory Screencast Of LaSalle Software', 'introductoryscreencastoflasallesoftware', '<p>Here&#39;s an introduction video of&nbsp;LaSalle Software Version 1.0:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/-mV0hHaVVu0\" width=\"420\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ve since tweaked some of the edit screen for the upcoming Version 1.01 release.</p>', 'Introductory screencast of LaSalle Software.', 'Introductory screencast of LaSalle Software.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/introductoryscreencastoflasallesoftware', 'screencast1.png', 1, 0, 0, '2015-12-01', '2015-12-02 23:25:52', 1, '2015-12-03 00:37:47', 1, NULL, NULL),
(167, 0, NULL, NULL, 'How I Used LaSalle Software To Build My Podcast Site Screencast', 'howiusedlasallesoftwaretobuildmypodcastsitescreencast', '<p>Here&#39;s a screencast about how I used my LaSalle Software to build my podcast site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/-3sWwM65SPU\" width=\"420\"></iframe></p>', 'Screencast about using my LaSalle Software to build my podcast site.', 'Screencast about using my LaSalle Software to build my podcast site.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/howiusedlasallesoftwaretobuildmypodcastsitescreencast', 'screencast1.png', 1, 0, 0, '2015-12-01', '2015-12-03 00:29:24', 1, '2015-12-03 00:38:14', 1, NULL, NULL),
(168, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Chamber Of Commerce Breakfast', 'chamberofcommercebreakfast', '<p><a href=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/images/2015dec09_rhcoc_breakfast/IMG_1005.JPG\"><img alt=\"At the Richmond Hill Chamber of Commerce Breakfast on Dec 09th, 2015\" src=\"https://www.southlasalle.com/images_resized/2015dec09_rhcoc_breakfast/IMG_1005-300x300.JPG\" style=\"float:left; height:300px; margin-right:10px; width:300px\" /></a>This morning I attended my first ever <a href=\"http://www.rhcoc.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Richmond Hill Chamber of Commerce</a> event -- a breakfast networking shmoozing event at the Richmond Hill Main Library.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With LaSalle Software Version 1.0 a month old, and with the polisihing up well in progress, should I reach out to local owner-managed businesses? If so, would my local Chamber of Commerce be an ideal way of reaching out?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As well, I am curious to see what these events are about.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the things I discovered is the Library has excellent facilities to host a Laravel meet-up! I sent a missive today to the LaravelTO organizer about hosting a &quot;905&quot; meet-up. Thank you to the Library&#39;s staff for the tour.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I had sixty seconds with which to stand up and give my &quot;elevator pitch&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Hi, my name is Bob Bloom, I am an independent freelance software developer living in Richmond Hill specializing in web applications based on the Laravel Framework (eyes glaze). Having just released version one of my software based on Laravel, I am here today to guage if the Chamber of Commerce is a good way to find clients. Thank you, that&#39;s my shpiel&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So the key to the fifteen second elevator pitch is to have sixty seconds, and then do it in twenty seconds.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I must&#39;ve mentioned something about WordPress, because a very nice gentleman introduced himself and then related his frustrations with WordPress. After engaging me in conversation, I&nbsp;suspect that the problem may be with the consultant-client relationship.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another very nice gentlemen, unbeknownst to me, was taking in our chit-chat, and posited a variant on a classic WordPress scenario afterwards. He was more successful in eliciting comments from me, than I was in eliciting details of his situation from him -- he definitely wanted &quot;grist for the mill&quot; about something. My sense was that this was not a frustration with consultants, as our chit-chat was technology focused.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I was surprised at my reticence in seeking local clients, despite this being an event specifically about seeking local clients.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember when I first started deep-diving into Laravel, and responded to a call for a Joomla consultant with the idea that I could &quot;do Joomla&quot; while learning&nbsp;Laravel, and the greater world of web applications. So, I eventually drove to their office, and was asked umpteen questions about Joomla. Then, after being pumped for info, I was then dumped -- did not even hear back from them. For me, this is a typcial local client experience: where the &quot;sales cycle&quot; is used to get free consulting -- while I spend considerable time in the &quot;sales cycle&quot;, and even visit the &quot;client&quot; site.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I definitely have a chip on my shoulder about this, except that it is much bigger with Laravel and LaSalle Software because our investment in it is gargantuan -- and the software is released as FOSS. I certainly felt this chip on my shoulder, which is not the best frame of mind with which to shmooze with potential clients, eh!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I had a few other mini-discussions, and in most of them, I said that the cost of web applications have fallen like a stone in the last few years, making this technology more accessible today. The body language on this point was very strong, and this is something I need to continue communicating.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This morning&#39;s breakfast networking meet-up helped me enunciate what I am really looking for, and it is really about. I will get into this in my upcoming December&#39;s&nbsp;The Bob Bloom Show podcast; and probably in future blog posts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'This morning I attended my first ever Richmond Hill Chamber of Commerce event -- a breakfast networking shmoozing event at the Richmond Hill Main Library. With LaSalle Software Version 1.0 a month old, and with the polisihing up well in progress, should I reach out to local owner-managed businesses? If so, would my local Chamber of Commerce be an ideal way of reaching out?', 'This morning I attended my first ever Richmond Hill Chamber of Commerce event -- a breakfast networking shmoozing event at the Richmond Hill Main Library. How should I reach out to potential clients?', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/chamberofcommercebreakfast', '2015dec09_rhcoc_breakfast/IMG_1005.JPG', 1, 1, 0, '2015-12-09', '2015-12-10 00:31:28', 1, '2015-12-22 20:20:03', 1, NULL, NULL),
(169, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalle Software Will Be Client Ready At Month-end', 'lasalle-software-client-ready-january-31-2016', '<p>Today I recorded my 55th episode of The Bob Bloom Show. It stinks. So badly that I will not publish it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I talked about LaSalle Software exclusively, which is not what this podcast is about. I have a separate podcast devoted to my software.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a lot of topics I want to cover, but right now, this month, I&#39;m focused on my software. I am weeks away from releasing LaSalle Software in a client-ready state, and that&#39;s where my mind is right now.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will re-do my 55th episode in February.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the end of this month, LaSalle Software version 1.01 will be released. It will be client-ready.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Client-ready&quot; means that I am confident in my Software to install/deploy it for clients.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I released version 1.0 in November, ahead of the PHP True North Conference. I moved my own sites to my own software, and deployed all six sites ahead of the PHP True North Conference. I was rather uneasy about my new sites going live, but two-and-half months later my LaSalle Software based sites are running fine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since deploying version 1.0, I&#39;ve polished up a few things, and have been adding some features, towards releasing LaSalle Software as client-ready.&nbsp;This effort will conclude at month-end.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is clear now that my granular access permissions package will not even be started for version 1.01. As well, I will not worry about getting a preliminary email micro-service up-and-running before month-end. The last big feature included in version 1.01 is Two Factor Authorization for front-end and admin logging; and, for front-end registration.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once version 1.01 is tagged, I will start LaSalleMart&#39;s API -- my ecommerce software.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My February podcast will have all the details.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'LaSalle Software version 1.01 will be released by January  31, 2016, in a client-ready state.', 'LaSalle Software version 1.01 will be released by January  31, 2016, in a client-ready state.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasalle-software-client-ready-january-31-2016', 'ready.png', 1, 0, 0, '2016-01-19', '2016-01-20 09:29:50', 1, '2016-01-20 09:49:06', 1, NULL, NULL),
(170, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Announcing LaSalle Software Version 1.01', 'announcing-lasalle-software-version-101', '<p>I am thrilled to announce the release of LaSalle Software version 1.01 &quot;client-ready&quot; today.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For the very first time, my LaSalle Software has reached a point where I am confident enough to install it on client sites.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are two reasons for my confidence:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>my own Lasalle Software based web applications have 3 months of stable performance on the live production deployments;</li>\r\n	<li>I smoothed out a lot of rough edges.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>When I released version 1.0 three months ago, the last thing I felt was confidence. Sure, I had brought my Software to a version one release, quite an achievement. But, it had never been deployed on a live cloud server. The deployment process itself was completely new and so much more involved than anything I had done. Hey, never mind deploying my own web apps based on my v1.0 Software -- just building my six web apps with LaSalle Software was a brand new experience.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fast forward three months:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>my own live web applications work fine on the cloud servers;</li>\r\n	<li>the deployment process works smoothly;</li>\r\n	<li>I fixed things in my own software that irritated me, such as adding a &quot;save-and-continue-editing&quot; button in my create/edit forms.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>What I could not possibly know when I released v1.0, I now know&nbsp;for v1.01.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am thrillled to be at this point, to be able to now offer my clients LaSalle Software.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The original intent of LaSalle Software was for my family to make a key investment for our clients, to enable our clients to get into web applications. I would build &quot;scaffolding software&quot;, and just give it away, in return for enabling an entirely new class of clients, who would otherwise build WordPress sites, to get into web applications instead.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Web application technology has come a long way. Getting into web applications is more accessible than ever. It&#39;s almost to the point where a high-ish end WordPress site can build a web application instead. The way I saw it, a huge barrier remained: the basic scaffolding -- a basic ready-to-go content system with user management and an admin back-end. I just could not find the scaffolding that felt right for me, and for my clients. So I decided to build my own, as free open source software (FOSS).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scaffolding software means that there&#39;s just enough of the critical functions to get us going. It is not full fledged software, but just enough to get my clients over the hump, into web applications. Otherwise, a&nbsp;client starting from scratch would have to ante up&nbsp;$25,000 to bootstrap the essential software, just to get to the starting point of their actual web application. A client paying that kind of money for scaffolding is not going to release it as FOSS, so each client would have to start from scratch. So, we would basically provide that initial investment to our clients.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What ended up happening is that, my guess, we invested an equivalent of somewhere&nbsp;between $100,000 to $200,000 initial investment to our clients.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was only sometime last month that I stopped calling my Software &quot;scaffolding&quot;. It passed that point, and is really full fledged software.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I come from deep Joomla and WordPress experience. My experiences with these content systems, and my experiences with clients using these content systems, have come into play whilst developing LaSalle Software. My intention was/is solidly <em>not</em> to recreate either content system. Why? Because, they have very different value propositions. If you want WordPress, you can still have your WordPress. You (and me) are in web applications for different reasons than you are in WordPress.&nbsp;My focus was unlocking the&nbsp;value of being in web applications.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which means that as much as I want to provide certain&nbsp;creature features, sometimes I simply did not. The most glaring creature feature absence, methinks, is the inablity to browser the server for existing image files. Something along the lines of the WordPress media manager. I assumed a third party installable package exists, but I just haven&#39;t come across the right package. Such a thing exists for CKEditor, but you have to pay up. So, you have to look at the server itself, via FileZilla (or whatever) to browse and upload. Oh, I built a &quot;featured image&quot; facility, which helps.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which brings me to something else: there is no &quot;page builder&quot; facility whatsoever in LaSalle Software. Nor is there going to be any. It is my bias that clients need to invest in their front-ends, so LaSalle Software is designed to force clients to invest in their front-ends! In so doing, the full power of the Laravel Framework, and in front-end development in general, is exposed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I mention this because there is some overall vision with LaSalle Software. Certainly, there is an attitude about it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once I had v1.0 done, I then built my own podcasting&nbsp;web application with it. It is a completely separate web app under my SouthLaSalleMedia.com domain. Instead of building one big app, I created four&nbsp;composer installable packages, so I can build other podcasting apps.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was the first time I used my administrative form automation feature in a &quot;real world&quot; setting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s a huge PITA setting up admin back-end forms to enter data. My custom admin form automation feature creates these back-end forms automatically. When I was working on my admin form automation feature, I was pretty sure it could save days of work. In a &quot;real world&quot; setting, it really did. But, in so doing, it put the focus on creating the custom database.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The database work has to be done first, up-front. The natural inclination to avoid thinking through the custom database that underlies custom web app development, because it is a grinding, unglamourous, and somewhat unforgiving, exercise is now countered by the need to do it first.&nbsp;Furthermore, my admin form automation forces you to build your custom database in a certain way -- which I consider to be a classic &quot;normalized&quot; structure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We can use my&nbsp;form automation as a discovery process, because instead of spending money to build forms, money can be invested in figuring out the database. We can &quot;spin up&quot; a proof-of-concept web app, that exists solely to work on the database. When the database is figured out, we delete the &quot;proof-of-concept&quot; web app.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Really, as it&#39;s turned out,&nbsp;I&#39;ve been my own first LaSalle Software client. Which was the only way I could understand how to bring v1.0 to a &quot;client-ready&quot; state. Every day I use one or both of my two major sites: this Flagship site; and, my podcasting site. My four single page software sites are pretty well static sites right now. My Flagship site has stuff on the back-end that does not display at all on the front-end: there&#39;s a Knowledge Base, a tiny little to-do app, and my customer database. All built with my form automation, and all are&nbsp;composer installable packages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have consistently resisted introducing javascript into LaSalle Software&#39;s administrative back-end.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I want to keep to strict Laravel in my admin. Javascript requires its own workflow, a workflow I do not want to introduce into the admin. So there is no edit-in-place right now, which is the one feature that I think has the most compelling reason to use javascript. On the other hand, without javascript to make it &quot;too easy&quot; to delete records, I created a separate form for delete confirmations, making it harder to blithely delete records before realizing you (me!) deleted the wrong record.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Laravel internal software workflow is preserved throughout the admin-side processing, which is what I value&nbsp;more right now than what I consider some finer &quot;consumer oriented&quot; &nbsp;creature features.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Access control levels was supposed to be an integral feature of v1.01. It never made it because access control went from &quot;if person is a &#39;super administrator&#39;, then person can access admin back-end&quot; to &quot;if person can use lookup table code &#39;publish&#39;, then trigger the &#39;publish&#39; event&quot;. I&#39;ll deal with the huge scope creep post-version 1.01.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Creating a set of customer database records is a big success. The original intent of creating this set of database tables was to have it available for integration when building other things. So, my to-do list is associated with my customer database. Upon registering, I built the ability to create customer records from the basic registration form.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Building out CRM features is not a priority right now. But, using one unified customer database is a huge priority right now, which is why the customer database exists. And I am glad that it is there, because I&#39;ve already integrated it with other features. And, I&#39;ve been able to integrate customers with LaSalle Software/Laravel Framework users as part of basic&nbsp;LaSalle Software.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am thrilled to release LaSalle Software Version 1.01.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It represents the fulfillment of its original intent, to provide critical software scaffolding allowing my clients to get into web applications.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It represents a stability of performing on modern cloud servers using modern deployment techniques.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It represents technological leverage --&nbsp;to speed up development, to focus investment in high-value added areas, to build on hooks for future development.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'I am thrilled to announce the release of LaSalle Software version 1.01 &#34;client-ready&#34; today....', 'I am thrilled to announce the release of LaSalle Software version 1.01 &#34;client-ready&#34; today....', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/announcing-lasalle-software-version-101', 'announcement-retro.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2016-02-08', '2016-02-09 09:29:00', 1, '2016-02-12 03:26:21', 1, NULL, NULL),
(171, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalle Software Post V1.01 Development', 'lasalle-software-post-v101-development', '<p>Releasing a major software version means a lot of development effort has concluded.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalle Software Version 1.01&#39;s release marks an end of a development&nbsp;era, and the start of a new development era.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which sounds a bit over-dramatic. Version 1.01 marks the culmination of the effort to get LaSalle Software off the ground, and to the point where the basic functions exist; and, where the software performs in a stable way in production.&nbsp;The basic functions exist; and, things were done with a keen eye on future development.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalle Software gives us a head start with our custom web application development. To give us a true head start, a full customer database exists with which to integrate with future development. Certain types of features were put into separate installable packages to make it easier for future development to access those features -- which is something you do not see visually on a site, but underneath is a big help. Version 1.01 has a lot of things that exist for future development, but would not otherwise exist if the prime objective was merely to provide basic scaffolding.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From here, the focus shifts from dealing with software &quot;infrastructure&quot; to feature building. With one massively huge exception: the building of granular access control.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The need to create access control levels (ACL) at the lookup table value level was enough to have me defer the entire ACL feature to post-v1.01.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ACL as a driver of workflow is something I had contemplated until I started talking to actual real people about what &quot;value bottlenecks&quot; they were experiencing. The initial answers were &quot;workflow&quot;. Given ACL&#39;s intimate association with workflow, its scope skyrocketed. Preventing one person from &quot;publishing&quot; a blog post; and, allowing another person to &quot;publish&quot; a blog post, increases the scope of ACL.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, I turned my attention to other v1.01 features.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I want to complete these packages over the next few months:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>events (get it started meaningfully, if not actually finish it, as I sense development will be ongoing);</li>\r\n	<li>email &quot;micro-service&quot; with Lumen and&nbsp;Mandrill;</li>\r\n	<li>enhanced contact form using LaSalleCRM;</li>\r\n	<li>list of installed LaSalle Software packages.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My first client is my volunteer proof-of-concept web application.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am developing the events package strictly due to this web app. I am relying on my admin form automation to speed things up, but in so doing I&#39;ll probably have to have a &quot;white board&quot; session to figure out the database. The crux of admin form automation is &quot;CRUD&quot; - the database tables and the &quot;create&quot;, &quot;read&quot;, &quot;update&quot;, and &quot;delete&quot; of records.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using email within LaSalle Software is one of my long-held pet projects. This proof-of-concept web app gives me a fine excuse to get going with it. I found an article describing how to get a basic email &quot;micro-service&quot; up-and-running with Lumen and Mandrill, so I am happy to have an excuse to get to it. Combined with what I learned at the True North PHP Conference last November, I have my fingers crossed that I can get this thing going in one sitting. Yeah, as if.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once I do get this email thing going, the idea is to associate emails with customers. Then, to create a front-end dashboard with emails. And, then, for any notifications, to put them on the dashboard as well. We&#39;ll see how far we get in a few months.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I want to get a solid handle on ACL over the next few months. I sense that it&#39;ll take iterative development to get a strong idea of how to really do it. Once we figure it out, ACL will become an intimate aspect of LaSalle Software. I&#39;m sure I&#39;ll have to retool things that I&#39;ve already done, and i want to retool just once!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>--</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Of course, what is upcomng is the start of ecommerce development. I call my ecommerce &quot;LaSalleMart&quot;. I will start with LaSalleMart&#39;s API. It will be a true API, not just an internal API. I have a separate blog post about that.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Development on deck now that LaSalle Software Version 1.01 is out...', 'Development on deck now that LaSalle Software Version 1.01 is out', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasalle-software-post-v101-development', 'software-development.png', 1, 0, 0, '2016-02-09', '2016-02-09 23:30:23', 1, '2016-02-12 03:40:27', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(172, 0, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalleMart Application Programming Interface Development', 'lasallemart-application-programming-interface-development', '<p>Back in April/May 2014, when I decided to move from Joomla development to the Laravel Framework, I was very eager to begin developing ecommerce software with Laravel. Well, I thought, I would probably find a Laravel based ecomm solution and so I would specializse in that, because why should I reinvent what already existed. But, deep down, I really wanted to develop my own thing. Probably because I had just seen my huge effort developing&nbsp;Joomla ecommerce go down the tubes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I actually did start my ecommerce development with Laravel right away. I had this wonderful data model already, so I revisited it as a head start for my Laravel ecommerce.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, I was bumping into the same wall over and over again. I needed a sub-system to for customer data. I needed a sub-system for login/logout/registration. I need basic authorization. I needed a back-end to manage the database. I had the scaffolding&nbsp;built in with Joomla, but now I had nothing. And without the basics, there was no way I could build the ecommerce. So I decided -- well, I was forced -- to focus on the scaffolding. I was building a tiny little blog app anyways just to learn Laravel -- you have to build something to learn it, and it seemed that the first thing people build with Laravel is a blog app -- so I added a few extra things to my list. So my little blog app grew into LaSalle Software... but I digress.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With a constant eye towards building ecommerce software -- with perhaps ecommerce becoming the crown jewel of LaSalle Software -- I built LaSalle Software to its current version 1.01 release. However, I have not actually developed the ecommerce at all since discovering that I need a whole bunch of stuff first.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, I have that &quot;whole bunch of stuff first&quot; now, so I can finally start my ecommerce development in earnest. Ah, but not the same development I had started back in 2014.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My initial impulse was to recreate what I did with my Joomla ecommerce add-on with Laravel. However, as I progressed with my LaSalle Software, I changed my attitude about LaSalleMart. I soon concluded, and it took a while to so conclude,&nbsp;that I absolutely had to create a true LaSalleMart API. Not just an internal API as I had built, where I isolate the processing, using the command bus to get the internal &quot;request&quot; to the processing package. No, a real API. Even though I was not building a software-as-a-service site, my clients need a real API for their ecommerce.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which is why at the True North PHP Conference I attended every API session I could get to. Which is why I&#39;ve been reading up on API development. API&#39;s have become a bit of a hobby for me, as I chip away at familiarizing with the in&#39;s-and-out&#39;s. It&#39;s clear that the real learning will start once I actually get going with LaSalleMart&#39;s API development.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am also going to dive into automated testing for the LaSalleMart API, in part because I need to get into it once-and-for-all; and, because there really is no manual way of testing an API. There is no web site with which to view the API. So, I need unit tests to ensure that the calculations are correct. The learning never ever ends, eh!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am quite sure now that I will use RAML and MuleSoft&#39;s API tools for LaSalleMart&#39;s API.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am quite sure now that I will use Lumen for LaSalleMart&#39;s API, after mulling using a stripped down version of Laravel. Lumen is the stripped down Laravel, adjusted specifically for API usage -- right?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ecommerce gets very&nbsp;involved. very quickly. I remember how scope exploded with coupons. Product price is hardly straight-forward. Shipping is a universe unto itself. My default development position is to figure out all the twists and turns, and build that into the data model right at the start of development. Because building in complexity later will necessitate re-writing software. Now that the time has arrived to dive into LaSalleMart API development, the reality is that there is no way I can plan up-front for complexity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is much more important, at this stage of development, to get a basic working LaSalleMart API in place. That I learn RAML, the API tools, the testing, and that I can set up little web app so I can see it in action -- and so I can confront the issues that will inevitably come up integrating LaSalleMart&#39;s API with the greater LaSalle Software that it integrates with. Further, I plan on building LaSalleMart composer installable packages for the API, as opposed to building &quot;one big app&quot;, which was such a disaster for LaSalle Software that I won&#39;t even try it for the ecomm API.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the time comes to create umpteen different coupon types, I trust that my&nbsp;package development approach, and my (somewhat) attention to building databases in &quot;fifth normal form&quot; (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fifth_normal_form\" target=\"_blank\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fifth_normal_form</a>), will be enough to handle all the upcoming feature&nbsp;twist and turns.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>--</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here&#39;s a good presentation about API&#39;s and RAML.&nbsp;It&#39;s from 2014, but still a good presentation:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/_RI5iZgOtis\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalleMart&#39;s API will be released FOSS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maybe down the road I&#39;ll place some packages in private repos -- such as a Canada Post Shipping package.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>---</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will blog about LaSalleMart&#39;s API development as I progress.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'LaSalleMart ecommerce API to be a true API, not an internal API. Will use RAML and MuleSoft Tools...', 'LaSalleMart ecommerce API to be a true API, not an internal API. Will use RAML and MuleSoft Tools', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasallemart-application-programming-interface-development', 'api_image.png', 1, 0, 0, '2016-02-09', '2016-02-10 00:36:39', 1, '2016-02-12 03:41:42', 1, NULL, NULL),
(173, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Announcing A Version Policy Change', 'announcing-a-version-policy-change', '<p>This is not an&nbsp;earth-shattering announcement. It&#39;s really just some housekeeping.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalle Software is not One Big Something that gets installed in a fell swoop.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalle Software is comprised of an actual thin web application that becomes your actual custom web app. And, it is comprised of a suite of composer installable packages. 17 packages last time I counted.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My LaSalle Software packages are grouped into &quot;Lines of Software&quot;. There are four packages comprising &quot;LaSalleCAST&quot;. You don&#39;t even have to install LaSalleCAST -- well, three of the four packages are in private software repositories so we&#39;d have to talk first!.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are four packages in my &quot;LaSalleCRM&quot; suite. You don&#39;t even have to install these -- although you probably will.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are nine packages comprising &quot;LaSalleCMS&quot;, most of which are mandatory. You&#39;re not going to get far without the User Management package.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So far, I&#39;ve synchronized the version numbers. Which is ok, because the packages were basically in &quot;beta&quot; until the v1.01 release.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, it&#39;s important to get fixes to you asap. Synchronizing version numbers means I cannot get updates to you until I get around to tagging the version numbers on all the packages at the same time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As well, I want to keep to Semantic Versioning (<a href=\"http://semver.org/\" target=\"_blank\">http://semver.org</a>).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So I will tag my packags individually as required. I will use the version numbers &quot;1.01.01&quot;, &quot;1.01.02&quot;, &quot;1.01.03&quot;, etc.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am pretty sure that I should have numbered this &quot;client-ready&quot; release &quot;1.1.0&quot;, but I am not going back and changing everything. However, the next major LaSalle Software release will be either &quot;1.1.0&quot;, or &quot;1.2.0&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am 99.999999% sure that there will be no backwards-compatibility breakage in the next major release. We&#39;re not even close to version &quot;2.0.0&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I anticipate that a basic LaSalleMart API, and Granular Access Control Levels, will necessitate some non-backwards-compatible-breaking retooling. This retooling I will tag all packages simultaneously as version &quot;1.2.0&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'LaSalle Software packages will be tagged individually until the next major version 1.2.0 release...', 'LaSalle Software packages will be tagged individually until the next major version 1.2.0 release.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/announcing-a-version-policy-change', 'semver.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2016-02-09', '2016-02-10 01:15:51', 1, '2016-02-12 03:43:23', 1, NULL, NULL),
(174, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Second LaSalle Software Client Is A Volunteer Site', 'second-lasalle-software-client-volunteer-site', '<p>My first LaSalle Software client is... me!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And a good thing too, because no one else should have taken the brunt of LaSalle Software v1.0&#39;s rawness. There were little things in the admin that irritated even me. Well, the only way to discover the rough edges was to deploy real web applications based on my Software. I decommissioned all my shared hosting sites, and live deployed six of my own web applications.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My second LaSalle Software client is... a volunteer site: a proof-of-concept web application for my synagogue.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The existing site is a going-concern WordPress site. The short story is that there is a need for customization, so I offered to do a proof-of-concept LaSalle Software web application. The things that need developing are the same things that my paying clients will need. Workflow and email are important for LaSalleMart. It will be good to develop these things with a real web app for a real organization, because it will increase the quality and relevance of the software. If things go wrong along the way, there are not the usual budgetary and time pressures associated with a paid engagement. OTOH, I think that it would be a Good Idea to take the proof-of-concept web app live by summer&#39;s end.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This month I will set up the proof-of-concept web application on my RetroRadioes.com, a domain I have for development. I will use my own accounts to deploy it. I will likely modify an HTML5/CSS3 template for blade, along the lines of my SouthLaSalle.com template, with more integration with Laravel&#39;s Elixer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will give about half-a-dozen people access to the admin, to get feedback on their experience so I can make improvementsl; and, to see if they get error messages that I do not encounter myself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a handful of packages I want to wrap up first:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>a service&nbsp;times package;</li>\r\n	<li>a candle lighting times package;</li>\r\n	<li>enhanced contact form that integrates with LaSalleCRM.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The event and email packages are more ambitious, so I want to get these out of the way first. These ambitious packages need a working Granular Access Control Level package, so I&#39;m looking forward to developing it all in a &quot;real&quot; web app.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I want to end this year with a solid line-up of Software, and this is a great opporunity for me to get reach that goal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'My next LaSalle Software client is a proof-of-concept volunteer web app...', 'My next LaSalle Software client is a proof-of-concept volunteer web application.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/second-lasalle-software-client-volunteer-site', 'volunteer.png', 1, 0, 0, '2016-02-09', '2016-02-10 01:34:46', 1, '2016-02-12 03:44:02', 1, NULL, NULL),
(175, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Inaugural PHP Group North Meet-up', 'inaugural-php-group-north-meet-up', '<p>This evening was the inaugural meet-up of a group that I hope finalizes itself as the &quot;GTA &#39;North&#39; PHP User Group&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was held at Highway 7 and Leslie Street -- very close to where I am. A refreshingly brief journey to the meet-up!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was superbly organized and moderated. Thank you to everyone who made this meet-up happen.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An especial thank you to the two GTA PHP User Group organizers who came out tonight. And a shout-out to the sponsor, <a href=\"http://www.maxxian.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Maxxian</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There were not quite twenty of us --&nbsp;we filled up the conference room nicely.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There were three presentations: coding best practices, tracking &quot;to-do&#39;s&quot; in small teams, and cache-ing. The time management was superb. The discussions we had about each were very interesting, and were so valuable that I hope the after-presentation discussions become a regular feature of these meet-ups -- as well as the moderation style.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am looking forward to more meet-ups!</p>', 'This evening was the inaugural meet-up of a group that I hope finalizes itself as the &#34;GTA &#39;North&#39; PHP User Group&#34;.', 'This evening was the inaugural meet-up of a group that I hope finalizes itself as the &#34;GTA &#39;North&#39; PHP User Group&#34;.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/inaugural-php-group-north-meet-up', '2016feb23_gta_north_php_user_group/2016feb23_php_meetup.jpg', 1, 1, 0, '2016-02-23', '2016-02-24 09:10:57', 1, '2016-02-24 09:34:21', 1, NULL, NULL),
(176, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Confessions Of A Software Purveyor', 'confessions-of-a-software-purveyor', '<p>With an ambitious development schedule that is only picking up after releasing LaSalle Software version 1.0, I am blogging a lot less than I used to.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And my podcasts keep sneaking up on me, I have an upcoming LaSalle Software News podcast due in a week.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I keep up with the Laravel goings-on&nbsp;voraciously -- and, even so, I miss things with the ever-growing community. So, I&nbsp;do not lack not topics with which to blog and podcast.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Before I tackle these topics, I need to keep communicating about LaSalle Software. I am doing a lousy job communicating, although I sense that I am settling down, now that my first &quot;client-ready&quot; version is released.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I confessed something to myself this week. Hey, why not share it with the world! Figuring out my own sites is hard. Figuring out my own marketing is hard. There is a big difference between advising a client, and doing it for myself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I confess something else: it&#39;s not really that hard, I have been on a singular path all along. The problem is that I have not found proper expression.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This evening, at the PHP meet-up, I surprised myself how intense I was in opposition to the idea of WordPress presentations in particular, and CMS presentations&nbsp;in general. Both presentations are reasonable for a PHP meet-up, but I, um, demurred at the idea.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Also last weekend, I had a brief chit-chat about WordPress that brought to bear the Value Proposition of LaSalle Software. I thought, well, would I want to actually say this stuff on my podcast? On my Flagship site&#39;s home page?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the one hand, I do not want to seem like I am bashing anything. On the other hand, LaSalle Software exists for a reason, and given the extensive effort and commitment that brought LaSalle Software to fruition, it&#39;s obvious that there was a need to satisfy with my Software.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Also, I seem especially twisted up in a ball when it comes to describing my LaSalle Software. I need to get down to the nub of things, and tell my story.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, basically, what I plan to do, is just give a no-shitter. Not that my next podcast will have that title. But that&#39;s the topic.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ok... look, first of all the landscape has changed tremendously over the last few years. Something I&#39;ve been communicating someone cogently, I trust. Traditional self-enclosed content systems hosted on shared servers made sense years ago, but is on the way out now. Yes, you heard me, on the way out.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There were three popular PHP content systems: Drupal, WordPress, and Joomla. Hard to believe that there was a time when Joomla was more popular than WordPress! Well,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Drupal dropped a bomb on itself and blew itself to smithereens. Drupal 8 is a complete&nbsp;re-invention, a full do-over, emerging as a web application platform with which to do your own custom web apps. They based their re-invention on the Symfony Framework, exactly like Laravel. I was very much interested in specializing in Drupal 8, but guess what? They took so long to release D8 that I released LaSalle Software v1.0 first. I&#39;ve had it up-to-here depending on open source projects to get around to releasing their software. Been there, done that. The key takeaway here is that Drupal decided to abandon their traditional content system, and create a brand new thing specifically for web applications.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joomla. Ah, Joomla. Joomla has had a web app framework for years. Did you know that? It&#39;s a separate thing from Joomla 3. You remember that my Joomla ecommerce extension was based on a fabulous third party framework? There is now a stand-alone version of this framework,&nbsp;separate from Joomla. There is a recent announcement of another third party web app framework for Joomla, or something. Look, all that I really want to convey is that Joomla is experiencing pressures with transforming into a web application development thing-a-ma-jig.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>WordPress is the CMS everyone seems to have heard about. Well, do you know that they are stuffing web application thingees into WordPress?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Web application technology is not chasing the traditional content systems. Au contraire! Oh no! It is the traditional content systems that are chasing web application technology.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If these projects are chasing web app technology, then shouldn&#39;t you be doing the same thing?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Drupal is backed by a commercial business, who&nbsp;decided that they will&nbsp;simply abandon their investment in favour of re-doing Drupal as a web app platform. WordPress is backed by a commercial business with a $1+Billion valuation, who want to keep what they have built up but still want to web app-i-fy it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Are these people, or are these people not, transmitting to you something about what you should be doing? They are! They are telling you to get into web applications. That maybe you need to dump what you have completely in order to do it. And, that, they are still at it doing the transformation. So, maybe if you are at it for a while, it&#39;s situation normal.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Web applications is about custom software development. It&#39;s not about bolting pre-fab stuff all over the place and coming up with this perfect thing just they way you want it. Web application technology is about the unprecedented access to custom software development. It&#39;s about costs dropping like a stone. The barriers are coming down.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, the general trend is moving to web applications.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>COMPOSER INSTALLABLE PACKAGES</p>\r\n\r\n<p>WORDPRESS SEEMS OVERSOLD TO ME, CONSULTANTS KNOW NOTHING ELSE, CONSULTANTS KNOW DIPSHIP ABOUT SOFTWARE DEVELOPMENT, DO NOT CODE PHP (or anything else), WORDPRESS HAS A &nbsp;PROPRIETARY non-normalized database design that matters a great deal when it comes to custom work -- and that WooCommerce weaves into instead of developing its own new fresh modern db design. Yeah, I know, WordPress is coming out with interfaces so you can use this crappy database in a modern way, so I&#39;ve read.&nbsp;</p>', 'With an ambitious development schedule that is only picking up after releasing LaSalle Software vers...', 'With an ambitious development schedule that is only picking up after releasing LaSalle Software vers...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/confessions-of-a-software-purveyor', 'confession1.jpg', 0, 0, 0, '2016-02-23', '2016-02-24 09:58:54', 1, '2016-02-24 10:48:55', 1, NULL, NULL),
(177, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Why MailChimp Removing Free Tiers Has Me Looking Elsewhere', 'why-mailchimp-removing-free-tiers-has-me-looking-elsewhere', '<p>The reason I am composing this brief article at all is due to years and years of recommending MailChimp and Mandrill to everyone.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the years, I&#39;ve tried a lot of email sites, and MaiChimp became my number one choice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead of releasing a MailChimp API, they released a separate product called Mandrill, which is fabulous.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>MailChimp&#39;s design is especially good. They had a good design, and then made it even better. Their site flows well. Very impressive UX.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In my opinion, MailChimp is uniquely superb at communications. They are candid, they are very detailed at explaining what they are thinking.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;announcement yesterday that they are going to close down their free tiers strikes me as being very out of character for MailChimp.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For such a major change, they would have communicated what they are considering when they were considering it -- and why there were considering it. Then they would have communicated milestone decisions along the way. Just getting an email out-of-the-blue that they are ending free tiers, and they are changing their systems in a month-ish -- I actually thought it was from another outfit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am interpreting the &quot;out-of-the-blue&quot; aspect of their announcement as something fundamental has changed at MailChimp. I&#39;ve heard nothing. I know nothing. Just a gut instinct. And, so, I&#39;m wondering what other changes might be in store.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The announcement included the suggestion that those who want a low-cost transactional email API use Amazon&#39;s Simple Email Service (SES). The Laravel Framework includes a MailGun &quot;driver&quot; (just wanted to sneak that in here). I will be taking them up on their suggestion, and I&#39;ll be frank here, likely never to return to MailChimp. I have plans to build email capabilities into LaSalle Software, and using SES is very attractive. Amazon just took their WorkMail live, with March being the first billable month (they&#39;ve been warning me for two months). SES can now handle incoming emails. Incoming SES emails can be routed to WorkMail, so that has possibilities. And, it wouldn&#39;t suprise me one bit if (when) Amazon includes MailChimp-type list and analytics.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'MailChimp is suddenly getting out of the &#34;free&#34; business. They suggest Amazon&#39;s Simple Email Service. Good idea!', 'MailChimp is suddenly getting out of the &#34;free&#34; business. They suggest Amazon&#39;s Simple Email Service. Good idea!', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/why-mailchimp-removing-free-tiers-has-me-looking-elsewhere', 'goodbetter.jpg', 1, 1, 0, '2016-02-26', '2016-02-27 04:43:09', 1, '2016-02-27 07:35:41', 1, NULL, NULL),
(178, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Amazon Web Services Now My Cloud Provider Of Choice', 'amazon-web-services-cloud-provider-of-choice', '<p>Amazon Web Services is now my cloud provider of choice.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ve been leaning this way for a while, but have not been in a rush to use AWS exclusively. One reason is that I wanted to try other cloud providers, especially those that are favoured by the Laravel community.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the time has come to use AWS as much as possible, so I can learn it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ve already started moving individual services to AWS. I am now using AWS&#39;s&nbsp;CloudFront content delivery network (CDN) instead of an independent CDN, for my podcast MP3&#39;s. This is more convenient for me as I&#39;m frequently logged into AWS&#39;s Simple Storage Service (S3) anyways -- and, one less invoice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;m going to redeploy my own six web apps to a fresh server instance. I want the latest Forge server config, including wanting to try the new MariaDB which may fix my MySQL issues that are crashing my web apps. I also want to tweak how I live deploy my apps.&nbsp;I will take this opportunity to deploy on AWS&#39;s EC2 instances instead of DigitalOcean. It&#39;s a big plus that Amazon is building a Canadian datacentre, which I&#39;ll move to when it goes online.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With MailChimp&#39;s getting out of the &quot;free&quot; business suddenly, I am taking MailChimp up on their suggestion to use AWS&#39;s Simple Email Service. This move is my final trigger to get into AWS, because SES works with other Amazon web services (such as its new WorkMail). &nbsp;This integration is good for LaSalle Software as I weave more email functions into my Software. So it&#39;s time to learn and use AWS to take advantage of this integration.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I can store my Git repositories in AWS. There is a way to push code to multiple repos -- to GitHub.com and to AWS -- so I&#39;ll sleep better having a backup for my code.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2014, Amazon started an explosion of new web services. I figured that at some point it would be a good idea to specialize in AWS. That time has come. It&#39;s a powerful&nbsp;trio: LaSalle Software + Laravel Framework + AWS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Amazon Web Services is now my cloud provider of choice.', 'Amazon Web Services is now my cloud provider of choice.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/amazon-web-services-cloud-provider-of-choice', 'aws1.png', 1, 1, 0, '2016-02-28', '2016-02-28 20:26:58', 1, '2016-02-28 20:39:08', 1, NULL, NULL),
(179, 4, NULL, NULL, 'The Major Content Systems Are Trying To Tell You Something: Web Apps!', 'major-content-systems-are-going-web-app', '<h3>Y&#39;know, the major traditional content systems are trying to tell you something!&nbsp;</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The Big Three traditional PHP self-enclosed, shared server hosted, are becoming/have become web application frameworks/platforms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/9Z8WRdGIZoU\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Achieving my LaSalle Software&#39;s first &quot;client-ready&quot; version, I&#39;ve been talking up my Software. And, I&#39;ll tell you something, peoples&#39; eyes glaze over when I describe my Software as &quot;web application&quot; software. Just because &quot;web application&quot; is not a phrase that has entered the mainstream lexicon, does not mean that the &quot;web application&quot; is a minor thing. Au contraire, &quot;web application&quot; is a huge major trend.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>WordPress REST API</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Does WordPress really need an introduction? It is the dominant content system, hands down.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This past December, WordPress released a <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/news/2015/12/clifford/\" target=\"_blank\">new version</a> that included a REST API &quot;...integrated into the core, marking a new era&nbsp;in developing with WordPress&quot;. Nothing more is said, so let&#39;s head on to <a href=\"https://premium.wpmudev.org/blog/wordpress-rest-api/\" target=\"_blank\">this article</a> for the money quote: &quot;To put it in a nutshell, the integration of the JSON REST API will mark the final transformation of WordPress from its humble roots as a blogging solution into a fully-featured application platform&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Drupal 8</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Something interesting happened with Drupal: they blew it up. Drupal 7 was the last &quot;traditional&quot; version. Drupal 8 is a completely new thing, unlike what was before. The decided that they took Drupal as far as it could go, but in the web application world, they needed to take Drupal farther. So they started from scratch, building a web application platform. Just like Laravel, they took the Symfony Framework as their base. This Schumpeter Creative Destruction took a lot of resolve and decisiveness of action. I was very interesting in adopting Drupal 8 as my new web app specialty. But, and it&#39;s a Biggee: they took a l-o-n-g &nbsp;t-i-m-e to get their baby to reversion one point oh. In fact, li&#39;l ol&#39; me got my own web app &quot;platform&quot; based on Laravel based on Symfony to version one point oh before they did -- which still amazes me. What was I supposed to do? Wait for them? BTDT with FOSS projects, and it&#39;s Very Bad For Business.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.godaddy.com/garage/webpro/development/what-you-need-to-know-about-drupal-8/\" target=\"_blank\">Here&#39;s an article</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They blew up what they had to cope with the web application world. Is that message enough?!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Joomla</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>I know of three Joomla related web application frameworks. They are &quot;true&quot; web app framworks to differing degrees. The point really is their existence. Each have their own history and raison d&#39;etre. The <a href=\"https://framework.joomla.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Joomla Framework</a> (not to be confused with plain ol&#39; Joomla). The <a href=\"https://github.com/akeeba/fof\" target=\"_blank\">Akeeba Framework on Framework</a> -- a standalone version now exists. The <a href=\"http://www.nooku.org/\" target=\"_blank\">JoomlaTools Framework</a>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I happen to think that &quot;selling you&quot; on the merits of web applications is moot. These top major projects are, in their own way, moving to web apps. They are sold. They are telling you something!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'The Big Three traditional PHP self-enclosed, shared server hosted, are becoming/have become web application frameworks/platforms. You should be doing the same!', 'The Big Three traditional PHP self-enclosed, shared server hosted, are becoming/have become web application frameworks/platforms. You should be doing the same!', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/major-content-systems-are-going-web-app', 'whisper1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2016-02-28', '2016-02-28 20:56:53', 1, '2016-03-16 01:03:29', 1, NULL, NULL),
(180, 5, NULL, NULL, 'Billion Dollar Investments Just To Make Web App Dev Accessible To You', 'billion-dollar-investments-just-to-make-web-app-dev-accessible-to-you', '<p>The investment into (web) application infrastructure over the last decade -- the last half decade! -- has been astronomical.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This investment went into cloud and software infrastructure. New technology exists that is offered at nominal cost, and even, incredibly, for free.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In no particular order, and hardly exhaustive, here are highlights of web app dev accessibility.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Cloud</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>All you have to do is look at Amazon Web Services to see what I mean. What started as renting out excess server capacity is now&nbsp;a multi-billion dollar line of business. In 2014, Amazon hit a critical mass of sorts, and focused huge dollars on expanding AWS -- fast. Amazon has been aggressive in lowering the costs, and the prices,&nbsp;of its web services. Very aggressive.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Remember when we had pay hundreds of dollars per month for an actual server in a server farm? Had to set the whole thing up from scratch too. If your site was popular, you had to physically scale your hardware to support the traffic? You can spin up your EC2 instance now for $10/month -- first year is free!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Composer</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Huh? What is composer? Composer is free open source software that makes web app PHP &quot;plugins&quot; (&quot;add-ons&quot;, &quot;extensions&quot;, &quot;modulels&quot;) possible.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You have a web app already, and&nbsp;you want to bolt a backup function to it? Just find a backup &quot;package&quot;, and install it using Composer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The PHP world did not have a good, acceptable way to cope with the equivalent of WordPress&#39; &quot;plugins&quot;. Now, it does. Its beauty is its independence, it is a stand-alone thing. So any framework can use it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a lot of Composer-installable packages out there, with more being released each week.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalle Software is comprised of composer-instalable package.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>PHP Improvements</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>PHP has come a long way. It is a modern language, not just a scripting language. PHP is extremely popular, and very established. Just wanted to mention this.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Continuous Software Development</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>It was programmers who developed a tool to help them with the software build process, because such a tool (and related processes) was lacking. I cannot stress enough that programmers knew exactly where value was, and selfishly created tools for themselves to extract this value. In so doing, they gave birth to an industry.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I trace the start of &quot;continuous&quot; with the advent of the Jenkins Server, which was, and is, incredibly, FOSS.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Unleashing &quot;continuous&quot; technology has driven down the cost of releasing software. But, it does put a technology burden on software creators. After all, it was the programmers themselves who birthed this technology.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Laravel Framework</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>In my opinion, the Laravel Framework makes web app software creation more accessible to programmers. What was a software sub-specialty is now mainstream software development, in large part to the Laravel Framework.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Git and GitHub.com</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Git is the name of version control software -- for software! Version control software for software is not new. But Git&#39;s innovations are new, and are now mainstream accepted. GitHub.com is the gold standard of git based cloud software repositories, and is the most popular site for open source software collaboration &amp; projects.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Application Programming Interfaces (API&#39;s)</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The more you get into building your web applications, the more youi&#39;ll be using cloud services and external API&#39;s. It&#39;s a big interconnected scalable world out there!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What I want to convey is that we are the beneficiaries of immense toil, passion, and investment. The sole outcome, it seems, is to make (web) application development accessible to everyone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Companies borrowed heavily in recent years, but often bought back stock rather than investing in the...', 'Companies borrowed heavily in recent years, but often bought back stock rather than investing in the...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/billion-dollar-investments-just-to-make-web-app-dev-accessible-to-you', 'inaccessible1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2016-02-28', '2016-02-29 00:24:34', 1, '2016-07-13 08:17:26', 1, NULL, NULL),
(181, 5, NULL, NULL, 'Inbound Email Handling And Token Based Login -- Getting Close!', 'inbound-email-handling-and-token-based-login-getting-close', '<p>It&#39;s been an intense couple of weeks getting into a whole new area for LaSalle Software.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oh, I&#39;ve always wanted LaSalle Software to have email handling; but, it&#39;s one of those things where so much has had to come before it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then, my first paid LaSalle Software gig changed my priorities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The concept comes down to sending pics through email as part of customer care.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The email is processed in the web app without any human intervention. No logging in, no file uploading, no fuss, no muss.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oh boy, what a journey of discovery this turned into. It&#39;s the details, oh, it&#39;s the details.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And, it&#39;s turned into a series of new core LaSalle Softwaere features.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Email Handling in the Administrative Back-end</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>My lovingly build admin form automation handles standard database &quot;CRUD&quot; actions. Email handling is its own thing altogether, so I hand crafted the admin forms. I gained a deeper appreciation for my own form automation feature, I can tell you that -- it really does save a lot of time setting up the back-end forms. I achieved a very basic type of email handling in the back-end, which is what I wanted. Not to mention I gained a very healthy respect for what it will take to develop truer email features.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, an email that comes in and is processed displays in the back-end.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, now, I can route a message from a contact form back to the web apps admin. To reply, you&#39;ll have to set up new outbound email in the admin, I didn&#39;t develop some miniature Zoho or something. In due time, although I&#39;m thinking more in terms of a ticketing system. Hmmm....</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Inbound Email Handling</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Whoa, is this a whole different thing than outbound email. Outbound is easy! Inbound is a completely different thing. Someone sends an email to a special email address. An API, I use Mailgun, receives the email, parses it, then sends the parsed data as POST variables to my web app&#39;s endpoint. If you did not understand that, then at least know that having left Kansas, you have arrived at your new destination!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have standard inbound processing for inbound email handling. It is based on Mailgun&#39;s specific POST vars, but the processing I kept as generic as I could -- so we can use an interface down the road regardless of the inbound API used.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Getting close to wrapping up the inbound email handling. With so much accomplished, the last piece is inbound attachment handling.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Token Base Front-end Login</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Another thing that I&#39;ve always wanted, but not a priority. Until now. Turns out that the groundwork was laid with Two Factor Authorization. The ability to click a link and then be automatically logged in as if you&#39;re jumping from one tablet app to another -- well, it&#39;s a beautiful thing. No passwords, no login screen.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Lowering Barriers to Web App Development</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>My LaSalle Software is supposed to get you into Laravel based web apps faster and inexpensively. It&#39;s feature set exists as an advanced starting point for your custom web app development. Most of my effort over these last couple of weeks was spent developing these new core features, rather than on the custom workflow my client needs. This is my first paid LaSalle Software gig, so it&#39;s my first opportunity to see if my intentions are realistic. Indeed, they are. Had these features already existed, I&#39;d already have my proof-of-concept done. Exactly what I am aiming for. I want my clients to have targeted-scoped web apps that are quickly and inexpensively built and maintained.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'It&#39;s been an intense couple of weeks getting into a whole new area for LaSalle Software. Oh, I&#39;ve always wanted LaSalle Software to have email handling; but, it&#39;s one of those things where so much has had to come before it. Then, my first paid LaSalle Software gig changed my priorities.', 'It&#39;s been an intense couple of weeks getting into a whole new area for LaSalle Software. Oh, I&#39;ve always wanted LaSalle Software to have email handling; but, it&#39;s one of those things where so much has had to come before it. Then, my first paid', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/inbound-email-handling-and-token-based-login-getting-close', 'inbound-outbound.jpg', 1, 1, 0, '2016-04-14', '2016-04-15 04:42:40', 1, '2016-05-05 05:20:04', 1, NULL, NULL),
(182, 5, NULL, NULL, 'Email List Management Package Finished', 'email-list-management-package-finished', '<p>I am thrilled that my latest round of development of&nbsp;my&nbsp;Email List Management package is now done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is a free open source LaSalle Software package <a href=\"https://github.com/lasallecrm/lasallecrm-l5-listmanagement-pkg\" target=\"_blank\">on GitHub</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I added a new link to this site so you can add your email address to my in-house list. When I save a post with the &quot;send to list&quot; workflow dropdown selected, internal events are triggered to send the post via outbound email to all the email addresses in the list.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Appended to each email is a token based&nbsp;unsubscribe link. Click it and you are unsubscribed from the list, just like that.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I always wanted this feature in my Software. Sometimes, I don&#39;t want to use a SaaS site. Instead, I want my own list that I send out via a transactional email API.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And, it links to my LaSalle Customer Management database -- yeah!</p>', 'I am thrilled that my latest round of development of my Email List Management package is now done', 'I am thrilled that my latest round of development of my Email List Management package is now done', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/email-list-management-package-finished', 'rss2email.png', 1, 0, 0, '2016-05-04', '2016-05-05 07:06:57', 1, '2016-07-13 07:59:24', 1, NULL, NULL),
(183, 5, NULL, NULL, 'Announcing LaSalle Software Version 1.2', 'announcing-lasalle-software-version-one-point-two', '<p>I am thrilled to announce the version 1.2 release of my LaSalle Software.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This version marks the first time a client engagement has contributed to free open source LaSalle Software. In this case, not one but three such packages: a token based login package, an inbound email processing package; and, a Mailgun inbound email parsing package. These packages represent stellar precedents of how sponsored features bring down the aggregate cost of a custom software development.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are now over two dozen packages comprising LaSalle Software version 1.2. New features include outbound SMS&nbsp;(via Twilio), multiple contact lists with custom contact form, and in-house email list management. This widening feature set speeds up custom development while lowering cost.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Two packages are on-deck for immediate development: a backup package; and a roles-and-permissions package. Both will round out this&nbsp;comprehensive version 1.2 release.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LaSalle Software is web application software based on the highly popular, and kick-ass, Laravel Framework. I do things &quot;The Laravel Way&quot; so the broadest range of third party packages can be used within LaSalle Software; and, so it&#39;s easy for people who use the hottest PHP framework to use LaSalle Software.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'I am thrilled to announce the version 1.2 release of my LaSalle Software.', 'I am thrilled to announce the version 1.2 release of my LaSalle Software.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/announcing-lasalle-software-version-one-point-two', 'lasallesoftware.png', 1, 0, 0, '2016-05-11', '2016-05-12 07:12:59', 1, '2016-07-13 23:43:43', 1, NULL, NULL),
(184, 5, NULL, NULL, 'Season For A New Web Host', 'season-for-a-new-webhost', '<p>For everything there is a season. And the season for my old standby favourite web host has long&nbsp;passed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/W4ga_M5Zdn4\" width=\"420\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is true, my sites are on cloud servers as web applications, based on my own LaSalle Software (based on the excellent Laravel Framework).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is true, I&#39;ve not had a web host account since last fall -- and I knew I was closing it months and months ahead of time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is true, my web apps, and the web apps I create for my clients, will be on cloud servers, not shared webhosts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So why is a webhost even an issue?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The reason is: I still take care of&nbsp;Joomla sites; and, I actively do WordPress sites &quot;on the quiet&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have another reason: email.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are not familiar with independent webhosts being acquired by a private equity firm, then <a href=\"http://www.digitalfaq.com/editorials/websites-blogs/hostgator-alternatives-eig-pt1.htm\" target=\"_blank\">read this article</a>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My favourite web host ceased to be my favourite for a while, noting the steady significant decline in service over the years. The problem is that the steady decline in service over the last year has become destructive. For example: there&#39;s no notification of impending SSL expiration (where there were before), and getting renewed is not necessarily an easy matter. But, it was the frequency of sites getting hacked that was the final straw. Was the hack due to the webhost? Well, we do not know precisely. For us, the pattern was disturbing enough.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The problem is: which webhost? My immediate thought was Rochen.com because they had a good reputation when I was active with Joomla. They are still <a href=\"http://website.informer.com/Rochen+NOC+Rochen+Limited.html\" target=\"_blank\">independently owned</a>, as far as I can tell. They still host the main Joomla site(s). They certainly understand Joomla &amp; WordPress and, word was, they customized their servers for &#39;em. But for all these reasons, and &nbsp;other reasons, a stand-out reason for me is reading through the Akeeba Backup support tickets. Whenever there is a problem with Akeeba Backup using Rochen, there is an exact set of steps to fix the problem. Rochen is favoured, and the hint -- at least to me -- is to switch to Rochen.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I can tell you that Akeeba Backup files&nbsp;over a mere 10Mb were failing to upload to Amazon&#39;s S3. Not only did none of my ministrations fix the problem, but I knew that it had to be the webhost. The backups were not failing because the jpa and sql files were on the local folder. The uploads were failing, and they were failing across different accounts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s been only a couple of weeks actually using Rochen, but so far, so good. I am happy with support. There is LetsEncrypt SSL at a click of the button. Support is very knowledgeable, and I&#39;ve not had to deal with &quot;switching you to level 2 support&quot; crapola.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I used to think that Rochen was very premium priced, but it is actually cheaper than the &quot;business plan&quot; at the ol&#39; standby. Each account comes with 60Gb of SSD which is very fair. I am taking well to the main portal &amp; cpanel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not that this is a review, mind you. We made a tough decision and made the move. And so far, so good.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oh, Akeeba Backup is workiing beautifully on Rochen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is important to note, especially if you are a client, is that Rochen is my new webhost of choice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, a note about email. I&#39;ve had a very interesting journey with email. There is no email hosting on my Digital Ocean cloud servers (well, unless I set &#39;em up, and I would not suggest it), so what to do with email? I am trying to avoid Google Apps. I am not enamoured with my domain registrator&#39;s email service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Look, to be frank, I really liked using my webhost&#39;s email. Unlimited email, forwarding was a snap, getting the email to work in regular Google was pretty easy. I was hoping that Amazon Web Service&#39;s Workmail would do the trick, but they&nbsp;need&nbsp;to build-out its feature set.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, I&#39;m going to get a Rochen account solely for the email. How &#39;bout that!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Rochen webhosting is my preferred web host.', 'Rochen webhosting is my preferred web host.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/season-for-a-new-webhost', 'university_spring.jpg', 1, 1, 0, '2016-05-30', '2016-05-31 07:01:47', 1, '2016-07-13 23:35:22', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(185, 5, NULL, NULL, 'Akeeba Backup For Laravel And WordPress', 'akeeba-backup-for-laravel-and-wordpress', '<p>I am using Akeeba Backup Professional for WordPress.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And, I am using Akeeba Backup Solo Professional for my Laravel web applications.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Akeeba Backup Professional for WordPress</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The wonderful thing about WordPress is its infinite availability of plugins. So there shouldn&#39;t be a problem finding a long established full featured backup plugin for WordPress, right? Well, for me, the answer is wrong.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the years, my dissatisfaction with free and commercial backup plugins has me searching again and again for backup plugins. Backing up the database and uploading it to Amazon&#39;s S3 is definitely covered, no trouble finding a plugin for this. The site files, and restoration? Well, that&#39;s a different matter.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What I&#39;ve found over the years is that backing up the WordPress folders and files is trickier than it appears. One reason is that errors emanate from the webhost, not from WordPress (or MySQL). Sometimes errors happen because of differing PHP versions. Sometimes the backup works but the upload to Dropbox or Rackspace or whatever fails. Yeah, there&#39;s a lot of cloud storage outfits to keep up with. And, y&#39;know, WordPress users just want&nbsp;plugins &quot;to just work&quot;. When it comes to backing up, it&#39;s enormously difficult to have it &quot;just work&quot; when there are so many potential externally based points of failure.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Restoring WordPress sites is not fully straight forward. Site URLs are stored in the database where they really shouldn&#39;t be in the first place -- confession: this little WordPress twist-and-turn so infuriates me that I refuse to fully understand it! Suffice to say, you have a development site, and now you want to go live on the live URL, you can&#39;t just import the database straight up.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ve seen some pretty whacky plugins that &quot;import&quot; and &quot;export&quot; WordPress sites. People who need to move WordPress sites around concocted their own plugins to deal with the WordPress idiosyncracies, and ended up publishing them. My hats off to people who release free open source software. But there&#39;s a certain point where I&#39;m not interested in, essentially, reverse engineering peoples&#39; home made solutions to idiosyncracies baked into the core software.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s no secret that I&#39;m a huge fan of Akeeba Backup for Joomla. I&#39;ve had the pleasure, and a pleasure it was, interviewing Akeeba&#39;s founder many times in the old days of my The Bob Bloom Show (<a href=\"https://southlasallemedia.com/tbbs48\" target=\"_blank\">https://southlasallemedia.com/tbbs48</a>). Nicholas has been through it all dealing with all the sordid issues involved backing up Joomla sites. It really does seem so straight forward at first, but it&#39;s incredible how un-straight-forward it becomes. I could not fathom doing a Joomla site without Akeeba Backup.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, when Akeeba Backup for WordPress came out, I was very excited. It took&nbsp;some time transmuting&nbsp;this wonderful Joomla extension into a WordPress plugin. A journey worthy of another podcast! Suffice to say, it was successfuly transmutted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, I cannot fathom doing a WordPress site without Akeeba Backup Pro for WP.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The combination of <a href=\"https://my.rochen.com/?link=12383\" target=\"_blank\">Rochen.com</a> hosting and Akeeba Backup is, so far, incredible. My Akeeba Backup CRON jobs -- they all upload to AWS S3 -- have 99% success (can never bat 1.000, eh!). Small database files, large full site archive files -- they all work (except for an outlier here-and-there), unattended, in the middle of the night, via CRON jobs.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Restoring an Akeeba backed up WordPress site is straight forward (and GUI based), once you get the hang of it. The WordPress idiosyncracies are handled well.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Akeeba Backup Solo Professional -- for Laravel!</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>For my Laravel web applications, I want to use a Laravel backup package. I want it Laravel all the way. Except, that, and does this sound familiar? I am unsatisfied with the backup packages. There&#39;s just not enough functionality to them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s fabulous that people publish free open source software. The backup packages hook in beautifully with Laravel -- and Forge. They use the Symfony console. They upload to S3. There is nothing wrong with the backup packages I tried. I wanted more functions, so, I forked a package. And, then, I deleted it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What&#39;s more valuable? Using a Laravel based backup package, or installing Akeeba Backup &quot;Solo&quot; Pro? This is the standalone version of Akeeba Backup Pro.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, a standalone version of Akeeba Backup.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So I tried it last night. Set up a subdomain on my DigitalOcean-slash-Forge-slash-Envoyer droplet. First time I set up a subdomain --&nbsp;figured it out. First time I set up a subdomain for LetsEncrypt SSL -- figured it out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Akeeba Backup Solo Professional works, and works beautifully. The one install backs up, with individual backup jobs, each database, and each set of files. Akeeba Backup sees the droplet&#39;s file structure, so I can have one job backup &quot;/home/forge/domainONE.com/storage/images&quot;, and another job backup &quot;/home/forge/domainTWO.com/storage/images&quot;. With Envoyer&#39;s symlinks, this is no moot point. Also, unlike backing up WordPress, I do not want to backup the entire folder structure of my app that resides on the droplet; rather, I only want to backup files that originate from the app&#39;s usage. Such as&nbsp;user uploaded images.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kudos to the <a href=\"https://www.akeebabackup.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Akeeba Team</a> for bringing their mature, full featured backup software to my Laravel web apps!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'I use, and recommend Akeeba Backup Professional for WordPress and Laravel web application backups.', 'I use, and recommend Akeeba Backup Professional for WordPress and Laravel web application backups.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/akeeba-backup-for-laravel-and-wordpress', 'akeebabackup.png', 1, 0, 0, '2016-07-14', '2016-07-14 18:02:11', 1, '2016-07-15 07:23:44', 1, NULL, NULL),
(186, 5, NULL, NULL, 'Keyword Search And Google', 'keyword-search-and-google', '<p>I had an interesting conversation yesterday about Google Adwords.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I assume that everyone, especially potential and actual clients, know about Google Adwords, and about keyword search in general. I also assume that the general public is similarily familiar given the general pervasiveness of keyword searches. After all, the Android operating system is made by Google (<a href=\"https://www.android.com/\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.android.com</a>).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wrong!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So I thought, while I&#39;m thinking of it, to post a little missive on this.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One reason is that I am opinionated about approaching SEO in the web apps that I build, and I want to blog about it sooner than later given that my new SouthLaSalle.ca site is in the works.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>First of all, I before I forget, &quot;keyword search&quot; is not social media. I was not sure if the person I was talking to was lumping in the idea of Search Engine Optimization (SEO) with social media.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Second of all, before I forget, remember that all the content you enter into social media is the property of that social medium. How they display your content, how they filter it, their tagging mechanisms -- all this stuff is entirely in their control and subject to their whims and fancies. It is their property, of which has value, that you&#39;ve contributed, whose mechanism to unlock that value is completely in their purview.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So the bedrock of SEO, in my opinion, is to have your own website. On your own (shared) server, with a domain that you own yourself (and not registered where you host your site).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We are all used to searching for sites based on a keyword search. What we are not used to is being one of those sites people find in those keyword searches.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have a business, you want people to find you when they do keyword searches. Which means, you want to be on the first page of search results that people see when the list of sites are displayed. You want to be one of those sites that are first displayed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here is where I get very opinionated:&nbsp;SEO does not stop at the point where people see your site displayed in search results.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Let&#39;s assume that everyone who sees your listing in the search results clicks to your site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Even then, what is the difference between a dozen people a day clicking to your site and then leaving, and a million people a day clicking to your site and then leaving. &nbsp;The issue for you is not getting people to your site, the issue is getting people to do that thing you want them to do once they are on your site. What it comes down to for you is people buying things. Or people sigining up for newsletters. Or people clicking the &quot;submit&quot; button on your contact form.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My opinion is that you first design your site for conversion. Conversion is the act of someone doing that thing you want them to do on your site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The way I look at it, there&#39;s only two ways to go when someone is on your website: abandonment, and conversion. There is no third thing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My opinion is that you need to reverse conventional wisdom: people obsess about SEO, but ignore conversion. Instead, you should focus on&nbsp;conversion first, then SEO. In fact, I am sure that by starting properly with conversion, you will do better with SEO.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ok, let&#39;s say you took care of conversion. A nice percentage of site visitors convert. So, what about SEO? What about social media?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Let&#39;s ignore social media here.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What about SEO?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, I have a secret for you! Google Analytics is free. Forget about paying for clicks, forget about that side of things. Sign up for Google Analytics, put the &quot;UA&quot; code on your site, and then traverse the GA dashboard. If you don&#39;t mind signing up to the Google &quot;Borg&quot;, then spend some time in the free GA dashboard to get an interesting perspective on your site. Check out the keywords people are using to find your site.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here&#39;s another secret: you can do keyword research for free. Yes, there are commercial tools to help. But getting your keyword research bearings is free.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In some things, a little bit of knowledge can be a bad thing. My opinion is that a client with a growing knowledge of SEO is a Good Thing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, if you are new to the idea of Google Analytics, and keyword research, this is a great area to go down the rabbit hole because frequently my client can do more than all the snake oil pitches; and, clients with a sense of SEO seem to grasp the conversion-abandon thing better; and, clients with a sense of SEO + conversion grasp how best to focus on social media.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And if you are wondering, my opinion is to focus on &quot;organic&quot; SEO at first, because it is there for the taking, and taking it has huge potential value.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'I assume everyone understands keyword marketing because everyone does keyword searches. I am reminded again that I am wrong. So here&#39;s a little missive on that, with my opinions.', 'I assume everyone understands keyword marketing because everyone does keyword searches. I am reminded again that I am wrong. So here&#39;s a little missive on that, with my opinions.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/keyword-search-and-google', 'seo2.jpg', 1, 1, 0, '2016-08-10', '2016-08-11 01:01:40', 1, '2016-08-11 07:49:11', 1, NULL, NULL),
(187, 1, NULL, NULL, 'Converting LaSalle Software To Laravel Version 5.3', 'converting-lasalle-software-to-laravel-version-5.3', '<p>Laravel 5.3 is so good that I am converting LaSalle Software to work with it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laravel 5.3 overview video by the Laravel founder at the Laracon US conference a couple of weeks ago:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://streamacon.com/video/laracon-us/taylor-otwell-laravel-53-overview\" target=\"_blank\">https://streamacon.com/video/laracon-us/taylor-otwell-laravel-53-overview</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here&#39;s a nice little article:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://laravel-news.com/2016/06/look-whats-coming-laravel-5-3/\" target=\"_blank\">https://laravel-news.com/2016/06/look-whats-coming-laravel-5-3/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laravel 5.3 improves on Laravel&#39;s basic proposition, at least the way I see it: to make web app development accessible.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s not the new features within the framework that have me so excited. It is the new FOSS packages. These packages are separate from the actual framework -- they have their own software repositories, their installation is optional, they install via <a href=\"https://getcomposer.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Composer</a>. The oauth package is a great example of a new L5.3 package that makes web app dev accessible -- it delivers a business proposition, and merely technical improvements.</p>', 'Laravel 5.3 is so good that I am converting LaSalle Software to work with it.\r\n\r\nLaravel 5.3 overvie...', 'Laravel 5.3 is so good that I am converting LaSalle Software to work with it.Laravel 5.3 overvie...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/converting-lasalle-software-to-laravel-version-5.3', '', 0, 0, 0, '2016-08-19', '2016-08-20 00:16:50', 1, '2016-08-20 00:32:40', 1, NULL, NULL),
(188, 1, NULL, NULL, 'Amazon Web Services Awsome Day Toronto', 'amazon-web-services-awsome-day-toronto', '<p><a href=\"https://southlasalle.com/images/2016aug24_awsome_day/2016aug24_awsome_day_conference3.jpg\"><img alt=\"Awsome Day Toronto 2016\" src=\"https://southlasalle.com/images/2016aug24_awsome_day/2016aug24_awsome_day_conference3.jpg\" style=\"float:left; height:533px; margin:0px 15px 20px 0px; width:400px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Wednesday, August 24, 2016, I attended the first Amazon Web Services &quot;Awsome Day&quot; held in Canada, at the Sheraton Centre in downtown Toronto.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The scuttlebug at lunch was that AWS will open its&nbsp;<a href=\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/aws/in-the-works-aws-region-in-canada/\" target=\"_blank\">Canadian data centre in Montreal</a>&nbsp;in September. That&nbsp;date is not confirmed, but the plan is to open by year&#39;s end. So, ahead of the opening, and ahead of the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://aws.amazon.com/summits/enterprise-summit-toronto/\" target=\"_blank\">Toronto Enterprise Summit</a>, AWS did this &quot;Awsome Day&quot; late summer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I attended because it was an opportunity to clear up the fuzziness I&#39;m having about AWS. Its services have exploded, and I&#39;m getting bogged down in what these services are; and, in the permissions settings in its &quot;IAM&quot;. Perhaps a day-long technical overview would clear up some cobwebs. It certainly helped that the day was free, and was designed for techies.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The day-long overview was conducted by an experienced AWS trainer, based on their&nbsp;<a href=\"https://aws.amazon.com/training/course-descriptions/essentials/\" target=\"_blank\">Technial Essentials</a>&nbsp;course. Thankfully, there was a section on IAM, so I scored big. The description of their data centers and &quot;Availability Zones&quot; was very helpful.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There were plenty of AWS people on hand to field questions during breaks and lunch. I was pleasantly surprised the day after to receive an email about a question I had asked, as promised.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The talk on &quot;IAM&quot; (AWS Identity and Access Management) was a Big Help to me as it cleared up a few things for me. The AWS technical overview was also a Big Help. Asking the AWS &quot;Architects&quot; the few bothersome questions I had was also beneficial. When I go through the AWS screens I will have more context now. With the explosion of AWS services, this is a significant plus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I estimate, and this is purely me guessing and nothing else, that between 300-400 techies were there. The presentation was well done. The food and beverages at breaks and lunch were fantastic -- someone spent some serious money, but that someone was not me&nbsp;as the event was gratis. I knew of this event via an email invitation from AWS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"Bob Bloom at Awsome Day Toronto 2016\" src=\"https://southlasalle.com/images/2016aug24_awsome_day/2016aug24_awsome_day_conference1.jpg\" style=\"float:right; height:500px; margin:0px 0px 15px 20px; width:375px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There was no selling. Which is to say, the entire event was selling. The presentation was a technical tour of what are&nbsp;very technical products. But the idea was not to &quot;sell&quot; us techies on the merits of AWS. Rather, to technically describe AWS, and to let that be enough. You know techies:&nbsp;we hate being sold stuff, but we love shiny new toys.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A huge issue with AWS is &quot;<a href=\"https://techcrunch.com/2015/12/26/the-clouds-biggest-threat-are-data-sovereignty-laws/\" target=\"_blank\">Data Sovereignty</a>&quot;. Like those commercials, data created in Canada needs to stay in Canada. Many&nbsp;Canuck corporations and government entities AWS is eyeing cannot use AWS right now because the data crosses the Canadian border. When the Montreal data centre opens, data does not have to cross the border.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, it seems to me that AWS wants&nbsp;techies to understand the technical basics, so that these techies then convince&nbsp;their managers to attend the upcoming Summit. At the Summit, AWS will work over the managers pretty good! So, when the Canadian data centre opens, there will be a nice critical mass of Canuck users ready-to-go.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>', 'On Wednesday, August 24, 2016, I attended the first Amazon Web Services &#34;Awsome Day&#34; held in Canada, at the Sheraton Centre in downtown Toronto.', 'On Wednesday, August 24, 2016, I attended the first Amazon Web Services &#34;Awsome Day&#34; held in Canada, at the Sheraton Centre in downtown Toronto.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/amazon-web-services-awsome-day-toronto', '2016aug24_awsome_day/2016aug24_awsome_day_conference1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2016-08-29', '2016-08-30 05:46:23', 1, '2016-09-07 21:49:40', 1, NULL, NULL),
(189, 1, NULL, NULL, 'Launched The York Region PHP User Group', 'launched-the-york-region-php-user-group', '<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://southlasalle.com/images/yorkregionphpusergroup1.png \" style=\"float:left; height:173px; margin:0px 10px 10px 0px; width:292px\" />I am thrilled to announce the launch of the York Region PHP User Group.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The website is at&nbsp;Meetup.com, at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.meetup.com/York-Region-PHP-User-Group/\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.meetup.com/York-Region-PHP-User-Group</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Recently, a local group trial ballooned a user group with an initial meet-up, but unfortunately that effort did not progress further (see my post&nbsp;at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://southlasalle.com/inaugural-php-group-north-meet-up\" target=\"_blank\">https://southlasalle.com/inaugural-php-group-north-meet-up</a>). I was so excited at the prospect of connecting with local devs, and so impressed at the turnout of that first meeting, and so frustrated that the efforts came to a grinding halt.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am deeply impressed with the volunteer efforts of Peter Meth and Vic Metcalfe, organizers of the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.meetup.com/GTA-PHP-User-Group-Toronto/\" style=\"line-height: 20.8px;\" target=\"_blank\">GTA PHP User Group</a>, to be at that initial meet-up to help get the &quot;GTA PHP User Group &#39;North&#39; &quot; group off the ground.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When it was clear that that group would not pursue the &quot;North&quot; meet-up group, I approached Vic about continuing the effort. With his critical help, and with his insistence that the new group be run independently, I am now the organizer of the new York Region PHP User Group. Oh sure, Vic is so mild mannered when you meet him. But when Vic insists...&nbsp;<a href=\"https://youtu.be/2D_zITtVJGA?t=6m12s\" target=\"_blank\">https://youtu.be/2D_zITtVJGA?t=6m12s</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I still want to head to the downtown meet-ups. Well, maybe I can&#39;t make it down to all of them, but I want the opportunity to go. I assume there are many York Region PHP devs who feel the same as me.&nbsp;So, generally, the downtown meet-ups happen on the first week of the month, and the York Region meet-ups will happen on the third week. This month, September, it&#39;s the second and fourth weeks.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am an avid subscriber of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://voicesoftheelephpant.com/\" target=\"_blank\">https://voicesoftheelephpant.com</a>, regular podcast publishers of 10 - 15 minute interviews with people active the PHP community. Especially in their local PHP user groups. A few interviewees have said that their biggest challenge in their local user group is finding speakers. So, they are arranging their meet-ups to be training grounds, so to speak, for local attendees to do presentations. What they have found, and what I am certain of here in York Region, is that there is a lot of talent and experience attending their local meet-ups, but it&#39;s hard to get developers to go up in front of a group -- especially a group of peers! -- and present something.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I want to take their lessons to heart. So, the first couple of York Region meet-ups, we&#39;ll have traditional styled meet-ups. But afterwards, I want to shake things up a bit to encourage attendees to share their knowledge and experience.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am looking forward to meeting you! Head on over to the meetup.com and RSVP an upcoming local meet-up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'I am thrilled to announce the launch of the York Region PHP User Group.\r\n\r\nThe website is atMeetup.c...', 'I am thrilled to announce the launch of the York Region PHP User Group.The website is atMeetup.c...', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/launched-the-york-region-php-user-group', 'yorkregionphpusergroup1.png', 1, 0, 0, '2016-09-07', '2016-09-07 23:15:33', 1, '2016-09-08 18:44:27', 1, NULL, NULL),
(190, 4, NULL, NULL, 'First Paid LaSalle Software Web App Now Live', 'first-paid-lasale-software-web-app-is-now-live', '<p>There are a few reasons why I do not blog about my consulting engagements.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My clients enjoy privacy. My clients enjoy that I do not link from their site to my site. My clients enjoy that I never create meta tags that refer to me.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&#39;s also the fact that I do a lot of work for other consultants, who do not want to see their clients on my blog.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Of course, I&#39;ve had bad experiences. The worst was a client held their testimonial hostage in return for extra unpaid work. All the clients testimonials and case studies on my website were unpublished within hours.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My first paid LaSalle Software web application is an exception. In fact, my first three paid web apps may be exceptions simply because someone at a meet-up said that new software has &quot;traction&quot; when there are three paid web apps. When he said that, &quot;3&quot; became my &quot;magic number&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Certainly, this first one is special. Being the first it is the recipient of so much love that I sometimes think that this is my web app. It doesn&#39;t help me that for this first web app, and only for this first web app, I am using my own entire deployment suite. So, this web app feels like it&#39;s part of my own personal web app family -- SouthLaSalle.com, SouthLaSalleMeda.com, and LaSalleSoftware.ca.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The reason I am hoisting this web app onto my own deployment accounts is that I really do not know what to expect doing a web app for a client. So, I&#39;d really take this one under my wing, and later we can move deployment to the client owned SaaS accounts. This turned out well for me, because I did a pretty good job focusing on the web app itself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The web app is Lely Tank Customer Care dot com (https://lelytankcustomerservice.com/).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The purpose of the site is to provide text &amp; image updates of custom truck construction&#39;s work-in-progress. Employees send text and images to the web app, and the web app displays this stuff to clients. The goal is to from smartphone to smartphone. An employee initials the update on their smartphone, and the customer sees their updates on their smartphone.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A fundamental proposition of LaSalle Software is it saves clients time and money, by giving them a&nbsp;software head start. Did this happen? Without a doubt, this is exactly what happened. What a thrill! I set up the initial web app and that was it. Had a one page home page. Had the admin. Had the logins management. How sweet it is!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I did not have a feature, oh boy, what a difference. Like day and night. The token-based login exists because we needed it. It&#39;s now a LaSalle Software FOSS&nbsp;installable package. I charged my client $0. Note for the future: will charge client, but probably not full rate, for packages that are released as LaSalle Software FOSS packages. It certainly is beneficial for clients to sponsor packages, in the &quot;we enjoy giving, we really enjoy getting&quot; department.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Being able to base the token-based login on existing software was a huge time saver.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The biggest programming to do was the email parsing, which was a new thing for me. I was able to dig right into it because I did not have other programming to worry about (except the token-based login package).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Did I have an opportunity to use my admin form automation? Well, actually, yes. I had to add a new database table. So satisfying to report to you that the admin form automation was a big time saver. For LaSalle Software v2, I will ponder how to make the forms more customizable without having to do a full blown template over-ride.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This web app was 95% done in May, but was on hold until recently while the main site enjoyed its makeover.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'My first paid LaSalle Software web application went live Halloween 2016.', 'Software web application went live Halloween 2016.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/first-paid-lasale-software-web-app-is-now-live', 'lelytankcustomercare_home_page.png', 1, 0, 0, '2016-11-01', '2016-11-02 22:04:47', 1, '2016-12-15 08:48:55', 1, NULL, NULL),
(191, 1, NULL, NULL, 'True North PHP Conference 2016', 'truenorthphpconference2016', '<p><a href=\"images/2016nov05_true_north_php_conference/IMG_0110.JPG\"><img src=\"images/2016nov05_true_north_php_conference/IMG_0110.JPG\" style=\"float:left; height:auto; overflow:hidden; padding:10px; width:400px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The True North PHP Conference was November 03rd to 05th, 2016. It was at Microsoft Canada&#39;s Conference Centre in Mississauga, at their Canadian head office --&nbsp;a fabulous venue.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The organizers of the GTA PHP Group run this Conference, the same people who are instrumental in helping me launch the York Region PHP Group. This was my <a href=\"https://southlasalle.com/truenorthphpconference2015\" target=\"_blank\">second</a> of the five annual TNPHP.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This year&#39;s theme: this was the final TNPHP Conference. Which was not the intent, but everyone knew.&nbsp;The final talk was &quot;Last One Out Please Shut down The Conference&quot;, where Chris, Peter, and Vic got a well deserved Standing O.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This &nbsp;year, I had three&nbsp;things I wanted from the Conference: API, software testing, and meet-and-greet. Thumbs up on all three.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Being on the cusp of re-doing LaSalle Software centred on an API, I wanted to absorb as much API goodness as I could. I attended specific API talks, but most of the talks that I attended touched on APIs in one form or another.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I brought a stack of index cards with me to the Conference. When something was mentioned that I should think about for my LaSalle Software&#39;s API, I wrote it down. I came home with a nice stack of cards. An indication that APIs are very mainstream now.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first two days I brought my laptop. A laptop is <em>de rigueur</em> for the tutorial day. For the first day of talks, maybe less so, but handy for looking things up.&nbsp;The third day I had&nbsp;enough of my laptop.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"clearfix\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"images/2016nov05_true_north_php_conference/2016nov03_tnphp_phpunit_tutorial.jpg\"><img src=\"images/2016nov05_true_north_php_conference/2016nov03_tnphp_phpunit_tutorial.jpg\" style=\"float:left; height:auto; overflow:hidden; padding:10px; width:400px\" /></a>The Hallway Track was an important part of this Conference. Enjoyed talking to the speakers, the width and breadth of their knowledge and experience is breathtaking. Talked to a lot of people I know from the local groups, including a handful from the York Region PHP Group.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I don&#39;t know what it is, but I find PHPUnit a bit mysterious. I always seem to have trouble with it. I made a point of attending the three hour PHPUnit workshop. It didn&#39;t take long before I could not replicate the instructor&#39;s results. Naturally. So I basically ignored the talk and went about trying to figure things out. If worse came to worse, I would beseech help, because I need to get over this hump. Well, I figured things out. Namespacing and composer autoloading&nbsp;turned out to be the culprits. After that, PHPUnit worked beautifully. I then went through the doc on the PHPUnit website. It just came together for me. I know it&#39;s crazy, what&#39;s so hard about it?&nbsp;Oh well...&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When it came time for the Laravel Testing talk on Saturday, I absorbed it all. Wrote lots of notes. Now, it&#39;s making sense. Wow, to see it in action with the live coding was a big help. For the first time, I am feeling confident about automated software tests for LaSalle Software v2. I was hoping the Conference would get me over the hump with this stuff and it did.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"clearfix\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"images/2016nov05_true_north_php_conference/IMG_0205.JPG\"><img src=\"images/2016nov05_true_north_php_conference/IMG_0205.JPG\" style=\"float:left; height:auto; overflow:hidden; padding:10px; width:400px\" /></a>I expected that the talk on Saturday about the Laravel Container would be a step-by-step journey of the code, and the concepts behind, Laravel&#39;s container. Nope. It was a history of PHP containers, with a primer on how the PHP frameworks are doing containers&nbsp;now. But, maybe there&#39;s a reason this wasn&#39;t a deep dive into Laravel&#39;s source code. The lead-up into Laravel&#39;s Container makes more sense with the historical context. Actually, I am so used to using Laravel that I did not appreciate how elegant Laravel&#39;s solution really is. Really nice to see the speaker so enthusiastic about Laravel!&nbsp;Now, I have to deep dive into Laravel&#39;s source code, now that I have a better idea about Laravel&#39;s &quot;inversion of control&quot; container.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The True North PHP Conference may have concluded, but the Toronto PHP community is stronger and growing. In no small part to the five annual TNPHP.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This final TNPHP was fabulous. Glad I did the 407 commute!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/afilina/sets/72157672545382013\" target=\"_blank\">Photos on Flickr</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/hashtag/tnphp16?src=hash\" target=\"_blank\">Twitter #tnphp16</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'The final annual True North PHP Conference was very good. Excellent talks, lots of choice with three concurrent tracks to choose from, deep dive tutorials on the Thursday...', 'The final annual True North PHP Conference was very good. Excellent talks, lots of choice with three concurrent tracks to choose from, deep dive tutorials on the Thursday.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/truenorthphpconference2016', 'IMG_0209.JPG', 1, 1, 0, '2016-11-05', '2016-11-06 07:37:24', 1, '2016-11-10 20:41:14', 1, NULL, NULL),
(192, 4, NULL, NULL, 'What I Learned From My Own Meet-up Talk: Stop Looking In The Rear View Mirror', 'what-i-learned-from-my-own-meet-up-talk-stop-looking-in-the-rear-view-mirror', '<p>I just deployed my write up of <a href=\"https://yorkregionphp.ca/2016nov14_meetup.php\" target=\"_blank\">last Monday&#39;s York Region PHP talk on design patterns</a>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Afterwards, I thought that it would be much better to do talks on&nbsp;&quot;CONTINUOUS&quot; technologies. Because, it is these technologies that are trending. That will change our professional lives forever.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Read the write-up...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'After my YRPHP talk on design patterns, I thought that it would be much better to do presentations about &#34;CONTINUOUS&#34; technologies. Because, it is these technologies that are trending. That will change our professional lives forever.', 'After my YRPHP talk on design patterns, I thought that it would be much better to do presentations about &#34;CONTINUOUS&#34; technologies. Because, it is these technologies that are trending. That will change our professional lives forever.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/what-i-learned-from-my-own-meet-up-talk-stop-looking-in-the-rear-view-mirror', 'IMG_0212.JPG', 1, 0, 0, '2016-11-17', '2016-11-18 02:12:10', 1, '2016-11-18 02:12:10', 1, NULL, NULL),
(194, 4, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalle Software Version Two Development Commences: It Begins From The End', 'lasalle-software-version-two-development-commences-it-begins-from-the-end', '<p>After going through a ton of prep, staring at my version one code, endless research, going down way too many rabbit holes, I am starting with my Version Two development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You would think that my software development starts with writing code. Well, it does not. It starts with setting up the environments. The local development environment, the repos, the build environment, and the live domains. I&#39;m setting &#39;em up now.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It feels very weird. But it&#39;s not the coding that concerns me right off the bat. What concerns me first is where the code resides, and ensuring that the code can get to all the places it is supposed to be in a completely automated fashion.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Just as a big lesson about software testing is that the software has to be testable, the big lesson with Continuous Integration&nbsp;is that the software is integratable.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here we go...</p>', 'After going through a ton of prep, staring at my version one code, endless research, going down way too many rabbit holes, I am starting with my Version Two development...', 'After going through a ton of prep, staring at my version one code, endless research, going down way too many rabbit holes, I am starting with my Version Two development.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasalle-software-version-two-development-commences-it-begins-from-the-end', 'let_the_games_begin.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2017-01-18', '2017-01-20 08:05:49', 1, '2017-01-20 08:18:15', 1, '2017-05-25 05:25:49', 1),
(195, 1, NULL, NULL, 'I Am Back!', 'i-am-back', 'I am back!\r\n<br /><br />\r\nThis year went differently than planned, the result being I ended up going off the digital grid -- no blog posts, no podcasts, no new public repo development on GitHub. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nIt\'s not a help that I am not on any social media, except for Twitter, so there was no corner of social media where you saw me. As for Twitter, I rely on Twitter to stay up-to-date on the technology that I am into, but technology has taken a back seat to politics. so I\'ve stayed away from Twitter.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nMy plan this year was to do a new version of LaSalle Software, get ecommerce going with LaSalle Software, consolidate all my content into one new site, and build up a renewed family of clients. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nAlthough things have not gone according to plan this year, things have been accomplished. What is clearly not good is that I\'ve been off the grid for far too long, and I can tell you now from hard experience that being off the grid is really bad for marketing! So I\'ve long concluded that once I\'m back on the grid, that I am staying on the grid. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nI felt pretty strongly that a false start would be very bad -- getting back on the grid, then falling off again, then coming back. I would line things up properly to ensure that once back, I\'d stay. So things are now lined up. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nI started this year doing something I had not done in a very long while: I took on short-term contracts. I was asked to \"help out\" with short term pressures on a contract basis not once, but twice back-to-back, by different people. I very much doubt I\'ll ever do contracting again. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nI decided to wait for my contracting to conclude to start work on my software development because, basically, the only time I could work on my software was when I was supposed to be sleeping. The way this year has progressed, I decided that I would get things out of the way first that I was doing, and so clear the path for development. This is exactly what has happened.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nOnce my contracts concluded, I had a client site to do, my meet-up sites to do, and my new consolidated site to do. They are all done and live. They took an immensely long time to do. I put the sites together with Laravel (of course), an admin package for Laravel (that was not quite plug-and-play), a generic template I modified for blade (there\'s a subject), and took code from version one of my LaSalle Software. Sometimes I think for all the effort to get these sites up I could have just developed the initial LaSalle Software packages first, but I know in full hindsight that I\'d have risked not having any sites up at all.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nNow that I have consolidated my sites into ibe new site, I have a list of things I want to communicate to you, so there\'s fresh content on the way, including re-starting my monthly podcast.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nI\'ve been working on a home page that is different from anything I\'ve ever put together. Ultimately, what made me decide to go ahead with my home page idea is to be an example to my clients. Our home pages need to be much more visual, less text-y, significantly less cluttered, and much more media-ish-y. My site is the same, just my home page is different. \n<br /><br />\nThere are still issues with my new home page, but I am going ahead with it for two main reasons: the exercise of building it and maintaining it are extremely valuable; and, I achieved the basic premise for myself that I was aiming for.  \r\n<br /><br />\r\nThis year we did something that we were not planning on doing, but had the opportunity to do, and we went for it. We made a major investment in our home office. We did a major home office reno, and we made major equipment investments. We were able to design and build from scratch a solution to accommodate our equipment, implement kick-ass wire management, make our modems accessible, and have a place for our stuff. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nI am literally taken by surprise how our morale has shot up. The lighting is better, we are better organized, it is easier to diagnose internet outages, and we know what each wire is for. Our morale boost is a wonderful surprise.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nWe now have equipment with the three major operating systems: Windows, Linux, and Mac OS. We also have a range of tablets and smartphones. Frankly, we have a finer home office set up than I\'ve seen at many workplaces. Logistically, I have never been more able to serve my clients. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nI also went off the beaten path by building what is called a \"Hackintosh\". I wanted more memory and hardware power for my MacOS, so I put together hand-picked computer hardware components myself to make a fully functioning computer. Then, I loaded the MacOS onto it. It was a real education. I call this computer my \"Laratosh\". \r\n<br /><br />\r\nI am very glad to be back!', 'After an extended hiatus in 2017, I am back!', 'After an extended hiatus in 2017, I am back!', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/i-am-back', 'imback.png', 1, 0, 1, '2012-09-11', '2017-09-11 16:30:05', 1, '2017-09-12 20:22:40', 1, NULL, NULL),
(196, 1, NULL, NULL, 'Why The Magna Centre?', 'why-the-magna-centre', 'The Magna Centre is a magnificent facility. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nIt is a modern community centre with wonderful amenities, the heart of which are its four hockey rinks. One rink is Olympic sized with seating. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nI chose this facility for the fall 2017 York Region PHP and Laravel meet-ups because of lessons learned from our first meet-up season; and, because of time pressures.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nLike so much of this year for me, my plan to do a deep scoping of York Region facilities for the meet-ups over the summer just did not go according to plan. Our home, and home office, renos were consuming and worthwhile (see my <a href=\"/i-am-back\">\"I\'\'m Back\"</a> post). Labour Day approached, and I went with the one facility that I knew that had most of what I was looking for. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nCheck out this map of York Region:\r\n<br /><br />\r\n<iframe src=\"https://www.google.com/maps/embed?pb=!1m18!1m12!1m3!1d367559.91274268966!2d-79.73088176123534!3d43.968429815179995!2m3!1f0!2f0!3f0!3m2!1i1024!2i768!4f13.1!3m3!1m2!1s0x882acdaee4d2a679%3A0x108dcfb46a288a64!2sYork+Regional+Municipality%2C+ON!5e0!3m2!1sen!2sca!4v1505312069846\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" frameborder=\"0\" style=\"border:0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n<br /><br />\r\nYork Region is huge! A larger land area than Toronto.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nA Big Lesson I learned from our inaugural York Region PHP season is: Go North! The meet-ups were concentrated in the south central-ish area of York Region, which was too south for some attendees. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nMost of York Region\'s population is in the south on the border with Toronto. I figured that most of our attendees would be from the south, so as long as attendees could easily traverse laterally east-west, the meet-ups should be in York Region\'s south end. Well, the bulk of York Region\'s population may be due south, but PHP devs are all over, including in the north. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nMy goal is to get north and west, to get closer to the cluster of devs in the Barrie area. Barrie is not in York Region. However, the top end of York Region is to the east of Barrie, just on the other side of Lake Simcoe, so geographically thinking about the Barrie area is reasonable.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nThere are two major north-south highways: the 400 is on the west side, and the 404 is on the east side. There is one major highway going east-west, and that\'s the 407. A fun aspect of the 407 is that it charges the highest toll fees in North America. Highway 7 is a highway in name only in York Region, as are many other east-west roads with the word \"highway\" in their name. Things to take into account.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nThose in the Barrie area will be coming down the 400. Having them exit at Davis Drive and heading to the Upper Canada Mall area, at Yonge Street, seems like a good idea. Except that the area is becoming more and more congested. I am told that the stoplights are brutal on the new VIVA area east of Yonge. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nThe Magna Centre is in Newmarket, which is good. It is on the 404 side, not the 400 side, which is not so good, but it is on Mulock Drive which should be an easier west-to-east traversal than Davis Drive (is it?).\r\n<br /><br />\r\nWe need to have meet-ups in venues where getting into the building is easy, getting into the actual meeting room is easy, and where going to the restroom is easy. We\'ve had attendees trying to get access to buildings after-hours in the middle of winter. We\'ve had attendees locked out of the meet-up after going to the restroom, and then knocking on the door to get back in. \n<br /><br />\nAll the downtown meet-ups I\'ve gone to are in corporate offices. Practically all of them are open concept, so despite the meet-ups being conducted in specific areas of the office, there are no physical barriers preventing attendees from going to areas that are private. Attendees are mindful of open-yet-private areas, and corporate hosts usually have staff at the meet-ups who keep on eye on things. I\'ve never heard of any incidents. \n<br /><br />\nAlso, there were \"open-yet-private\" issues last season that I am happily avoiding this fall by not contemplating corporate offices as venues. \n<br /><br />\r\nThe Magna Centre is a great choice for what I wanted. So I booked all our fall meet-ups there, and I paid the room rental fees. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nThe one downside to the Magna Centre is that one of the meeting rooms we will be in has a glass wall giving a fabulous view of the hockey rink. \r\n<br /><br />\r\n<br /><br />', 'Why did I choose the Magna Centre for the York Region PHP and Laravel meet-ups in the fall of 2017?', 'Why I chose the Magna Centre for the York Region PHP and Laravel meet-ups in the fall of 2017.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/why-the-magna-centre', 'magna_centre1.jpg', 1, 0, 0, '2017-09-11', '2017-09-11 13:45:59', 1, '2017-09-13 18:48:44', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `lookup_workflow_status_id`, `categories`, `tags`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `meta_description`, `canonical_url`, `featured_image`, `enabled`, `postupdate`, `sticky`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(197, 1, NULL, NULL, 'York Region PHP Meet-up Topics and Speakers for 2017-\'18', 'york-region-php-meet-up-topics-and-speakers-for-2017-2018', 'I organize the York Region PHP meet-up group (we are on Toronto\'s north border). What topics should we cover? What speakers should we pursue?\r\n<br /><br />\r\nLast season was the first for our meet-up group. I intentionally tried different venues, speakers, and topics for the simple reason that to find out what works I need to try different things. Let\'s get as many different types of venues, speakers, and topics covered just to see what is well received. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nActually, IMO, there were too many venues and too wide a range of topics and I want things to settle down this season. I hope to eventually have two venues that alternate: one at or near Newmarket, and the other either in the Beaver Creek area (404/407/7) or near the <a href=\"https://www.ttc.ca/Spadina/Stations/Vaughan_Metropolitan_Centre_Station/index.jsp\" target=\"_blank\">new Vaughan Metropolitan subway</a> at Jane/7 (close to 400/7). I\'m sure to have another post devoted to venues.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nI learned that there is a tremendous range of topics of interest to PHP developers. Ok, so this is not exactly new. However, I find it shocking that we can spend an entire meet-up not talking about PHP. This is so because the fundamental nature of PHP development is having skills in a myriad of areas. A prime attraction of PHP meet-ups is staying up-to-date with the topics we need to know. But, what about devoting whole meet-ups talking about everything but PHP? <em>At what point do we become a meet-up group about general software development and not a PHP group?</em> And, what about deferring talks about specific topics where separate groups exist for those topics? Why devote presentations about WordPress or AWS or Symfony when local groups (and local conferences) exist for those frameworks and technologies? It\'s a tough call, because it\'s great to listen to overviews -- and then the discussions afterwards. On the other hand, as someone who attends meet-ups,  where is the meet-up about PHP?! \r\n<br /><br />\r\nA predecessor to the York Region PHP group was a Coffee-and-Code group that met each Sunday at a Richmond Hill Starbucks. So it was no surprise, and very welcomed, when the request for coffee-and-code workshops was raised. So we alternated months between a traditional meet-up, and a coffee-and-code workshop.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nThe coffee-and-code workshops were great. So much so that we should establish a York Region PHP Coffee and Code Group! The main reason to establish this new group is to delegate the organizing duties to someone else. I will gladly co-organize, but someone else has to take the reins. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nThe <a href=\"http://www.zendcon.com/\" target=\"_blank\">ZendCon 2017 conference</a> is a great example of the huge range of topics of interest to PHP developers. There are six speaking tracks, six! \"PHP best practices\", \"PHP frameworks\", \"PHP communities\", \"IBM | development\", \"DevOps & Continuous Delivery\", and \"Open source ecosystem\". Wow, what a range. And the range within each track is vast. So there is no end of potential presentation topics for our local PHP group. And, there is an ever widening array of topics that are not so much PHP but are important skills for PHP devs. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nIMO, CI is profound. It changes the very nature of how we go about doing PHP development. So profound that I am willing to devote the bulk of the winter/spring meet-ups to CI. It is ridiculous the pressure PHP devs have on learning professional specialities that were so outside the purview of devs not so long ago. The pressure to understand dev-ops is intense. But this is the world we live in: technology has fused the various disciplines together into a seamless process. If our PHP group did not devote meet-ups every year to this profound change in the nature of our profession, would we not be remiss?  We can debate interfaces and design patterns until we are blue in the face, but it is more important to make sure PHP devs don\'t become obsolete by ignoring CI! \r\n<br /><br />\r\nBut, I digress... I want to get \"back to basics\" with PHP this fall. Hence the initial \"PHP 7\" presentation. However, the imperatives of mentoring local speakers will, in large part, determine the topics.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nWhich brings me to the main thing: LOCAL SPEAKERS!\r\n<br /><br />\r\nI\'ve talked to meet-up organizers. I\'ve listened to a great many number of podcasts on organizing meet-ups and conferences. There is one huge massive lesson that is always conveyed: <em>long term meet-up success is tied to local speakers</em>. And, of course, naturally, the biggest challenge of organizing meet-ups: local speakers!\r\n<br /><br />\r\nOur Group is blessed to have the support of the GTA-PHP-slash-True-North-Conference organizers. Very Tangible Support. So we are connected to the growing number of PHP groups in the GTA, which definitely brings a richer experience to our local group. We now need to use this strength to become a self-supporting group, which means we need to develop our own local speakers. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nThere is no doubt in my mind -- none! -- that an imperative of our Group is to develop local speakers. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nI know, I know. Most people do not want to do public speaking. And even for experienced speakers, putting together slides and speaking notes is daunting. So some presentations should be done sitting down, should be brief, and should have no slides. Let\'s just relax about the whole thing. Of course, we are PHP devs, so if you can show us some code, that would be great! Funny enough, but sometimes I think we should just throw some code on a whiteboard. But, if you have a little repo on GitHub that would be great too!\r\n<br /><br />\r\nOne thing I learned from going to meet-ups over the years is that you need 20 minutes minimum for a presentation and discussion. You\'re going to hit on something that piques interest. You look at the time and 15 minutes blew by in the Q&A. You realize from the Q&A that it would have helped to have \"that pictogram that I saw a week ago\". So the next time you share your experience and knowledge, you have in mind to include code or something to show. For that part of your presentation, you stand up to point to something you are presenting. And that is how people get into doing presentations. Not because they are \"brave\", or are \"extroverted\", or are \"especially trained on topic\", but it\'s just easier to explain the thing with that pictogram!\r\n<br /><br />\r\nThe first presentation a local speaker should do is just share how they solved an intense PHP programming problem. At a recent downtown meet-up, a very experienced speaker said they had a problem with API authentication that none of the usual solutions solved, so they wrote their own. The exposition of what the problem was and why the usual frameworks/packages/best practices failed was fascinating. They pushed things and had to innovate. This is the type of thing a first time local presenter should do. Attendees love real-world stuff, so share your stories. Can you please bring alone some code samples -- maybe create a new public GitHub.com repo that we can look at on our laptops?\r\n<br /><br />\r\nSo think about a PITA problem you solved, and go through it at our next meet-up. Or, maybe it\'s not 100% solved and you want to hear ideas -- seen this too!\r\n<br /><br />\r\nSend me a missive!\r\n<br /><br />', 'I organize the York Region PHP meet-up group (we are on Toronto\'s north border). What topics should we cover? What speakers should we pursue?', 'I organize the York Region PHP meet-up group (we are on Toronto\'s north border). What topics should we cover? What speakers should we pursue?', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/york-region-php-meet-up-topics-and-speakers-for-2017-2018', NULL, 1, 0, 0, '2011-09-27', '2017-09-27 14:51:47', 1, '2017-09-28 16:30:18', 1, NULL, NULL),
(199, 1, NULL, NULL, 'LaSalle Software in the Microservice Style', 'lasalle-software-in-the-microservice-style', 'One of the best things about the Laravel Framework is being able to write packages. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nThird party packages is the reason that the Laravel Framework has a package facility. However, it is really handy to break one’s own app into packages. My LaSalle Software version 1 was designed to use internal packages.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nMy experience with version 1 was that it did not take long for the code to get unwieldy. When I added a feature, despite organizing the code well, it became difficult to track down the code that needed updating. There was always so much other code to wade through too, which was quite distracting.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nExtracting features into packages made things so much better. I could work on a package without worrying that I would inadvertently break unrelated app features. I could work on multiple packages at once. I could see all the code for the package. I could tag as many releases as I wanted for a package without having to go through a release cycle for the app itself. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nMicroservices is a product of our times, now that we live in the age of The Cloud. Why have one big app, using packages, when we can break down our app into multiple apps. Each individual app can be optimized according to its size and usage. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nNow that The Cloud is accessible and cheap, microservices is as much about the infrastructure as it is about anything else. Sometimes while reading up on microservices I get the impression that it’s really all about the infrastructure. Deploying each app automatically is a big thing. Apps talking to the other apps securely is a huge thing. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nI’ve been feeling the growing presence of DevOps as an aspect to software development. This intimate integration seems to have full expression in the microservice architecture. You can’t have one without the other, and each must understand the other. I have to figure out the infrastructure that I am going to use before I write one line of code. My thinking right now is to be very practical about the infrastructure. Despite reading about Netflix and SoundCloud’s implementation, I will take a light touch to infrastructure, as I am hardly building out the new Netflix.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nRight now, I am looking at how my independent service apps will securely talk to each other. This is itself a sub-specialty topic. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nOnce I figure out how my independent service apps will securely talk to each other, I will design my service API’s with an API design tool. Even with a modest number of API’s — perhaps just three or four service API’s — I can see how it can get out of hand without using an API design spec. It’s enough that these tools can generate documentation.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nSometimes, I do think it’s crazy going through all of this just to create a blog. But, clients will want more than just a blog. So this is the way to go. \r\n<br /><br />', 'The emphasis on infrastructure in the microservice architecture is intense. Hence, my focus on it at the beginning of LaSalle Software version 2.0\'s development.', 'The emphasis on infrastructure in the microservice architecture is intense. Hence, my focus on it at the beginning of LaSalle Software version 2.0\'s development.', 'https://lasallesoftware.ca/lasalle-software-in-the-microservice-style', 'microservices1.png', 1, 0, 0, '2017-12-05', '2017-12-06 16:01:00', 1, '2017-12-06 16:15:10', 1, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `postupdates` (`id`, `post_id`, `title`, `content`, `excerpt`, `enabled`, `publish_on`, `created_at`, `created_by`, `updated_at`, `updated_by`, `locked_at`, `locked_by`) VALUES
(1, 168, 'Pics From Business@Breakfast With The Chamber', '<p>Local newspaper took pics. I&#39;m in one!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://richmondhill.snapd.com/event/891197#/\" target=\"_blank\">https://richmondhill.snapd.com/event/891197#/</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Library&#39;s Facebook page with pics:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.994237467301312.1073741873.167307019994365&amp;type=3\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.994237467301312.1073741873.167307019994365&amp;type=3</a></p>', 'Local newspaper took pics at this event.  I&#39;m in one of &#39;em.', 1, '2016-01-01', '2016-01-01 21:02:09', 1, '2016-01-09 04:20:47', 1, NULL, NULL),
(2, 175, 'MySQL Tip Does The Trick', '<p>A MySQL tip suggested during the cache presentation seems to, initially, have helped my Digital Ocean MySQL crash problem. Thank you!</p>', 'A MySQL tip suggested during the cache presentation seems to, initially, have helped my Digital Ocean MySQL crash problem.', 1, '2016-02-24', '2016-02-24 19:30:14', 1, '2016-02-24 19:30:14', 1, NULL, NULL),
