(4, 180, 'Article About The History Of AWS', '<p><a href=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/on-it/the-rise-of-amazon-web-services/2015/04/23/fe1b3980-e795-11e4-9a6a-c1ab95a0600b_story.html\" style=\"color: rgb(17, 85, 204); font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12.8px; line-height: normal;\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/on-it/the-rise-of-amazon-web-services/2015/04/23/fe1b3980-e795-11e4-9a6a-c1ab95a0600b_story.html</a></p>', 'https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/on-it/the-rise-of-amazon-web-services/2015/04/23/fe1b3980-e795-11e4-9a6a-Article about the history of AWS', 1, '2016-03-01', '2016-03-02 08:16:53', 1, '2016-03-02 08:16:53', 1, NULL, NULL),
(5, 178, 'EC2 Might Be My Exception', '<p>Taking a deep look into EC2 pricing. I can see why I might want to stick with Digital Ocean.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://aws.amazon.com/ec2/pricing/\" target=\"_blank\">https://aws.amazon.com/ec2/pricing</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.ec2instances.info/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.ec2instances.info</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.digitalocean.com/pricing/\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.digitalocean.com/pricing</a></p>', 'EC2 might be my exception', 1, '2016-03-02', '2016-03-03 08:54:23', 1, '2016-03-03 08:54:23', 1, NULL, NULL),
(6, 177, 'Mandrill Covered In Recent Laravel News Podcast', '<p>Good discussion about Mandrill around the 8min mark:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://laravel-news.com/2016/03/episode-11-spark-watch-interview-shawn-mccool/\" target=\"_blank\">https://laravel-news.com/2016/03/episode-11-spark-watch-interview-shawn-mccool</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, the communications were not clear. Something to think about: if you have a drastic policy change to announce, make some notes and then do a video.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>BTW: It looks like MailChimp&#39;s free version will remain intact, by virtue of the lack of mention about MC.</p>', 'Good discussion about Mandrill in the recent Laravel News podcast.', 1, '2016-03-08', '2016-03-08 22:05:44', 1, '2016-03-08 22:05:44', 1, NULL, NULL),
(7, 177, 'Looks Like MailChimp Retaining Free Tier For MailChimp', '<p>I am reading&nbsp;<a href=\"http://blog.mandrill.com/important-changes-to-mandrill.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://blog.mandrill.com/important-changes-to-mandrill.html</a>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Originally, I thought Mandrill and MailChimp were losing their free tier. Now, it looks like Mandrill is losing its free tier, but MailChimp is retaining its free tier.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;m in the midst of developing my li&#39;l&nbsp;in-house email list management feature (<a href=\"https://github.com/lasallecrm/lasallecrm-l5-listmanagement-pkg/issues/14\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/lasallecrm/lasallecrm-l5-listmanagement-pkg/issues/14</a>). I&#39;ll be trying out AWS for my own in-house lists.&nbsp;</p>', 'Looks like MailChimp is retaining free tier for MailChimp', 1, '2016-03-16', '2016-03-16 21:50:15', 1, '2016-03-16 21:50:15', 1, NULL, NULL),
(8, 178, 'My Choice Is Getting Cloudy!', '<p>As much as AWS holds a great promise for email handling, having gone through its&nbsp;various alphabet soup of email services I am drifiting elsewhere already.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It does seem complicated. But, more striking to me is the investment required to learn it. Despite the online docs, it&#39;s clear I need some type of Laracasts to get into it. I have enough to learn, so at some point it&#39;s not worth it for me to invest that extra time. Sure I can figure it out, but the time it will take for the payoff gained is not worth it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ll tell you the moment when I told myself, &quot;self, it would be great to use AWS more deeply, but I&#39;m having second thoughts&quot;. When I struggled to find out exactly how to save attachments to S3. The email comes into SES, where a rule set saves it to S3 as a raw email. Then, launch a&nbsp;Lambda function, so I read (on StackExchange, if memory serves), to save the attachments on another S3 bucket. Then, how do I mark the attachments as public? And, the example Lambda function failed, so I spent 1/2 hour figuring out how to fix it. Oh... no, it was the sample policy to give SES permission to write to my S3 bucket...&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I returned to my computer, I did not go to my AWS console. Instead, I looked up other email transactional API&#39;s. Having selected one for my in-bound emails, I deleted my DNS settings for AWS, and then deleted my WorkMail user, deleted my SES related S3&nbsp;bucket, and reverted my SES rule set to my original one. So, maybe at another time I will deep dive into AWS. But for now, it&#39;ll just have to wait.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'As much as AWS holds a great promise for email handling, having gone through itsvarious alphabet sou...', 1, '2016-03-25', '2016-03-26 00:19:40', 1, '2016-03-26 00:34:06', 1, NULL, NULL),
(9, 181, 'Finished!', '<p>I finished this round of development, which produced three new free open source LaSalle Software packages:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Standard inbound email handling package<br />\r\n	(<a href=\"https://github.com/lasallecms/lasallecms-l5-lasallecmsemail-pkg\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/lasallecms/lasallecms-l5-lasallecmsemail-pkg</a>);</li>\r\n	<li>MailGun.com inbound email parsing package<br />\r\n	(<a href=\"https://github.com/lasallecms/lasallecms-l5-mailgun-pkg\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/lasallecms/lasallecms-l5-mailgun-pkg</a>);</li>\r\n	<li>Token Based Login package<br />\r\n	(<a href=\"https://github.com/lasallecms/lasallecms-l5-tokenbasedlogin-pkg\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/lasallecms/lasallecms-l5-tokenbasedlogin-pkg</a>).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'I finished this round of development, which produced three new free open source LaSalle Software pac...', 1, '2016-05-04', '2016-05-05 06:54:27', 1, '2016-05-05 06:54:27', 1, NULL, NULL),
(10, 186, 'Woopra.com', '<p>Want to post this link to an alternative to Google Analytics (there are many): <a href=\"https://www.woopra.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Woopra</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Want to post a link to Woopra.com.', 1, '2016-08-14', '2016-08-14 17:54:14', 1, '2016-08-14 17:54:14', 1, NULL, NULL),
(11, 186, 'Link To A Previous SEO Blog Post', '<p>Want to reference a previous post: <a href=\"https://southlasalle.com/search-engine-optimization-magic-pill1\">SEO - Take Two of These and Call Me in the Morning</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Referencing another blog post about SEO', 1, '2016-08-14', '2016-08-14 17:57:15', 1, '2016-08-14 17:57:15', 1, NULL, NULL),
(12, 184, 'Pay For Your Webhost Month-by-month Only', '<p>Although you pay more per month than by paying for a year (in advance), I counsel you to pay for your webhosting month-by-month.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The reason is that you do <u>no</u>t want to be bound to your webhost in any way, lest you need to move your site to another webhost (or cloud server).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You do <u>not</u> want your domain registered with your webhost either, for the same reason.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If your webhost goes down, if your site was hacked, if you do not like your webhost&#39;s service, if your webhost is slow installing your SSL certificate, if for any reason... you want the ability to get your site onto another webhost (or cloud server) ASAP.</p>', 'I counsel you to pay for your webhosting month-by-month', 1, '2016-08-31', '2016-09-01 18:51:37', 1, '2016-09-01 18:51:37', 1, NULL, NULL),
(13, 191, 'Another Post About TNPHP2016', '<p>Good one! &nbsp;<a href=\"http://srcmvn.com/blog/2016/11/11/truenorthphp-2016\" target=\"_blank\">http://srcmvn.com/blog/2016/11/11/truenorthphp-2016</a></p>', 'A good one!', 1, '2016-11-11', '2016-11-12 07:52:12', 1, '2016-11-12 07:52:12', 1, NULL, NULL);
